<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBLEE'S JUST HORSING AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It wasn't exactly a grand arrival for Brandel
Chamblee when he made his noontime drive up Magnolia Lane last
weekend. He nearly missed the entrance and tiny guard house several
hundred yards from the Augusta National clubhouse at the end of the
roadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of snuck up on me,'' said the Texan who qualified for
the 63d Masters by winning the Greater Vancouver Open last August.
``I almost drove right by the entrance.''
</P>
<P>
   After Chamblee got his bearings, he approached the guard house
to show his calling card _ his PGA Tour money clip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I don't need to see that. What's your name?' ''
Chamblee related. ``I told him, and he said, `Go on in.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't ask for an ID or anything like that. Very trusting.
I thought, `Man, I'm going to ask my buddies to give that a shot.'
I was dropped off by my wife, so I just walked into the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `This was pretty easy.' I walked in, and I thought
we'd have lockers. You don't. It's just a small, intimate
environment in the locker room. They put my shoes in Jack Baker's
locker. I know Jack. I thought there might be a bottle of scotch in
there, knowing Jack. I went out and had lunch by myself under the
oak tree overlooking the 18th green.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee, who grew up riding cutting horses and roping calves on
an Irving, Texas, ranch that is now the site of a Tournament
Players Club, usually spends Masters weekend doing his taxes and
hosting a party at his home outside Phoenix to watch the tournament
on TV.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly was having more fun Thursday, when he posted an
opening round of 69, 3 under par, to tie for the lead with Davis
Love, Scott McCarron, and Nick Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the course played pretty much the way I expected it
to play,'' said Chamblee. ``I came here early and played a number
of rounds on the golf course. So I felt comfortable. I thought the
course played pretty similar to way it played Tuesday and
Wednesday. They do a good job keeping the greens consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how I was going to handle the first day. You
never know how you're going to feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee, who went to the University of Texas, was asked how
riding cutting horses compares to the excitement of Amen Corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very similar when you get your foot caught in the saddle
and you fall off,'' said Chamblee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to ride competitively, but a couple horses reared up
and fell over on me. When you ride horses, you're going to get
hurt. I never got hurt playing golf. So it was an easy choice. I
still love horses though, and I hope to get one soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee certainly endeared himself to the membership of this
very private club.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear how it's a pretty tight ship,'' said Chamblee. ``It
is. Essentially it's a pretty tight club 51 weeks out of the year.
They open it one week. So that's the intriguing thing about this
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to see it, and they can't get in here but one
week of the year. I don't know anybody who wouldn't love to be a
member of this golf club. But they have their club and it's an
exclusive membership. Some people frown on that, and some people
say, `You have a right to do that.' Personally, I think this is a
wonderful place, and I'd love to be a member here. Who wouldn't?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia is golf's newest golden boy. The 19-year-old
Spaniard, who won the British Amateur a year ago, plays out The
Golf Club of Georgia in Atlanta and may turn professional following
the Masters. He qualified for the Mediterranean Open on the Eurpean
PGA Tour at the age of 14, and since 1995 he has played in 80
amateur and professional events in 20 countries. He was a
semifinalist in the US Amateur last year at Oak Hill. He says his
decision to go pro is on hold until Monday. ``I can't tell you for
sure,'' Garcia said. ``That's a thing I have to just be with my dad
on, with all of my family after this tournament. I can't tell you
for sure.'' Is it because of the Ryder Cup? ``I'm not thinking
about the Ryder Cup at this moment,'' he said. ``Once I turn pro, I
want to make my European card. If I can get on the Ryder Cup team,
it would be perfect. But I'm just going step by step, and we'll see
how it goes.'' . . . Fred Couples on the Tiger Woods-David Duval
rivalry: ``You know Tiger Woods can do anything. You know David
Duval can do anything. They're just totally different. They play
differently. Tiger plays with a boatload of emotion, and when he's
going strong he's pumping his fists and he's hitting it farther.
David hits it the same every single time, and that's how they both
play to their strong points.'' . . . Joe Durant, who won the
Western Open to qualify for the Masters, won Wednesday's par 3
tournament and realized no winner of that event has ever won the
Masters. ``I'm the sacrificial lamb,'' quipped Durant. ``I came out
and had fun. I birdied 2, 3, 4, and 5 without thinking about it.''
He shot 87 Thursday. Duval took the right approach in the par 3,
shooting a plus-14 round of 41 and permitting caddies to hit shots
for him . . . Paul Runyon, who played with tournament founder Bobby
Jones in the inaugural Masters in 1934, returned to participate in
the par 3 tournament, and he and his wife Bernice were given a
shuttle ride from their hotel to the course. The driver left them
at the wrong gate; so here was 90-year-old Runyon lugging a heavy
golf bag up Washington Road to the clubhouse. Fortunately someone
stopped to give them a ride. Runyon played in a threesome with Tom
Watson and Ben Crenshaw in the par 3 . . . Isn't this 1999? Some
people at Augusta National seem to still be living in the 1930s.
There is a copy of the front page of the Augusta Chronicle from
July 15, 1931, framed and hanging in a men's room. The banner
headline proclaims, ``Bobby Jones to Build His Ideal Golf Course on
Berckman's place.'' Nothing wrong with that, but tucked on the
bottom left of the page is a crude attempt at humor under the
heading ``Hambone's Meditations.'' A black cartoon character named
``Hambone'' is sitting on a wall saying, ``You jes cain' do good
work en hurry . . . Dey might apt to ketch you in de' lie. What you
fixes up right quick!'' It's so tasteless you wonder why it could
be left hanging there all these years _ and you have to wonder
whether Woods has seen it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Caddie Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan, who was fired by Woods March 8,
signed on with Jim Furyk and worked the Masters. ``I want him to be
my full-time caddie, and I want him to be happy working for me,''
said Furyk. ``He's one of the best caddies out here. I was
fortunate when I needed a caddie that he was available and he
wanted to work for me.'' Before they teed off in the final grouping
Thursday, Cowan said, ``I hope it's a permanent job. We'll see.'' .
. . There were separate pretournament meetings laced with anguish
involving golf writers' associations based in the United States and
the United Kingdom. The subject was the price of a single room at
the Sheraton Boston the week of the Ryder Cup at The Country Club.
The going rate is $237 per night before taxes. The rub is that
rooms at nearby hotels are topping $400 and the Sheraton Boston
tried to get out of its contract with the writers. PGA of America
representatives said they'd sue to hold the hotel to its contract.
There will be courtesy transportation to and from The Country Club
so visitors won't have to rent cars, but residents should be
concerned about what is happening to the image of Boston, which is
becoming known as ``Ripoff City'' _ and the Ryder Cup is still more
than five months down the road . . . Then there is this story
regarding price gouging at the Masters: According to the Augusta
Chronicle, a man named Love was in the Medical College of Georgia
Hospital after being critically injured in his hometown of
Moultrie. His wife reserved a room at a Holiday Inn to be near him,
but the room rates went from $59 to $200 a day because it was
Masters week. ``It's a touch-and-go, critical situation with my
husband,'' she told the Chronicle. ``It's not right. The sports
part of it has overshadowed anything else, and we don't think
that's right.'' She and her sister-in-law had to vacate because
they couldn't afford the Masters rates . . . The 60th PGA Senior
Championship is this week at PGA National GC in North Palm Beach,
Fla., and 20 international players representing 10 countries are in
the field. Hale Irwin is defending champion . . . The PGA of
America will honor Judy Rankin with its First Lady of Golf award .
. . This is the final year the Masters will extend invitations to
players who have won on the PGA Tour in the previous 12 months. The
two new criteria state that the top 40 money-winners on the Tour,
instead of the top 30, will get in and the top 50 players on the
season-ending World Golf Rankings will receive invitations. ``We
wanted the most consistent players over the balance of the year,''
said Will Nicholson, chairman of the competition committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
