<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3694 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXINGNOTEBOOK-BO     04-11 1591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWARD SPEAKS TO SHERIDAN'S TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bob Sheridan was not feeling well but it didn't
matter, even though his idea of not feeling well was like most
everything else about him _ larger than life.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime international broadcasting voice of championship
boxing had suffered his third heart attack two days earlier and had
had an emergency angioplasty performed in a Las Vegas hospital, but
this was Big Fight Night, so he knew where he had to go.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan was going to the place where his heart has been for
more than 25 years. He was going to the fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably wasn't the smartest thing I ever did, but if this was
it, I wanted to get in one more big fight,'' said Sheridan, who was
presented the Sam Taub Award from the Professional Boxing Writers
Association Friday night in New York as its broadcaster of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ram K. Singh, who performed the emergency operation,
protested loudly, but not as loudly as Sheridan, who talks for a
living and thus had the advantage. He also had a 7-foot-2-inch,
500-pound bodyguard named Pancho who made it clear to Singh that
they were going to go to the arena to broadcast a fight between
Evander Holyfield and Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   So off they went, Sheridan, Singh, Pancho, an ambulance, and a
ringside defibrillator just in case. For six endless hours on June
8, 1997, Sheridan called the action of one fight after another as
Singh sat nervously by his side, handing him water and monitoring
his vital signs. This would be the night Tyson bit off a chunk of
Holyfield's ear, but even with blood dripping onto his shoulder,
Holyfield was not in as difficult straits as the 320-pound
heavyweight broadcaster sitting at ringside trying to explain to
the world what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Tyson was disqualified and all hell had broken
loose inside the MGM Grand Garden arena, Pancho cleared a path for
Sheridan from ringside to the ambulance. There Sheridan was given
fluids and taken back to the hospital, where the following morning
Singh did two more angioplasties. Sheridan has not missed a
broadcast since then, and he will work his 616th world title fight
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no name or voice is better known to boxing fans around
the world than Sheridan's, because the Lexington-bred former
baseball star and rodeo bull rider has done more fights in more
places watched by more people than anyone else in history. But if
you've never heard of him, you can be excused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably the most famous boxing announcer in the world not
known in the United States,'' Sheridan joked. ``Maybe that's why
this award meant so much to me. Being recognized by my peers, by
the writers who know boxing best, that's great!''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, so is the Colonel, so called because of his rank in the
Ancient and Honorable Artillery Company of Massachusetts, the
oldest chartered military organization in the Western Hemisphere.
His baritone is as smooth as 30-weight oil and just as valuable to
the engine that keeps boxing running _ television.
</P>
<P>
   When Sheridan calls a fight, which he has done more than 10,000
times since his first radio broadcast on WGBS in Miami of a card
promoted by Chris Dundee in the '60s, you not only know what has
happened but also why it happened, how it happened, and whether
it's likely to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   When Holyfield was destroying Tyson in their first fight,
Showtime's crew kept telling America that Tyson was starting to
come on and Holyfield was ``showing the first signs of fatigue.''
On the international broadcast, Sheridan was telling the rest of
the English-speaking world that Tyson was taking the worst beating
of his life. A round later, Tyson was on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you wish they had erasers on microphones,'' Sheridan
said. ``We all say things we wish we hadn't. But I try to work at
the job, to talk to the fighters and their trainers and gather
information that can help me tell the listener why the things
they're seeing are happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan began doing that not long after leaving the University
of Miami, where he was ``the worst scholarship athlete in the
history of the university.'' Soon he was broadcasting Florida State
League baseball games and within a few years had graduated to doing
play-by-play for University of Miami football and the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   He became a big name in Miami, moving to local television and
doing a daily radio talk show. But it was boxing that he loved, so
he continued to do Dundee's weekly cards, calling more than 5,000
radio fights before his big break came in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a chance to do Ken Buchanan's world title fight against
Frankie Otero for Video Techniques on worldwide television because
all the New York broadcasters were off doing more important
stuff,'' Sheridan said. ``I was about 29 years old and I knew it
was my big break.''
</P>
<P>
   From that fight call, he landed a contract with Video Techniques
and two years later found himself in the Congo, calling one of the
most historic fights in boxing: the Rumble in the Jungle between
Muhammad Ali and George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan did a call so memorable that it was the one used on the
Academy Award-winning documentary about the fight, ``When We Were
Kings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a night that was,'' Sheridan said. ``It was everything I
love about boxing. It was a great fight with two great champions.
It was excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me boxing is the ultimate in sports _ two gladiators trying
to make the other guy's mind go blank for 10 seconds. I love it! I
love the hustle of boxing. All of sports is a hustle, but what I
love about boxing is it's so blatant about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan has been hustling, too, replacing the only broadcaster
in boxing's Hall of Fame, the late Don Dunphy, on closed-circuit
telecasts in the mid-1970s and signing on with Don King, for whom
he has broadcast every title fight since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   How, you might ask, could anyone work 26 years for the bombastic
promoter? For the affable Sheridan, it has been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never talk to Don,'' Sheridan said. ``I interview him at the
start of most of our international broadcasts because KingVision is
his network, but otherwise we seldom talk. I've been loyal to him
for 26 years and he's been loyal to me, but we don't spend a lot of
time chatting. It's a good way to do business with your boss.''
</P>
<P>
   It has paid off well enough that Sheridan recently landed a
contract to work all of US Satellite Broadcasting's cards as well
as King's shows, a schedule so heavy that he has left Massachusetts
for Las Vegas so he can be home with his wife once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hectic schedule, Sheridan knows he has not worked a
day in his life, not even on the day he risked his life to call a
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father told me when I was young to find a job you like and
you'll never have to work a day in your life,'' the 54-year-old
Sheridan recalled. ``That's me. I still love doing this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go to the arena it's exciting. How can you get
tired of this? I've drank in every corner of the world and known
some of the greatest fighters and fight people you could imagine.
If you don't love this job, you don't love living.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield originally was upset at the Boxing Writers Association
for awarding Lennox Lewis an ``undisputed heavyweight
championship'' belt at Friday night's dinner, but after speaking
with the organization's president, Newark Star-Ledger writer Chris
Thorne, Holyfield sent a letter congratulating Lewis and saying he
hoped that belt would be on the line in their rematch along with
the World Boxing Council one Lewis holds and the World Boxing
Association and International Boxing Federation versions Holyfield
still wears . . . Speaking of that rematch, King has asked the
Nevada State Athletic Commission to hold open Nov. 6 and Nov. 13, a
sign that it likely will be in Las Vegas . . . Reform efforts
continued in New York, where state legislators filed a bill
proposing open scoring and another calling for an extra round if a
fight ends in a draw. Gov. George Pataki said he would wait for a
report from the state athletic commission before backing any
changes in the boxing rules. But here's why they never work. The
same week, the New York commission sent former IBF junior
middleweight champion Paul Vaden home to California without a
payday after he'd flown there to fight on a card at Yonkers Raceway
against Edwin Rodriguez, a fighter approved by the commission. When
it came time for the weigh-in, the fighter who showed up was not
the Edwin Rodriguez the commission expected. He was supposed to be
a guy with a 13-3-1 record, but the one who showed up was a kid
from the Bronx who had never won in 13 fights. So the fight was
canceled and Vaden had to fly back to San Diego, about $3,000
poorer in travel expenses. What makes this worse is that the
Rodriguez the commission had approved was on a medical suspension
dating back to March 23, 1998, and could not have fought . . . The
anticipated shakeup of the Duvas' family boxing business went down
last week, but not as expected. Instead of Lou and Dino Duva buying
out the interest of deceased brother Dan Duva's wife, Kathy, Dino
took a leave and Kathy has taken over the day-to-day operation
along with Mike Boorman, Lou's son-in-law and a former publicist
who had left the company a month ago after tiring of the bickering
between the company's warring parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
