<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART ON FAST TRACK TO STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With each race he starts, Tony Stewart is feeling more
and more at home in the NASCAR Winston Cup Series. And with each
race he finishes, it is becoming more and more apparent that the
rookie driver from Rushville, Ind., is the sport's next budding
superstar, certainly its Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Gibbs lured Stewart away from the Indy Racing League _
which had pinned so much of its future on the local sprint car hero
_ the plan was to put him in a Busch Grand National car, get him
acclimated to stock car racing, then have him make the jump to
Winston Cup this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart, much to Gibbs's surprise, has proven to be more
than just a shotgun-riding sidekick to Bobby Labonte, the primary
driver at Gibbs Racing. Stewart, driver of the No. 20 Home Depot
Pontiac, has been a quick study in learning the ropes from Labonte
and is emerging as a driver to be reckoned with after a pair of
front-row starts and sixth-place finishes in the last two races.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see the 20 car with Tony step out there with that all-new
race team,'' Gibbs marveled. ``I think that was one that, if there
was a surprise in here, certainly that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, driver of the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac, has
benefitted from the expansion of the Gibbs Racing stable. With the
proliferation of multicar teams in Winston Cup, it was imperative
that Labonte have a teammate with whom to work, and to generate and
share information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's the one that has the experience, and I know Tony's
constantly asking Bobby questions,'' Gibbs said. ``I think Bobby's
our lead guy that directs things out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about Tony is his attitude. He doesn't have an ego
thing. He is wanting to learn every single thing he can learn. He's
excited about it. He talks to Bobby. He's a willing learner and
looks at it that way. And people like that, who have a lot of
talent, which he does, I think are going to make quick learners.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Winston Cup series resumes with Sunday's Food City 500
at Bristol, Tenn., Labonte will enter a scant 2 points behind Jeff
Burton in the standings (909-907), while Stewart is in 13th place
with 696.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say if you asked almost anybody, here or anywhere in
NASCAR, they would say that has been a real surprise to see Tony
run that well,'' Gibbs said. ``He's only had one wreck, and that
wasn't his fault. Somebody else wrecked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's run extremely well, he's qualified every week on the
first day. We've just been really excited and pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may not all be smooth sailing for Stewart, especially come
May when he'll attempt to drive in both the Indy 500 and the
Coca-Cola 600 the same day. He has been given license by Gibbs to
attempt the Memorial Day double in Indianapolis and Charlotte,
N.C., but Stewart may have to negotiate a legal pothole opened by
John Menard, Stewart's former IRL owner. Menard, who claims to hold
an option on Stewart's contract, apparently has threatened to file
a lawsuit against Gibbs, Stewart, and their Home Depot sponsor to
prevent him from racing for any other team at Indy. But Stewart,
who was under contract to Menard from 1996-98, maintains he is no
longer contractually obligated to Menard and is free to drive for
his own IRL outfit, Tri-Star Motorsports, which he co-owns with
Larry Curry, former team manager for Team Menard. ``I'm confident
I'm free of any obligations to that team,'' Stewart said. ``I'm not
going to guess on what John is going to do. The important thing to
me is I'm confident I've fulfilled all of my obligations there and
I'm looking forward to the future and moving forward with this.'' .
. . Jeff Gordon, the defending Winston Cup champion, will aim for a
record fifth victory in the Food City 500 at Bristol Motor
Speedway. Gordon, who experienced ``the hardest hits I've ever
had'' when he smacked the outside retaining wall in the Primestar
500 at Texas Motor Speedway March 28, appears to be in much better
shape for the season's first short-track event, a grueling
500-miler at Bristol's .533-mile bullring. ``I'm feeling much
better,'' said Gordon. ``My ribs are still a little bit sore, and I
can feel it mostly when I take a deep breath. I feel fortunate that
nothing was cracked, chipped, or broken. I've just been sore. But
I'm ready for Bristol, though. I won't need a relief driver or
anything like that.'' . . . That is not likely to be the case for
Mike Skinner, who broke his right shoulder blade at Texas.
According to Skinner's crew chief, Larry McReynolds, Randy LaJoie
will be on stand-by in case Skinner is unable to go . . . Andy
Santerre, the Cherryfield, Maine, native who won the 1998 Busch
Series Rookie of the Year award, has marked his calendar and plans
to be back behind the wheel of his Busch car June 5 for the MBNA
200 at Dover, Del. Santerre fractured his right leg in an accident
at Daytona in February and had to have surgery. ``I'm feeling
better every day,'' he said. ``But it was rough right after the
accident.'' The slender Santerre said he lost 17 pounds when he
couldn't afford to lose even one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roger Penske tabbed 23-year-old Brazilian driver Tarso Marques
as Al Unser Jr.'s replacement in this weekend's Firestone Firehawk
500 at Motegi, Japan. Marques jumped into the ride after Unser
fractured his right ankle in the first turn of the first lap of the
CART FedEx Series opener at Homestead, Fla., March 21. Unser, who
also sustained a small fracture and a torn ligament in his left
knee, underwent two hours of surgery at Indianapolis Methodist
Hospital and is expected to be back racing in 4-6 weeks, but will
not be able to walk for 8-12 weeks, according to his surgeon, Terry
Trammell . . . After rain postponed the initial Ice Breaker at New
Thompson (Conn.) Speedway at the end of last month, the NASCAR
Featherlite Modified Series will try this weekend to kick off its
season at New Thompson. With two-time defending series champion
Mike Stefanik now racing as a rookie on the NASCAR Craftsman Truck
Series, a new champion will be crowned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
