r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMELESS-SCHOOL-AZR &LR;      04-11 2898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-SCHOOL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION, HOMELESS SCHOOL CLASH OVER CASH, CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Thomas J. Pappas School for homeless children and the
charitable foundation created to support it are scrapping like
schoolyard bullies for control of thousands of dollars in private
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by personal animosity between school officials and top
officers of the Thomas J. Pappas Regional Education Center
Foundation, the conflict over management of donations has left a
$15,000 construction project in limbo. It also indirectly led one
donor to recall a $15,000 grant because the school didn't use the
money quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   School officials are so upset that they say they're willing to
sever the relationship with the foundation and give up the money
rather than give the foundation control of the school budget. The
foundation, meanwhile, has expanded its mission far beyond helping
only Pappas School.
</P>
<P>
   The rift comes at a critical point in the school's young life,
with enrollment doubling over the past year alone. Most of the
school's funding comes from public sources, which are not
endangered, and the school appears to be thriving. However, private
donations totaling about $1.7 million over the past four years have
been tapped to pay for everything from physical education classes
to computer labs.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County Regional School District officials say the
foundation is being stingy by not handing over all the money it has
raised, because the foundation doesn't trust the school district.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation board says it's just showing financial
responsibility and it suggests it has good reason to be concerned:
One school employee admitted embezzling a donation, and other
donations were taken without school permission.
</P>
<P>
   Amid deepening tensions, the foundation board three weeks ago
removed foundation President Ron Cooper as liaison to the school,
hoping to ease personality conflicts between Cooper and top county
school officials, including Art Parker, the district's director of
finance and administration.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, county officials are adamant that they will pass up
future funding from the foundation if its board keeps interfering
in spending decisions and berating school district employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem here has been the attempt, notably by Ron
Cooper, to say, `Here's our money, we want to run the school,' ''
Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Those comments are echoed by county schools Superintendent
Sandra Dowling, Parker's boss, who said she is ready to end the
relationship between the school and the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   County officials were dismayed three weeks ago to learn, from a
reporter, that the foundation quietly expanded its mission last
November so it can raise money for underprivileged children
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The news left county officials chafing over the foundation's
continuing use of the Pappas name, one most Valley residents
associate specifically with the downtown school for homeless kids.
</P>
<P>
   Dowling said she would prefer the foundation change its name,
give Pappas School all money raised in its name, then move on to
new fund-raising horizons without the school. That would allow a
new foundation to be created that would have closer ties to the
school.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs the foundation is thinking along the same lines,
although Cooper said it intends to keep the Pappas name.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 31 letter to ``The Republic,'' the foundation board
said its ``success in raising funds and community attention has
contributed to the school's ability to raise funds independently,
allowing us to move forward in a positive manner and assist other
less fortunate schools and organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides at least agree on this: The Pappas School is
providing a unique and invaluable community service, one whose
importance grows every year, along with the number of homeless
families seeking help in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   As details of the rift have spread, however, both sides fear its
disclosure will cost the Pappas School and the foundation vital
public support.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, the Pappas Foundation has raised $1,725,752 in cash
and in-kind donations, according to Kristi Donaldson, the
foundation's lone paid staff member. Pledged donations total
$225,166 more, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, a Phoenix businessman who has been the foundation
board's unpaid president since 1996, was taken aback by the school
district's increasingly open criticism, saying board members have
worked hard to help the school in recent years. The foundation's
sole reason for being, according to its articles of incorporation,
had been to support the school.
</P>
<P>
   But last November, Cooper and board members amended those
articles with the Arizona Corporation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment expands the foundation's funding horizons to
``other poor, distressed, underprivileged or homeless children from
preschool through high school in the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   During initial interviews on the subject in mid-March,
foundation board members said they were considering how to advise
donors of the change in focus. Three weeks ago, a letter went out.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Don Zavala, an attorney, said it informs donors
that all money raised before April 1 will be used ``only for Pappas
School.'' Money raised strictly for Pappas will be held in a
separate account, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Donaldson, $847,589 _ slightly less than half of
the $1.7 million reportedly raised by the foundation since 1996 _
has been given to the Pappas School in cash or donated goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
   However, about $190,000 worth of goods and services reported as
contributed through the foundation was, in fact, given directly to
the school by donors. Although often arranged through the
foundation, those donations were not reported to the Internal
Revenue Service as charitable contributions to the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said a preliminary accounting indicates $726,472 in
cash and investments remains in foundation checking, savings,
investment and equity accounts.
</P>
<P>
   She said $151,691 _ or over 8 percent of the total raised since
1996 _ has paid for fund-raising, administration and overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising alone has been a relatively small cost, amounting
to about 5 percent of total contributions, according to the
foundation's 1997 report to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Administrative costs have included one staff person's salary,
which the foundation would not disclose.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Philanthropic Advisory Service, which offers
guidelines by which donors may judge charities, suggests reasonable
fund-raising and administrative costs should not exceed half the
total income of an organization. It also suggests that at least
half of total income should be applied to program activities.
</P>
<P>
   By those standards, the four-year financial history prepared by
the foundation shows that its fund-raising expenses are well in
line, but it is not donating at least half its total income to
program activities. Its report to the IRS for 1997 alone showed
that only about 45 percent of the direct contributions went to
program services, falling slightly short of the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Although school district officials don't have a bone to pick
with the foundation's overhead or fund-raising costs, they do
object to the process the foundation established to dole out money
to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Dowling and Parker repeatedly complained in recent interviews
about having to apply for funding and the foundation's tight-fisted
distribution methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not going to trust us, then we shouldn't be doing
business,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation board members say they are simply doing what they
should: making sure money is used precisely as donors intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question the school district would like to have
funds without all the strings attached and not to have to go into
some planning process,'' said David Hansen, an Arizona Public
Service executive and foundation board member who replaced Cooper
as liaison to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little bit more diligent in the process,'' Hansen
said. ``They kind of resent some of those controls. So that may
foster some bad feelings and, maybe, the impression that we want to
be more involved in their business than we really do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to make sure that funds are being used at the
right time, in the right place, for the right purpose, in the best
interest of the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pappas School has carved a permanent spot in the hearts of
many Valley residents because it uniquely addresses three popular
public concerns: children, schools and the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Starting nearly a decade ago as a ragtag program housed at local
churches, the Pappas School found a permanent home last school year
at 355 N. Fifth Ave., Phoenix, where a new campus was opened by the
Maricopa County Regional School District. Built with a bond-backed
loan, the campus now serves kindergarten through Grade 5. Grades 6
through 9 are housed at nearby First Presbyterian Church.
</P>
<P>
   It's a learning center, a safe haven, a feeding station and a
clearinghouse for social services that often go undelivered to
children with no permanent address.
</P>
<P>
   But it is only one part of a network of county alternative
schools serving children overlooked by regular school districts _
kids who were expelled, homeless children, pregnant teens and
residents of the northern tip of the Gila River Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the foundation board's concern is that money intended
for Pappas not be mingled with money headed to other county
alternative schools.
</P>
<P>
   It is also worried about other irregularities. A school employee
was fired last year after admitting embezzling a $1,046.75 donation
check to the foundation, according to school officials. The
foundation also complains that $1,900 in checks sent to the
foundation via the school were cashed by the school without
foundation authority. The school is in the process of reimbursing
the funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Pappas Foundation was incorporated in late 1995 by Nancy
Haas, an Arizona State University education professor, to raise
money to equip the new school once it was built.
</P>
<P>
   It was intended to pay for things that the school could not
afford or spend public money on.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, thousands of dollars in cash, goods and services
have been donated both to the school and to the foundation. The
school's enrollment has doubled to between 670 and 680 in the past
year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Its sudden growth has prompted the school to receive more than
its usual share of specially allocated growth funds from the state.
But that money won't always be there, Parker said, and supplemental
funds from private sources have always been a part of the mix to
improve programs and facilities at Pappas.
</P>
<P>
   Broad public interest in the plight of homeless children
prompted not only bountiful donations to the foundation but a
mountain of goods _ from blankets to computers _ given directly to
the school.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the school recently bought several trailers to
house the donations, then set up a system to sort and store them.
The cost: about $50,000. Parker says the foundation offered no
help.
</P>
<P>
   The wealth of donations to both the foundation and the school is
due largely to the positive publicity the school has always
enjoyed. Attracting both local and national attention, Pappas
School also spurred a tug of war of sorts between Cooper and
Dowling over who deserves credit for its success _ the county or
the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing friction prompted Dowling to name Parker her point
man in dealing with the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that if there was a personality problem with me, I
wasn't going to let it interfere with Pappas or the fund-raising
for the kids, so I turned it over to Art about eight or nine months
ago,'' Dowling said. ``He's been dealing with it ever since, and
it's been horror stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, while guarded in his comments about Dowling, had this to
say: ``I'm not the only one who's been in Sandra's way _ I'm the
flavor of the month. Sandra's a kind of divide-and-conquer
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper also called attention to a lengthy and unflattering 1997
story about Dowling that appeared in the local weekly ``New
Times.''``'' The article questioned Dowling's status as the lone
board member for the regional school district, saying her unchecked
power led to abuses, poor management and nepotism.
</P>
<P>
   The backdrop of mutual mistrust led the foundation board three
weeks ago to remove Cooper as its liaison with the school district,
replacing him with Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the effort to minimize personality conflicts, Parker
said fundamental differences remain. The county, he said, can't
live with foundation requirements for specific written and oral
funding requests. Nor does it like its policy of requiring the
district to pay for goods and services in advance, using district
funds that are later reimbursed by the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bookkeeping nightmare,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the foundation often wants the school district to
spend its own money on foundation-backed items, then submit
receipts for reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm subsidizing the foundation until they get around to paying
me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dowling said she would rather pass up future funding than fight
such budget wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not pay for me to have full-time people running around
on staff trying to figure out how to work the system so they can
get the foundation to give them what they need,'' Dowling said. ``I
said, `Just forget it. Don't ask for anything, we'll find another
way to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The result: For the past several months, Parker has not asked
for any specific funding from the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The school's capital and operating costs are paid by a
combination of state funding, county taxes and whatever private
donations roll in. Operating costs last year were roughly $1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation board members generally have required written and
oral funding requests from the school, including details on
precisely how donated money will be spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have run this like you run a business,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the standoff, donors sometimes have to wait a
long time to see their money put to use.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one corporate donor put up more than $20,000 for
school operations and supplies, giving the money to the foundation
to ensure full tax deductibility. The foundation, as a tax-exempt
organization, can offer donors greater tax benefits than if the
money is given directly to the school.
</P>
<P>
   The school district was told by the foundation that it needed to
document how the money would be used before a cent would be turned
over. The district refused, complaining that it would not create
special budgets to accommodate the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after several weeks of back-and-forth charges, a
check for $22,500 arrived in Parker's mail _ without any paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   The same argument surrounds funds that ostensibly would be used
to build shade areas on the Pappas school playground. The project
would cost roughly $15,000, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   A donor has pledged money for the project through the
foundation, but the foundation wants detailed plans from the school
before it accepts the money, according to Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the school sent several proposed bids to the
foundation. Foundation board members say they have seen no plans,
and they won't free up any money as long as there is no detailed
accounting from the school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``What might be unique about our situation _ as opposed to other
non-profits _ is . . . we're supporting a quasi-governmental agency
here that has a budget for their light bill, their salaries, the
operation of the school,'' said foundation board member Brenda
Armour, a Sears National Bank executive. ``We want to ensure that
the donated funds are being used for appropriate purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen was more direct, criticizing the school's unwillingness
to work closely with the foundation on mutually agreeable short-
and long-term budget plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd fire me if I ran the business that way,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more than $700,000 sits in the foundation's savings,
checking, investment and equity accounts. Though district officials
say it should be put to use, foundation board members see no danger
in sitting on the nest egg if the school isn't willing to come up
with specific spending plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to be able to help the school not only this month, but
next month, the following month, the following year, two years from
now,'' Zavala said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one donor didn't think banking his donation was such a
good idea. Jonathan Marshall, founder of the Marshall Fund of
Arizona, withdrew a $15,000 pledge for school counseling programs
after the first $7,500 sat idle for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it wasn't the foundation's fault. The foundation
gave the school the money five months after the donation arrived,
but the school district then had trouble hiring a part-time
counselor. The money was unused.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, unsure where the problem was, simply decided to get
his money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them, if you can straighten your problems out, we'll
be happy to reconsider in the future because we still think the
program is good,'' Marshall said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
