<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER APPEARS TO LACKING SOME BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Environmental Alert. The Tiger is an endangered
species in America.
</P>
<P>
   The Tiger must be saved. Quick, spare no expense. Find that
Tiger who used to roam the greensward of America a mere year or two
ago. The species seems to be on the way to extinction, a quick
extinction, too, the Tiger's sharp bite smoothed by fame,
expectations, hype, and the sheer weight of carrying an entire
sport on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Where is that Tiger who used to shoot a 67 and say, ``I didn't
have my A-game?'' Where is that Tiger who used to snarl at par 5s,
ripping that orange Tiger-faced cover off his driver before booming
his drive over any and all bunkers. Now, Tiger Woods pulls out his
2-iron and lays up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens, happens,'' the man who used to be Tiger
Woods said Saturday after he struck the golf ball from tee to green
as well as any human can strike a golf ball. ``Our objective right
now is to get to the point where we can legitimately contend with
nine holes to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are words Mark O'Meara might say. Those are words David
Duval might utter. Those are words any number of good golfers might
mouth if they had shot a nice, safe, sound, and comfortable
2-under-par round of 70 on a Saturday at the Masters and were
within shouting distance of the leaders. Not words the man who used
to be Tiger Woods would say, especially when his round could have
been 65 or 66.
</P>
<P>
   Especially after this: Woods hit 17 of 18 greens Saturday, and
on the one he missed, the seventh, he was on the fringe by a foot.
Woods hit 11 of 14 fairways Saturday and the three fairways he
missed, he missed by a foot or 2 or 3, his ball sitting up nicely
in the pseudo-rough.
</P>
<P>
   But Tiger Woods could not putt Saturday. He had an astonishing
36 putts, one three-putt green, and a one-putt green, the 16 others
two putts each. The old Tiger Woods would have been fuming, smoke
billowing from his ears at this chance puttered away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more comfortable _ by far _ with my putting (Saturday,
compared to the first two rounds),'' said the man who used to be
Tiger Woods. ``I'm starting to get used to the slower speed (of the
greens). I've left a lot of putts short this week. I've been here
four years now, this is my fifth year and I'm used to seeing the
putts a little faster. Putts that I've run by the hole in the past,
I'm leaving them short.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Faxon could have given that reply. Larry Mize, too. But if
the golfer who used to be Tiger Woods twice left makeable _ and
straight uphill, at that _ birdie putts short at the Masters, as
Woods did Saturday on the sixth and 16th holes, the Tiger would
have been snarling. Now, this Tiger Woods has explanations.
</P>
<P>
   Told his round could have been four to five shots better, if
only a few of his makeable first putts had dropped, Woods agreed,
``Yeah, easily.'' But he then added, ``Just as it could have been
four to five strokes worse (Friday), too. It all evens out in the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   When? Next month? Where? In the Quad-Cities Open?
</P>
<P>
   This new Tiger Woods has donned a pleasant mask. It's as if the
sports psychobabblers have gotten to him, telling him everything is
OK just as long as he thinks it's OK.
</P>
<P>
   Two examples: On Friday, Woods hit a horrible tee shot on the
par-3 12th, his ball bungee-jumping up and down into Rae's Creek.
Woods either misclubbed badly or misswung terribly, but he chose a
safe-to-the-psyche explanation, that ``I hit it perfect'' but the
wind ballooned his ball into disaster.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, when Woods needed eight strokes to complete his
horticultural tour of the par-5 eighth hole, again he was kind to
his psyche. Despite the eight swings, Woods argued, he had hit
several good shots.
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone imagine the former Tiger Woods distorting reality so
flagrantly?
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all can sympathize with Woods. He is barely into his
third year as a pro, into his second year as the cause of a social
revolution _ Saturday, just as two years ago, waiters flocked out
of the Augusta National clubhouse just as Woods was about to tee it
up on the first hole, the occasion too momentous to miss for black
fans everywhere _ and he has had so much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm in good shape,'' Woods replied when asked about his
chances Sunday. ``Anybody who'll be 4 or 5 under par with nine
holes to go will be right there in the ballgame. Anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but only if the Tiger can be saved from extinction, only
if the old Tiger can be found, only if Tiger Woods drops this new
bland mask and snarls once again.
</P>
<P>
   It was near excruciating to watch how virtually perfect Woods
was from tee to green Saturday, and then how poorly he putted,
missing all but two of his 17 chances to lower his score. It was
even worse to listen to this new Tiger say he really hadn't putted
that poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I hit a lot of good putts,'' said Woods, ``but it
was just that my feel was just a little off. I was leaving them a
little short on the low side, or I burned a couple on the top side.
It's just the matter of getting the right speed.''
</P>
<P>
   And then these words, ``You know you've just to got hang in
there. You've just got to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   America's last and only Tiger may already be extinct if words
like that are repeated. So, it is more than urgent. The old Tiger
must be found. Quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
