<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-LIGHTNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS DEFUSE LIGHTNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Goodbye and good riddance.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins couldn't wait to put their back-to-back series with
the Tampa Bay Lightning behind them. After a long battle to earn a
playoff berth that ended last Wednesday with a victory over
Florida, the Bruins were just dreadful against the Lightning in
Tampa, Fla., the following night. They were shut out and couldn't
do anything right.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Tampa Bay was in town, and after a sluggish start, the
Bruins kicked it into high gear in the final two periods and earned
a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The club breathed a big sigh of relief. Now the Bruins have four
days off to nurse many nagging injuries and then will play three
games in four nights against contending teams to wind up the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't analyze these last two games,'' said coach Pat Burns,
who would just as soon burn the videotape. ``These were probably
the worst two games we've played in God knows when and these are
tough games to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins picked up where they left off, falling behind, 1-0,
on a goal by center Chris Gratton at 8:10 of the first period. Rob
Tallas, who was the hard-luck loser Thursday, looked as if he might
get no support again.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston came back at 14:19 on the power play with Steve
Heinze potting his 22d to tie it. Heinze also had two assists.
Defenseman Pavel Kubina gave the Lightning back the lead at 18:52
with his eighth. In the second period, center Joe Thornton picked
up goal No. 15 on the power play to pull Boston even again at 2:07.
It was Anson Carter who tallied the winner, his 22d, scoring at
7:43 of the third period. Carter, who had a hat trick Wednesday
against Florida, took the puck from Thornton and fired a shot past
goalie Corey Schwab from low in the slot.
</P>
<P>
   The game took a turn for the weird at 12:40 with the Lightning
on a power play. Darcy Tucker was called for a high stick for
clipping Ray Bourque in the mouth. Carter was then called for an
illegal stick. Tampa players Rob Zamuner and Mike Sillinger spotted
it and pointed it out to coach Jacques Demers. Referee Kerry Fraser
measured Carter's stick and found that the blade was wider than the
3 inches allowed and assessed a minor penalty. What was odd was the
timing. The penalties ended up being coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't amount to anything,'' said Bourque. ``He was too
smart for his own good. All he had to do was wait five seconds and
let that go by and he would've had an odd-man situation. It worked
out all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said 90 percent of all sticks in the NHL are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we learned something,'' said Burns. ``I think the players
learned something. It's something to be aware of in the playoffs. I
hope I don't have to start measuring hockey sticks now before every
game. I have enough to worry about. The onus is the player. We'll
have to take a little bit of money out of A.C.'s pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter didn't know why he was singled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was in a lot of guys' faces early in the game, maybe
they wanted to make me pay for it,'' said Carter. ``I don't really
know. It could've been anybody. I saw Petr Svoboda come over and
take a glance at my stick. I tried to hide it just in case because
I wasn't really sure what he was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing puzzled him as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they'd gain something more out of it than they
did,'' said Carter. ``I was really wondering what they were
thinking. I don't know if they were trying to get under Burnsie's
skin. I don't know if Burnsie and Demers have a little French
rivalry going or what.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns waved off the measurement (``That's Jacques,'' he said)
and said he's just glad it resulted in a victory after such a
letdown Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had the pedal to the metal for the last two months,'' he
said. ``It's been a playoff game every single night. Now you have a
sigh of relief because you clinch in Florida and it's tough for the
players and it's tough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said he's just glad the Lightning are out of here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get rid of these guys after the other night,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
