<HEADLINE>
HOT DAY FOR PATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ In the calm and almost summerlike heat that
turned Saturday's third round of the 63d Masters into a scorer's
delight at Augusta National GC, Steve Pate left the first tee at
11:40 a.m. and must have sent shivers up the spines of the leaders
as he played one of the tournament's heroic stretches of golf to
set up what could very well be one of its finest hours.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the par-4 seventh, Pate ran off a remarkable record
stretch of seven consecutive birdies, punctuated by a 50-foot
birdie putt on the 10th, to soar from a tie for 28th place to a tie
for third as Moving Day became Stagnation Day in conditions that
were ideal. ``I have no explanation for what happened out there,''
said Pate. ``People started appearing out of the trees like Big
Foot.''
</P>
<P>
   When he finished his early round at 5-under-par 65_211, it
appeared he had merely shot himself into contention entering
Sunday's final round. Instead, he ended up just two shots behind
leader and 1994 champion Jose Maria Olazabal. This was an afternoon
when Greg Norman lost a ball in the azaleas on the 12th hole; when
Davis Love, who was leading at the time, wound up in water on the
15th and took a double bogey; and when Lee Janzen went bogey-bogey
on the 15th and 16th.
</P>
<P>
   The final accounting showed Olazabal (73_209) rising to the
occasion when it mattered for the second straight round to stand on
the threshold of making it back all the way after he sat out
virtually an entire year with what was originally diagnosed as a
foot injury but turned into a back ailment that threatened his
career. Norman, who holed a sizable putt for a bogey on the 12th,
floated a 9-iron out of the rough on the 18th to set up a 4-foot
birdie putt and second place at 71_210.
</P>
<P>
   Pate, who won the final PGA tournament at Pleasant Valley CC in
Sutton last summer, wound up tied with Love (70) as the sifting and
sorting process became a story of survival. Paraguayan Carlos
Franco (68) birdied the par-5 13th and 15th holes and was in a tie
with Ernie Els (69), Bob Estes (69), and Janzen (73) at 212.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, who saved par out of the left rough on the 18th,
salted away his lead with a birdie on the 15th. Norman, who had to
return to the tee on the 12th, ended up holing a 22-foot putt for
bogey. Then he had to come to grips with a second shot on No. 13
that ended up in a divot. ``I'll give 500 bucks if anyone can go
find that ball,'' said Norman. ``I hit the same shot the second
time. I never doubted I was going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, who started the round in the lead, bogeyed the third
and sixth holes and made the turn in 38. He had pars until the
15th, which has become a threatening hole with its rock-hard green,
and made the only birdie of his round when he hit a 3-iron second
shot into the green. ``It was a tough day out there,'' said the
Spaniard. ``I couldn't make any putts out there, which is the exact
opposite of yesterday, when I made everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate's run of birdies started at the seventh hole, where he hit
a 3-wood within 8 feet of the pin. He then birdied the eighth
(pitching wedge, 20 feet), ninth (9-iron, 1 1/2 feet), 10th
(6-iron, 50 feet), 11th (wedge, 20 feet), 12th (8-iron, 1 foot),
and 13th (lob wedge, 7 feet). The 12th? ``Just a shock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His bogey on the 17th, when he left a 9-iron short and took
three putts, was the only blemish in the round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today it just seemed easy,'' said Pate. ``Everything I was
doing was turning out well. It was probably the easiest stretch of
holes I've played all week. The first 36 holes I played well and
didn't get anything out of it, and that seemed harder than watching
the balls dive in the holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Love, who has been in contention in this tournament in the past
but has won just one major, the 1997 PGA Championship, seized the
lead when he made a 25-foot birdie putt on the 13th. Then came the
15th, when an errant drive forced him to lay up. ``That was the
mistake,'' said Love. ``I drove left, laid up, and the ball was
sitting down a little.'' His third shot went into the water, and he
wound up two-putting for a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an interesting day,'' said Love. ``I rode the roller
coaster of emotion. I just had a great, solid day all day. It's
nice to be this close.''
</P>
<P>
   What transpired Saturday didn't surprise Love. ``It's Masters
Saturday,'' he said. ``It's conditions. There were some very, very
hard greens. Tomorrow? You never know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
