<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFT GUTHRIE NOW ALL RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GUTHRIE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The man who may be the missing link in
the Red Sox bullpen has a missing rib.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep it at home,'' Mark Guthrie said. ``John Hudek wears his
on a necklace, but he's a little crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what it looks like? Just like one of those ribs you
eat in a restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie can make light of it now, but in 1993, when doctors
removed the top rib on Guthrie's left side, the lefthanded reliever
could not be certain he would pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   The rib had to come out in order to relieve a 7-inch blood clot
that had developed in the large vein that supplied blood to
Guthrie's left arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happened to a few relievers,'' Guthrie said, citing the
Reds' Hudek, among others. ``The muscles in your shoulder get large
from pitching. My first rib was too big, and the rib and muscles
were squeezing the vein, impinging the flow of blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie, then with the Twins, was pitching against the Indians
when his arm suddenly went numb. Somehow, he was able to register
four more outs, but when he returned to the clubhouse after the
game and took off his uniform jersey, his arm was swollen, blue
from his shoulder to his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he'd just need some antiflammatory medication, but
the gravity of the situation was brought home to him the next
morning, when he awoke and found that his skin had turned black in
a large area extending from his collarbone to his shoulder and down
his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie reached for the phone and called the Twins' doctor. For
four days, doctors pumped medication into his arm in an attempt to
dissolve the clot. ``They called it liquid gold, because it was so
expensive,'' Guthrie told reporters afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Howard Saylor, a vascular specialist in Minneapolis,
performed the surgery and removed most of Guthrie's top left rib.
``I guess I didn't really think about how serious the operation
was,'' Guthrie said.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part was still to come. It would take months for
Guthrie to regain the strength in his shoulder. ``Your first rib
may not seem that important,'' he said, ``but because of the way
your skeletal structure works, they warned me that I could have
problems in other parts of my body, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Galica, the therapist who supervised Guthrie's
rehabilitation, told the St. Paul Pioneer Press that the muscles in
Guthrie's left arm were so weak he could not resist the pressure
applied by a single finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark would extend his left arm and I could put a finger on the
back of his hand and push it down,'' Galica said. ``Two months
later, I would have to lean on his arm with force to push it down.
Mark has worked very hard to get his strength back.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie returned to the Twins the following season, but he did
not pitch well, going 4-2 with a 6.14 ERA in 50 appearances. The
Twins traded him to the Dodgers in mid-1995, in a deal for
infielder Ron Coomer and two minor league pitchers, and Guthrie
appeared in 205 games for the Dodgers until signing a two-year,
$3.2 million free agent contract with Boston this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie's best pitch is a split-fingered fastball, though scouts
here say he doesn't throw it with the velocity he did in the past.
Both his splitter and his sinker are in the mid-80s, which means he
doesn't change speeds quite as effectively as is ideal.
</P>
<P>
   But in his first two appearances for the Sox, the 33-year-old
fit the profile of exactly what the Sox were seeking, an effective
lefthanded specialist. He relieved Bret Saberhagen in a 4-0 game in
Kansas City and breezed through a 1-2-3 seventh inning, striking
out two. Then, Friday night against Tampa Bay, he relieved Mark
Portugal with two on and one out and needed just one pitch to
induce Wade Boggs to hit into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to make a good impression,'' he said. ``Glad
to get the first one out of the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
