<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRWNDALE-LADN-(SL     04-11 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWNDALE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUMMINGS LIKES BEING HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Saturday was the beginning of what Val
Cummings hopes is the road to the American Race Trucks regional
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The West Covina resident, who returned to oval-track racing two
years ago after a 19-year hiatus, won the championship in 1997 and
finished a strong third in 1998. Now, helped by the close proximity
of Irwindale Speedway, he's ready to etch his name on the regional
trophy for the second time in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got a good shot at it,'' said Cummings, who
Saturday piloted his No. 1 Chevrolet Truck for the first time on
Irwindale Speedway's half-mile oval. ``I won the (American) Truck
championship in 1997, my first year out. We finished third last
year. And we'll see what happens this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good track. The series is good with a bunch of nice
guys, and this year we won't have much traveling to do. The first
year we traveled as much as 10,000 miles. (Irwindale Speedway) is
real nice because I'm only five miles away.''
</P>
<P>
   Cummings, who competed at the old Speedway 605, raced quarter
midgets in the 1960s and 1970s. He retired 19 years ago and
returned in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids were older and I had some extra money,'' Cummings said
of why he pondered a return to his first love. ``Plus, I could
afford to do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Nice night: Saturday was a strong night for Rick Harbaugh.
The Santa Fe Springs resident paced the American Race Trucks field
with a fast lap of 85.71 mph during qualifying, then, despite
starting in the back row of an inverted field, won the American
Race Trucks trophy dash race. He beat John Hulsebosch to the line
of the six-lap sprint by 1.394 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   __ NASCAR sportsman update: Saturday concluded the second night
drivers in the NASCAR sportsman classes could compete for both the
track- and regional-season championships in the respective classes.
</P>
<P>
   Gerrit Cromsigt has the early lead for the track championship in
Late Model after capturing his second victory here in as many weeks
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty McDonald, who finished second to Cromsigt last week,
believes the race to the Irwindale Speedway season championship in
the division is wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a good car, a great team and a good crew chief,''
said McDonald, a Simi Valley resident. ``It's hard to say who has
an advantage. I seen a lot of guys who have gone fast in the past,
continue to go fast. We'll just have to wait and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Upcoming: The NASCAR Super Late Model regional series, which
made it's second of 21 stops at Irwindale Speedway on Saturday,
returns to the twin ring next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Late Models, the same type of cars that launched the
careers of NASCAR Winston Cup star Bobby Labonte and 1998 NASCAR
Busch Grand National champion Dale Earnhardt Jr., highlight Friday
night's event that also includes the third Late Model race and
Super Stocks and Mini Stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Grand American Modifieds, which made their second appearance
this past Friday, return Saturday, April 17 as part of a combined
NASCAR/USAC show that includes Midgets and Quarter-Midgets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
