<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3711 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COLLINS-DRAFT-HNS     04-11 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLLINS-DRAFT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Collins hopes NFL team sees his love for game, gives him a chance
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cecil ``the Diesel'' Collins is a legend in Louisiana. Legendary
for one glimpse of almost unparalleled greatness at LSU.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary for failing drug tests, being arrested twice and
getting kicked out of two colleges.
</P>
<P>
   In next weekend's NFL draft, Collins won't be the first or
second running back selected. He might not even be third or fourth.
But general managers, coaches, personnel directors and scouts agree
no prospect is more intriguing than Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this,'' Collins says with a huge grin. ``There can't be
any back hungrier than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins isn't just hungry _ he's starved for football. Once he's
drafted, he has a chance to be a model case for a player who turned
around his life and fulfilled his enormous potential. Or he can go
down as a blown pick, a con artist who wasted the kind of God-given
talent many scouts call extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've missed the game so much, too much,'' Collins says. ``It's
been so long since I've played. I'm trying to prove I'm not a bad
person, that I'm a good person who can do all the right things on
and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to church and trying to get back with the Lord. I'm
trying to get my life straight. I'm looking forward to having an
opportunity to take care of my family. I want to be a role model.''
</P>
<P>
   Cecil the Diesel a role model?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a role model for kids, to show them I got
everything straightened out, that I worked hard and came back from
a lot of adversity,'' Collins says.
</P>
<P>
   And Collins knows about adversity. Like a hurricane, Collins
blew through Baton Rouge in a flash, and then he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   At Leesville High School, Collins became the second-leading
rusher in Louisiana history. In 1996 at LSU, he was a Proposition
48 casualty. He began the 1997 season on the bench behind Kevin
Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   When Faulk was injured, fans in football-mad Baton Rouge got
another look at the Diesel. In his first appearance for the Tigers,
Collins carried 22 times for 172 yards against Mississippi State.
In the next game against Auburn, he carried 27 times for 232 yards.
He followed those Southeastern Conference games with 179 yards
against Akron.
</P>
<P>
   But one week later at Vanderbilt, the Diesel ran out of fuel. On
his third carry, Collins suffered a fractured fibula and ligament
damage in his ankle. His season was over, but his rsum showed 583
yards rushing on 69 carries, an incredible 8.4-yard average per
carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was tough,'' Collins says. ``While I had it going, it was
a lot of fun. It was fun to get that opportunity to play at that
level, especially playing in the SEC. It was great.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, hey, things happen to everybody, all types of things.
Now, I'm ready for better things.''
</P>
<P>
   After undergoing surgery on his leg and ankle, Collins began the
long and arduous rehabilitation period. In the summer of 1998, his
life and his football career began to unravel, and he had no one to
blame but himself.
</P>
<P>
   In separate incidents in June and July, he was arrested twice.
He was indicted on two counts each of unauthorized entry and simple
battery. He pleaded guilty. Last week, a judge suspended his
sentence, and Collins was given supervised probation for four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Because Collins had flunked three drug tests at LSU for smoking
marijuana, he was kicked off the team. He transferred to McNeese
State and reported overweight and out of shape. In two games last
season, he rushed for 46 yards on 12 carries against Southeast
Oklahoma and 71 yards on 17 carries against Northern Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a drug test was ordered, and he failed for smoking
marijuana. Because it was a violation of his probation, Collins
spent 27 days in East Baton Rouge Parish Prison and two months in a
halfway house.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those things happened, but I can't dwell on them,''
Collins says. ``It was bad, but I turned into a man. I just got
through it. You've got to move on with your life. I've tried to
correct everything and do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I sat down and analyzed everything. Not only did I
harm myself, but I harmed my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins sought the counsel of his father, James, a prison
officer in Richmond. He thought about his two children _ daughter
Zakei, 2, and son Brandon, 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did will affect my children, too,'' he says. ``They
look up to me. I want them to respect their father. Right now, I'm
feeling good about myself and my family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably stronger because of what's happened to me, but
I've always been a positive person. It's changed me for sure, but
I'm not the first person who's made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins laughs a lot. He's comfortable answering uncomfortable
questions. His agent, Jimmy Sexton, has prepared him well for his
indoctrination into the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   At the Indianapolis scouting combine, Collins, 22, was 5-8{ and
209 pounds. On a sore hamstring, he ran the 40-yard dash in 4.45
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams know everything about Collins on and off the field. He
has spent the last three months trying to tell them what's in his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know where I've been,'' Collins says. ``I've been in
hiding. They know the things that went on in my life. But everybody
goes through changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm back on the scene now. It's been a while since I've played
football, but, hey, I'm an athlete. I don't think it's going to be
tough to be ready. I'm in shape right now. Once I get back on the
field, I think things will go good. I'm just waiting for that
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Randy Moss' success with the Vikings last season should
benefit Collins. Like Collins, Moss had a checkered past. The team
that drafts Collins can remind the fans and media what happened to
Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give him a lot of credit because of the problems he had
going into the draft,'' Collins says. ``A lot of people were
doubting him. He dropped down in the first round. Then he proved
everybody wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think I'm going to prove everybody wrong.
Fortunately, you're allowed to get a second chance in life. That's
what Moss got. Right now, that's what I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins isn't concerned about where he will be drafted. Miami
loves him. Coach Jimmy Johnson is secure enough to draft Collins
and withstand criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really optimistic, but I'm not expecting the worst,
either,'' Collins says. ``I'm kind of in between. I'm just lucky to
get the opportunity. But I think the team that takes me is going to
be lucky, too. Hey, even if I don't get drafted, I'm going to make
the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Collins is asked where he thinks he would be rated if he
hadn't had the off-the-field problems, he hesitates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the future would have held,'' he says.
``Those things just happened at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's a mystery. Just like the game's a mystery. I'm
a strong person, but I feel like I'm a mystery to them (teams). I
just look them in the eye, tell them the truth and try to explain
what's going on in my life and which direction I'm headed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, Collins is headed up. University of Texas Heisman
Trophy winner Ricky Williams will be the first back selected. Miami
underclassman Edgerrin James will be the second. Collins or Faulk,
his former LSU teammate, could be third.
</P>
<P>
   Collins doesn't think he should take a back seat to any back,
including Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say he's any better than me, but I'm not
going to say I'm better than him,'' Collins says. ``I like Ricky. I
like his style. He's a great player. I think we have a similar
style of running downhill. By that, I mean I ain't no jitterbug. I
just run downhill and try to put the ball in the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   If Collins doesn't go early in the draft, he can draw
inspiration from Terrell Davis, Jamal Anderson and Dorsey Levens,
three of the NFL's best backs _ all of whom were drafted after the
fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody respected them because they didn't do too much in
college,'' Collins says. ``They weren't expected to do much in the
NFL. It's not where you get drafted. It's what you do when you get
there. If you've got heart and your mind's right, you can be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins insists he has heart, and he claims his mind's right.
Many of his fans in Louisiana hope he will succeed, but his critics
wait for him to fail. Only time will tell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
