<DOCNO> NYT19990411.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3712 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-DRAFT-HN     04-11 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-DRAFT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Three factors jeopardize Williams' status as top pick
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
It might not be the same as going from a penthouse to an outhouse
or even seeing your fluffy French pastry turn into a pop tart, but
it hurts.
</P>
<P>
   After a yearlong worship service in his honor, Ricky Williams is
finding out he is not the perfect football player after all, or at
least that is what some NFL teams are trying to tell him.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time recently when the University of Texas running
back was considered the best college football player in the
country. Even his stiffest competition for the subjective honor _
Tim Couch, Cade McNown, Michael Bishop and others _ proclaimed the
NCAA's all-time leading rusher to be just that.
</P>
<P>
   But a few weeks ago there were rumblings from the front offices
in Cleveland, Philadelphia, Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Washington
that Williams might be the best college football player available
for the 1999 NFL draft, but he might not be the best one available
for those teams.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to prove there is no one better, Williams held an open
house in San Diego on Monday and then went on a door-to-door sales
trip in hopes of preventing a slide from the top of the NFL draft
board.
</P>
<P>
   In the short span of three days, Williams threw dirt on the
floor and plugged in his vacuum cleaner in St. Louis, New Orleans,
Washington, Philadelphia, Cleveland and Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allowed a 21-year-old young man to meet football people he
would have not otherwise had a chance to meet,'' said Leland Hardy,
Williams' agent. ``It was a chance for building relationships with
owners, general managers and coaches in a sport where he is going
to be a prominent player.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is in little danger of coming down with the dreaded
``draft-day slippage.'' You know, sitting around an embarrassingly
long time April 17 _ a la Thurman Thomas, Darren Lewis or Randy
Moss _ waiting for his name to be called.
</P>
<P>
   No, he almost assuredly will go in the first six picks, but he
believes he should be No. 1. Of course, he thought that before the
NFL started to review his rsum. There have even been reports some
teams are concerned because he has shorter arms and smaller hands
than normal, which might lead to fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the top guys are scrutinized the most to try to find
out the kinks in their armor,'' Williams said as he toured the
country this week. ``And I understand that they're investing a lot
of money in players like myself so it's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way things are, if it's not one thing it's going
to be something else. So, I'm not worried about it. I'm sure if it
wasn't if I had bigger hands then it would be something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the questions, some will do whatever it takes to get
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans has stated it would trade its entire 1999 draft
allotment, including the 12th pick of the first round, to move up
high enough to choose Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone thought Williams would be the top pick until
three postseason events affected his stock _ Couch escapes,
Williams inflates, Master P negotiates. Those three factors
introduced a question to the foregone conclusion Williams would be
the first player taken.
</P>
<P>
   That honor might well go to Couch or Oregon's Akili Smith. The
first three draft picks might be quarterbacks for the first time
since 1971, when Jim Plunkett, Archie Manning and Dan Pastorini
went 1-2-3.
</P>
<P>
   But hold on. Cleveland coach Chris Palmer met with Williams on
Friday and told the San Diego native no decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very candid with him and told him what direction we
possibly can go, that there were several avenues we can take and we
would not have brought him in here unless we were truly interested
in him,'' Palmer said. ``I told him he was definitely in the
hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is why Williams might be in the hunt, but is no longer the
pick of the litter.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback factor &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When Couch elected to go to the University of Kentucky to play
football, some questioned his sanity. Had he decided to stay for a
fourth year at the basketball-dominated school, the questions would
have been answered.
</P>
<P>
   When the record-setting quarterback chose to enter the NFL draft
after his junior season, there was talk the expansion Cleveland
Browns could not go wrong in selecting a franchise quarterback as
the team's first pick.
</P>
<P>
   Couch's decision gave Williams instant competition for the
coveted No. 1 slot in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Clouding matters is the group of subpar little-knowns, who last
season were the starting quarterbacks for Philadelphia, Cincinnati,
Washington and St. Louis _ the teams with the Nos. 2, 3, 5 and 6
draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   This draft is considered to have the most quarterback prospects
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis, which has the fourth pick, has a franchise
quarterback in Peyton Manning, the No. 1 selection in 1998, and a
top-notch running back in Marshall Faulk. The Colts might opt to
take Williams should he be available, and trade Faulk. Miami is
rumored to be interested in Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns might not be sold on Couch as their top pick after an
earlier workout, but they were leaning toward another quarterback,
Smith, instead of Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' workout last week apparently did not change that, but
you never know. Couch gets his chance in a workout for the team
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky helped himself,'' Cleveland general manager Dwight Clark
said of Monday's workout. ``But as far as him being our clear-cut
No. 1 guy, it's tough to say. We still have the Couch workout to go
through. That will tell us some more and we'll make our decision
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland owner Al Lerner and team president Carmen Policy, who
have not attended any other potential draft pick's workout, are
scheduled to attend Couch's workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Couch's workout will make or break him, but
it's certainly important,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   With quarterback being such a precious commodity, Williams'
can't-miss status still does not guarantee a spot among the top
three picks. It might have had he not exhibited a weight problem
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter-pounder factor &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After a glorious season, Williams packed home such prestigious
honors as the Heisman Trophy, the Doak Walker Award, the Maxwell
Award and an ESPY. Problem is, each award has its own celebration,
banquet or dinner, or maybe all three.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the airline meals, hotel room service and banquet
fare hit Williams in the gut, literally.
</P>
<P>
   The usually rock-hard 5-10, 225-pounder ballooned to 244 pounds.
There was probably little cause for alarm though because Williams
said in November that he regularly gains 20 to 30 pounds every
offseason. The difference is this offseason the NFL was watching.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams showed up at the NFL combine, he measured 5-10,
244 pounds. He had shrunk two inches and gained 20 pounds from his
listed size at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most media guides are wrong and Texas' was as well,'' Hardy
said. ``Ricky probably played at 235 pounds and he put on a few
pounds, because for the first time in his life he wasn't in the
weight room every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The French Quarter factor &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This might be the most important ingredient in Williams'
rise-and-fall formula, though it is difficult to get an NFL
executive to admit to it.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans is the stomping ground of Williams' agent, Percy
Miller. Even Williams' mother questioned the hiring of No Limit
Sports at first.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is upset at what he calls an attack on his character by
those questioning his decision to sign with Miller's No Limit
Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who also represents Ron Mercer of the Boston Celtics and
Ricky Davis of the Charlotte Hornets, has said he is a businessman
and not involved in negotiating the contracts of any of his
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Clark says the fears, which gained momentum at the combine, are
unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was drifting around at the time of the combine, and
somebody sat him down and said, `Do this and that,' and he's done
it,'' Clark said. ``We've checked on him thoroughly and he's a
really good kid. To talk to him, you know he's genuine. I really
like him.''
</P>
<P>
   But does he like him enough to draft him No. 1?
</P>
<P>
   Williams hopes so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself fitting in, in Cleveland,'' Williams said. ``It's
a great organization. They have the best fans in the NFL. Maybe I
can charm them into taking me No. 1. But it looks like they are
bent on drafting a quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy says Williams will ``be doing two-a-days before any other
1999 draftee,'' meaning his client will be easy to sign.
</P>
<P>
   That is good news to whichever teams chooses him. What team that
will be is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is sure. Williams is positive that team will get the
best player available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to be No. 1, that's human nature, that's why
we compete,'' Williams said. ``But if I don't go No. 1 somebody
will get a hard-working player, who gives it his all every time
out. I think they'll be happy with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
