<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIES ARE NO OBSTACLE TO DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Brown can mix intensity with poise,
understand and deal with the magnitude of an event such as opening
day, yet be able to eliminate emotion from it.
</P>
<P>
   It's his strength and, he said in hindsight, one of the
weaknesses in his first start with the Dodgers. Brown rarely makes
the same mistake twice.
</P>
<P>
   If the last season of the 1900s unfolds the way the Dodgers
believe it will, they will undoubtedly remember Brown's second
outing much more than his first.
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed three hits in eight innings and the Dodgers got
homers from Raul Mondesi and Eric Karros in a 2-0 win against the
Colorado Rockies at Dodger Stadium on Saturday. It was the
antithesis of Brown's opening day _ a three-homer outing in which
he was pulled after 52/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is probably going to happen a lot more frequently than
what happened opening day,'' Karros said. ``This is Kevin Brown.
It's why he's been to the World Series the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies looked as though they had one glorious opportunity
to score against Brown _ but in reality, they never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's throwing error in the fourth put Rockies on second and
third with none out and the middle of the lineup due up. Brown also
tweaked his right hip on the play when he and third baseman Adrian
Beltre bumped fielding Neifi Perez's dribbler down the line.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter. Brown stuck out Pat Watkins and Dante Bichette
and got Vinny Castilla to fly to left to end the inning. The
Rockies had two more baserunners the rest of the way. Brown (1-0)
and closer Jeff Shaw, who notched his third save, retired the last
12 Rockies in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have tried so much to keep the adrenaline out of
(opening day) that I may not have been pumped up enough,'' Brown
said. ``I probably threw more and worked more (between starts). I
tried to find a comfort zone. I was searching.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown found the downward action on his pitches. Sixteen of his
outs were on groundballs, including one double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was going to have a good start,'' Beltre said. ``He
was throwing strikes and had good speed on his fastball and it was
sinking. I knew there would be a lot of groundballs.''
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Brown didn't try for his 16th career shutout was
the slight stiffness he told manager Davey Johnson he was
experiencing before the eighth inning. It was a result of the brush
with Beltre and it bothered Brown so much he went out and threw his
fourth 1-2-3 inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm going back out there,' but if anyone got on I
would have hooked him,'' Johnson said. ``There was no question for
me after the eighth.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned into the type of pitchers' duel that was expected
opening day when Brown and Randy Johnson met. The Dodgers won that
one 8-6 in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the fireballing Johnson, it was Colorado's Darryl
Kile (1-1) baffling the Dodger hitters with effective wildness. He
hit three batters, walked another five and pitched his way out of
three bases-loaded situations in six innings. The most crucial was
the fourth inning when the Dodgers loaded the bases with none out
but failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   While the clutch single never came, the long ball did on Kile's
first pitch of the seventh. It was a belt-high fastball that
Mondesi whacked to left for his league-leading fourth homer. Two
batters later, Karros hit his first homer of the season, a towering
shot down the left-field line.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to go out there and keep them from scoring,'' Brown
said. ``They (his teammates) picked me up the other day and I did
my job today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
