<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS MUST DECIDE WHICH WAY TO GO IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Imagine a speedy receiver _ say Torry Holt or
David Boston _ sprinting past the opponent's secondary to snare a
long touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   Or a revamped linebacking corps _ say Chris Claiborne or Andy
Katzenmoyer in the middle, or Rahim Abdullah outside _ finally
stuffing the New York Giants' rushing game.
</P>
<P>
   Or a huge left tackle _ such as Tempe native John Tait _
protecting quarterback Jake Plummer and opening holes for Adrian
Murrell.
</P>
<P>
   Or Plummer handing off on third-and-2 to a big back with the
size and strength to move a pile and convert.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals can envision it.
</P>
<P>
   Matter of fact, they expect to make at least one of the above
reality in the annual NFL draft next Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be prepared to go a lot of different directions on draft
day,'' Coach Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are coming off their first winning record (9-7)
since 1984, their first playoff appearance in a full-length season
since 1975, and their first playoff win since 1947, when they won
the NFL championship.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to build on that momentum with their 11 draft picks,
including eighth and 21st in the opening round, the biggest
question facing them is which position to address first.
</P>
<P>
   Signs point to wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess where a difference of opinion could occur is when you
address a particular need,'' Tobin said. ``When you draft that high
you don't want to get a player who is going to sit on the bench for
couple of years. You hope you draft a guy there who is going to
play and be a very, very good football player, have an impact on
your team.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt, of North Carolina State, is considered the best receiver
in this year's crop. At 6-feet, 190 pounds, he has been compared
with Jerry Rice of the San Francisco 49ers. He also is an
outstanding return specialist, another Cardinals need with Eric
Metcalf not expected back.
</P>
<P>
   Holt almost came out a year early last season. By all accounts,
he benefitted from staying for his senior season. He should be a
solid top-10 pick.
</P>
<P>
   The only negative on Holt is a reportedly low score on the NFL's
intelligence test during the league scouting combine in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Others think Boston, of Ohio State, has an edge because he is
slightly larger (6-2, 205) and nearly as fast. What scouts must
sort out is whether Boston, who is leaving the Buckeyes after his
junior year, is ready for pro football.
</P>
<P>
   They also have to satisfy themselves that he can be a main
weapon. Holt was without question the leader of the Wolfpack
offense. Boston was surrounded by several luminaries at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals offensive coordinator Marc Trestman wanted to use
three- and four-wide receiver sets but often was thwarted because
Metcalf was injured and not productive, and because fourth receiver
Fred Brock, who went to Cleveland in the expansion draft, was
inexperienced and short.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' receiving tandem of Rob Moore and Frank Sanders
has been one of the league's best for three years. Adding another
target for Plummer, especially one with breakaway speed, would make
an emerging offense even more explosive.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, however, are coming off a year in which they paid
a $7.5 million signing bonus to defensive tackle Eric Swann, just
under $11 million to defensive end Andre Wadsworth and a
league-record $15 million to Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   That's about as deep as their pockets are. Estimates of the
signing bonus for the eighth pick this season run at about $6
million. That opens the possibility of a trade down, possibly to
10th or 12th in the first round, where the Cardinals would not have
to shell out as much cash and still be able to land Boston or Tait.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that their first pick is used for a receiver, the
Cardinals then face some decision-making. Do they spend still more
time and energy trying to re-sign free-agent outside linebacker
Jamir Miller, their leading tackler last season, who now is
represented by agent Leigh Steinberg? Could Steinberg get another
of his clients, fullback Larry Centers, to restructure his contract
to create salary-cap room that would allow the club to offer more
to Miller?
</P>
<P>
   Or should they tell Miller once and for all to go fish and then
go another way in the draft?
</P>
<P>
   Given that Miller might have been the most valuable player of
the defense last year after Swann was felled by a season-ending
knee injury, they should not blow him off. They should find a way
to salvage him, if Miller is willing, as he says, to now bite the
bullet for one year with a below-market incentive-laced
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Cardinals more than likely will have their choice
of middle linebacker Katzenmoyer, another Ohio State player leaving
after his junior year, or outside linebacker Abdullah of Clemson,
with the 21st pick.
</P>
<P>
   But if a quick arrangement is reached this week with Miller _
considered unlikely because the club's personnel people now are
engrossed with draft preparation _ then they would draft a tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Four tackles are considered to have first-round potential _ Tait
(6-7, 290) of Brigham Young; Lonnie Shelton (6-5, 324) of Eastern
Michigan; Matt Stinchcomb (6-6, 295) of Georgia, and Aaron Gibson
(6-7, 371) of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Some early mock drafts have all four of them being taken before
the Cardinals' 21st pick.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals have drafted a receiver at No. 8 and agreed to
terms with Miller, they could package some of their remaining draft
picks with the No. 21 pick and move up to get a tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tobin and Bob Ferguson, Cardinals vice president for player
personnel, downplay the need for a left tackle, saying backup Matt
Joyce and Anthony Clement, who missed all of last season after
surgery on a herniated disk, are excellent candidates to replace
seven-time Pro Bowler Lomas Brown, who left for Cleveland via free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't have a gun to our heads as far as a left
tackle goes,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   In the lower rounds, the Cardinals need to find a big back,
depth across the offensive line and a third quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said he is thankful the draft has several first-round
prospects at quarterback. Four teams drafting ahead of the
Cardinals in the opening round need starting quarterbacks. The
Cardinals, with Plummer, do not. Perhaps three of the first four
picks will be quarterbacks, in turn driving players at positions of
greater need lower where they would be available to the Cardinals.
Claiborne, a middle linebacker from Southern California, could be
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 11 picks in this draft, and it's a deep draft,''
Ferguson said. ``We just want to get the best player. I hope
everybody ahead of us takes a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you for sure what we're going to do, but I can
tell you that we will not draft a quarterback at No. 8.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
