<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3715 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-DRUGS_AZR &LR;      04-11 3317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-DRUGS_AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG CASE PAVED WAY FOR EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There will be a birthday of sorts this Friday. Nobody
will celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, the big league sports market, will turn 12 years old.
As a historical marker, the day is unofficial. Publicists and
marketing directors probably would prefer to memorialize the
official arrival of the NFL, NHL, major league baseball, arenas and
ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Without all of them, there is no big top. No show.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the stage was set on April 16, 1987. That's when a
major league town grew out of a major league scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Five players who were former or current Suns that year were
indicted by a Maricopa County grand jury. The indictments and
subsequent headlines told a sordid tale of suspected drug use and
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Six others were mentioned in indictments but not charged.
Testimony from one _ the Suns' leading scorer, Walter Davis _ was
crucial through the entire incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Illustrated'' called the case ``the biggest drug bust
in the history of professional sports.'' As it turned out, it was
something less than that.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the five players, there were eight other people
in the Valley restaurant business who were indicted on drug-related
charges such as conspiracy to possess or conspiracy to traffic in
narcotics, mostly cocaine. Of the 13, only one spent time in jail,
and that was on a charge not related to the investigation and
prosecution of the players.
</P>
<P>
   On the law enforcement scoreboard, it was a forgettable case.
</P>
<P>
   But Suns President and Diamondbacks Chief Executive Officer
Jerry Colangelo hasn't forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Without an investigation by the Phoenix Police Department and
the subsequent charges filed by the Maricopa County Attorney's
Office, the Suns owners might not have been so eager to put the
franchise up for sale. But they did, and Colangelo, then the Suns
general manager, put together a group that purchased the team in
1988 for $44.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the estimated value of the team has at least
quadrupled, according to various business magazines. And downtown
has been transformed. The old vacant lot is not so empty anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's speculation, but the opportunity presented itself because
the old owners were disenchanted,'' said Colangelo, managing
general partner of a group that bought the Suns from Donald Pitt
and Don Diamond of Tucson and Richard Bloch of Santa Fe. ``I used
to read about this, but sometimes, yes, opportunity does come out
of adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, you could build a case that because of that, a
team was purchased, an arena was built, a ballpark was constructed
and a major league baseball team was acquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed the landscape of Phoenix forever.''
</P>
<P>
   It also changed Colangelo forever. His confrontation with the
crisis turned a relatively anonymous NBA general manager into a
powerful and sometimes controversial figure. He emerged like the
city itself. A winner. One of the few.
</P>
<P>
   There weren't many victories for anyone else who had a role in
the scandal. There were lessons. And some regrets. For one person,
there was tragedy that in some minds is still a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Former Suns guard Johnny High died early in the morning of June
13, 1987, at a spot that today sits near the late-afternoon shadows
cast by Bank One Ballpark. High was alone behind the wheel when his
car hit a light pole at 20th and Jefferson streets.
</P>
<P>
   The former Suns guard had testified to the grand jury. He also
was not charged. &QL; 
Moving on &QL; 
Since then, the players involved have drifted on to other lives and
other cities. So have most of their friends and acquaintances who
were either charged or somehow drawn into the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Most don't want to talk. They have families, jobs and lives to
live. Others have players from a different generation to coach.
They don't want to be remembered for a time when the NBA was a
fast-paced reflection of an era when drugs were cool.
</P>
<P>
   It was life on the run. Basketball and ``Boogie Nights.''
Players served up triple-doubles on the floor and were served
triple-doubles at last call. Cocaine was felonious, chic and
available in trendy nightspots coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a learning experience,'' said Alvin Scott, a 6-foot-7
forward who was not charged. He was named an unindicted
co-conspirator two years after he completed an eight-season career
with the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was part of growing up. That's all I can say,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bitter or angry with anybody else about what happened.
It was just part of those times, and I was there. I've moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, a Southwest Gas employee for the past 10 years, continues
to live and work in the Valley, unlike the players indicted. James
Edwards, Jay Humphries, Grant Gondrezick, Garfield Heard and Mike
Bratz were indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a center, entered a plea bargain in which he agreed to
undergo drug counseling. Charges were dismissed. The Suns then
traded him to Detroit midway through the 1987-88 season. He played
in the NBA for eight more years and won three championship rings,
two with Detroit and one with Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Humphries, a guard, entered a drug diversion program that
included counseling. Charges were dismissed. The Suns traded him to
Milwaukee, where he played for a few years. Today he's working as
an NBA scout and lives in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Gondrezick, a guard, pleaded guilty to witness tampering in a
plea bargain that called for a $100 fine and three years of
probation in exchange for dismissal of felony charges. The Suns
waived him. He played in Europe for a couple of years. Today he's
living in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Bratz, a guard, had ended his playing career at the time of the
indictments and was living in Sacramento. California authorities
refused to extradite him. A Sacramento assistant district attorney
called the charges vague and unsubstantiated. Eventually, they were
dismissed. Bratz worked as a Sacramento Kings assistant coach
through last season. Today he's a scout. This week, he'll be
coaching one of the teams of NBA draft prospects at the Nike Desert
Classic at Wells Fargo Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Heard, a former Suns forward, also was retired at the time of
the indictment. Charges were dropped. Heard then was hired as an
assistant to then-Dallas Mavericks Coach John MacLeod, who was
fired by the Suns before the indictments came down. Heard is now an
assistant coach of the Detroit Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like me, I guess the other fellas are trying to move on with
their lives,'' said Scott, the father of three daughters who range
in age from the early teens to the mid-20s. ``I can't speak for
everybody, but I know I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said he has no contact with Davis, who lives in Denver.
Davis worked as a broadcaster after playing for the Nuggets, who
signed him as a free agent after the Suns let him go in July 1988.
He then moved into the Nuggets community relations department,
where he worked through last season. He could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Others touched by the case include:
</P>
<P>
   Former Suns guard Don Buse, who has been living in Hammond, Ind.
He was not charged in the case, but his name was included in
national wire service reports. When the story broke, Buse was an
assistant coach with the Spurs. San Antonio newspapers ran
headlines that linked his name to alleged cocaine use. He left the
Spurs' coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Dennis Johnson has been living in Orlando, where the
former Celtics assistant coach was charged with spousal abuse in
November 1998. This month, he was hired to coach a Continental
Basketball Association team in La Crosse, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   DJ also was not charged in the case, but, like Buse, he was
mentioned in the widely publicized allegations. At the time, he was
starting for the Celtics, who would lose to the Los Angeles Lakers
in the NBA Finals that year. In a memorable news conference before
a Celtics-Bucks playoff game at Milwaukee, DJ was asked if he were
a casual user of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   DJ angrily dismissed the question by saying he didn't know what
was meant by casual. He said he simply didn't use the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bucks center Paul Mokeski sobbed as he stood next to
DJ, whose number was retired by the Celtics a couple of years ago.
Mokeski had not been charged, either. His name wasn't in an
indictment, but it was in newsprint. In terms of his reputation,
there wasn't much difference between the two. &QL; 
Drug policy under fire &QL; 
Questions remain about how much the NBA has moved beyond those
difficult days.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 12 years after the indictments, the NBA drug policy
continued to be a source of controversy last fall. It was an issue
in negotiations to end the owners' lockout. The players agreed to
be tested for marijuana for the first time since an NBA drug policy
was implemented.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987 and in years since, the league's drug policy has been
questioned. Is it a serious campaign or mere window dressing?
</P>
<P>
   The question was often at the philosophical heart of the 1987
investigation, which was led by then-Phoenix Police Chief Ruben
Ortega, Maricopa County Attorney Tom Collins, prosecutor James
Keppel and Detective Gary Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Like the players they investigated and tried to prosecute, these
men have moved on to different lives. Ortega is the police chief in
Salt Lake City. Collins is an attorney in southern Arizona's
Cochise County. Keppel is a Maricopa County Superior Court judge.
Ball is retired in Pocatello, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what got my eyes opened in this whole thing is that
you have star athletes who have been idolized since they were in
grade school,'' said Collins, who has been in Cochise County for
nearly 10 years. ``There is all this adulation, and then they are
handed all this money. They travel all over the country, put up in
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have this moving party atmosphere, this movable-feast
aspect. They are in this kind of specialized shell. They are not
mature emotionally. They're extremely vulnerable to what happened
then and, from what I hear, happens now.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he is not a sports fan. But he said he couldn't
help remembering what happened in 1987 when he heard about Magic
Johnson's HIV diagnosis a few years ago and Latrell Sprewell's
assault last season of Golden State Coach P.J. Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   Keppel declined comment. It would be inappropriate because of
his responsibilities as a judge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before he moved to the bench, however, Keppel talked to writers
Armen Keteyian, Harvey Araton and Martin F. Dardis for a 1997 book
titled ``Inside The New NBA, Money Players.''
</P>
<P>
   A portion of an early chapter is devoted to the Phoenix
investigation and how it exposed the NBA drug policy as a
well-marketed but hollow campaign against substance abuse. Keppel
recalled a visit from Gary Bettman, then deputy commissioner of the
NBA and current National Hockey League commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Keppel said Bettman was worried that the widely praised policy,
adopted in 1983, might be destroyed by the investigation. The book
quoted Keppel as saying he didn't think the policy ``was that
effective in the beginning.'' Ball is quoted as saying Bettman
wanted to protect the league's image and sweep evidence of
potential problems ``under the rug.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, however, said he does not recall any overt pressure
from the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really couldn't put pressure on me or Ruben Ortega or
anybody else working on the case,'' Collins said. ``They came into
our offices very self-importantly and expressed their concerns.
There was a lot of strutting around by guys in very expensive
suits. But not much more than that.'' &QL; 
Case falls apart &QL; 
Collins' case came apart within three months after April 17, 1987,
when a shopping cart full of indictments was pushed into a room
jammed with reporters. The news conference itself became a target.
Defense attorneys dismissed it as a publicity stunt. Critics called
it a cheap platform for the political ambitions of Collins and
Ortega.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he was stunned by the backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the story about the investigation had been on the
front pages for days,'' Collins said. ``We had been besieged by the
press for days to say something, say anything. Finally, we called
that press conference, which was the biggest circus I had ever seen
in my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically stood up in front of that screaming, howling mob
and read the indictments. Then we sat down. That was our big
publicity stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a flood of leaks to the media detailing grand
jury testimony from Davis, or High, or Scott, or former center and
first-round draft pick William Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   Collins contends that the leaks killed his case because stories
were changed or potential witnesses quit talking after details were
disclosed. Davis changed his story. High went back on part of his.
Some evidence was thrown out after Scott complained that testimony
he provided to Detective Ball had been summarized inaccurately.
</P>
<P>
   But defense attorneys and the NBA argued that the case was
flawed from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation itself began with rumors of a gambling tip,
supposedly furnished by Mokeski and Jack Sikma, also of the Bucks,
to a bartender at an old Valley nightspot, Malarkey's. The two
Bucks reportedly advised the bartender to bet the ``under'' on a
Bucks-Suns game on Feb. 21, 1987, at Veterans Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The over-under betting line was 226 points, and the Suns lost,
115-107, a victory for the under. The information was allegedly
exchanged over some cocaine provided by the bar manager.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Collins, Keppel and Ball said there was nothing to the
gambling allegations. The self-inflicted blow bloodied their
credibility. It was only a matter of time before defense attorneys
would finish the job. Skepticism was furthered by California's
refusal to honor a fugitive complaint filed against Bratz. The
implication was clear: Law enforcement in a neighboring state
didn't think much of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Then High died.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurt our prosecution a little bit,'' said Collins, who
continues to argue that changes in Davis' story were insurmountable
for prosecutors. &QL; 
Not ordinary guys &QL; 
Erosion in Collins' case undoubtedly pleased the NBA, whose
officials were angered by what they saw as misuse of the league's
drug policy to further police work.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was targeted by law enforcement, the NBA argued, because
he already had admitted to cocaine use. He had talked about it in
newspaper stories and for television cameras. He had spent time in
an NBA-appointed rehabilitation center near Los Angeles during the
1985-86 season. The argument was that it was easy to haul Davis in
front of the grand jury and ask him, under oath, for the names of
suppliers and fellow users.
</P>
<P>
   Other players, the NBA argued, were targeted because their
celebrity put the spotlight on what otherwise might have been just
another drug bust. But it was the celebrity aspect that caused the
most trouble, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I didn't have much consideration for the NBA or
even knew that much about sports,'' Collins said. ``I was
surprised, frankly, that the public thought it was a lot more
important than I did. The public reaction was far more than I had
anticipated. I just wanted to treat the players like anybody else,
just like any other guy.'' &QL; 
Just 1 did time &QL; 
Some average, any other guys were caught up in the storm. They were
waiters and bartenders at nightspots the players frequented after
games. Seven were charged on a variety of drug offenses. One was
charged with obstruction of justice. Of the eight, only one did
time. Superior Court Judge Michael Ryan sentenced Terrence Kelly,
then a waiter at Avanti's restaurant, to 30 days in jail for a
charge unrelated to the Suns case.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went before the judge, he told me: `I sure can't
sentence you if I can't sentence Walter Davis,' '' said Kelly, who
had eight Suns-related charges dismissed by Ryan. ``But then he
looked at me and said, `However, there is this other matter of
selling pot to an undercover cop.' They got me on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly sounds today a lot like Scott. He's moved on with his
life. He's a successful liquor salesman in the Valley. There were
lessons from those days, but Kelly said they didn't have to be
learned through what he believes was an overblown case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a real deal,'' Kelly said. ``They thought we were a
bunch of drug dealers. We weren't. We were just guys having fun the
way a lot of people did in those days. You grow up. Hey, the whole
thing put a damper on my life for a while. No doubt about that. It
was tough, but I got through all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly continues to be a sports fan. He applauded Colangelo for
the sports empire he built out of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire the guy, more than anything,'' he said. ``Look at
what he did for the town.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kelly stays in touch with Bratz, now an old friend.
He also has had Suns season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three rows back,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   From his seat at America West Arena, Kelly can see a symbol of
that troubled time. It is a remnant that angers him to this day.
Davis' old jersey number, 6, hangs alongside numbers worn by Dick
Van Arsdale, Connie Hawkins, Alvan Adams and Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns retired it a few years ago in a ceremony that resulted
in an emotional standing ovation. The crowd forgave Davis, the
all-time leading scorer in the franchise's 30-year history. But
Kelly said Davis doesn't deserve the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry shouldn't have done that,'' Kelly said. ``He (Davis)
brought down his friends, teammates and some other people, who
didn't deserve to be treated that way. It hurt me. It hurt Bratz.
Edwards didn't have any fun with it, I know that. We tagged along
with him. What I did is my fault. But for him to go scot-free just
isn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the retirement of Davis' number was a rite of passage.
Davis played in a different building, Veterans Memorial Coliseum.
When his number was given an honored spot at America West Arena, it
was an acknowledgement that he had a lot to do with all that
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it was good. A generation of Suns fans grew up watching
Davis' graceful moves and jump shots along the baseline. He was
Michael Jordan's basketball model. He provided Phoenix and the
league a hint of what about to emerge with Jordan's brilliant play.
Davis was a reason to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the profound irony is that Davis' most important role in
Suns history came about because he was the central figure in a
crisis that forced a remake of the team and its city. Davis marks
the first step in a series of changes that continue. &QL; 
Rising from the ashes &QL; 
Opportunity sprang from the crisis. It's Phoenix, in name and fact.
America West Arena, Bank One Ballpark and the Diamondbacks grew
from the abyss.
</P>
<P>
   But the price was steep. For some, it's forgotten. Paid in full.
For others, it's still there, like some old debt that can never be
wiped off the books.
</P>
<P>
   For Colangelo and the city, from crisis to skyline, 1987 and
1999 are part of a single continuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the case broke, I'm sure it was a particularly painful
time for Mr. Colangelo,'' Collins said. ``But the whole team went
on to much bigger and better things. From a distance, it looks like
it all worked out for the best, at least for the Suns and Mr.
Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I didn't realize how much the basketball
team was tied to big money, stadiums and downtown development.
Everything was so intertwined. I guess I never appreciated all of
the ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of downtown seemed to hinge on what happened to that
basketball team. Like I said, it was a real eye-opener.''
</P>
<P>
   It still is. &QL; 
Norm Frauenheim can be reached at (602) 444-8259 or at
norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
