<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 CHOICE IN ENTRY DRAFT NOT CLEAR CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Lightning keeps telling anyone who will listen
that the club will not trade away the No. 1 overall pick in the
upcoming June entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I traded the pick, the fans would kill me,'' said
Coach/General Manager  &UR; Jacques Demers. ``I'd come walking out of a
restaurant and they'd shoot me and never find who did it. Are you
kidding me?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, don't be surprised if he trades it anyway. And here's why.
Unlike last year's draft class, which featured top-pick  &UR; Vincent
 &UR; Lecavalier, &UR; whom Tampa promptly plucked, this year's crop of top
picks isn't as certain as it was months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The player most scouts expected to go No. 1,  &UR; Patrik Stefan,
recently suffered his second concussion of the season while playing
for the Long Beach Ice Dogs in the International Hockey League.
It's the third one of his young career, and now there are some
questions as to his future.
</P>
<P>
   The next-best prospects are twins  &UR; Daniel and  &UR; Henrik Sedin from
Sweden, but they are telling teams they plan to remain in Europe
for another season and they don't want to be separated. They've
played on the same teams since they were 5, and they want whoever
takes them to put a package together to bring them both to the same
NHL team, which isn't likely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is goal-scorer extraordinaire  &UR; Pavel Brendl from
Calgary in the Western Hockey League. He's scored 70 goals this
season, but he's reportedly a head case who takes too many games
off and tends to coast.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever ends up with the No. 1 pick will have some interesting
decisions to make, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see a few of the teams who pick high scrambling
on draft day to trade down,'' one NHL scout said. ``But you might
not find too many takers.'' &QL; 
Say that again?
</P>
<P>
   Just when it looked like  &UR; Jaromir Jagr's silly feud was over
with Penguins Coach  &UR; Kevin Constantine, it reared its ugly head
again when some of Jagr's comments to a Czech Republic newspaper
made their way back to Pittsburgh via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the way he prepares the team, and I'm not the
only one among the players,'' Jagr reportedly told the Prague
newspaper ``MF'' ``Dnes.'' ``His communication with us is just
awful. Either he yells at us, or he just hides someplace. Right
now, it's just impossible to talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can turn below-average players into at least average
ones,'' Jagr said, ``but he also does everything he can to turn top
players into average ones, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by a beat writer about the remarks, Jagr became
agitated and didn't wish to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about it,'' he said. ``Do what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he apparently shouted some obscenities and refused to talk
altogether. Constantine's response?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (comments) are water under the bridge as far as I'm
concerned.'' &QL; 
Tough times for Robinson
</P>
<P>
   His contract is up after this season, and Los Angeles Kings
Coach
 &UR; Larry Robinson, rumored to be leaving for Montreal this summer,
doesn't sound as if he plans to be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. It's been a tough year,'' he said. ``When even
my wife is finding it tough, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, whose last-place Kings have fallen to 13 games below
.500, was asked whether these could be his last few days on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I think about it,'' he said, ``but it's not something
I think keeps me up at night. What keeps me up at night is not
winning hockey games.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be a total insomniac if the Kings somehow manage to lose
for the fourth straight time this season to the expansion Nashville
Predators, whom they meet Monday. &QL; 
Oilers find Roy offensive
</P>
<P>
   After barely missing a chance at an empty-net goal earlier this
season against Philadelphia, Colorado Avalanche goalie  &UR; Patrick Roy
decided he'd take a couple of chances with the net unguarded last
Saturday during a game against the Edmonton Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers, though, took exception because of the way Roy went
about it. He strayed well away from the crease and into corners for
loose pucks to try to fling a shot down toward the other end, which
infuriated Edmonton players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling: ``He's got an ego bigger than the Goodyear blimp,''
Oilers assistant coach  &UR; Ted Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last minute, we're pressing and Patrick is making a
mockery of the game by trying to score,'' forward  &UR; Doug Weight
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Ron Low said his team should be allowed to bowl Roy over
if he's going to stray from the nets like that in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Roy took it all in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they respect my shot because they were all ready at
the blue line,'' he said. ``I tried (to score). I had my chances.
Maybe it's going to come one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy and the Avalanche meet the Oilers again on Friday in
Colorado. Could be interesting, unless the Avs start Roy the night
before against Calgary and give him the day off against Edmonton. &QL; 
Squawking Ducks
</P>
<P>
   They're in a slump, but that hasn't stopped the Mighty Ducks
from doing a little chirping lately.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Anaheim would have to face Detroit or Colorado in
the first round by finishing sixth or seventh in the West instead
of fifth, where they have been for most of the season, high-scoring
forward  &UR; Teemu Selanne said fifth place is definitely the way to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a way better situation, to play against
Phoenix,'' Selanne said. ``That's our goal right now. We don't have
anything else on our mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty Ducks are 2-1-2 this season against the Coyotes, whom
they meet today. They are 1-3 against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we have a chance to even beat Detroit,'' Selanne
said, ``but I think it would be a big difference to play Phoenix.
If we look at our record against Detroit, it's not as good as it is
against Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Paul Kariya said he also would prefer to meet the Coyotes, but
after a 1-4-1 slide, he wisely cautions that the Mighty Ducks
shouldn't take any team lightly. Especially now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our desperation once we clinched the playoffs,''
Kariya said. ``We've got to get it back because we're not a good
enough team to float. Our whole game is awful.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at (602) 444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
