<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHARK' CIRCLING  
 NORMAN IN POSITION TO STRIKE AT MASTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. - Tied for the lead, Greg Norman watched his ball
take flight, blue eyes upturned, his tanned hard-cast face
squinting into the afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   Over the water. Over the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Oh no ''.`` .''`` .''``''
</P>
<P>
   In sympathy, the spectators groaned, a familiar sound at this
picturesque little theater nestled in Amen Corner, the most famous
par 3 in golf. Norman recognized the sound. He knows it well.
</P>
<P>
   His nickname is the Shark but he is known by other aliases. The
Choker. Mr. Heartbreak. The No. 1 Victim of Golf's Inexorable Fate.
A Disaster Waiting To Happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Man Who Can't Win The Masters was tied for the third-round
lead. But not for long.
</P>
<P>
   Norman soon found himself behind the 12th green where no one
wants to be. Bending over, he sighed. He peered into a thick bush.
His ball had to be there ``somewhere.'' But where was it hiding?
The clock ticking, his heart sinking, Norman parted the foliage
with both hands, up to his elbows in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   His caddie joined in the search. Even his playing partner, Lee
Janzen, helped them look. From afar they could have been kids at a
backyard party, hunting for colored eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Norman's head-shaking history is well documented. The man has
lost numerous major championships in ways that defy belief and
mathematical odds.
</P>
<P>
   Norman lost the 1986 PGA when Bob Tway holed out from a sand
trap on the last hole. A year later The Masters slipped away in a
sudden-death playoff when Larry Mize performed a miracle in the
purple twilight, making a 140-foot chip.
</P>
<P>
   Norman led the 1996 Masters by 6 shots after Saturday. ``Shark
Smells Blood'' the banner headline in the ``Augusta Chronicle''
warned. On Sunday, the only blood in the water was his own.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo won. Norman was runner-up, for the third time. The
biggest collapse in Masters history inspired comparisons with the
'64 Phillies and the Hindenburg disaster. A multimillionaire,
Norman owns a fleet of expensive cars. It was said that day that
the Titanic went down and took four Ferraris with it.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a way to lose a major Norman surely can find it. On
Saturday his optimism dimmed when he lost his ball. ``Mystifying,'
he said later.
</P>
<P>
   Penalized 1 stroke, Norman marched grimly back to the 12th tee.
The gallery's heart went out to him. ``I don't think there was one
individual who didn't want to see me hit the green,'' Norman said.
``They didn't want me to make a six or an eight and take myself out
of the tournament. They know what the anguish is. I could feel
their emotions.'' Their support. ``It's the most I've ever felt in
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   After Norman had shoulder surgery last year critics and skeptics
wrote his obituary. But the 44-year-old Australian isn't finished
and he showed me something Saturday. Courage. Determination. Grit.
</P>
<P>
   Norman landed his second tee shot onto the green. Then he rammed
in a 22-foot putt to save bogey. Another bogey followed on the
par-five 13th hole after he laid up with his second shot and his
ball landed in a sandy divot. Murphy's Law.
</P>
<P>
   This man who carries a trunk load of emotional baggage sensed
his round, and his chances, slipping away. ``I had to fight hard to
keep my composure,'' Norman admitted.
</P>
<P>
   But he came back, with birdies on two of the last four holes,
including the 18th, and at day's end the Man Who Can't Win The
Masters found himself alone in second place trailing Jose Maria
Olazabal by 1 shot.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't sure whether the public views him as the sentimental
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you determine that? From '96 or because I'm getting
old,'' Norman joked, flashing his toothpaste-ad smile.
</P>
<P>
   He long ago gave up trying to foresee the future, saying, ``I
don't know what my destiny is.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman's swing doctor, David Leadbetter, won't offer a
prediction either. ``The losses have an effect,'' Leadbetter said.
``We're trying to eradicate those. . . But I can't control the
brain. . .''
</P>
<P>
   No, but Greg Norman's name is on the big board, again. He has
worked hard to give himself another opportunity to win the
tournament he covets more than any other, and, if by chance he
does, what a story that would be. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
