<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3718 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-3RD-ROUND     04-11 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-3RD-ROUND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMEN CORNER SHOULD DECIDE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ For some, the nightmares are real. Others can
only imagine. Both will come together today in a violent mental
collision at The Masters, where the three most terrifying words
uttered at Augusta National will once again be on everyone's lips.
</P>
<P>
   The back nine.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Maria Olazabal, the Spaniard who won here in 1994, has been
through the fabled war zone on a previous Sunday. He recalls the
final nine holes against Tom Lehman that year, which ended with
Olazabal out front by 2 strokes, chiefly the result of a brilliant
eagle at the 15th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I won here in '94, I think virtually everybody was
rooting for Tom,'' said Olazabal, who watched Lehman miss birdie
after birdie coming down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be pretty much like that (today). Everyone will be
rooting for Greg, after what happened to him here (in 1996). It
might make it just a little bit more difficult, but that's what
we're here for.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal knows. He realizes that his 1-stroke lead is tentative
at best against Norman entering the final fray. And if the Great
White Shark doesn't get him, maybe Steve Pate, the human birdie
machine, or supersolid David Love III, each 2 shots back, might get
the job done.
</P>
<P>
   There are others of merit, such as Ernie Els and Lee Janzen (3
off the pace); Steve Elkington, Colin Montgomerie and Nick Price (4
back); and even Tiger Woods and Phil Mickelson (down by 5).
</P>
<P>
   ``When you reach the back nine, you have to be good, and you
have to be tough,'' said Olazabal, whose 1-over 73 was good enough
to keep the lead at 7-under 209 on a sunbaked, sometimes windy day.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I find it very difficult to score on the front nine. And
the start is so important here if you're to have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, who had opened the day with a 3-stroke lead, lost his
advantage by the sixth hole, where he made his second bogey. But
eight straight pars through the most dangerous stretch of the
course, coupled with a birdie at the ever-difficult 15th got him
back on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough day out there, but I managed to hang on,'' said
Olazabal, who is winning this tournament mostly by not making
mistakes (four bogeys through 54 holes).
</P>
<P>
   Norman also is playing well, but was mystified on this day when
he tee shot at No. 12 _ the famed middle hole of Amen Corner _
became lost in an jasmine bush. After searching for five minutes,
the Shark abandoned the mission, went back to the tee and promptly
stuck his third shot 22 feet from the cup, holing the putt for a
brilliant bogey (if there is such a thing).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give 500 bucks if anybody can go out and find that ball
on No. 12, because I don't have a clue,'' said Norman, who shot 71.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the ball was found by a CBS camera crew and tournament
officials about 50 minutes after Norman departed. It was deep in a
clump of pine needles and ivy.
</P>
<P>
   Norman has to wonder if he's cursed around here. He also got a
bad lie in a sandy divot on No. 13, which led to yet another bogey.
But Norman insisted afterward that he doesn't have any bad vibes
dating back to '96, when he took a 6-shot lead into the final
round, and lost by 5 to Nick Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't reflect on negative situations,'' said Norman, who has
two British Opens wins but has folded in eight other majors,
including runner-up finishes here in '86 and '87.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where my strength of mind comes in. I don't cry over
spilled milk.''
</P>
<P>
   Love, who also was at 7 under before he took a dip at the 15th,
also will need some strength of mind. His horror stories at the
Masters are limited to a runner-up finish in '95. But in that
tournament, Ben Crenshaw went out and won it with birdies on the
16th and 17th holes rather than Love choking it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rode the roller coaster of emotions,'' said Love, who closed
out his round with four straight pars for a 70. ``But in the end,
I've still got a chance going into (today), and that's all you can
hope for around here.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other highs and lows, like the record-setting seven
consecutive birdies made by Pate beginning at the seventh hole that
led to a tournament-best 65. Scott McCarron felt the extreme, as
his triple-bogey 6 at the 12th knocked him out of a share of the
lead. He finished with a 76 and is 3 under.
</P>
<P>
   But that's Augusta National, it giveth and it taketh away like
no other course in the universe. Over the years, the 11th, 12th and
13th holes have gained a reputation as perhaps the most scary
stretch of golf. Coupled them with the toughened-up 15th, and
that's probably the equation which will determine who wears the
green jacket today.
</P>
<P>
   Norman fully expects the outcome to be settled on those four
holes ``because they're just hard shots to play, and you don't have
any room to bail out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Shinnecock's probably the hardest golf course in the
world to play,'' he said. ``But this one gets there in the last two
days when it's drying fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
