<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ANGELS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' HELLING HIT HARD AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Reserve outfielder Scarborough Green soon
might become a luxury the Rangers no longer can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Green's destiny could be determined by the performance of the
Rangers' rotation, and that may not be comforting to the
late-inning specialist after last night's 10-0 defeat to the
Anaheim Angels at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got two relievers who've thrown more innings than three
of our starters,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``That's not a good
sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Rick Helling (0-2) failed to complete the fourth
inning for the second time in as many starts this season, and the
Rangers' bullpen soon will require reinforcements if the rotation
does not begin to pitch deeper into games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't keep going on like this very much longer,'' Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   Helling's 3 2/3-inning appearance marked the fourth time through
five games that a member of the rotation failed to complete the
fifth inning. Right-hander Aaron Sele, who pitched seven scoreless
innings during Tuesday's 6-0 victory against Detroit, remains the
rotation's only member to surpass the five-inning barrier.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers need a performance similar to the one right-hander
Omar Olivares gave the Angels. Olivares required only 97 pitchers
to complete 7 1/3 scoreless innings in which the Rangers managed
only three singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is someone to go out and give us seven or eight
strong innings,'' Oates said. ``That would be the best shot in the
arm for our ballclub. I feel like we've got that guy going tomorrow
in Aaron.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling allowed 12 of the 20 batters he faced to reach safely
and departed after surrendering six runs on nine hits and two
walks. His brief appearance forced the bullpen to accumulate
another 4 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all been in this game long enough to know that this is
going to happen sometimes,'' Helling said. ``You just don't want
this trend to continue. We just haven't had quality starts in four
of these five games.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-handers Mike Morgan and Esteban Loaiza have pitched seven
and 6 1/3 innings, respectively, during their relief appearances.
Morgan, though, will join the rotation and start Tuesday's game
against the Seattle Mariners at The Kingdome, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Rangers' seven-member bullpen will be reduced to
six beginning with tonight's game. That makes it even more
imperative that Sele provide the Rangers quality innings tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who earned a berth on the Rangers' Opening Day roster by
hitting .361 (13-for-36) during his final 16 exhibition games,
likely would be the one who pays the price should the Rangers
require a 12th pitcher. Oates envisioned utilizing the 24-year-old
outfielder as a late-inning pinch-runner in close games.
</P>
<P>
   ``One run might not be the difference if we don't start getting
people out,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Green could be optioned to Triple-A Oklahoma in favor of a 12th
pitcher to help what soon could become the Rangers' depleted
bullpen. Right-handers Jeff Zimmerman and Jonathan Johnson likely
would be the favorites to be recalled from Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (1-0, 3.60) earned the victory for the RedHawks during
Friday's 7-4 triumph against Vancouver. Johnson surrendered two
runs on seven hits and two walks during his five-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, who impressed the Rangers with his performance this
spring, earned the save during Johnson's start with two innings of
perfect relief that included one strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it gets dark, you never ever think you're going to see
the light at the end of the tunnel again,'' Oates said. ``Believe
me, I've been there, and I promise you that you will.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
