<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BRAVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON FANS 15 IN D-BACKS' WIN OVER BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Diamondbacks' Brian Anderson peered through the
gate of the bullpen in the left-field corner at Turner Field and
watched fellow left-hander Randy Johnson go about his business
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson gave up a run to the Atlanta Braves in the first inning
and another in the second. Anderson noticed a change in him after
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been around him long enough through the spring that we
can tell a lot by his body language,'' Anderson said. ``Even though
we were that far away, we could tell in a heartbeat that he was
getting mad, that he was saying to himself, `All right, I'm going
out and taking control.' His stuff just exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned to the guys and said, `I don't think we're going to
be throwing tonight, boys.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's complete-game, six-hit, club record 15-strikeout
performance not only gave the beleaguered bullpen a breather, but
it was like water down the parched throat of a person dying of
thirst in the desert. After four close losses to begin the season,
the Diamondbacks drank from the victory cup, 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 103rd time that Johnson struck out 10 or more batters
in a game, the 25th time he had fanned 14 or more and the 19th time
for 15 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson threw 125 pitches in seven innings while getting a
no-decision in a season-opening loss in Los Angeles on Monday, and
he threw 123 this time, including 83 strikes. He walked two
Saturday night as compared with six on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That right there was a big difference,'' Johnson said. ``This
was a good win for the team after a couple of heartbreaking losses.
Those are part of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win our share of games coming back like people
came back on us. Tonight, all the guys battled out there for me and
scored some runs for me. That makes it a lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still made some big mistakes today. I went against the book
a couple of times and found that the book was right. But I was able
to adjust. I don't know the hitters (in the National League) like I
would like to, but I think I'll make the adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson relied on his trademark fastball that reached speeds of
97 mph, but it was his slider that had the Braves twisting like a
pretzel, usually swinging and missing. Only Brian Hunter and
Chipper Jones did significant damage to Johnson, hitting solo
homers in the second and sixth innings, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get three off him, you've put in a good night's work,''
Braves Manager Bobby Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Said outfielder Brian Jordan, who had two hits off Johnson: ``If
you don't get to him early, you're in trouble. We didn't get enough
of him, and he was dominating.''
</P>
<P>
   On the field, Braves second baseman Bret Boone was lamenting to
Arizona third baseman Matt Williams about the slider's virtual
invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him about the time I was with Cleveland and Kevin
Seitzer had an 0-2 count against Randy (who was with Seattle),''
Williams said. ``The slider looks almost the same as a fastball
leaving his hand, and Kevin was so far out in front of it that when
he took a big cut and missed, the ball hit his front knee and he
went down.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Damian Miller, who came up with three hits and a pair of
RBIs, enjoyed the performance, up close and personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd see Randy on TV strike out what seemed like 30 guys and
you would think, `Man, I'd like to be a part of that sometime,' ''
Miller said. ``You see him stare from behind that glove and even as
a catcher you say, `Wow, this guy means business.' He threw a lot
of sliders today, and they were nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was locked in a 2-2 duel with Atlanta left-hander Tom
Glavine, the 1998 NL Cy Young Award winner, for the first three
innings. Arizona's two runs came in the second on Bernard Gilkey's
one-out solo home run and an RBI double by Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The hit scored shortstop Tony Batista, who had singled. Batista,
who began the season 0-14 entering Friday night's game, went on to
record four more hits, including a solo homer in the fourth, giving
him a club record seven in a row going back to Friday night. He
also had four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Batista and Miller combined to produce two more runs in the
sixth. Williams, who had three hits, including two doubles, drove
in one run in the seventh and Batista another. Batista drove in
Williams again in the ninth for Arizona's final run.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter said it was good to get the first
victory, particularly since the Braves are one of the top-hitting
clubs in the league, but ``it won't mean anything in less than 24
hours, because we'll be going up against Greg Maddux. Although come
to think of it, it's better than the alternative.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
