r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     04-11 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' OFFENSE PACKS A WALLOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ All winter there was talk the Angels needed
another starting pitcher _ someone who could eat up valuable
innings and give the club a chance to win. Omar Olivares thought he
was the guy for the job all along, so he remained patient and
Saturday night he got his chance to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares (1-0) produced the best pitching performance by an
Angels starter this season, throwing 71/3 scoreless innings in the
Angels' 10-0 victory over the Texas Rangers before 37,974 at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense made things easy for Olivares, getting 19
hits, including four each by Randy Velarde and Garret Anderson. But
Olivares, the No. 5 man in the starting rotation, obviously didn't
need it all.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got only three hits off him and only one Rangers
baserunner even got as far as second base. The key for Olivares is
control, and Saturday he walked only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's had trouble, it's when he'd walk guys, because he's
not a strikeout pitcher,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said.
``Tonight if somebody got on base, he made big pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about guys you know. . . . If these guys step up and
give you more than you anticipate, it's a surprise. Rick Helling
was a surprise last year because he won 20 games (for Texas). I'm
not saying Omar's going to win 20, but if he pitches consistently
he's going to win a lot for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Rangers, Helling (0-2) pitched the way he
did in his first start this season in an 11-5 loss to the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Helling lasted only 32/3 innings Saturday, getting yanked in the
fourth after allowing six runs and nine hits. The Angels did not
put together a big inning, never scoring more than two in a frame.
But they scored at least once in every inning except the seventh
and ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde was a big part of it, getting a single in the first, a
two-run single in the fourth, a single and run scored in the sixth,
and a single in the seventh. But he wasn't about to pat himself on
the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised because traditionally I'm a slow starter in
April,'' he said. ``All of a sudden I'm getting all these hits, so
I'll take advantage of it. You know how this game is _ you don't
own it, you rent it.
</P>
<P>
   When Todd Greene singled with one out in the fifth inning, every
Angels starter had at least one hit. Besides Velarde and Anderson,
Orlando Palmeiro, Tim Salmon, Troy Glaus, Greene and Matt Walbeck
all had two hits apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Angels would like to have Mo Vaughn, Jim Edmonds and
Gary DiSarcina in the lineup. But they insist it isn't that bad
without them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hear anybody talking about it,'' Anderson said.
``They're gone. What are you going to do? We're not going to sit
here and cry, because the next thing you know we'll be 2-20. . . .
People always talk about what we don't have instead of (the players
we can) field every day. But we have a pretty good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the Angels' 19 hits were singles, and they didn't
hit even one home run. But they scored runs by moving runners and
putting the ball into play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we've got to do,'' Collins said. ``We should
always play that way anyway. We've got guys that can do some
damage, but we have to do the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had everything today,'' Olivares said. ``Great hitting,
good defense, good pitching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
