r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOCKEY-ARENA-AZR &LR;      04-11 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEY-ARENA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE LINES DRAWN AS HOCKEY ARENA VOTE NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL SOWERS AND DIANA BALAZS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It appeared at first that opponents of a Phoenix Coyotes arena
in south Scottsdale would finance their ``vote no'' campaign by
selling 75-cent cookies and $4 yard-sale dresses.
</P>
<P>
   With just weeks left before a crucial May 18 vote on the
project, they were counting their pennies, up against the hockey
team, a high-profile developer willing to spend more than $100,000
on ads and a savvy political consultant from Dallas with a track
record for delivering ``yes'' votes.
</P>
<P>
   Cookies vs. cash. Goliath on a power play.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, the gap narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   Business interests that might be razed to make way for the $624
million redevelopment of Los Arcos Mall announced that they could
pledge at least $50,000 to A Better Way, a new umbrella
organization for anti-arena factions.
</P>
<P>
   The group was forged after project advocates changed their name
from Don't Let Los Arcos Die to Vote Yes Scottsdale. The
name-changing underscores the high emotion and dizzying stakes
riding on the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In five weeks, Scottsdale residents will decide whether to
approve the formation of a stadium district, a tax-supported plan
that could pave the way for a massive makeover of the fading Los
Arcos into a sports-entertainment complex anchored by the Coyotes'
National Hockey League arena.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale voters aren't the only ones being asked to give
thumbs up or down to sports-entertainment meccas. Mesa residents
will go to the polls on May 18 to vote on a city sales-tax hike to
help pay for a $1.8 billion convention complex and football stadium
for the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In Scottsdale, a yes vote would mean about $100 million in
state sales taxes generated in the project over the next decade
would go to the Ellman Cos. and the Coyotes. They say they need the
money to transform the area around Los Arcos into an inviting
collection of shops, restaurants, a convention center and a hotel.
Without the tax break, they warn that Los Arcos will decay further
into ``empty and run-down storefronts.''
</P>
<P>
   Not true, say A Better Way and other opponents.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that a yes vote would destroy a neighborhood by
erecting looming parking garages and a too-tall arena. And they
condemn stadium districts as flagrant corporate welfare, benefiting
the rich and diverting state tax money needed for schools and other
services. They disagree with promoters' insistence that Los Arcos
needs an arena to seduce other businesses and free-spending
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of other plans out there,'' said Alan
Kaufman, a Scottsdale lawyer, chairman of A Better Way.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming vote could do more than determine the fate of the
arena or the makeover of the Los Arcos area. It could also decide
whether the Coyotes move to Scottsdale or stay in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have long been dissatisfied with America West Arena,
where 4,300 seats have a limited view of the action on the ice. But
if Scottsdale voters turn down the stadium district, an
entertainment group headed by producer Barry Kemp has offered to
buy the team and keep it in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes owner Richard Burke says he hasn't accepted the offer
and is confident that Scottsdale voters will welcome his team and a
new Los Arcos.
</P>
<P>
   A Better Way wants to make sure that doesn't happen. Now with a
bigger bankroll, the group won't have to depend on bake sales'
profits to pay for television and newspaper ads, or campaign signs
and brochures to try to persuade voters to defeat the stadium
district.
</P>
<P>
   The emotion roiling around the project is not limited to south
Scottsdale. The Coalition of Pinnacle Peak, a powerful slow-growth
faction from north Scottsdale, also is pledging money to help
defeat the stadium district. Its target is ``irresponsible
development, and they think the arena fits that category,'' said
Kaufman, also a COPP member.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the new infusion of green, A Better Way is likely to
be outspent by the pro-project groups 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kaufman, senior vice presi dent for the Ellman Cos. and no
relation to Alan Kaufman, says his company and the Coyotes and
other contributors plan to spend ``north of $100,000'' on the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Ellman Cos. came off the bench early with television ads in
December. They have also taken out full-page newspaper ads, planted
a thicket of signs throughout Scottsdale and hired political
consultant Carol Reed, who helped win voter approval of the $230
million American Airlines Center in Dallas, set to open in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters are orchestrating their publicity blitz from a pair
of rent-free offices in the largely Ellman-owned Los Arcos Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Action shots of the Coyotes decorate one of the offices. Inside,
volunteers and paid staffers answer phones and punch voter
information into computers.
</P>
<P>
   In an adjoining office, Mark Booth, a paid staffer, answers
questions from visitor Andrew Young, a hockey fan. Pastel drawings
of the entertainment-sports complex are displayed like artwork on
easels, depicting lush landscaping, a home-entertainment and
grocery store, restaurants, movie theaters, a convention center,
500-room hotel and a 20,000-seat arena.
</P>
<P>
   When Young noticed that a giant screen would beam arena events
into the mall, he was pumped. ``No kidding? That would be great,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Young plans to vote yes May 18.
</P>
<P>
   But project opponents worry about what a yes vote will mean to
people like Kathryn Crittenden, 85, who lives at what they call
ground zero, the home closest to the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sick about it,'' said Crittenden, who has a ``No
Arena'' sign in her manicured front yard.
</P>
<P>
   There's no hope that project backers will win over Crittenden
and voters like her. But both campaigns may have a chance with the
undecideds, including Mike Thomas, who lives about two miles from
Los Arcos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed emotions,'' he said. ``I realize that Los Arcos
has been a negative area for Scottsdale. But some residents here
stand to lose a lot from it. I don't think the needs of the
residents have been addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides claim converts.
</P>
<P>
   The pro faction points to Lynn Doiron, who lives a mile east and
a mile north of Los Arcos. Undecided at first, she now says the
project makes sense. In a show of support, she planted a pro-arena
sign in her yard. The next day, it had been strung with toilet
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Such strong feelings mean votes, and both groups want to get
their messages out by April 19, when early ballots become
available.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the project is just as much about taxes as it is
about hockey or convention centers or a grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge facing both groups is untangling the complex
stadium-district law for confused voters. A Better Way says stadium
districts are tax giveaways for developers. Worse, it says, the
districts are immune from certain property taxes and, with city and
court approval, can condemn businesses, more than 50 in the
redevelopment boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Vote Yes Scottsdale argues that the tax breaks will be a
windfall for Scottsdale and triple the state sales-tax revenues
that sagging Los Arcos generates. And it points out that
condemnation has long been a tool for redevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, developers keep half the state sales taxes
generated in the new complex for 10 years. Ellman Cos. says that
would mean $10 million a year over the next decade, money used to
help pay for free parking garages and the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   The other $10 million half in state sales-tax revenues would be
new money to be returned to the state for schools and other
services.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan of project supporters _ ``No New Taxes'' _ is a clear
attempt to distance their plan from the Bank One Ballpark in
Phoenix, which was partly funded by a quarter-cent increase in
Maricopa County sales tax. The hike, which voters didn't get a
chance to vote on, soured many voters countywide on using public
money to build stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   The Ellman Cos. and Coyotes are planning to invest about $400
million in the project, including $140 million for the arena. Even
with the state sales-tax money, the developers will be $120 million
short, and have said they will ask for a share of city sales taxes
produced in the new complex to help fill the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our challenge,'' said Ellman's Bob Kaufman. ``We are
working with Scottsdale to make that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether Scottsdale can take up the slack is uncertain. The
thought of ``well-heeled developers'' using tax money enrages
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to build an arena, let them pay for it
themselves,'' Alan Kaufman said, adding that diverting state taxes
could sap money from education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools, not skates,'' he said, voicing an anti-arena anthem.
</P>
<P>
   He says opponents don't object to a new mall to revive south
Scottsdale, but one built without an arena and tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these arenas are so attractive,'' he asked, ``wouldn't a
bank finance it?''
</P>
<P>
   But Bud Sampson, who has owned a rental business in south
Scottsdale for more than 30 years, says the sports-entertainment
complex would be a big score for the long-neglected Los Arcos area.
</P>
<P>
   This project, he said, would ``make it a destination for people
to go to.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 0127EDT &QL; 
