<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS COACH NOT AFRAID TO BENCH STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Kurt Rambis may have a short tenure as the Lakers head coach,
but at least he's going to do the job on his terms, interim tag or
not.
</P>
<P>
   In a day when many league superstars influence coaching
decisions, practice routines and personnel moves, Rambis has taken
a stand. He has shown he's more than willing to seat both his
superstars,
 &UR; Shaquille O'Neal and  &UR; Kobe Bryant, next to him on the bench if
they're not getting the job done.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis has been pulling O'Neal in late-game situations because
he can't be counted on to hit free throws, such as a game at
Phoenix in which the Suns began fouling O'Neal away from the ball
just to make him shoot.  &UR; Glen Rice won the game with a baseline
jumper as O'Neal watched from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   And in a game against Utah, Rambis yanked Bryant, who was
getting torched by Jazz forward  &UR; Shandon Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine with it,'' Bryant told Los Angeles reporters after
the move. ``I told Kurt, `Man, I'm with you.' Now, obviously, I
don't like getting taken out of the game at any point. You want to
play. But I'm always with Kurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Kurt because he has the (guts) to make those types
of decisions. A lot of coaches, they would just panic and say, `OK,
regardless of what's going on, regardless of the mistakes that
you're making, I'm just going to stick with you, because if we
lose, I can say we lost with our best guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt, he really doesn't care about any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Rambis have met and talked about Rambis' decision to
avoid ``Hack-a-Shaq'' tactics that teams have employed, and he also
has taken forward  &UR; Dennis Rodman off the floor for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis and O'Neal say they have cleared the air, but it's clear
O'Neal does not like the strategy _ which Rambis employed again
Friday night against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a player, Kurt is the coach,'' O'Neal said early last
week. ``Whatever he decides to do, I'll always be behind him. But
keep in mind, in any relationship, we're going to have arguments. I
mean, I wouldn't want to date anybody not having any arguments.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, O'Neal may thank Rambis, who is either going to
force O'Neal to improve his free-throw shooting or go down trying.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is a career 53.5 percent free-throw shooter, and he knows
teams are going to intentionally foul him with the game on the line
to try to make him beat them with his weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, probably,'' O'Neal said. ``But I'd rather get the chance
to prove myself. I've been in that situation before, and I've
knocked them down. I want to prove myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I miss a shot and lose a game, I'll take the blame. And
I'll come back and try to be better next game. But I'd rather be
put in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis, however, is trying to give his entire team the best
chance to win. For that, he deserves respect _ even from his stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine,'' Rambis said of his relationship with O'Neal.
``He's fine. I know where he's coming from, he knows where I'm
coming from. My ballplayers can speak their mind with me.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has been out early before games working on his free
throws, and he has told reporters he's trying to go back to the
shooting technique he used early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize I have to step that part of my game up,'' O'Neal
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis said he thought O'Neal could improve dramatically, and
maybe that's why he's forcing O'Neal to work on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's capable of being between 65 and 70 (percent),''
Rambis said. ``I think that's fairly realistic. But I am in no way
putting any pressure on him. I think he is capable of getting to
that level.''
</P>
<P>
   The underachieving Lakers may not realize it, but Rambis'
approach is exactly what they need. &QL; 
It could be worse &QL; 
At least Rambis doesn't have  &UR; Paul Westphal's &UR; headaches in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal has had to endure a report from ESPN, apparently
unfounded, that the Sonics were ready to mutiny and wanted
assistant  &UR; Nate
 &UR; McMillan to replace Westphal, who is in the first year of a
three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   And his two stars,  &UR; Vin Baker and  &UR; Gary Payton, got into a
heated argument during a practice the day before Baker returned
from the injured list because of torn thumb ligaments.
</P>
<P>
   During a scrimmage, Baker and Payton reportedly began arguing,
with Payton calling Baker a ``fat (expletive)'' and a ``fake
All-Star.'' At one point, Baker reportedly said, ``So this is
getting personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, yeah.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the two downplayed the incident, as did Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just Gary and I being competitive,'' Baker said. ``Gary
and I are the best of friends. We're like brothers. We're not going
to let one incident in practice break us apart. We talked it over,
and it's washed.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said, ``Crazy, stupid things happen in basketball all
the time,'' citing the time he had to make a run for it from an
angered
 &UR; Steve Kuberski during a Boston Celtics' practice and another time
in which  &UR; Charles Barkley pounded on  &UR; Oliver Miller during a Suns
workout. &QL; 
Labels &QL; 
Charlotte interim Coach  &UR; Paul Silas has his sights set on keeping
the job permanently, although the possible sale of at least half
interest in the team to  &UR; Michael Jordan could have an impact on his
future.
</P>
<P>
   But Silas has the Hornets playing respectably again, with the
help of the  &UR; Glen Rice trade that brought  &UR; Eddie Jones and  &UR; Elden
Campbell from the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Silas' name often pops up in coaching searches, but he hasn't
had a head coaching job since he guided the 1982-83 San Diego
Clippers. Silas said he thought he had been labeled as a career
assistant. He got interviews in Chicago, Seattle and Sacramento
last summer, but no offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a stigma, but it is a perception,'' said Silas, a
former Phoenix assistant. ``And it's hard to take. But (good)
things happen when you least expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornets Vice President  &UR; Bob Bass reportedly has told Silas his
future depends on three factors: wins, improvement and how players
relate to him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's if Bass is calling the shots when the time for
a decision comes. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob Young can be
reached at (602) 444-8271 or at bob.young(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
