<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-PLAYOFFS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME ICE ON THE LINE  
 COYOTES CAN CINCH 4TH SEED WITH WIN IN ANAHEIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Is it really a race to catch Phoenix for the fourth
seed in the Western Conference and the home-ice advantage in the
first round of the NHL playoffs that goes along with it?
</P>
<P>
   Or, is it a three-way dogfight between St. Louis, Anaheim, and
San Jose to win the fifth playoff spot and a match up with the
Coyotes, instead of a playoff meeting with Colorado or Detroit,
which will meet the sixth and seventh place finishers?
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes can eliminate themselves from this scrambled scene
with a win over the Mighty Ducks tonight at Arrowhead Pond, which
would clinch fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, with 88 points, holds a seven-point edge over St. Louis
and an eight-point margin over the Mighty Ducks with four games
remaining for each team. Any Phoenix win, or a loss by St. Louis
and Anaheim, makes it mathematically impossible for the Coyotes to
be caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it (fourth) is in our hands,'' Coyotes defenseman
Keith Carney said. ``If we concentrate on playing our game and
playing it well, it will take care of itself. I think we are going
to be playing our kind of hockey the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   But Phoenix doesn't have a cake walk ahead. After tonight's
meeting with Anaheim, the Coyotes travel to Dallas, which has
clinched the best record in the NHL, then come home to host St.
Louis and Dallas. Four very loseable hockey games.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the coin is the mad scramble going on for
the fifth, sixth and seventh positions; a race separated by a grand
total of two points.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis has 81 points, followed by the suddenly sagging Mighty
Ducks at 80. San Jose is right behind with 79, although the Sharks
have only three games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Phoenix tonight, the Mighty Ducks host St. Louis
on Wednesday, travel to crosstown Los Angeles on Thursday and close
the season Saturday in San Jose. St. Louis meets Colorado today,
then goes to Anaheim, visits Phoenix and closes the year at LA.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose finishes on home ice. The Sharks host Edmonton, which
has opened a three-point edge over Calgary for the eighth playoff
spot, Los Angeles and the Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Trends of late? The Coyotes have lost two straight at home and
are 2-3 in their past five. St. Louis and San Jose are 5-3-2 in
their past 10 outings, while the Mighty Ducks have gone 1-4-1 in
their past six, and are 0-3-1 since clinching a playoff spot April
2 against the Rangers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While the Coyotes were busy blowing a 4-3 decision to Nashville
on Friday night, the Mighty Ducks were putting on a fowl
performance themselves in a 4-1 loss at home to San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were awful,'' star Paul Kariya told the ``Los Angeles
Times'' after the game. ``We didn't do what we talked about. We
didn't work. We didn't play the systems right. You can't win like
this. You can't play like this and expect to win in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has got to give each other a kick in the butt and
get going. We have to get things in gear. You play soft and cheat
for scoring chances in the playoffs and team will kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   If one didn't know better, Kariya could have been standing in
the Phoenix locker room Friday night, doing a perfect imitation of
any one of several Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Think not? A few words from Mr. Carney, explaining the Nashville
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took it too easy and played down to their level,'' he said,
disgustedly. ``Even though we had the lead and were in control, we
just didn't put them away. It's disappointing. We want to win games
at this point. We came out hard but didn't sustain it for 60
minutes, which is inexcusable at this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideal situation for the Coyotes would be to close out
speculation about the fourth seed tonight, enabling them to rest
some players this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we need rest,'' Carney said. ``Our schedule
hasn't been that tough recently; it has been pretty easy on us, and
we'll probably have four or five days off before the playoffs
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more important that we get to playing well and playing
our kind of hockey for 60 minutes. We want to be playing our best
going into the playoffs and have everybody's confidence up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
