<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3725 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOTBALL-STADIUM-AZR &LR;      04-11 1663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-STADIUM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE OF PRO FOOTBALL-CONVENTION COMPLEX TOO CLOSE TO CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBBIE SHERWOOD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Voters in Mesa, Gilbert and Queen Creek will go to the polls in
a little more than five weeks to answer the $1.8 billion question:
Hitch or ditch?
</P>
<P>
   Will the East Valley hitch its economic and cultural wagon to
the massive Rio Salado Crossing convention center and football
stadium, or ditch the notion of spending tax money for a
professional sports and convention complex?
</P>
<P>
   Mesa, the nation's 51st-largest city and growing, stands to shed
its non-image as an average city and proud of it to create a name
for itself as a big-time convention destination and Super Bowl
playground, supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   Rio Salado Crossing opponents in Mesa like their city as it is
and loathe the use of taxpayer money to benefit the Arizona
Cardinals. As the May 18 vote nears, the competition for the
relatively few available votes is growing intense, but not in the
way usually associated with big-ticket campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   You won't be hearing television and radio ads about this vote.
The Rio Salado Crossing campaign is well-funded, with the Cardinals
as primary bankroller, but it's not so fat it can waste backfields
of cash selling a stadium to 2 million Maricopa County residents
who can't vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   Only the 219,000 registered voters of Mesa, Gilbert and Queen
Creek can decide the project's fate.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, supporters have adopted a more passive-aggressive
strategy. They're engaged in an intensive person-to-person campaign
that injects the pro-stadium stand into just about any crowd that
gathers in the three voting cities. And they're trying to lock in
``yes'' votes through a concerted push for early voting by mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I see two guys at a bus stop, I'm there talking to them,''
said Kerry Dunne, director of the Rio Salado Crossing Association
and the East Valley Partnership, which supports the project.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign booths were noticeable additions to Chicago Cubs
spring-training games in Mesa and such events as the Airshow
Spectacular at Williams Gateway Airport. Supporters recently
mass-mailed a videotape touting the project, and they meet with up
to four civic organizations, church groups and unions a day.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was enough to snare the attention of Marc
Jablonowski and family last month at Mesa's Chicagofest blues
festival. A large-scale model of the futuristic Rio Salado Crossing
stadium and convention center was declared cool by Jablonowski's
two young sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's cool, too,'' said Jablonowski, 32, a Mesa
resident who works in electronics. ``If it were just a stadium, I'd
say no way. But I think this is a good economic idea. I travel to a
lot of seminars, and the convention business is huge.''
</P>
<P>
   A campaign staff member of Yes! On Rio Salado Crossing stood
nearby, poised to answer any questions or help potential voters
sign pledges to vote for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The message struck the wrong note with Brian McCord, 38, of
Mesa, who was also at the blues festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can find some way to build it other than raising
taxes, it would be a better idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State University political pollster Bruce Merrill
describes the stadium backers' strategy of attending sporting and
recreational events as preaching to the converts. It's the wisest
move, he said, with recent polls putting supporters slightly
behind. Voter turnout is expected to be low.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a low turnout, generally it's a matter of who goes to the
polls and who doesn't,'' Merrill said. ``It's in (stadium backers')
interest to go get their people out to vote and not make this a
controversial thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to whether it's going to fail is whether opponents can
have any kind of focused opposition. They need to have a
respectable group or coalition come out against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers Against Rio Salado is the small but feisty group
taking up the challenge. Its members dog the Yes! On Rio Salado
Crossing crowd at as many stops as they can.
</P>
<P>
   The Yes! campaign's budget has exceeded $250,000; &UR; Against
chairman Manny Cortez would be thrilled if his reached four. But
the group has some political muscle. State Sens. Rusty Bowers and
Tom Freestone, as well as Mesa City Council members Keno Hawker and
John Giles, have declared war on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers instigated a move to kill legislative amendments that
stadium supporters need to make their financing plan work.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium-district law allows a project's developer to
recapture 50 percent of the state sales tax the project generates
for 10 years. Rio Salado Crossing supporters want permission to
begin the 10-year recapture during the construction phase. The law
doesn't address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Backers expect the amendments to pass eventually. But even if
they're killed, stadium district chairman Marty Whalen said, the
election will go on. It would get more expensive, however, as the
project likely would face lawsuits, or have to shop for a judge's
legal opinion supporting the early recapture.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents made their strongest showing to date during
Chicagofest at Riverview Park _ a fitting site, because the
convention facility and its surrounding shopping plazas, golf
courses and canal walks would occupy this area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not against the stadium, we're just against using tax
money for private enterprise,'' Jan Gurtin said from a makeshift
protest area.
</P>
<P>
   She and Art Kauffman of Sun City, who led anti-stadium efforts
against Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix, handed out protest fliers.
Gurtin isn't from one of the voting cities, but has offered her
services to fight the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Tempe, and originally this was going to be built in
both cities, so I came down to help out,'' Gurtin said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents couldn't match the endless supply of pro-stadium
stickers and brochures, the glossy display or the cool scale model.
They fought back with Vince Fantozzi, who donned a Cardinals
football helmet and paraded around Chicagofest with a bright-red
sign board that read ``You: play. Me: pay. That's fair, right? Give
me your lunch money, kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also gave away about three dozen T-shirts. It cost
them $236, leaving the campaign with about $600 in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Yes! On Rio Salado Crossing has spent nearly $200,000, according
to campaign finance reports. Rio Salado Association's Dunne said
the campaign signed up at least 1,200 new supporters during the
three-day Chicagofest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a David and Goliath situation,'' Cortez acknowledged.
``But so what? David won, didn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters plan to pick up the pace in coming weeks,
distributing 4- by 4-foot campaign signs, Yes! bumper stickers and
displays that can be set up inside sports bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put on the gas,'' said Brad Wright, executive
director of Yes! On Rio Salado Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of radio and TV, supporters and opponents alike
have turned to direct mail and early voting.
</P>
<P>
   The Yes! campaign has been gathering pledges of support since
before the project was put on the ballot, and it now has a database
of thousands of promised yes votes. Those supporters will be mailed
request forms for early voting ballots, courtesy of Yes! On Rio
Salado Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Project opponents want traditionally anti-tax retirees to vote
before they leave for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium foe Bob Powers said supporters ``make it extremely easy
to vote yes on this, so we have to work to get the people who are
not in favor to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Early voting could be key to the campaign. Since the state
changed the law in 1991, making it unnecessary to provide a reason
to receive an early ballot, voting by mail in Mesa elections has
grown from 700 ballots in 1994 to 13,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The county will mail out early ballots beginning Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dunne said, the campaign's focus will continue to be
face-to-face meetings to explain how the project works.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' presence in the campaign has been ubiquitous and
understated. Most of the funding for the campaign is coming from
the Cardinals' checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have also hosted events where stadium campaigners
do their thing, and the team is at least a supportive presence at
most of the events targeted by the campaign. But Cardinals vice
president Michael Bidwill shies from taking a leading campaign
role.
</P>
<P>
   ```We are part of the project and it's important to us,''
Bidwill said, ``but there are also many other parts to this project
which the community and some leaders are taking an active role
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The pro-stadium campaign's most consistent presence so far was
at Mesa's HoHoKam Park during Cactus League games. Campaign
volunteers or former Cardinals players, such as Garth Jax, engaged
Cubs fans strolling by or stopping at the condiment carts.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Riverview Park, C.A. Cole listened to a campaign spiel
and looked over the model stadium but remained unswayed. The
72-year-old retiree lives less than a mile from the park's lake and
ballfields and doesn't want to see them replaced with restaurants,
privately owned golf courses and, least of all, a behemoth stadium
and convention center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too many families that enjoy this park to put in a
commercial venture like this,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Right behind him stood Joe and Kathy McCabe of Phoenix, who wish
they could vote on the project. Joe drives a van for SuperShuttle.
He predicts a huge boost to business with a convention center just
six freeway miles from Sky Harbor International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just don't realize the economic impact of the
convention business in the Valley,'' Joe said. ``But I see it
firsthand, and I see what Scottsdale gets at all those hotels. To
be honest with you, I don't like the economic blackmail of the NFL
offering the Super Bowl if the project passes, but I still think
it's a great project.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
