<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3726 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-COWBOYS-TEX     04-11 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS GO WITH NEW DRAFT STRATEGY THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys scouting director Larry Lacewell's
office sits on one side of the team's Valley Ranch headquarters,
far away from the cozy confines of Cowboys owner/general manager
Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell might be 62 years old, but he hears very well.
</P>
<P>
   From his position, the criticism leveled at Jones for the
Cowboys' drafts the past five years are really grievances against
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry needs a football man, they say,'' Lacewell said. ``I've
been in this business for 43 years. I think I know a little bit
about football.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson, who has credited Lacewell
with teaching him more about football than any other person.
</P>
<P>
   So what gives with the Cowboys' draft shortfalls since Johnson's
bitter departure as coach after the 1993 season? Forty-four picks
in the past five drafts have resulted in just six starters and just
one Pro Bowl-caliber performer, tackle Larry Allen.
</P>
<P>
   And what hope do Cowboys fans have that things will be different
in the 1999 draft next weekend?
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell points to a change in philosophy, born partially out of
necessity and partially out of design.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, he said, are going into the draft looking to take
``the best athlete available'' with their top pick rather than
trying to fill a specific need, as they've done in recent years.
The Cowboys, who have eight selections, own the 22nd pick in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful feeling,'' said Lacewell of the best-athlete
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell said the Cowboys are in that position because they've
worked to address their most pressing needs in free agency. The
Cowboys are confident wide receiver Raghib Ismail, linebacker
Quentin Coryatt and center Mark Stepnoski, all free agents, will
sign with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it happens very often that you are in position
to draft the best athlete,'' Lacewell said. ``This day and age with
the cap and free agency, when you lose a player and you need to go
get a guy. It goes back to the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said the Cowboys have no choice but to
adopt that credo because of their low-draft position.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we pick, you can't look at a certain position because you
don't know what you are going to get at 22,'' Gailey said. ``You
have to take the best athlete available.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' top pick could come from one of five positions _
wide receiver, offensive line, defensive line, linebacker and
defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   The team slightly tipped its hand about which positions it
covets the most this past weekend when it hosted 20 prospects for a
visit. The group was dominated by linebackers, wide receivers and
defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Among the top players who could slide to the Cowboys at No. 22
are Tennessee linebacker Al Wilson, LSU defensive tackle Anthony
McFarland and receivers Troy Edwards of Louisiana Tech and Kevin
Johnson of Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell, who said the Cowboys aren't leaning in any direction,
is just glad to have options. And while he said some of the
criticism the Cowboys have received for their drafts is unfair, he
acknowledges some mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a blind ego,'' Lacewell said. ``We know we made
mistakes, and mistakes are part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell said part of the team's problems the past five years
was that few starting spots were open. Shante Carver was brought in
to back up defensive end Charles Haley in 1994. In 1995, running
back Sherman Williams was drafted to be a backup for Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't explain the team's No. 1 pick in 1996, however. The
Cowboys wanted Texas defensive end Tony Brackens, but gambled that
they could move down into the second round and get him and
linebacker Randall Godfrey. Jacksonville nabbed Brackens, forcing
the Cowboys to ``reach'' for Kavika Pittman with their first pick
because of their need for an end.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman's slow development has caused the Cowboys to continue to
be haunted by that decision. Last year, they again took a defensive
end, Greg Ellis, with their top pick, the third time in five years
they've used their first pick on a defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Just seven players remain on the team from the 26 taken in the
1994, 1995 and 1996 drafts combined. If not for Allen, 1994 might
have been one of the worst drafts in Cowboys history.
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell said the Cowboys have learned and moved forward _
pointing to solid draft classes of 1997 and 1998, though they
drafted for need first both years. All nine picks in 1997 made the
team as rookies and the top two picks _ tight end David LaFleur
(first round) and linebacker Dexter Coakley (second round) _ are
firmly entrenched as starters. Only five of those players are still
on the roster, however.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the nine from last season are still on the team. Ellis
started as a rookie and is considered to be a longtime fixture on
the Cowboys' defensive line. Second-round pick Flozell Adams, an
offensive lineman, might the best selection since Allen. He started
10 games as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Of Adams, Lacewell says it was a case of the Cowboys being
patient that he would be available in the second round and then
``taking the best player available.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what they plan to do for the entire draft this time
around.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
