A3727 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-DRUGS-DAVIS-     04-11 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-DRUGS-DAVIS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BREAK DOWN THAT STARTED IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The beginning of the 1987 drug investigation and
attempted prosecution of Suns players by Valley law enforcement
authorities can be traced to an earlier date and a different city.
</P>
<P>
   The day: Dec. 12, 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The place: Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   That's the when and where of Walter Davis' first reported
problems with cocaine. The day after Davis scored a career-high 47
points in a Suns victory at Golden State, he notified the NBA that
he wanted treatment for cocaine and alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Al Bianchi remembers the day, perhaps the most stunning in the
30-year history of the Suns. At the time, Bianchi was a Suns
assistant to then-head coach John MacLeod.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the Suns' career leading scorer, could not be reached for
comment. He is living in Denver, where he played for the Nuggets
from 1988 through 1992. He then worked as a broadcaster for the
Nuggets and had been part of the team's community-relations
department until last year.
</P>
<P>
   Davis missed the Suns' flight on the morning after his brilliant
play at Golden State. In those days, NBA teams flew commercial,
instead of charter.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, he had been seen by teammates in a bar at an
Oakland hotel near the airport. The Suns and other visiting NBA
teams stayed there in those days.
</P>
<P>
   The bar was a notorious nightspot that always was jammed after
Golden State games. The place was jokingly compared with the weird
bar crowd in ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis left the bar near closing time and, as it turned out,
wasn't seen again by his teammates for nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, not much was thought about his absence. On the
morning of Dec. 13, the Suns flew from Oakland to Los Angeles,
where they were scheduled to play the Lakers that night. There were
plenty of flights. The assumption was that Davis would board a
later one, pay a fine and be in uniform at tip-off.
</P>
<P>
   But by midday, it was clear there were problems.
</P>
<P>
   MacLeod sent Bianchi back to Oakland. Bianchi, now a Suns scout,
remembers that he found Davis in his Oakland hotel room with Al
Attles, then Golden State's general manager. Attles had rushed to
help when he heard Davis was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was literally sobbing,'' Bianchi said of the 6-foot-6
swingman, whose jersey, No. 6, hangs high above the seats at
America West Arena. It was retired by the Suns a couple of years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   From Oakland, Davis went to Van Nuys, Calif., where he entered a
rehabilitation center that had been selected by the NBA upon its
1983 adoption of a drug policy. The league had imposed that policy
after former New York Knicks guard Michael Ray Richardson's widely
publicized substance-abuse problems.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, former Atlanta Hawks forward John Drew and two
former Houston players, Mitchell Wiggins and Lewis Lloyd, underwent
treatment and were eventually suspended by the league before Davis
spent 28 days in rehab. He returned to the Suns on Jan. 13, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a year later, Davis was brought in by
Maricopa County prosecutors and Phoenix police to testify to a
grand jury about where and from whom he had acquired cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Indictments were handed down on April 16 and announced at a news
conference the next day. Davis was back in rehab for a second
28-day stretch that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' drug problems stunned the Suns and Phoenix fans, who saw
him as a model citizen. There were no signs.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, recognition of potential drug problems was not a
skill of most basketball coaches in those days. MacLeod said he
hadn't seen the signs.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, he couldn't have seen them. He didn't know what they
were.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what we know now,'' said Bianchi, a former
Seattle SuperSonics head coach who also was the New York Knicks
general manager from 1987 through 1991. ``If we had, we could have
helped Walter right away.'' &QL; 
Norm Frauenheim can be reached at (602) 444-8259 or
norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
