A3728 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-DRUGS-HIGH-A     04-11 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-DRUGS-HIGH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH'S DEATH STILL PUZZLES AFTER 12 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Johnny High died nearly 12 years ago, but suspicion
that his death was the result of foul play is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   In the early-morning hours of June 13, 1987, High was alone,
driving a blue 1979 Mazda RX-7. The estimated time was 2 a.m.,
according to police reports.
</P>
<P>
   High was traveling east on Jefferson Street about 35 mph. His
vehicle went through the right-hand turn lane at 20th Street and
slammed into a utility pole.
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived at the scene, High, 30, was reported to be
unconscious. He was taken to Maricopa Medical Center, where he died
about 3:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   A toxicology report showed his blood-alcohol level at 0.11
percent. Under Arizona law, drivers with a blood-alcohol level of
0.10 percent are considered intoxicated. According to accident
investigators, High took no evasive action. There were no skid
marks in the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   The Maricopa County Medical Examiner's office ruled that the
death was accidental. According to the report, High suffered a
crushing chest injury when he hit the steering wheel at the moment
of impact. He was not wearing a seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   But the hour of the accident, the relatively low speed and
High's role as a grand jury witness in an ongoing drug case against
former Suns teammates left behind questions. Doubts that still
exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I drive by 20th Street and Jefferson, I wonder what
happened there,'' said Dick Todd, a former police detective who
today runs a Valley drug-screening company.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, High was working part time for Todd in his
investigation business. High sold shoes during the day and worked
as a process server for Todd during the evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Todd recalls that High had begun to complain about threats. The
former Suns guard wasn't specific. But, Todd said, he was worried.
In a tearful interview with Channel 12 before the crash, High said
he had been threatened after it became known that he had provided
damaging information against three people who were indicted.
</P>
<P>
   After his death, Channel 12 sportscaster Mark Curtis said in an
editorial that he was sure High had been murdered. Curtis didn't
provide any solid evidence to support his contention. Curtis said
he continues to believe that High was a victim of foul play.
</P>
<P>
   What really happened?
</P>
<P>
   If anybody knows for certain, he or she hasn't talked.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to retrace High's steps on that fateful night, there
are several scenarios. He was seen at a bar near Chris-Town Mall
and then another one near Metrocenter. There were reports that he
then showed up with an unidentified professional athlete at an
after-hours club in south Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   There also were reports of a car chase on Interstate 10, near
the 16th Street exit. But to this day, a reliable witness to the
accident has never stepped forward. At 2 a.m., there is little
traffic at 20th and Jefferson streets. The site is surrounded by
warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators at the time theorized that High might have fallen
asleep at the wheel. An independent expert, Ed Maciag, ruled out
suicide and/or foul play. A problem with the brakes or some other
mechanism in the vehicle was not reported. In the collision, the
light pole penetrated 21 inches into the nose of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Collins, the Maricopa County attorney at the time, is
convinced High died in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do recall a great deal of controversy about what happened
there,'' said Collins, adding that High's death did some small
damage to the prosecution of his case. ``But the accident report
indicated pretty clearly that he probably fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every little indicator showed that it was not a suicide or a
deliberately caused crash. None of that was there. Every indicator
aligned with the thesis that it was simply an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   But Todd is one among many who remains unconvinced. He said
there is no way to prove exactly what caused the death of High, a
reserve guard for the Suns between 1979 and 1984.
</P>
<P>
   High's grave is in Bessemer, Ala., his hometown, which is
located about 10 miles southwest of Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   One of his former Phoenix teammates, Alvin Scott, said he often
thinks about High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a wall at my house where I keep team photos from my
eight years with the Suns,'' Scott said. ``He was a teammate, a
friend. I remember him that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, no, I never think about what happened on that night.
We'll just never know. There could be a million stories out there.
It'll always be kind of a mystery, I think.'' &QL; 
Norm Frauenheim can be reached at (602) 444-8259 or
norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
