r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-DOLPHINS-TE     04-11 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-DOLPHINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON'S EYE FOR TALENT FREQUENTLY SHOWS IN DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much as he did during his days in Dallas, Miami Dolphins coach
Jimmy Johnson is using a keen eye for talent and multiple picks in
the college draft to build a perennial playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   Since Johnson joined the Dolphins as head coach and general
manager before the 1996 season, he has retooled a roster of old
players, adding eight starters through the draft. According to a
draft formula devised by the Star-Telegram, only the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers have drafted better than Johnson over the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy is the only coach I've worked for that personally
interviews his own assistant coaches and the individual scouts
one-on-one about a particular player _ he knows everything about a
guy on draft day,'' said Tom Braatz, the Dolphins' director of
college scouting.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson often trades down in the draft to obtain extra picks.
With more picks, he has more chances of hitting on a player.
Johnson selected a league-high 26 players in his first two drafts.
With the last of three picks in the fifth round of 1996, he landed
linebacker Zach Thomas, who in 1998 turned out to be the club's
first first-team All-Pro since offensive tackle Richmond Webb and
place-kicker Pete Stoyanovich in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people probably overlooked Zach because of his
height,'' said Braatz of Thomas, who is 5-foot-11. ``Jimmy doesn't
care about height. He cares about whether or not the guy makes
plays. That is his only criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins are still an offensive weapon or two from being
considered a legitimate Super Bowl contender. And this is where
Johnson has had trouble drafting. He has been much more adept at
drafting defensive players than offensive players.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, for example, he wanted to draft Baylor linebacker
James Francis and had to ``settle'' for Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's misjudging of offensive talent has followed him to
Miami. Of the eight starters he has drafted, all but running back
Karim Abdul-Jabbar (third round, 1996) and fullback Stanley
Pritchett (fourth round, 1996) have been defensive players.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas (fifth round, 1996) was a first-team All-Pro in 1998.
Defensive linemen Daryl Gardener (first round, 1996), Jason Taylor
(third round, 1997), and Kenny Mixon (second round, 1998), and
linebacker Derrick Rodgers (third round, 1997) have started at
least 75 percent of the time for a defense that ranked third
overall in 1998. Cornerback Sam Madison led the team in
interceptions in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most of the offensive players Johnson has drafted have not
been productive. Johnson spent a No. 1 on wide receiver Yatil Green
in 1997 and a No. 1 on running back John Avery in 1998. Green,
because of injuries, has not played in an NFL game. Avery fumbled
five times and averaged 3.5 yards per rush as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Dolphins are pleased with their recent drafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to draft the best football player, not the guy who
runs the fastest or is maybe the strongest,'' Braatz said. ``We're
still working, but we'd like to think we've done a good job.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
