<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3731 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZ     04-11 2460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBUTE LONG OVERDUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a wonderful celebration the Atlanta Braves put on Thursday
night to honor the often-forgotten accomplishments of  &UR; Hank Aaron,
who is arguably baseball's greatest living player.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's low-key and dignified manner often made it easy to
overlook the feats of the quiet leader of the Milwaukee/Atlanta
Braves for so many years. Even after he returned to Milwaukee to
finish out his career with the Brewers, he had a way about him that
made that then-young club realize how fortunate they were to be
playing baseball for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a discussion ensues over the greatest players ever,
Aaron's name quite often is left out. It's not because someone
might not believe Aaron belongs on such a list, it's just that his
effortless style often made baseball fans believe he was not giving
his all every moment he was on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Aaron was so gifted he made playing the game look
too easy. He glided through baseball games, never appearing to work
up a sweat. When it's all said and done, Aaron deserves to be
listed among the top five players ever.
</P>
<P>
   Put whoever you want in the other four slots, but Aaron's
accomplishments, highlighted by his major league record 755 home
runs, deserve the most select company.
</P>
<P>
   We should never forget what Aaron went through on and off the
field in the days, weeks and months leading up to his eclipsing
 &UR; Babe Ruth's home run record. That Aaron did not allow us to know
of the pain and exact harshness of some of those ugly letters and
phone calls at the time, speaks volumes about Aaron the man.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he is the epitome of grace and elegance, an equal to
 &UR; Joe
 &UR; DiMaggio in that respect, but someone who went through so much more
grief than most human beings will ever know.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron is a true American hero, more than worthy of all the
praise he has received through the years and someone we should all
make an effort to remember. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Name the nine active players on big-league rosters who have been
with their current club for at least 10 years and have never played
for another major league club. &QL; 
Return of the Bronx Zoo? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tired of  &UR; George Steinbrenner's meddling during the last week,
interim Yankees Manager  &UR; Don Zimmer openly chastised the Yankees
boss as few have during the 27 years since Steinbrenner bought the
Yankees away from CBS for $13 million (who advised CBS on that
deal?).
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Steinbrenner basically insisted  &UR; Hideki Irabu
should have started last Wednesday's game, Zimmer asserted his
intention to defy Steinbrenner and wound up starting  &UR; Ramiro
Mendoza, who turned in eight shutout innings before Irabu pitched a
scoreless ninth in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Steinbrenner) has done a lot of good things for me,'' Zimmer
said. ``He's been good to me, but I always tried to do the right
thing working for George Steinbrenner, too. I can't sit here and be
a little wimp and scared of something. I haven't been scared of my
job in my life, and I'm not scared of it now.''
</P>
<P>
   They are words that so many previous and current employees would
love to tell Steinbrenner. Surprisingly, it's the type of response
Steinbrenner respects more than any other, those who have worked
for him have said. After all, this is a man who basically devours
those who show weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would resign if Steinbrenner tendered an ultimatum,
Zimmer responded, ``It won't be resigning if something happens,
I'll quit. I'm not saying I'm quitting. But there ain't nobody who
is going to tell me one thing and then double-talk on something
else. I mean, I ain't going to buy it.'' &QL; 
The Queen's Zoo? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the New York Mets' 6-2 opening day loss in Florida, the
``New'' ``York Pos''t's back-page headline screamed, ``$75M Flop.''
One caller to the Big Apple's lead sports radio station was
seriously concerned about ``a pattern developing'' that he did not
like.
</P>
<P>
   Almost on cue, the Mets' front office and staff went bonkers
after reading the coverage of their loss, to the point where the
``Post'' ran a second-day story with the headline ``Phillips: It's
Way Too Early To Write Us Off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was humorous,'' Mets General Manager  &UR; Steve Phillips said.
``It was more like, `You've got to be kidding me.' I did not
anticipate that. I guess I should have. That's why it's great to
play in New York. But writing off the whole season seems a little
extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets went out the next two games in Miami and drilled the
Marlins by a combined score of 18-3, causing  &UR; Orel Hershiser to
warn his teammates, ``Don't be too arrogant in your interviews.
It's only one game.'' &QL; 
Mo-mentum &QL; 
The hottest items selling in Orange County have  &UR; Mo Vaughn's name
stamped all over them. T-shirts with ``The Beginning of a New
Mo-llennium,'' are $23 for adults and $20 for kids. A baseball cap
that reads ``Mo-llennium'' runs for $20.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addition of Mo did wonders for us,'' said Angels vice
president of sales and marketing  &UR; Ron Minegar.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Angels made their splash by signing Vaughn
away from the Boston Red Sox, the club sent out pizza boxes to its
season ticket holders. On the top of the box was a smiling picture
of Vaughn. Above were the words, ``We Deliver.'' &QL; 
Lookin' out my back door &QL; 
Los Angeles' $105 million pitcher,  &UR; Kevin Brown, finally recovered
from his initial ``sticker shock'' of the Southern California
housing market and managed to purchase a quaint $3.8 million home
in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The 7,800-square-foot home, which sits on an acre, is described
as ``Country English.'' It belonged to  &UR; John Fogerty, the lead
singer for the 1960s and '70s band Credence Clearwater Revival. It
has seven bedrooms, a pool, a spa and views of the city.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Brown bought the lot next door for $1.5 million. He
is also building a new home on 60 acres in his year-round residence
of Macon, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Sticktoitivness &QL; 
Veteran  &UR; Mike Morgan pitched his way into the record books last
week when he entered a Texas Rangers game, giving him 11 different
clubs he has played for, the most of any athlete in any pro sport.
Morgan was tied with  &UR; Tommy Davis,  &UR; Bob L. Miller and  &UR; Ken Brett.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means somebody wants you, and that's not all bad,'' Morgan
said. ``It might be broken by a guy in this room (pointing to  &UR; Todd
Zeile, who is on his seventh club).''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who made his big-league debut within weeks of graduating
high school in Las Vegas, has played for 22 different managers,
starting with  &UR; Bobby Winkles in Oakland in 1978 and leading all the
way to current Rangers Manager  &UR; Johnny Oates. Some other notable
managers include  &UR; Bobby Cox,  &UR; Cal Ripken Sr.,  &UR; Frank Robinson,
 &UR; Tony La Russa and
 &UR; Tom Kelly. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
The parade of loyalists is led by Baltimore's  &UR; Cal Ripken Jr., and
San Diego's  &UR; Tony Gwynn. Also on the list are Cincinnati's  &UR; Barry
Larkin, Atlanta's  &UR; Tom Glavine, Anaheim's  &UR; Chuck Finley, Seattle's
 &UR; Ken Griffey &UR; Jr. and  &UR; Edgar Martinez, Houston's  &UR; Craig Biggio and
the Cubs'  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Grace. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; That's a lot of history they're fighting: The Chicago Cubs have not
had consecutive winning seasons since  &UR; Leo Durocher managed the
club to that feat in 1970-71. The last time the Cubs posted
back-to-back playoff clubs was 1907-08.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; It's a message, but what kind?: The name of Chicago White Sox
Manager  &UR; Jerry Manuel's pastor is  &UR; Frank Thomas. Honest. ``I was
like, `Dang, I finally met the real  &UR; Frank Thomas,' '' Manuel said.
We're not quite sure what he meant by ``the real'' Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Ron LeFlore.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Cincinnati Bearded Blonds?: Now that the Reds have relaxed
their long-standing facial hair policy, the club had 13 of its 25
opening day players sporting some form of hair on their faces. Six
of the players had colored their hair with peroxide.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The walking man: San Francisco outfielder  &UR; Barry
 &UR; Bonds made his way into the record book last week when he was
intentionally walked for the 290th time in his career, surpassing
 &UR; Hank
 &UR; Aaron for the National League record. With another four intentional
walks, Bonds will pass Aaron for the major league record. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
 &UR; Juan Encarnacion, a leading candidate for AL Rookie of the Year,
slammed a leadoff home run for Detroit in the first inning of the
first game of the season. It was the first time a Detroit leadoff
hitter began a season with a home run since  &UR; Roy Johnson did it for
the 1932 Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Phillies entered the season with 8,260 losses
during the current century, easily the most among any professional
sports franchise, and equates to an average of more than 84 losses
per season. The Phillies' .458 winning percentage is the worst
among the original 16 major league clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The trade that sent reliever  &UR; Bobby Ayala, a Valley resident,
from Seattle to Montreal last week included the Mariners also
agreeing to pay $1.2 million of Ayala's $1.8 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   Short bites from Cubland include  &UR; Henry Rodriguez becoming the
first left fielder to start two straight opening days since  &UR; Brian
Dayett in 1986-'87 and  &UR; Mark Grace joining  &UR; Cap Anson as the only
Cub to start at the same position on opening day an entire decade.
Anson's decade was the 1880s.
</P>
<P>
   When second baseman  &UR; Carlos Feebles and outfielder
 &UR; Carlos Beltran were in Kansas City's opening day lineup, it marked
the first time since 1987 that two rookies were in the Royals'
first lineup of the season. The last time featured third baseman
 &UR; Kevin
 &UR; Seitzer and outfielder  &UR; Bo Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; James Baldwin, who was the Chicago White Sox opening day
starter, is now an incredible 10-0 when pitching in domed stadiums.
Baldwin was the winning pitcher in the White Sox opening day win at
Seattle's Kingdome. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Cleveland was hot and heavy to make a trade with Oakland for
starter  &UR; Kenny Rogers but has apparently cooled on the idea for now
because of Rogers' elbow pains during the spring. The Indians were
talking about sending  &UR; Richie Sexson and  &UR; Dwight Gooden to the
Athletics for Rogers, a deal that could be resurrected in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has targeted pitcher  &UR; Jamie Moyer as its first priority
among pitchers, leaving  &UR; Jeff Fassero's status up in the air for
now. Moyer and the team are close to agreeing to a three-year
extension.
</P>
<P>
   The agent for  &UR; David Wells and the Toronto Blue Jays have begun
negotiations to extend the pitcher's contract beyond this season.
Wells has an extension for 2000 but can be guaranteed a trade after
the season since he was traded in the midst of a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Baltimore starter  &UR; Scott Kamienicki back anytime
soon. His pulled hamstring is still a concern, and the Orioles
aren't counting on the right-hander's return before the first week
of May at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mark Langston, who retired two weeks ago and is now pitching
minor league games for Cleveland, could very well be placed into
the Indians' pitching plans, probably in the bullpen initially,
before the month is out. &QL; 
The final word &QL; 
The Pittsburgh Pirates finally stuck the first shovel in the ground
where PNC Park, their new home starting in 2001, will be built.
This was a franchise on the brink of leaving Pittsburgh not long
ago, which would have been a sad day for all in baseball. The $228
million ballpark will come with a fabulous reminder to all since
the Sixth Street Bridge, which runs from downtown to where the park
will be located, was renamed last week Roberto Clemente Bridge. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. BostonGreat start, but Nomar Garciaparra is ailing again. Not a
good sign.  &QL; 
2. N.Y. YankeesAlready, the Bronx Bombers are flexing their
muscles.  &QL; 
3. San FranciscoNever consider this club out of any game or
divisional race.  &QL; 
4. ClevelandNo reason why the Tribe shouldn't win their fifth
straight division title.  &QL; 
5. AtlantaTroubles ahead? This bullpen is awfully young and
inexperienced.  &QL; 
6. Los AngelesRaul Mondesi's heroics have the Dodgers riding high.
 &QL; 
7. N.Y. MetsHot out of the gate, which can only lead to higher
confidence.  &QL; 
8. Chicago CubsSammy Sosa's not even doing his thing yet.  &QL; 
9. TexasQuite an impressive series in Detroit, especially after
losing the first one. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. Kansas CityIt goes to show that spring training means
absolutely nothing.  &QL; 
29. MinnesotaThe season's one week old, and it's already gotten
ugly in the Twin Cities.  &QL; 
28. OaklandHow many designated hitters can one club have?  &QL; 
27. CincinnatiToo bad starter Pete Harnisch can't pitch every day.
 &QL; 
26. ArizonaThe players' self-confidence is definitely shaken right
now.  &QL; 
25. San DiegoStarting the season in Mexico made no sense at all.  &QL; 
24. TorontoLost to Minnesota while scoring nine runs Thursday.  &QL; 
23. Tampa BayIn two opening days, Wilson Alvarez has given up 12
runs in 5 innings.  &QL; 
22. MontrealIt's so bad that for the first time in 31 years the
opener was not on TV. ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Chicago White Sox: Yes, it's only the first week of the season, but
the White Sox went into the Kingdome and basically toyed with the
Seattle Mariners, a far more talented ballclub. Respected Manager
 &UR; Jerry Manuel is now in his second season, and maybe his eloquent
demeanor is filtering its way down to the players. This club is not
good enough to contend, however. It's a scrappy bunch that very
well could wind up having the better record in Chicago this
season. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Baltimore Orioles: The starting pitchers are giving up runs by the
truck load, and the offense did little the first week. This is a
club that will not respond well to losing, especially with Manager
 &UR; Ray
 &UR; Miller's status very much in question. A poor April would probably
cost Miller his job. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Judging by this response, count Philadelphia outfielder  &UR; Ron &UR; Gant
among those who strongly disapprove of the idea Major League
Baseball is kicking around of putting small advertising patches on
big-league uniforms: ``Ads belong on billboards and walls, not
uniforms. To me, my uniform is sacred, and I'd like to keep it that
way.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
This space is normally reserved for up-and-coming players, but this
week we will deviate and offer it to the New York Mets' 40-year-old
wonder,  &UR; Rickey Henderson. The 10-time All-Star blazed out of the
blocks, batting .545 in the Mets first three games. Henderson had
three doubles, two home runs, four RBIs, a stolen base and five
runs scored. He has been staving off challenges from younger
players for more than 10 years and continues to be a productive
player. &QL; 
