<HEADLINE>
BATISTA FULL OF FIRE _ INSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The thing about Tony Batista is you can never tell
what type of day he's having simply by looking at his face.
</P>
<P>
   This is a player whose emotional speedometer never varies. Even
on a night when the Diamondbacks shortstop went 5 for 5 with a home
run and four RBIs, Batista refused to show much of anything.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to assume that Batista isn't giving his all. His
smooth and laid-back approach has often been interpreted as his
having little or no drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I was coming up through the Oakland system,''
Batista recalled after the Diamondbacks' first victory of the
season Saturday night. ``I had players and coaches tell me my body
language made it seem like I didn't want to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way I approach the game. I don't put pressure
on myself. I can't be in the bottom of the ninth inning thinking,
`Oh my, I have to make this play.' I get the ball easy and make my
throw. Different people take different approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of different approaches, how about Batista's
batting stance? As a keen baseball observer once noted of Batista's
awkward batting stance, ``It's looks like he lost a bet or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Batista has taken grief from fans and even opponents, who have
openly mocked him, because of his wide-open stance. He stands with
both feet squarely facing the pitcher before he begins the
transition to a more traditional stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hits the way he did tonight, I don't care if he stands
on his head,'' said Randy Johnson, who in some form, had to be the
pitcher to give the Diamondbacks their first victory. ``Who knows,
maybe he lulls the opposing pitcher to sleep with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Batista began using the exaggerated stance two years ago while
playing winter ball in his native Dominican Republic, where he is
considered the best current Dominican-born shortstop in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's weird,'' Batista said. ``But I see the ball better
with both eyes facing the pitcher. I can pick up what kind of pitch
is coming easier. It's almost like I am a fan sitting in the
stands, being able to see the pitch with both eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   As is the overwhelming feeling within the Diamondbacks
organization: If it works, who cares what it looks like.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't mean Batista doesn't hear it from the fans. In
Los Angeles last week, several fans were all over him, yelling that
he would never hit with that stance.
</P>
<P>
   After swatting 18 home runs last season in fewer than 300
at-bats, the Diamondbacks were convinced that Batista had at least
earned the right to open the season as the every day shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter never came out and said that, wanting to
see how Batista would react to competition with rookie Danny
Klassen, who eventually was sent to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   But Batista reacted the same way he always has. This is a player
who was signed to a $2,000 bonus at 17 in 1991. Considered little
more than a live body in the Athletics chain during his first three
years, Batista finally caught the attention of the front office
after his 17-home run season at Class A Modesto in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He followed that with 16 home runs at Double A the next season
and made his major league debut in the middle of the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With God's help, I have been able to make myself a major
league player,'' he said. ``All those times that nobody considered
me anything, I used that as motivation. I wanted to demonstrate
that I could play. Thankfully, somebody noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Batista, who has seven consecutive hits, certainly grabbed
Atlanta starter Tom Glavine's attention in the fourth inning when
he rocketed a line drive into the left field seats and continued
ripping line drives the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   He easily can be overlooked on this club. But if the
Diamondbacks are to contend for the National League West title,
which they plan to do, then their shortstop must play a big role.
</P>
<P>
   Batista said he's ready for the challenge, which is simply the
latest in a line of them. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
