<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3734 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZ     04-11 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BEANBALL WILL SURELY FLY, BUT WHY SHOULD IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once, I tried out for a baseball team. Near the end of a
gymnasium cattle call, I stepped into a long, rectangular net. My
turn to go deep.
</P>
<P>
   Two upperclassmen were standing over the pitching machine,
feeding a wicked contraption with wheels spinning furiously. One of
them smirked as he showed me the ball. Then . . .
</P>
<P>
   THWAAAACK.
</P>
<P>
   It should've been the sound of crushed cowhide. Except my bat
was gone, rolling on the floor. And so was I, giving birth to a
bruise that would strangely resemble the state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   I learned then what I know now: Beanballs are for sissies.
</P>
<P>
   And so, under an ominous backdrop, the Diamondbacks return home
tomorrow, opening their season at Bank One Ballpark. The Dodgers
will be in town, and six games into the season, there is already an
unspoken bounty waiting to be claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Todd Stottlemyre pitches today and will miss the
series. But someone else on the Diamondbacks will be expected to
lose control of a fastball, one that somehow finds Dodgers flesh.
If not, the home team will be labeled for its lack of spine, and
the scouting report will spread to every clubhouse in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   Every sport has its rituals, things that go unquestioned because
they've always happened in the past, and therefore, mistakenly
placed into the fabric of competition. Somehow, the beanball has
fallen into the category of necessary evil.
</P>
<P>
   The logic is baffling. The best hitters in the game fail seven
of every 10 at-bats. But if they succeed, as Matt Williams did with
a home run in Los Angeles followed by a long foul ball in his next
appearance, a pitcher is suddenly privileged to commit a cowardly
act of revenge. In this case, it was Dodger hurler Chan Ho Park who
felt compelled to send Williams sprawling.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Diamondbacks are forced to retaliate? Risk losing a
starting pitcher and possibly another game for their own pound of
flesh? Please.
</P>
<P>
   There is a strong need for reform. To eliminate a barbaric act
that has no place in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it will never happen under a clueless commissioner.
And here's all you need to know about Bud Selig. Upon returning
from a controversial trip to Cuba, Selig was interviewed by ``Miami
Herald'' columnist Dan LeBatard. Selig is Jewish, and was asked how
he would feel if a major league baseball team went to Germany and
he saw the commissioner sitting next to Adolph Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, um,'' Selig replied, followed by a 10-second pause.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good bet that Selig has no idea of the impending chaos at
BOB.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was particularly incensed over the incident because his
home run trot is steeped in embarrassment, a man who runs the bases
with his head down. In truth, humility shouldn't mean squat.
</P>
<P>
   It is a pitcher's right to throw inside, to back hitters off the
plate. But no one should have the license to throw a
90-mile-per-hour fastball at someone's cranium just because he's
insulted. Just because he failed.
</P>
<P>
   That is a weapon for the weak, and any pitcher who indulges in
such malice should be ejected on the spot, placed on probation,
subjected to a heavy fine.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the burden is placed on the victim.
</P>
<P>
   The same applies to Stottlemyre, who blew a gasket during spring
training after Sammy Sosa crossed home plate and bowed to the fans.
Because of the ensuing retaliation, the game turned vicious, and
the Cubs' June journey to BOB is already circled on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   After that game, Sosa vowed to quit styling on the field. Not
because Stottlemyre was offended. Rather, because one of his
teammates, Mark Grace, openly feared a steady diet of
hit-by-pitches, the result of Sosa's crowd-pleasing antics.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to pitchers everywhere: If you don't like it, get the guy
out.
</P>
<P>
   In football, there is a natural deterrent, and any cheap shot
can be dealt with legally on the ensuing play. In basketball,
unless you're Dennis Rodman, no one is undercutting an opponent
just because he drained a three-pointer. In hockey, fighting is
allowed because it's the final line of accountability.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball players don't want to fight. They want to run on
the field with 20 of their closest friends and act tough. And when
it's all over, they want one of their pitchers to even the score.
</P>
<P>
   Stop already. Before someone loses his career, and maybe his
life. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
