A3735 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTEBOOK-     04-11 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL, WOODS CLING TO HOPES OF COMEBACK VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ When the final 18 holes are played out today in
the 63rd Masters, don't look past the 1-2 punch that was favored to
win this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; David Duval and  &UR; Tiger Woods, the Nos. 1 and 2 players, are
lurking, and are very much in it. OK, Woods is 5 shots back and
Duval is 6, but with the course playing harder than in past years
after a redesign and added rough, and with the nature of the beast
called Augusta National, anything is possible if you're just close.
</P>
<P>
   Look how much ground  &UR; Steve Pate made up during Saturday's third
round with a 7-under 65. Spain's  &UR; Jose Maria Olazabal might be at 7
under but . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``As you now, it's not easy to go low on this course when you're
near the lead,'' said Woods, who finally got off the 72s with a 70
in the third round that featured two birdies on the back side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in good shape. Really good shape. Anybody 4 or 5 under
after nine holes is in the ballgame. Anything can happen on that
back nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who is going for his third straight victory, was
perplexed after also shooting 70. Along the way, he birdied his way
through Amen Corner (Nos. 11-13).
</P>
<P>
   ``How far back am I?'' Duval asked as he walked off the course,
his tunnel vision causing him to be oblivious to what was going on
around him. ``That's a little bit of a reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you just never know what's going to happen here. I was
just happy to get back in it a little bit on the back (side). I
might still have a chance.'' &QL; 
Arizona connection &QL; 
 &UR; Phil Mickelson said Augusta National is playing ``the fairest I've
ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really surprised that no one has gone 10 or 12 under,''
said the Scottsdale pro, who is 2 under after a 71 on Saturday.
``The golf course is very susceptible to a low score.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson even predicted that someone would come from 2 or 3
back on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different kinds of shots you have to play
out there at the end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson had one of those at No. 15, where he made an
incredible recovery from the trees on the right side to make par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no shot,'' he said. ``So I hit a 3-iron under, between,
around and over these branches to just right of the bunker. And
that wasn't even one of the more difficult ones I've had out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's other four entrants,  &UR; Brandel Chamblee (1 over, 75),
 &UR; Tom
 &UR; Lehman (2 over, 73),  &UR; Tim Herron (2 over, 74) and  &UR; Andrew Magee (3
over, 72) are probably too far back.
</P>
<P>
   Of that group, Magee did have one of the big moments of the day,
holing out a sand wedge from 115 yards at the troublesome 15th
hole. It marked the first eagle of the week on the redesigned
hole. &QL; 
The payout &QL; 
The official purse was announced at $4 million on Saturday, with
$720,000 going to the winner along with a $200 green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   The payout places the season's first major championship above
regular PGA Tour events, but below the Tour Championship, Players
Championship and the three World Golf Championship events, which
are worth $5 million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
