<HEADLINE>
PATE SETS MASTERS RECORD  
 MISHAP MAGNET HITS 7 BIRDIES IN A ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ After going through a series of accidents that
would make even the most careless guy look over his shoulder,
temperamental Steve Pate has become a ``dormant volcano.'' At least
that's what his caddie, Allan Mellan, calls ``Pater.''
</P>
<P>
   But the volcano erupted on Saturday at The Masters, and this
time he let his clubs do the talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no explanation for what happened,'' said Pate, who
somehow strung together seven consecutive birdies at Augusta
National beginning at the seventh hole.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he walked off the 13th green, the record for birdies
in a row at The Masters firmly in his hand, playing partner Lee
Westwood was fanning him with a towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just kind of laughing,'' said Pate, whose 7-under 65 is
the best round of this tournament so far, moving him to 5 under and
within 2 shots of the lead going into today's final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much to be said after I made those two putts in a
row on (Nos.) 10 and 11 _ a 45-footer backed up by a 30-footer.
Things were going well.''
</P>
<P>
   A routine par at the 14th finally cooled him off, but not before
he usurped three other players from the past who had holed six in a
row _ Johnny Miller in 1975 beginning at No. 2; Ahwatukee's Mark
Calcavecchia in '92 starting at No. 13; and David Toms in '98
beginning at No. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Pate birdied his way through famed Amen Corner,
which includes the 11th, 12th and 13th holes.
</P>
<P>
   As the run grew, so did his gallery with ``people coming out of
the woods like Big Foot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that was kind of cool,'' Pate said, his best shot being a
7-iron to 1 foot at the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Pate is an amazing story. He almost ended his career three years
ago with a series of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he drove his car into a truck at 75 miles an hour,
breaking his hand and wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have come out a lot worse,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he was riding his bike in the family driveway and got
hit by a deer that his dog was chasing, but he escaped with minor
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Later that summer, he tripped on the dock at Lake Powell during
a family vacation and broke the other wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've settled down a little,'' Pate said. ``I wouldn't say (my
temper) has disappeared, but after (the accidents), a bad shot
doesn't seem like such a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate hit only one of those in Round 3, which led to a bogey at
the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   But he said his birdie binge was really no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I play is usually to par the course to death and
somewhere during the week have one or two stretches where I make
seven birdies in 10 holes,'' said the 37-year-old Californian who
has won six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 36 holes, I played well and didn't get anything out
of it. Then boom. I've done this before, but seven is about my
limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate's run was the longest on the PGA Tour this season. Steve
Elkington made six in a row at the Doral Open, a tournament he won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
