<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLESHMAN RUNS A NATIONAL BEST AT ARCADIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Lauren Fleshman conquered a cold and a stellar
field in the girls' 3,200 meters in the Arcadia Invitational on
Saturday night at Arcadia High.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clarita, Calif., Canyon High senior ran 10 minutes,
21.36 seconds, the fastest time in the nation this season, an
improvement of nearly 17 seconds off her career-best 10:38.13 run
as a sophomore. In addition, Fleshman moved into eighth on the
area's all-time list. Not bad for somebody not feeling exactly 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of phlegm,'' Fleshman said. ``I had enough phlegm to
rehydrate the entire field of girls out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford-bound Fleshman had more than enough to run away
from one of the nation's strongest fields, clocking 68.0 seconds
over the final 400. She won comfortably over a field which included
Catherine Guiney of New Jersey, the national scholastic indoor
champion, and Indiana's Michelle De La Vina, the freshman national
indoor record-holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is more there,'' said Fleshman, who has run only
one interval workout on the track this year. ``I am sick, but I
can't wait to get back out there on the track. I am really ready to
run fast. Things can only get better from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleshman passed through the mile among a lead pack of four in
5:12.8 but took the lead with two laps to go after the pace
dwindled to 81 and 83 seconds over the next 800. Canyon coach Dave
DeLong instructed Fleshman to take the lead and she was never
challenged the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really talk about time,'' DeLong said. ``We talk
about racing. I say, `You're here to win. You're here to race as
fast as you can. Do not blow this opportunity to get something
special done. Take a risk and go for it.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a breakthrough night for Glendale Hoover sophomore
Anita Siraki, who chopped 25 seconds off her lifetime best in
placing second in 10:30.81. The mark moved her into 10th on the
region list. Siraki moved into second after Fleshman's break and
maintained it to the finish. Katie Brizgys of Palo Alto and Liana
Tuson of Australia finished third and fourth, respectively, in
10:35.44 and 10:35.74.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace was fast at the beginning,'' Siraki said. ``And I was
a little intimidated with everybody up there. I just wanted to keep
my position when I was second and stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   Simi Valley Royal junior Oliver Jackson reaffirmed his position
as the state's top long jumper. The junior sailed 24 feet, 3 inches
to improve on his nation-leading best of 24-1 and a five-inch
victory over Sacramento El Camino's Robert Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   In the boys' pole vault, Troy Becker of Malibu finished second
at 15-6 and Shane Hackeett of Los Angeles Verdugo Hills tied for
seventh at 14-6. Tim Adrian of Moorpark, who has signed a letter of
intent with Syracuse, placed eighth in the boys' discus at 178-10.
</P>
<P>
   Annmarie Turpin of Simi Valley and Bridget Pearson of Glendale
Hoover registered runner-up performances in the girls' high jump
and pole vault, respectively. Turpin equaled her state-leading mark
of 5-8 but finished second on misses. Pearson, the 1997 state
champion, cleared 11-6.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hectic day for Turpin, who also competed in the long
jump, 400 and 300 hurdles during the open session earlier in the
day. Turpin cleared both 5-6 and 5-8 on her third attempt before
taking three attempts at 5-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what you can do with fresh legs, but I like to
do an event or two before I high jump to get warmed up,'' Turpin
said. ``I am used to doing that in league meets so I did not feel
too tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Deneeka Torrey of L.A. Taft, who won the 100, 100-meter hurdles
and 300-meter low hurdles in a Northwest Valley Conference meet
against L.A. Birmingham on Friday, was fourth in the 100 hurdles in
14.58 and third in the 300 low hurdles in 44.35 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Rhodes of L.A. Loyola finished second in the boys'
seeded 110-meter high hurdles in 14.53 and fifth in the
invitational 300-meter intermediate hurdles in 38.64. L.A. Notre
Dame's Sierra Hauser-Price was a winner in the girls' seeded 100 in
12.22 and second in the seeded 200 in 24.87. &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
