<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-LONGLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGLEY: MALONE TRIED TO INJURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -  &UR; Luc Longley has seen the video now, and he's
convinced: The Suns center believes Utah forward  &UR; Karl Malone was
out to hurt him Friday night when Malone crashed into Longley,
hyperextending Longley's left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Dr.  &UR; Richard Emerson, the Suns' orthopedic surgeon, examined
X-rays and a magnetic resonance imaging test and said Longley has a
bone bruise and capsular sprain, but there is no ligament damage.
</P>
<P>
   For that, Longley said he's lucky.
</P>
<P>
   But still mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked pretty bloody flagrant to me,'' Longley said after
viewing a tape. ``There's a fine line between trying to draw a foul
and going straight for someone's leg. It looked like he went for my
knee, and that's piss-weak, as far as I'm concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (term) is probably Australian.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter, the message was clear enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the knee was damaged,'' he said. ``I think I'm
lucky. It was pretty sore, but I knew when I got up (Saturday) I
wasn't in too much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just amazed that someone would do that. He had a smile on
his face when he was going back down the court. I looked at that on
the video and I was amazed. We all make our living with our
bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   And Longley suggested maybe Malone might be trying to settle a
score. Malone and the Jazz lost in the last two NBA Finals to
Longley's former team, the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize the last two years haven't been great for him, as
far as playing against the Bulls,'' he said. ``But I don't know why
he would do that, especially for a guy who projects himself as
being a class act.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley is expected to be out for at least a week with the
injury. He will not make the club's trip to San Antonio and Seattle
Monday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Suns Coach  &UR; Danny Ainge said the Suns probably won't try to sign
a big man to a 10-day contract for a couple of reasons. One, there
aren't any big men available that would be likely to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``And by the time we brought somebody in, and they learned what
we're doing, Luc will probably be back,'' Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said he didn't think Malone was trying to hurt Longley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always lowering his shoulder and bulling into people,''
Ainge said. ``But I didn't think he was trying to intentionally
hurt Luc.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
