<HEADER>
A3739 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLDRAFT-KONRAD-B     04-11 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KONRAD'S THE FULL PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-KONRAD-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ As someone who has lived in North Andover
since he was 8 years old, Rob Konrad, not surprisingly, has a
preference as to which NFL team he'd most like to be drafted by
next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a lot of pride in being from Massachusetts, and my
dream is to play for the Patriots,'' said Konrad, the Syracuse
fullback who this weekend was scheduled to visit St. Louis
following his stop in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Konrad visited with the Patriots two weeks ago, one of several
stops on a hectic tour around the country. Teams such as the
Patriots, Cowboys, Dolphins, Falcons, and Rams are truly intrigued
by the tremendous athleticism in a back who is 6 feet 3 inches and
255 pounds. He runs a 4.53 40-yard dash and is considered a
physical specimen.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are intrigued because they see Konrad as more than just a
fullback. He can run with the ball, catch it, and block, though
he's not considered the smash-mouth blocker Sam Gash is. There is
more finesse and skill to his game, which fascinates some teams and
scares others.
</P>
<P>
   Some draft gurus have Konrad going late in the first round to
Minnesota or late in the second round to New England. He probably
won't have to settle for third-round money, for he is the top-rated
fullback in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   In visits with coaches such as Dan Reeves, Jimmy Johnson, Pete
Carroll, Dick Vermeil, and Chan Gailey, he often finds himself
answering the same questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hear a lot is, `Can you line up and carry it 25 times a
game?' I answer it, `Sure, I could.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was given the chance to do that, I could, but with our
offense, I wasn't called on to do that. If I had gone to Wisconsin,
I would have carried it 25-35 times a game and people wouldn't be
asking me that question. I know one thing: The fact they're asking
means they think I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some think he can be a feature back, and almost everyone agrees
he could be a versatile player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any team that drafts me is going to use me as more
than just a fullback,'' said Konrad. ``I'll be used a little as the
lone back, and I'll probably be used as a second tight end and an
H-back. I don't envision being a guy who carries the ball 25 times
a game, but you never know. I think the guy I'm closest to in the
NFL is a Mike Alstott at Tampa Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Which should be enough to get him drafted no later than the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a pride point of view, I'd like to think I'm one of the
top 30 players in the draft, but I understand how it works,'' said
Konrad. ``The last fullback drafted in the first round was Tommy
Vardell by the 49ers in 1992, and he didn't have a real long
career. Drafting a fullback in the first round just isn't done in
the NFL. Hopefully, a team will look at me a little differently and
picture me being an all-purpose type of player in their offense.''
</P>
<P>
   While visiting the Cowboys' Valley Ranch complex Thursday,
Konrad hooked up with Darryl ``Moose'' Johnston, another former
Syracuse fullback of note. He also met Deion Sanders, whom he
compared to the Patriots' Tebucky Jones _ a former teammate with
the Orangemen _ in terms of athleticism. Some say it was Konrad who
forced Jones to defense because it was when Konrad came along that
Syracuse moved Jones out of the running back spot to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't too many people as athletically gifted as `Buck,'
'' said Konrad. ``He's Deion Sanders-like. He's that type of
athlete. I really didn't beat him out for a job, he was just one of
those special players who was able to fill another need on the
team. Now he's playing corner, and if people are patient with him,
he'll do a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Konrad was a star tailback/linebacker at St. John's Prep in
Danvers. He was big and fast and there were few high school
defenses that could stop him. He also was a promising baseball
player who drew the attention of some pro scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought I was a better baseball player than a
football player, but I just didn't love it,'' said Konrad. ``I
wanted to play football.''
</P>
<P>
   He was highly recruited throughout the country and had his pick
of the top football programs, including Notre Dame and Florida
State. There also was a possibility that he would stay home and
play for Boston College, but Konrad broke hearts at the Heights and
chose Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation there just wasn't right,'' said Konrad. ``If Tom
Coughlin had stayed, I probably would have gone there, but Dan
Henning took over and some of the things they were doing with the
offense there didn't seem to suit my game. Syracuse seemed like the
right place for me, and I've never regretted that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   As a recruiting inducement, the Orangemen offered Konrad the
seldom-used and storied No. 44, which had been worn by Jim Brown,
Ernie Davis, and Floyd Little. The number is huge in Syracuse lore,
so huge that there's a bar near campus called ``44s'' and the
Syracuse ZIP code also ends with 44.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a number that I asked for,'' said Konrad, who even
has a phone number with 44. ``At the time, I didn't even know the
story behind the number. I came to realize that it was a
significant thing, and in my years at Syracuse, I got to meet and
sit down with both Jim Brown and Floyd Little and talked to them
about football. That meant a lot to me and they are conversations
I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Konrad may not live up to the deeds of Brown, Davis, and Little,
but he is used much differently than they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my junior year, I got a taste of being the primary
runner,'' said Konrad, ``and while I was in there I was averaging
about 7 yards per carry and things were going really well for me. I
was being considered as a finalist for the Doak Walker Award, but
then I got hurt. It was very disappointing, but I think it built
character and it helped me get through adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Konrad suffered a severe hamstring injury as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hamstring was torn off the bone on my leg,'' he said.
``But it was clean and they were able to pull it off the bone and
screw it back in.''
</P>
<P>
   That is an issue that comes up during his NFL visits, but he
feels he has quelled any concerns about his physical status.
</P>
<P>
   Konrad was injured in each of his seasons at Syracuse, leading
some to wonder whether he was like a skilled boxer with a glass
jaw. As a sophomore, he broke his hand. As a junior, he had the
hamstring and knee problem, along with cracked ribs. Last season he
sprained his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's been an issue with the teams I've
interviewed with,'' said Konrad. ``I think they know that all the
injuries had nothing to do with a lack of conditioning or anything
like that. They were fluke things that could have happened to
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much talent Konrad actually has may be unknown because
the injuries always seemed to set him back when he was on the verge
of really wowing the country. Many described him as the key to the
high-powered Syracuse offense directed by Donovan McNabb. Konrad,
when healthy, seemed to give McNabb incredible options.
</P>
<P>
   Konrad carried the ball 295 times in his career for 1,516 yards,
a 5.1-yard average, with 20 rushing touchdowns. He also made 41
catches for 473 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catching the ball is a second-nature thing to me,'' said
Konrad. ``It's just something I do and that I have to do at the
position I play. It's definitely something I can help an NFL team
with.''
</P>
<P>
   The modern NFL fullback is used almost exclusively for blocking,
but Konrad could very well be a throwback to a John Riggins type,
i.e. the featured runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been prepared for the NFL with our program at
Syracuse,'' said Konrad. ``I think there are some unique things I
can offer. It's just a waiting game right now, just like it is for
everyone else. I'm going to enjoy it because it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if he's a Patriot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
