<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAIBORNE TALENTED ENOUGH TO BE INSIDE OR OUTSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-LINEBACKERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Maybe Chris Claiborne's workouts haven't
been top-shelf this spring, but who cares? There is a reason
Claiborne wore the honored No. 55 at Southern Cal, just as there's
a reason he'll likely be the first linebacker selected in
Saturday's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got inside toughness and outside speed,'' said a West
Coast scout. ``He could play either position in the NFL, but with
that quickness, he's going to be intriguing on the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne's 6-foot-2 1/2-inch, 248-pound frame makes him big
enough to shake off blockers and his 4.6-4.7 speed in the 40
enables him to chase down the fastest running backs.
</P>
<P>
   There are always exceptionally talented players that scouts say
lack motivation or are inconsistent performers. But would anyone
dare pass him up based on that? He'll likely be there for the
taking at No. 4 for the Indianapolis Colts, who desperately need
help on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Right behind Claiborne as a strong inside guy is Ohio State's
linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer. At 6-2 1/2, 258, he is a ferocious
hitter and a high-energy player. Some scouts believe he never
achieved his full potential in college and may be overrated, but he
plays the game hard and on adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   Jevon Kearse was technically a defensive end at Florida, but
he'll likely play linebacker or an elephant spot in the NFL. He is
6-5 but only 262 pounds, which could mean trouble against 300-pound
linemen. He could gain weight and become a pure end, but regardless
he will be a good pass rusher with quick feet and long arms.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia's Gary Stills, Clemson's Rahim Abdullah, and
Florida's Mike Peterson are highly rated outside linebackers.
Peterson could be a terrific replacement for Todd Collins on the
weak side if the Patriots are looking for that type of linebacker.
Stills, 24, rushes the passer well and is one of the best blitzing
linebackers in the draft. Abdullah is just plain big; at 6-5, 245,
he gobbles up smaller running backs.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Al Wilson may be the best inside guy after Claiborne
and Katzenmoyer. He is only 6 feet but his 239-pound frame is a
killer.
</P>
<P>
   Fall River's Marc Megna, at 6-1, 250, is too small to play nose
tackle as he did at Richmond and is projected as an inside
linebacker and a middle-to-late rounder. UMass linebacker Khari
Samuel, at 6-2 1/2, 242, also may be taken in the late rounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
