<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER CAUGHT IN STICKUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fortunately for Anson Carter, National Hockey League
justice is not retroactive.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the sheepish grin he wore in the Bruins' dressing
room Saturday after their 3-2 win over the Tampa Bay Lightning at
the FleetCenter would have been a frown of remorse. And the winning
goal he scored at 7:43 of the third period would have gone the way
of the stick he used to score it _ into infamy.
</P>
<P>
   Just under five minutes after depositing a Joe Thornton feed
into the right side of the Lightning net, increasing his
career-high goal total to 22, Carter was in the penalty box. His
felony: a stick blade that exceeded the NHL limit of 3 inches in
width.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd measured it before without the tape and it was fine, but
the tape must have pushed it over,'' said Boston's quicksilver
forward. ``I'm going to make sure I'm real careful about it the
last couple of games and in the playoffs. I don't want to cost the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't cost the team Saturday because the Bruins' penalty
killers, statistically the best in the business, lived up to their
reputation by holding the Lightning without a shot on the power
play, though Pavel Kubina did ring one off the left post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to put the guys in that position,'' said Carter.
``But I have faith in our penalty killers.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was put in a potentialy embarrassing position because
Lightning coach Jacques Demers tried to replicate the ploy he used
to help the Montreal Canadiens win the 1993 Stanley Cup. Back then,
with his team having lost the opener of the finals against Los
Angeles, Demers challenged the stick of the Kings' Marty McSorley.
It was found to be illegal, Montreal cashed in on the power play,
and the Canadiens were never headed again in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday the stakes were a tad lower: This was a garbage-time
special between one team locked into the playoffs and another
residing in oblivion. Nevertheless, Demers was willing to try every
strategic wrinkle to give woeful Tampa a sweep of this
home-and-home series. But he may have outfoxed himself.
</P>
<P>
   During the third period, while watching the action from the
bench, Tampa wingers Mike Sillinger and Rob Zamuner took special
note of Carter's blade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was skating by and we said, `Holy cow, look at that,' ''
said Sillinger. ``We told the coach, but it's up to him what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Demers decided to save that intelligence until it could best
serve the Lightning, and by then, Carter already had done his
damage, snapping the 2-2 tie. Trying to recoup at 12:40, with
Boston's Cameron Mann already in the penalty box for hooking,
Demers decided it was time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to try to get the power play at the right time,''
said Demers. ``We're trying to teach our young guys to play by the
rules, and this was an example.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it wasn't purely educational.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a five-on-four,'' said Sillinger, ``so he figured it
was a good time to call for the measurement, try to get a
five-on-three.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem. Tampa's Darcy Tucker had been called for
high-sticking at 12:40, just before Demers called for the
measurement. So although referee Kerry Fraser's metal gauge found
the stick to be illegal, it didn't give the Lightning a two-man
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacques still thought he was in the 1993 Stanley Cup finals,''
said Bruins coach Pat Burns. ``The only thing was he forgot about
the coincidental minors, so it stayed a five-on-four instead of a
five-on-three.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who stands to be assessed a kangaroo court-type fine by
Burns, also wondered whether Demers's effort was worth the bother.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect something like that to happen, especially at
this time of the year with them out of the race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Demers may have done him a favor in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned my lesson,'' said the Bruins' chastened hero, now
fully aware that crime won't always pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
