</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALL-STAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADATZ RAN OUT OF GAS IN 1964 
</HEADLINE>
 GAME-RADATZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dick Radatz was so close to being named Most Valuable
Player of the 1964 All-Star Game that he was already imaging what
it would be like to slip behind the wheel of the Corvette that the
game's MVP received.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then that son of a gun backed it right out of my garage,''
said the former Red Sox fireballer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That son of a gun'' was Philadelphia Phillies outfielder
Johnny Callison, who took Radatz deep for a three-run home run in
the bottom of the ninth to give the National League a stunning 7-4
win over the American Leaguers, who did not take kindly to losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My locker was in between (Mickey) Mantle and (Rocky) Colavito,
and there must have been 30 reporters around me after the game,''
Radatz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reporters asked, `What did he hit, Dick?' Mantle
turned around and said, `One of the damnedest home runs you've ever
seen.' And he wasn't laughing, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Radatz, known as the Monster for his imposing size and
terrifying fastball, was an All-Star in both 1963 and '64, when he
reigned as the AL's best closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I struck out 10 guys in 4 2/3 innings in those games,
and all I have to show for it is an 0-1 record and a 7-plus ERA,''
Radatz said.
</P>
<P>
   Radatz struck out five NL Stars in 1963, including future Hall
of Famers Willie Mays, Willie McCovey, and Duke Snider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate him,'' Pirates shortstop Dick Groat, a former NL MVP
and Radatz strikeout victim, told the Globe's Harold Kaese after
that game. ``I hate all big guys who throw the ball with such
little effort.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 7, 1964, the game was played in a brand-new ballpark,
Shea Stadium, located next to the site of that year's World's Fair.
The NL took an early 3-1 lead on home runs by Billy Williams and
Ken Boyer off Johnny Wyatt, who pitched for the Kansas City
Athletics at the time but later would be a star reliever for the
1967 Sox Impossible Dreamers.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Radatz took the mound in the seventh, the AL had
taken a 4-3 lead. Future Hall of Famer Brooks Robinson hit a
two-run triple to tie the score, and Jim Fregosi's sacrifice fly
scored Elston Howard with the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   Radatz held the lead through the eighth, but in the ninth he
walked Mays, still a beloved figure in New York six years after the
Giants had left the Polo Grounds for San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had Willie struck out,'' Radatz said 35 years later. ``The
umpire was Ed Sudol, and on a 2-and-2 pitch Willie took one step
toward the dugout. Sudol called it a ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mays walked, I never heard such a roar. I stepped off the
mound, it was so exciting. It was so loud, you could feel the
ground shake. I may have gotten caught up in it a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mays then stole second, racheting up the noise level, and
Orlando Cepeda followed with a bloop single to right on which Joe
Pepitone threw past catcher Howard for an error, allowing Cepeda to
score.
</P>
<P>
   Radatz induced Boyer to pop up for the first out, then
intentionally walked Johnny Edwards. Ron Hunt was the scheduled
hitter, but instead Radatz saw a pinch hitter: Henry Aaron, who 10
years later would become the all-time home run king. Howard came to
the mound to talk with Radatz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Ellie, I don't know this guy,' '' Radatz said.
``Howard said, `He likes the ball up. Keep it down. You have the
control to do it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I lived on the high fastball, but I threw him three
straight fastballs down around his knees and he swung at all three
of them. Afterward, he told a reporter, `I never saw a fastball
like that.' I kept the article.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then Callison came up, and bingo.''
</P>
<P>
   Radatz went out to dinner with his parents after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother, Virginia, said, `Son, it's a privilege just to be
chosen to the team. You did very good.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Mom, I know you're right, but not  &UR; today &LR; .' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
