<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX STAY PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-DEVIL RAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ At this rate, the only question left may
revolve around how many fans intend to be at Logan Airport Sunday
night if the Red Sox finish their season-opening trip undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects a throng like the 10,000 that mobbed Logan when
the '67 Impossible Dreamers returned home with a 10-game winning
streak in August. That was during the summer in a pennant race.
This is April _ before the Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   But these Red Sox, who stand alone as the only team in major
league baseball without a loss after they held on against the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays, 5-3, Saturday &UR;  &LR; night for their fifth straight win,
are stirring spring's annual hope in New England every bit as much
as the crocuses and daffodils blossoming in backyards.
</P>
<P>
   The Sons of Jimy Williams became the first Sox team since the
'46 World Series contestants to open 5-0, and if they can sweep the
Devil Rays Sunday afternoon behind newcomer Pat Rapp, they will be
the first 6-0 Sox team since 1918. The rest of the planet recalls
that as the year World War I ended. Locals cherish it as the last
time the Sox won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez squashed Tampa Bay hitters like they were the
Florida state bird (the palmetto bug) until they tagged him for
four hits and all of their runs at the start of the eighth; Jose
Offerman continued trying to earn his $26 million contract in the
season's first week; and John Valentin and Troy O'Leary hit home
runs, with O'Leary also hitting a two-run double in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to him a little bit in the eighth,'' Wade Boggs said of
Martinez, who is 2-0, 27-7 in April and May over the last five
seasons. ``Up until then, he was basically unhittable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have not trailed in 42 innings since the third inning of
their opener at Kansas City, taking advantage of a schedule in
which they don't play a team that had a winning record last year
until they host Cleveland, 15 games into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still too early _ it doesn't matter,'' Martinez said.
``But I can tell you, we're playing solid. It's not going to be
that easy, but we have a very deep bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be a big surprise, but don't make it too much of a
big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But surely Martinez has spent enough time in Boston to know how
baseball fever can grip the Hub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a small city,'' he said with a smile. ``Hopefully,
we can keep it in Boston, and no one else will know until it's too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who in one stretch struck out 9 of 15 batters and
allowed just three hits, two of them infield singles, said he
wasn't tired in the eighth, when the home team finally awakened.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Cairo singled and Kevin Stocker beat out a bunt that
Martinez probably should have allowed third baseman Valentin to
handle instead of taking himself. Quinton McCracken then lined a
double to center to spoil the shutout, and when Dave Martinez
followed by cracking a two-run double, Williams lifted Martinez for
Jim Corsi.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping in against Corsi was new Tampa Bay strongman Jose
Canseco, who tapped out to Valentin, making him hitless in his
first seven at-bats before the hometown fans, who already have
resorted to some scattered booing. Fred McGriff then swung at
Corsi's first pitch and grounded out to second baseman Jeff Frye.
And when John Flaherty flied out to center, Corsi bounded off the
mound triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really did an outstanding job against the middle part of
their lineup,'' Williams said. ``Nobody out, tying run at the
plate. A big inning for us, a big inning for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez takes great joy in needling Corsi, who leaves no target
untouched in the Sox clubhouse.  &UR; Last night &LR; , Martinez was serious,
for a moment at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corsi's a very good pitcher,'' he said. ``Believe me, as much
as I make fun of him, he knows his duty and has been around
forever. Believe me, I'd give him the ball every time.''
</P>
<P>
   But is he handsome, someone asked?
</P>
<P>
   ``Shhh,'' Martinez said. ``He thinks so, but don't tell him, his
mama told me he's ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gordon walked Wade Boggs to open the ninth but struck out
two of the last three batters for his third save and 46th in a row,
extending his major league record.
</P>
<P>
   How good has the bullpen been in the early going? Sox relievers
have pitched 13 1/3 innings and have allowed just one earned run
(McGriff's home run off Derek Lowe Friday night), two overall.
They've allowed just three hits, while walking six and striking out
14.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's two-run double after an error by McGriff and a hit
batsman gave the Sox a 2-0 lead in the first, which grew to 3-0
when O'Leary led off the fourth with a drive deep into the
right-field seats for his first home run of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin made it 5-0 in the fifth with his second home run with
Darren Lewis aboard on a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez gave the Devil Rays one chance early, when McGriff
singled off Valentin's glove and Flaherty doubled to left to open
the second. But the Red Sox ace retired Boggs on a checked-swing
comebacker to the mound, Valentin threw out McGriff at the plate on
Danny Clyburn's grounder, and Cairo struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was nasty, real nasty,'' Canseco said of Martinez. ``I
think he lost a little bit in the eighth, but I don't think I've
ever seen a ball move so much coming out of a pitcher's hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, who has had at least two hits in each of the first
five games, tripled and doubled Saturday &UR;  &LR; night and now has eight
extra-base hits, six doubles and two triples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990411.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-UNITED     04-11 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-UNITED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION POINTLESS IN HOME OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution's home season started in a
familiar manner: A commendable crowd of 18,373 arrived but the team
failed to win Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. The Revolution rallied twice to tie
D.C. United, 2-2, in regulation time before losing the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   And, as player-coach Walter Zenga noted, this was the first time
the Revolution have not lost in regulation time after their first
three games. The semantics become complicated for what has been
described as ``the simplest game,'' but the Revolution should be
encouraged by having played three opponents even.
</P>
<P>
   They recovered from a last-second goal in the first half,
remained compact defensively, and demonstrated attacking
resourcefulness. Jair contrived a free kick out of a spontaneous
dribble through the center of the field, leading to Joe-Max Moore's
second goal of the season, and newcomer Tony Kuhn provided a tall
target to complement Johnny Torres, who converted the Revolution's
second goal in the 83d minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will always play for the win,'' Zenga said. ``It is a big
satisfaction for us that nobody has beaten us (in regulation time)
in three games. We are trying to improve the team and bring the
team on top of the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Revolution have only 3 points in three games, they
have established a style of play that could keep them in
contention, especially during a stretch that continues against
Columbus Saturday and at D.C. United April 24.
</P>
<P>
   They disrupted United, which has 7 points in three games, just
enough to stay in contention, and created just enough offense to
eventually knock the visitors off balance. Moore nearly scored in
the third minute, but hesitated after losing sight of the ball in
the lights and was stripped from behind by Ben Olsen on the edge of
the goal area.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Aunger headed in Marco Etcheverry's cross for the first
goal with 11 seconds remaining on the scoreboard clock of a
45-minute-30-second first half. This was a demoralizing blow for
the Revolution, who had possession in the final minute, but Moore
lost control about 40 yards from the goal. Etcheverry and Jaime
Moreno combined to quickly counterattack, then Aunger redirected
Etcheverry's cross into the far upper corner of the goal, leaving
Zenga no chance.
</P>
<P>
   Moore slammed a perfectly placed free kick into the left side of
the goal four minutes into the second half. But United capitalized
on its midfield dominance to create excellent chances, only to be
stopped by Zenga until Roy Lassiter converted an Olsen cross in the
72d minute.
</P>
<P>
   But the combination of Edwin Gorter in midfield, and Torres's
persistence, paid off for the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   Gorter, making his first appearance after serving a two-game
suspension, soon placed his stamp on game after replacing Kuhn, who
was picked up after being waived by Chicago last week, in the 69th
minute. His curling shot was tipped for a corner by goalkeeper Tom
Presthus. Then, Gorter combined with Torres, whose shot was blocked
by Carlos Llamosa. But Torres remained composed and sent the
deflection into the far side of the net to tie the score, then ran
50 yards to the bench to embrace Giuseppe Galderisi, who was acting
as assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution entered the match with only one regulation-time
victory in 14 attempts against United. They had thrice surrendered
deciding goals in the final minutes of games, but they maintained
their poise this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed good fight,'' Revolution defender Dan Calichman
said. ``We got right back in the game in the second half and fought
even harder. These are great signs for the future, it shows we are
playing together as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a real situation, we would have two ties. But, in any case,
we didn't get beat and we'll get the 3 points later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
