<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-PATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDIE RUN HELPS PATE TAKE FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Steve Pate was just about to make the turn
Saturday when he noticed ``a lot of people appearing out of
nowhere. They started appearing out of the trees like Big Foot.''
Remarkable Pate could notice, considering the zone he was in.
</P>
<P>
   Pate accomplished the remarkable, birdieing seven consecutive
holes _ the seventh through 13th at Augusta National _ to catapult
himself from 1 over par to 6 under. He finished with a 65, the low
round of the tournament, and at 5-under 211 he is just two shots
behind leader Jose Maria Olazabal starting Sunday's final round of
the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like this came out of nowhere,'' Pate said of his
Masters record-breaking streak that, of course, came out of
nowhere. ``It's not like where I've struggled and then did this.
I've played solidly for three days and I expect to do the same
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for nothing is Pate known as ``Volcano.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I have no explanation for what happened out there,''
said Pate. ``I didn't really do anything differently than I did the
first two days. I don't know why. I just made a couple of putts and
it just . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   There is no terrestrial explanation for extraterrestrial golf.
He started the run with a wedge into the par-4 seventh that left
him a 8-foot putt straight uphill. Plop. Followed by a 20-footer on
the par-5 eighth that also went plop. A 9-iron on the ninth left
his ball a foot and a half away, and another plop.
</P>
<P>
   On and on it went, the gallery growing and finally a storm of
people rushing over to see this phenomenon of Steve Pate leveling
Augusta National. On the par-5 13th, Pate hit a lob wedge to 7 feet
for another plop.
</P>
<P>
   Pate tried to explain this zone to those who might make seven
birdies a season or, for the fortunate, seven birdies a month. ``It
just seemed easy,'' he said. ``Everything I was doing was turning
out well. It was probably the easiest stretch of holes I've played
all week.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Miller (1975), Mark Calcavecchia (1992), and David Toms
(1998) held the previous mark of six birdies in a row, but Pate
merely shrugged at the feat. ``I've done it before,'' he said,
though he was not able to remember where or when.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea I had a record,'' he said. ``Actually, the
thought crossed my mind after I made the seventh one. I don't know
why, but it popped into my head I might get my name in the record
book, which might be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate seemed much more nonplussed than the media or the
spectators. ``I've done a lot of amazing things in 15 years, some
good, some bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And some absolutely incredible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
