</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-TORRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRES ELEVATES GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Johnny Torres was wondering when this day
would come.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution forward had not scored a goal since last June 7
against the Los Angeles Galaxy, spending most of the second half of
his Major League Soccer rookie season on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night he got back on the scoreboard, and his goal in
the 83d minute lifted the Revolution into a 2-2 tie before D.C.
United won the shootout, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   The goal didn't come easily. After a nifty setup pass from
midfielder Edwin Gorter, Torres had his first shot attempt blocked
by a defender but scored on his second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the first shot and it bounced _ I didn't get full
contact on the ball,'' said Torres, a native of Colombia who won
the 1997 Hermann Award as college player of year during his career
at Creighton University. ``Luckily, I was able to get a second shot
at it and I was able to finish. It's very difficult to shoot while
you're running in the opposite direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres sent both of his shots toward the far post. ``As a
forward, you know that the goalie's going to stand at the near
post,'' Torres said. ``It feels good to get a goal. You can't get
frustrated, you can't look for it too hard. That just makes it
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres's goal enabled the Revolution to make their first tying
comeback of the season. In their opener, they led until the final
minutes before Miami sent the game into a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great thing for the team, for myself,'' said Torres
of the comeback. ``Hopefully I can get a little bit of confidence
from it, and hopefully I can knock in a couple more.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ultimate defeat, Torres feels his team showed its
strength. ``I think we showed we can play against anybody in the
league,'' he said. ``D.C.'s a great team, and we proved something
by coming from behind twice. There are little things that we can
work on _ maybe a little more discipline. I really think we have a
lot of potential to go far.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres made a point to say hello after the game to United coach
Thomas Rongen, the former Revolution coach. ``I have a lot of
respect for Thomas Rongen,'' said Torres. ``After all, he's the guy
who believed in me and drafted me out of college.''
</P>
<P>
   In the shootout, Torres took the 12th shot and missed. He
doesn't like that method of deciding tie games. ``It's a sad thing
that it can go to any team,'' Torres said. ``What can you say?
Shootouts are the luck of the draw, and, unfortunately, we couldn't
finish it off. It could have gone either way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what a better way is, but I don't like this way
very much, ever since the MLS started. Maybe it's best to end it
the way the rest of the world does it.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be to call the game a draw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
