<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN12-COX     04-11 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We don't have to buy abuses from Beijing
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I mailed two pairs of little-girl shoes, wrapped in
pink tissue, to my 4- and 6-year-old granddaughters. Shoes aren't
gifts I send from afar, but these were irresistible _ shiny black
pumps with tiny flowers embossed on them. Of course, they were made
in China.
</P>
<P>
   What should I tell the granddaughters about ``Made in China''?
</P>
<P>
   If they were older, I'd tell them that even though the Chinese
people make perfect shoes for little girls, the Chinese government
still sends people to prison for speaking the truth. I'd tell them
to pay attention to what Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji is saying about
U.S.-China trade relations on his current U.S. visit. (The
70-year-old Zhu spoke in Los Angeles, near Georgia's home, and
soon, he'll be in Denver, where Sydney lives.)
</P>
<P>
   The girls are too little to understand that even though Zhu
smiles a lot, he's done nothing to release hundreds of brave
Chinese young people who marched for freedom 10 years ago and who
are still political prisoners. But someday, I'll tell them the
story of Harry Wu, who broke his back when forced to do impossible
work in a Chinese coal mine. Wu kept criticizing the government
anyhow _ despite five arrests and 19 years in prison. He spoke out
against the Chinese laogai system. Laogai means ``thought reform
through labor,'' hard labor under cruel conditions for those who
refuse to think and talk like the government says they should.
</P>
<P>
   I hope laogai will be history by the time the girls grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is only in first grade, but she can write some Chinese
characters and sing Chinese songs. That's because my daughter Lisa,
her mother, studied in Beijing when she was in college, returning
home just months before the pro-democracy students were killed in
Tiananmen Square. When Lisa returned from China, she talked a lot
about how happy Chinese families are with simple pleasures _ flying
kites together, going to market on their bicycles, sharing an apple
with a stranger from America.
</P>
<P>
   The smiling Zhu says a lot of things we like to hear from a
Chinese leader: how he will open China's markets wider to the
United States, how admission to the World Trade Organization will
further China's market economy. But I can't forget that he also
believes it's none of our business when people are beaten or killed
in China or any other country.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a reason to push aside the human rights stuff, just
because the government of Zhu and President Jiang Zemin allow the
Chinese people to produce and sell more goods than ever? Or because
American corporations want U.S. political leaders to focus
exclusively on trade issues with China?
</P>
<P>
   America cannot respect Zhu's ``none of your business'' rule when
it comes to internal human rights abuses. My granddaughters will
learn that. Like other American children, they ask questions about
the NATO planes they see on television bombing Serbia, about the
Kosovar children who are crying or sick. They understand that bad
people are doing bad things to others who are different from them,
and that the United States is trying to put a stop to it.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has a record $57 billion trade deficit with
China now _ partly because of the Asian financial crisis, but
partly because people like me buy ``Made in China.'' There's no
direct line from a free market to a free society, but there's a
relationship. Tying trade issues to human rights doesn't work
anymore. But I want Sydney and Georgia to learn that standing up
for human rights always does.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
