<HEADER>
A3796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX     04-11 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Families carry burden they could dump on state
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ In Texas we grow 'em up strong, tall and
self-sufficient. Except when they are mentally retarded, partially
deaf, legally blind and have seizure disorders _ like 21-year-old
Della Marie Messer.
</P>
<P>
   Self-sufficiency rules in Texas. Parents Bill and Margaret
Messer worry that motto can be taken to self-defeating extremes.
</P>
<P>
   They worry that Texas isn't going to give them much help once
Della Marie's out of school, even though they helped Texas big-time
almost 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Lorena couple took Della Marie as a foster
child, later to adopt her.
</P>
<P>
   Texas should be ever in their debt. She could have been in an
institution all that time, costing the taxpayers bundles. Instead,
the Messers raised her.
</P>
<P>
   Someone should slap our faces at this point for talking about
cost. What the Messers did was right, humane, loving. They gave
Della Marie a home, a real home, not a ward, not a sea of tile, not
overseers in shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Messer points out that his daughter had behavior problems
as a toddler. She was a likely candidate for medication _ Thorazine
the drug of choice 20 years ago. She might have spent much of that
time zombie-like.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, representatives of families like the Messers
asked the Senate Appropriations Committee to increase the funding
for home and community services _ HCS.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has close to 10,000 people like Della Marie on a waiting
list for HCS. These are clients of the State Department of Mental
Health-Mental Retardation who are young adults or are approaching
life after school. House budget writers authorized a mere pittance,
enough to take 110 people off the waiting list. MHMR officials are
pleading for funds to remove 800 from the list. A Senate mark-up is
expected this week. Interests compete within the MHMR budget _
state schools vs. community care. The irony is that some families
that don't qualify for HCS end up tearfully turning to institutions
for their grown children.
</P>
<P>
   This is how Texas, always near the bottom in spending on human
services, and proud of it, ends up shortchanging lots of caring
families.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the extent of the disabilities in question, those
on the waiting list need several things. They might need someone to
care for or watch their disabled child when they are away from the
house, at work or simply taking care of other personal matters.
They might need need job training and continuing education for
these children.
</P>
<P>
   Della Marie has one more year in Lorena schools before she
enters unknown territory. Her parents say she'll need to continue
sign-language lessons she's getting in school, or she'll forget
what she's learned. They want her to be in a sheltered workshop to
make more friends and learn some life skills.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Kagle, far less disabled than Della Marie, has been on the
HCS waiting list for five years. His need is different. Adopted as
a Korean orphan by Joe and Anne Kagle of Waco, Chris is 25 and
wants to be in a group living setting, to move out of his parents'
home yet remain in his home town.
</P>
<P>
   HCS is not needed while these children are growing up and in
special education. The school is their support arm. But they can
only go to school until they're 22.
</P>
<P>
   After that, they are home, and in these cases they wait for the
funds for HCS support services or opportunities to relocate in a
community-based living arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   What often happens in cases like Della Marie's is the parents
can't continue to care for a grown child 24 hours a day.
Regretfully, they place the child in an institution, sometimes far
from home.
</P>
<P>
   That's the irony about the waiting list. Rather than
self-sufficiency, some people like Della Marie end up in
institutions costing us bundles. That's some economy measure. Slap
our faces.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
