<DOCNO> NYT19990411.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOPMAYOR12-COX     04-11 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOPMAYOR12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-migrant worker reaps harvest of fame
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BAY, Fla. _ When Clarence Anthony goes to the mountaintop,
it's just a short drive.
</P>
<P>
   But the view he gets of his humble hometown from the 40-foot
levee surrounding Lake Okeechobee fills him with an almost
unspeakable pride and contentment.
</P>
<P>
   Raised a dirt-poor migrant farm worker in a time when
opportunities for African-Americans were just opening up after
segregation, Anthony was never expected to climb to the heights of
national prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, through a childhood of picking celery in South
Bay and rattling around the country in a school bus with his family
to follow the harvest up the East Coast, he managed to build dreams
and ambitions for a life beyond the vegetable fields.
</P>
<P>
   After working his way through college sacking groceries, Anthony
began fulfilling those dreams when he was elected tiny South Bay's
mayor at the tender age of 24.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 15 years later, he's been recognized by his colleagues from
across the nation as a leader of uncommon skills and vision. In
December, Anthony was elected president of the 17,000-member
National League of Cities, a post that typically goes to chief
executives of giant cities, not struggling farm hamlets like South
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mayor of this one stop-light town sometimes sits at his
government-issue metal desk in his windowless office and takes
calls from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone gets real excited here when one of those calls comes
in,'' said Anthony, who at 38 still looks young enough to be in
college. ``It's been a wonderful experience. Sometimes I pinch
myself because I can't believe I'm serving in a position like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly overcame the odds to get there.
</P>
<P>
   South Bay is not the kind of town a casual visitor would
identify as a hotbed of national leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Hard by the southern shore of Lake Okeechobee, the town is 90
percent minority, with a per capita income of only $13,000 and a
chronic unemployment rate running near 30 percent. The main reason
for South Bay's existence is to serve the vast fields of sugar cane
and vegetables that stretch, flat as a table top, in nearly every
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Southern blacks migrated here in the 1930s and '40s to do
the backbreaking work of tending the fields, and they were joined
in the 1960s and '70s by equally poor Haitians and other Caribbean
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions for the workers were so bad they spawned famed
journalist Edward R. Murrow's shocking documentary, ``Harvest of
Shame.'' The program, depicting hard labor, low wages and pitiful
living conditions, stunned many Americans who didn't know their
country harbored such misery.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony was right there in those fields, living in a tattered
housing project, spending hours after school each day working the
celery fields. ``It sounds like it was so bad, but I really had a
very loving childhood,'' he said. ``You don't even realize you're
poor when everybody around you is in the same state. We had the
basics _ food, shelter and each other. That was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony's mother pressed him to stay in school, even when each
academic year was interrupted by the family's yearly treks to
Maryland and New York to follow the harvests.
</P>
<P>
   It was in school that he got his first taste of politics. He
liked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got elected president of the student body at Glades Central
High School,'' he said. ``Even then I was tinkering with
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   As a ninth-grader, Anthony graduated from working in the celery
fields to an indoor job that paid wages cut by check: a grocery bag
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had it made,'' he recalls. ``I got to wear a
tie.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony worked at the grocery all through high school, community
college and and even after he enrolled at Florida Atlantic
University in Boca Raton. He remembers telling the produce manager
that he had ambitions to succeed him and to one day become a store
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was going to fire me the next day if I kept
talking that way,'' Anthony said, recalling his shock. ``He told me
I could do better than to spend my life in a grocery store.''
</P>
<P>
   After earning a graduate degree in public administration _ and
serving as head of FAU's Student Government Association _ Anthony
did something surprising on his own: He returned to South Bay.
Clearly his hometown had a hold on him, because it was a place of
such limited horizons that many youth with freshly-minted college
degrees would have rushed to leave.
</P>
<P>
   South Bay then didn't look much different from the run-down
village portrayed in Murrow's documentary. A couple of gas stations
and garages, one motel and several liquor stores lined U.S. 27, the
main drag that still roars all day with heavy trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing from his own experience, Anthony decided the way for the
town's poor to rise was through education. His first big project
after he was elected mayor in 1984 was to secure a branch of the
Palm Beach County library for South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took four years,'' he said. ``The county commissioners and
legislators got so used to hearing my speech they would introduce
me as Clarence `I-want-my-library' Anthony.'' Another big goal
during Anthony's tenure has been to bring more jobs and new
industry to South Bay. On that count, he and his town suffered a
devastating blow.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, South Bay's main employer had been a vegetable
packing house, which in season employed hundreds, giving them just
enough wages to get by. But the packing house closed down in 1994,
taking with it a $17 million payroll and 1,300 jobs _ including
that of Anthony's own mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the lowest,'' Anthony recalls. ``It made me feel like
I had failed. It looked like South Bay might become a ghost town.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony turned to contacts he had made in state government
through his years of activity in groups like the Florida League of
Cities. He secured a prison that soon opened and employed 300
people in steady, good-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Now his goal is to broaden and diversify South Bay's economic
base. Working again with state officials, he arranged for the city
to obtain 170 acres of property that had been confiscated from a
convicted drug dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Already South Bay has opened an RV park on part of the land
nearest the Lake Okeechobee levee, where there are boat ramps for
sportsmen attracted by the lake's world-class bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   There are plans for a new housing development and a commerce
park that the city hopes will attract small- to medium-sized firms
that would employ a few dozen people each.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony often takes his morning coffee on the levee, reading and
contemplating as he gazes over his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Along with his own career satisfaction, he has enjoyed watching
his son, Reidel, excel in a football career that has taken him from
the University of Florida to the NFL's Tampa Bay Buccaneers, where
he is now a star wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up he was always the mayor's son,'' Anthony said.
``Now I'm Reidel Anthony's father. I just love that. I'm as proud
of him as of anything I've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   During his yearlong tenure as the National League of Cities
president, Anthony is stressing the concept of building a sense of
community by involving citizens in the life of their towns.
</P>
<P>
   It's the magnet that has kept him in South Bay, and despite the
town's struggles, he believes it is the glue that holds any
successful community together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you're from Detroit or Orlando or Atlanta, that's what
makes a city work,'' he said. ``People participating, feeling like
this is their home town.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
