<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALISM REVIEW CHANGES APPROACH  
 COVER OF FORTUNE RAISES RIVALS' EYEBROWS  
 ANOTHER APOLOGY BY `60 MINUTES' 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI and FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Faced with an environment in which media practices
are scrutinized by every outlet from consumer magazines like
Brill's Content to an ever-multiplying band of Internet scribes,
The Columbia Journalism Review is rethinking its approach.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Konner, the publisher of the Review since 1988, will step
down on July 1. David Laventhol, a longtime newspaper executive who
has been publisher of The Los Angeles Times, publisher and editor
of Newsday and president of the Times Mirror Co., will take her
place. Laventhol retired from Times Mirror last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goldstein, dean of Columbia University's Graduate School of
Journalism, said that the appointment of Laventhol _ whose name is
closely associated with New York Newsday _ was a step toward
retooling the approach of the Review, a bimonthly with a
circulation of about 30,000 that is published out of the journalism
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``CJR was first published in 1962, and that's almost 40 years
ago,'' Goldstein said. ``It is an understatement to say that
journalism has changed considerably since then. And it's also an
understatement to say that journalism criticism has grown up since
then. But there's a lot of it out there and some of it is very good
and some of it just adds to the noise. What we have now is an
opportunity to really think about what we should be doing, and we
can spend the next year trying to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's on the table,'' Goldstein said. ``From an
enhanced Web presence, to changing its size, to changing the
frequency of the magazine's appearance to either more or less. We
have a little bit of time in which we can make these decisions and
we will do it with deliberation.''
</P>
<P>
   Laventhol said he was not yet sure how he would specifically
shift the magazine's perspective, but he said he was keenly aware
of the ever-growing arena of media critique.
</P>
<P>
   Laventhol had resigned from his duties at Times Mirror partly
because he has Parkinson's disease, but he said that he had been
taking medication for about a year ``that has given me a lot of
energy and endurance and enables me to do this job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit of an awkward discussion, but I am fine,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cover of Fortune Raises Rivals' Eyebrows
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Fortune magazine ran different covers on the
same issue, and half of the split run has the other financial
magazines buzzing.
</P>
<P>
   One version of the issue dated April 12 announces ``Speed
Sells!'' across a picture of Jeff Gordon, Nascar's 1998 driver of
the year. It was sent to subscribers and was sold on newsstands in
the South, most of the Midwest and as Fortune's managing editor,
John Huey, put it, ``wherever there are motorheads.''
</P>
<P>
   The other cover, which featured an article about Levi Strauss &AMP;
Co., displayed a curvy female bottom clad in a pair of fashionably
snug Levi's jeans and was sold in markets more amenable to bottoms
on newsstands: New York and most of the East Coast, Chicago and
California.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis D'Vorkin, the executive editor of Forbes magazine,
criticized the Levi's cover as sensational. ``It was a cover solely
for the purposes of titillation and had nothing to do with the
thrust of the story,'' he said. ``When you look at that cover, you
think, Levi's is a sexy company on the move. The story, if you read
it, says Levi's is a disastrous scenario. It was deceptive.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for McGraw-Hill's Business Week, Robert Pondiscio,
said that the Levi's cover had been the subject of discussion and
that the general consensus was that ``it looks like John Huey's bid
to become editor of Maxim magazine.'' He was referring to the
popular men's magazine that often features female models on its
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Huey said that he based his decision to run split covers largely
on research that suggested that ``Nascar sells really well in
certain parts of the country and doesn't sell in other parts of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Huey said that he was not guilty of sensationalism. He said that
his competitors at Forbes and Business Week were jealous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not our model for how to sell on the newsstand,'' Huey
said. ``And Maxim isn't either, come to think of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Final sales figures for the two covers of Fortune, which is
owned by Time Warner, won't be available for months.
</P>
<P>
   Another Apology by `60 Minutes'
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in four months, the CBS News program ``60
Minutes'' is acknowledging that it was snookered.
</P>
<P>
   A statement prepared for Sunday night's broadcast says that a
1997 report on drug smuggling at the California-Mexico border
highlighted a supposedly official memo that was actually a fake.
The memo, designed to look as if it came from the local district
director of the service, called on Customs agents to process ``as
quickly as possible'' the trucks owned by a company linked to
Mexican drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have concluded that we were deceived,'' the CBS statement
reads. The Customs Service, it says, was correct in saying that the
memo was ``fraudulent'' and that ``60 Minutes'' had been ``the
victim of a hoax.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement also apologizes to Rudy M. Camacho, the San
Diego-based district director of the Customs Service, whose name
was attached to the bogus memo, featured at the end of a report by
correspondent Mike Wallace and producer Lee Zeidman.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the program's executive producer, Don Hewitt,
apologized on the air for broadcasting an independent filmmaker's
report about drug smuggling, which also contained faked material.
That June 1997 report, broadcast two months after the Mexican
border report, purported to show people described as Colombian drug
couriers swallowing heroin-filled latex containers before their
flights to London. A British newspaper, The Guardian, later
reported that the film maker hired the purported couriers to play
scripted roles.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho filed a defamation suit a year ago against CBS over the
report. When asked for comment on the case Friday, both Camacho's
lawyer, David Hicks, and the ``60 Minutes'' spokesman, Kevin
Tedesco, offered an identical one-sentence response: ``The matter
was amicably resolved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
