A3906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHITECTURE-PRIZE-NY     04-11 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-PRIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH ARCHITECT WINS $100,000 PRITZKER ARCHITECTURE PRIZE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sir Norman Foster, the British architect whose work celebrates
the power of modern building technology, has been awarded the
Pritzker Architecture Prize for 1999. The prize, which includes a
stipend of $100,000, is to be presented at a ceremony on June 6 in
Berlin, where Foster has recently completed a redesign of the
historic Reichstag building.
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent buildings designed by Foster, who is 73, include
the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp. in Hong Kong, Stansted
Airport outside London, and the Sainsbury Center for Visual Arts,
in Norfolk, England.
</P>
<P>
   Foster is the second British architect to be honored with the
Pritzker Prize, considered the profession's most prestigious award.
The first, James Stirling, was awarded the prize in 1981. Unlike
Stirling, however, Foster has remained faithful to esthetic
concepts developed by the modern movement in the early decades of
the century: the bold expression of structure, a lavish use of
glass, and dramatic interior spaces unimpeded by walls.
</P>
<P>
   At the 47-story Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp., perhaps
Foster's best known project, tall, thin slabs of metal, glass and
concrete appear to be clamped together by three immense steel
trusses.
</P>
<P>
   For the Sainsbury Art Center, he designed a hangarlike
structure: a metal space frame, inset with glass, in the form of an
inverted U. His design for the Carre d'Art in Nimes, France,
emphasized formal and structural affinities between modern
architecture and the classical vernacular of the adjacent Maison
Carree.
</P>
<P>
   Born to a working-class family in Manchester in 1935, Foster has
refined an esthetic whose roots lie in the Industrial Revolution
and in the split that developed in the 19th century between
architecture and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting that the Pritzker Prize will be awarded to Foster
in Berlin, for that is where architects sought to eliminate that
split by deriving forms from modern structural techniques in the
period between the world wars. Foster's design for the Reichstag,
which features a glass dome enclosing spiral ramps, is a crowning
achievement of this 20th-century tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The Pritzker Prize will be presented at the Altes Museum, a
Neo-Classical landmark designed by Karl Friedrick Schinkel in
1923-30. A reception will then be held at the New National Gallery,
the final work of Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, which was completed in
1967.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1979, the Pritzker Architecture Prize is sponsored by
the Hyatt Foundation of Los Angeles. The jury for this year's prize
included J. Carter Brown, Giovanni Agnelli, Ada Louise Huxtable,
Toshio Nakamura, Jorge Silvetti and Lord Rothschild. Bill Lacy was
executive director. Previous winners include Philip Johnson, Luis
Barragan, I.M. Pei, Aldo Rossi, Alvaro Siza, Tadao Ando and Renzo
Piano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
