</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOKYO-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEETHOVEN VIA TOKYO WITH A RUSSIAN TOUCH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Beethoven string quartets, a specialty of the
Tokyo String Quartet in its earlier configurations, have been
notably absent from one listener's experience of the group since
Mikhail Kopelman became first violinist in 1996. So a special
curiosity attached to the performance of Beethoven's C major
``Razumovsky'' Quartet (Op. 59, No. 3) that ended the Tokyo's
concert on Wednesday evening at Alice Tully Hall.
</P>
<P>
   It was a marvel. True, the deck was stacked a bit with this
work, tinged as it is with Russian folk music, since Kopelman, who
was trained in Russia, has given the group a certain Slavic quality
of its own. But the unanimity of spirit here was remarkable by any
standard, and individual voices were no less impressive on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Sadao Harada, the cellist, gave the Andante a firm grounding
with his squarely tuned and resoundingly plucked bass notes.
Kazuhide Isomura, the violist, set the fugue of the finale spinning
with fine rhythmic definition and delicious vigor and was answered
in kind by Kopelman, Harada and Kikuei Ikeda, the second violinist.
In all, the work sounded freshly minted and brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   The Tokyo also gave a compelling account of a work that was
freshly minted, the Third Quartet by Michio Mamiya, a 69-year-old
Japanese composer, subtitled ``A Song of the White Wind.'' Vaguely
programmatic in relation to the American Indian god of the wind,
and amiably asymmetric, the work offsets an engaging, angularly
stated thesis in the first movement with a sentimental antithesis
in the second, offering no attempt at synthesis.
</P>
<P>
   As gripping as many of the Tokyo's interpretations have been
with Kopelman, there has been a persistent unevenness in the
quality of performance, whether because certain works have yet to
settle into the altered group's repertory or because Kopelman is
slow to warm up.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, the first performance in the program, in this
case, Schumann's A minor Quartet (Op. 41, No. 1), was the least
impressive, because of sour or slightly mistuned attacks from
Kopelman: something perhaps in keeping with Russian style but
foreign to the Tokyo's. Still the group conveyed the work's
Mendelssohnian spirit in exuberant fashion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
