<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VACCINE THAT MAY PREVENT SHINGLES  
 GETTING THE GOODS OUT OF A BOTTLE 
SAFER STICKS FOR FLAG WAVERS 
SAVING MONEY BY REUSING STEAM 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Md., Mass.)   By Teresa Riordan   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicken pox is a classic childhood ailment that can leave a kid
housebound with a sore throat, fever, and itchy sores. After two
weeks, the chicken pox symptoms usually have vanished, but the
varicella-zoster virus lingers behind, hiding in sensory nerve
cells near the spinal cord. It lies dormant through adulthood when,
for some people, it becomes active again, causing another disease _
shingles.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 600,000 to 1.2 million cases of shingles occur
every year, in the elderly or in people whose immune systems are
compromised. ``It can be very painful because it pinches the nerve
cells,'' said Dr. Abbas Vafai, chief of biologics at the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta. ``The rash area
causes excruciating pain. It may last for four weeks or longer.''
</P>
<P>
   While antiviral drugs can reduce the length of the rash, no drug
currently available prevents the disease from occurring or
recurring. Vafai hopes that a vaccine he recently patented will do
exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a vaccine currently available against chicken pox,''
Vafai said. ``But it uses a live, attenuated virus. While it is
very effective against chicken pox, the vaccine itself becomes
latent again and can reactivate later in life to cause shingles.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using a live virus to create his vaccine, Vafai took
a piece of a glycoprotein _ which attaches to the surface of the
varicella-zoster virus _ and chopped it off at one end. The
remaining part of the glycoprotein stimulates the immune system to
produce virus-neutralizing antibodies, which when used as a
vaccine, Vafai said, would prevent a dormant virus already in the
body from reactivating and causing shingles.
</P>
<P>
   So far Vafai's vaccine has been tested on lab animals. He was
granted patent 5,824,319, which has been assigned to Research Corp.
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the Goods Out of a Bottle
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's shampoo or ketchup, the problem is the same: how to
get those last dribs and drabs out of the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Moheb M. Ibrahim, a machinist in Baltimore, thinks he has solved
the problem with his recently patented double-ended bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The bottle looks like a normal bottle with one big exception: It
has a neck and opening at each end. Although the necks of the
bottle are narrow, the caps that cover them are wide, so that the
bottle will be stable resting on either end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The caps are larger to allow the bottle to stand freely, and
there's a plug in the caps to keep the product from leaking,''
Ibrahim said.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim hopes to license patent 5,829,607.
</P>
<P>
   Safer Sticks For Flag Wavers
</P>
<P>
   Carol Goodman Kaufman, a mother of three, used to think of
flag-waving as a harmless fun for kids. Until, that is, she saw a
girl almost get her eye poked out by an overzealous flag-wielding
sister at a holiday celebration a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaufman has patented a flag stick made of a flexible foam
plastic that bends when jabbed into a firm object.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaufman now sells her Flexi-Flags through her one-woman
business in Worcester, Mass. She received patent 5,862,773.
</P>
<P>
   Saving Money By Reusing Steam
</P>
<P>
   An inventor in New York City has patented a way to cut energy
costs for factories that use high-pressure steam in their
production processes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, they just vent the exhaust steam into the
atmosphere,'' said Gerald Fisher, whose system captures excess
steam and diverts it into a series of pipes and valves so that it
can be used to heat the plant.
</P>
<P>
   One of his systems, Fisher said, has been installed at the
Smurfit-Stone Corp.'s plant in Wakefield, Mass., which uses
high-pressure steam to stiffen and dry cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not 100 percent efficient,'' he said. ``But they've been
saving 15 percent of their total energy bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and Joseph Manaseri received patent 5,865,369.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
