<HEADER>
A3914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LETTERS-TV-REVIEW-NYT     04-11 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETTERS-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE LETTERS:' RICH FOLKS, ONE INSCRUTABLE, THE OTHER VULNERABLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When rich people go bad, at least in fiction, they do it in one
of two ways. Like Andrew Makepeace Ladd III, they shut down
emotionally and rely on taste and convention to make life seem
controllable. Or like Melissa Gardner, they seek out sensation and,
intoxicated by the freedom that money allows, eventually drown.
</P>
<P>
   It was probably a mistake to turn Andy and Melissa's
two-character epistolary play, ``Love Letters,'' into a
full-fledged television movie (Monday night on ABC). But there are
enormously talented people at work here: A.R. Gurney wrote the
script, based on his own play, and Stanley Donen, doing his first
television project at the age of 75, directed.
</P>
<P>
   So it's safe to say that in less gifted hands the result could
have been much worse, given the inevitable loss of impact when
described events are acted out and visible, rather than revealed a
sentence at a time through the written word. For those who missed
the stage production, it's worthwhile seeing the film just to get
to know the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Letters'' was first performed in New York in 1989 by
Kathleen Turner and John Rubinstein. Over the years scores of
couples from Brat Pack members to Jayne Meadows and Steve Allen
have taken a turn in the roles, in New York and Los Angeles. For an
actor it's a low-commitment job: minimal rehearsals, no sets, no
costume changes; the two characters just sit at a table side by
side and read.
</P>
<P>
   Now Laura Linney, who has played some intriguing variations on
all-American innocence (in ``The Truman Show'' and in Armistead
Maupin's ``Tales of the City''), is Melissa, and Steven Weber, best
known for the sitcom ``Wings,'' is Andy. Ms. Linney makes every
facial expression enchanting. Weber stands there like a lump,
resistant to emotion even when his father dies; but that's
certainly true to character. It would just be nice if at times we
could see an emotion trying to bubble to the surface before he
pushes it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Letters'' begins in the characters' childhoods, with an
invitation to Melissa's seventh birthday party and her thank-you
note for Andy's gift. It follows the characters through boarding
school, college, war, marriages, children, divorce, career
decisions, alcoholism and, finally after all those years, an
affair. With each other. In the end (and in the beginning, in the
television version), Andy is a middle-aged U.S. Senator, coming
home from Melissa's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone familiar with Gurney's work knows that his characters are
almost always affluent East Coast WASPs, and these two are no
exception. In one letter Andy apologizes to Melissa's nanny. He
remembers her family's butler bringing them ginger ale and cookies
on a silver tray.
</P>
<P>
   But Melissa at least is irreverent about it all. In college she
turns up for the Yale-Harvard game in a new red convertible,
announcing: ``Granny died. She left me tons of dough.'' She never
loses her sense of humor. Years later, when Andy's annual Christmas
card, with family photograph, arrives (``Joy to the world from all
the Ladds _ Andy, Jane, Drew, Nicholas and Ted''), she replies with
one sentence, ``Remind me to send a check to Planned Parenthood.''
</P>
<P>
   She always bounces back: after her husband cheats on her, she
loses custody of her daughters, and she pays a return visit to the
drying-out center with the rolling green lawns. She keeps traveling
and painting and having shows in SoHo, until finally it's all too
much. Andy is such an idiot that he never notices, over the
decades, that Melissa's descents into drinking and depression
always come right after he has disappointed her. That's his
tragedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
