   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Sunday,
April 11. If you have any questions, please call Kevin Catalano on
the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
WAR-VETERAN (Kansas City, Mo.) Ben Alvarado, a World War II
veteran, recently returned to Germany and now grapples with
memories of the war's effect on his brother. By DONALD BRADLEY.
Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-MURDER (Kansas City, Mo.) _ As the details of five puzzling
murders begin to unfold, the neighborhood where the crimes occurred
still is trying to recover from the shock. By MATT CAMPBELL. Story
will move in the ``a'' category.
SPRINT-CHIEF (Undated) Call him the $280 million man. That's the
windfall _ so far _ that Sprint Corp. Chief Executive Officer
William T. Esrey stands to collect when he cashes in the gargantuan
stock option grants he has received in the past two years. Forget
his salary and bonus. Options alone have earned him the equivalent
of $2.7 million a week, $538,000 per workday, or $67,000 an hour,
as of the close of business Friday. The company response, however,
echoes others caught up in the national debate about the widening
wage gap between executives and workers. By TED SICKINGER. Story
will move in the ``f'' category.
MILITARY-CONFLICTS (Undated) Although U.S. involvement in
Yugoslavia and Iraq do not yet meet the Pentagon's idea of a major
war, every sortie flown and each missile launched pushes America's
military closer to its limits. Likewise, flights bringing relief
supplies to Kosovar refugees or whisking those exiles out of the
region further tax American military wherewithal. The danger,
experts say, is a small but growing risk that U.S. forces could
find themselves shorthanded if trouble cropped up elsewhere. By
SCOTT CANON. Story will move in the ``w'' category.
Y2K-BILL (Undated) Customers stacked up 20 deep in 1995 on the
opening day of a gourmet grocery in Warren, Mich., before finally
walking out in a huff.
</P>
<P>
   The swipe of a single credit card with a year 2000 expiration
date had crashed the Produce Palace's computer register, which was
high-tech but not Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   That made owner Mike Yarsike an early victim of the Y2K bug. He
settled for $260,000 from the cash register company after becoming
one of the first victims to file a Y2K lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But few others will have that option if some federal and state
lawmakers have their way. By FINN BULLERS. Story will move in the
``w'' category.
</P>
