<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-VETERAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN TO GERMANY IS POIGNANT JOURNEY FOR WORLD WAR II VETERAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ Two pieces of paper. One more than a
half-century old, the other new.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Alvarado sat at his kitchen table and tried to fit the two
together like a puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a worn photograph taken in 1944 of his brother,
Mike. It showed a young soldier with bright eyes, shiny gold
buttons on his lapel and a confident, almost cocksure, smile.
</P>
<P>
   The other was an invitation to Ben Alvarado and other members of
the 80th Infantry Division to return to Weimar, Germany, where in
April 1945 they took part in a bizarre capture _ involving a
bicycle courier and a sleepy mayor _ that ended World War II for
the small German town.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Weimar now want those GIs to return for a
celebration of life, and to thank the American soldiers for sparing
their town that day 54 years ago Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Bible says, `Love thy enemy,' but this is
confusing,'' Alvarado said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   There was no humor. His chuckle was a plea to help him
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Alvarado, who loved to sing and dance to swing music, had
lied about his age to get into the Army. He was full of spunk and
wanted to go where his brother, Ben, was. Their parents were dead.
</P>
<P>
   Mike was only 17 when he landed on Utah Beach on D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his vigor in places such as Cherbourg and Bastogne. He
came back to Kansas City, Mo., in 1945 and spent the next 20 years
in mental hospitals. Then he lived with Ben for 24 years in south
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Mike never recovered. He never held a job. He never married.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you at Cherbourg?'' he would ask strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ben Alvarado, who landed on Omaha Beach and was later shot
and spent three months in a hospital, has been invited to celebrate
life with a country that took so much from him.
</P>
<P>
   And he accepted. He arrived in Weimar Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make friends there,'' he said last week before leaving.
``I'm easy to get along with.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he holds no bitterness toward the German soldiers. They
were following orders, just like he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were scared and they cried, just like us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he sees the strangeness of a mutual celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is highly unusual, said a spokesman for the Veterans of
Foreign Wars.
</P>
<P>
   Weimar isn't in France or Belgium, countries that were liberated
by Allied forces and where citizens embraced American GIs. Many
reunions have been staged in those places.
</P>
<P>
   But Germany was the enemy. Its people weren't liberated. They
were defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of another case where a German city has wanted to
thank American GIs,'' VFW spokesman Bill Smith said from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gerlinde Schmidt, a Weimar resident who helped arrange the
reunion, said the town wanted to thank the American soldiers for
capturing the city ``without running blood.''
Ben Alvarado, 73, lives in south Kansas City. He's been married 50
years to his wife, Victoria, and the couple raised five children.
He has a pet donkey and seldom misses church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie to anybody,'' he said last week. ``I
wasn't a very good soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   He was just a guy who was drafted at age 18 and went where he
was told and did what he was told.
</P>
<P>
   That meant landing at Omaha Beach on D-Day. The first wave was
still pinned on the beach when his outfit scrambled ashore 30
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't fighting. We were just being shot at. We couldn't
see anything and it was so loud,'' Alvarado said. ``I knew it was
the end of my life ... There was no way to get out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, he figured, Mike was doing pretty much the same
thing. Because of secrecy of the D-Day landing, Alvarado had just
learned that his brother had joined the Army and had actually
beaten him to England.
</P>
<P>
   Ben was mad, but understood. Mike had always wanted to tag along
when Ben would go off with friends.
</P>
<P>
   Ben wrote Mike: ``Take care of yourself. I'll see you back in
Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
