<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3922 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-VETERAN-2NDTAKE-K     04-11 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-VETERAN-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
[HEAD RETURN TO GERMANY IS POIGNANT JOURNEY FOR WORLD WAR II
VETERAN After D-Day, Ben's 80th Infantry made its way inland.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike's unit went west to Cherbourg. The deep channel port was
vital for the Allied advance. The fighting raged three weeks before
Patton broke through June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Alvarado was shot Sept. 27 during night fighting near St.
Genevieve. He spent the rest of 1944 in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Mike found himself surrounded in Bastogne during the Battle of
the Bulge. Americans fought off repeated German attempts to take
the city.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Mike, barely old enough to drive, decided he'd had
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just sat down and said he couldn't fight no more,'' Ben
Alvarado said.
</P>
<P>
   About that same time, Ben Alvarado rejoined the 80th Infantry,
which later that spring would cross the Rhine River and push into
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   On April 12, 1945, the 80th arrived on hills above Weimar. Ben
Alvarado was in a nearby town guarding prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The American commander, Col. N.O. Costello, knew that surrender
talks had begun and that the war would soon be over.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to give Weimar a chance to save itself. But the
Buchenwald concentration camp was nearby, and he knew SS troops
were in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Costello summoned a burgermeister from another town and gave the
man an ultimatum to deliver by bicycle to the Weimar mayor. If the
town would fly a white flag, the American guns would spare the
city.
</P>
<P>
   The burgermeister roused the town's mayor from bed.
</P>
<P>
   A town meeting was convened as American tanks and artillery sat
poised above. SS soldiers argued against surrender, saying Hitler
wouldn't approve.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were hoping the city would go for the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was spring,'' remembered Richard Bobb, now 80, of Ormond
Beach, Fla. ``The trees were blooming and the birds were singing.
We didn't want to fight anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   That evening, a white flag was hoisted. The SS troops fled into
the woods shortly before American jeeps rolled into town.
Last week in their kitchen, Victoria Alvarado tried to help her
husband make sense of the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about winners and losers or conquerors and heroes.
This is about surviving,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   Think about the German children and their children who came from
those who were there that day, she said. That's what these people
are talking about. Many of them may never have been born if the
town meeting had turned out differently.
</P>
<P>
   Ben knew she was right.
</P>
<P>
   So he went to Weimar, and this week will visit those who
remember that day. He will talk to children who, as his wife said,
may never have been born.
</P>
<P>
   And he will think of his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Ben had tried to get Mike to talk about the war.
What had he seen so terrible at Cherbourg and Bastogne to render
him a shell of the young man who would jump, jive and wail to Benny
Goodman?
</P>
<P>
   Mike never answered. Maybe he didn't remember.
</P>
<P>
   There were times when Ben caught Mike singing, in a near
whisper, a song from the days before the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``His voice was weak and would break,'' Ben remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Alvarado died of a heart attack on a summer day in 1989 in
Ben's back yard. Ben found him, a leaf rake clutched in his
brother's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Ben often wondered why he was able to come home, get married,
work and raise a family while his brother never stopped hearing the
bombs of Cherbourg and would sing the old songs in a broken voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the difference was that I ignored it. ... I refused to
believe it was real,'' Ben said. ``Mike couldn't do that. He was
too young. It was too real for him.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
