<HEADER>
A3924 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASS-MURDER2NDTAKE-KA     04-11 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-MURDER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECONSTRUCTION OF A MASS MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL and CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Beach's neighborhood, people sit on their front porches on
warm evenings. The street he lived on is secluded, but the lights
and sounds of the Westport area _ bustling bars, packed restaurants
and live music _ are in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the residents are renters, and their houses are being
bought up by a subsidiary of DST Systems Inc. for redevelopment.
Residents in these single-story and two-story frame homes include
waitresses, children who ride bicycles, young musicians and a few
partyers. Beach and Davis were limousine drivers who took
passengers to and from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Phillips, lead singer of the band Frogpond, recalled
residents barricading the one-way street for a block party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd play on someone's porch to entertain everyone,'' she
said. Now she can't imagine something like that happening. Phillips
spent the night at a friend's home after hearing news of the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was creepy,'' she said. ``The vibe on the street was too
weird. I've never been that close to something that weird.''
</P>
<P>
   To Brian Miller, who moved in down the block about a year ago,
the street used to be unnoticed. But the killings have brought
gawkers and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, nobody knew this street was here,'' he said.
`` Now everybody does.''
</P>
<P>
   The killings also have affected waitresses at nearby Nichols
Lunch, where Beach, Davis and Nickerson frequently dined. The
waitresses shook their heads in amazement one day last week while
swapping stories about having served Beach many meals.
</P>
<P>
   Tears welling in her eyes, Angelina Wood bragged about the
kindness Beach, Davis and Nickerson showed her one Christmas,
giving her a Chiefs pin as a gift. They knew she collected pins and
wanted to thank her for her service.
</P>
<P>
   For years Beach had come in virtually every day, often for more
than one meal a day. Davis called him ``Dad,'' and Beach would
always pay for his stepson's meals, they remembered. Police who
searched the Beach house and a cleanup team that later disinfected
it reported an unforgettable scene:
</P>
<P>
   There was virtually no furniture. A couch and easy chair
apparently served as beds. Several cats lived in the house, which
reeked of cat waste.
</P>
<P>
   Police discovered a dozen or more stick-on air fresheners
throughout the house and a window-unit air conditioner turned on
high. They were not enough to mask the odor left by the cats and
the killings.
</P>
<P>
   After the bodies were removed, the blood remained.
</P>
<P>
   Cobwebs and dust blanketed shelves and walls. Shredded remnants
of drapes were strung across some windows. A back-door window was
covered by a white terry-cloth towel.
</P>
<P>
   There were no lamps. The rooms were lighted by bare light bulbs
in ceiling fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   The living area had stereos, televisions and a VCR containing
the rental movie ``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   Several plastic model cars and trucks and numerous wall posters
of military aircraft also were found. Wall-mounted display cases
held dozens of Matchbox cars. A laminated map of Kansas City _
useful for livery drivers _ was tacked to a wall.
</P>
<P>
   There was no kitchen table. Conveniences for everyday living
were missing. The sinks were rusted and piled with rusted pans. The
refrigerator was not running. The stove was crusted and inoperable.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning the house was a task that fell to Don McNulty and Shawn
Bayouth of Bio Cleaning Services of America, which specializes in
cleaning crime scenes. The house, protected by plastic and duct
tape, was worked on by the men for seven hours Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two days, families of the five victims said their
final goodbyes.
</P>
<P>
   At Nativity of Mary Catholic Church in Independence, Mo., on
Saturday, Beach's ex-wife, Erika Bauer, and her other children
mourned the loss of Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Their faces bathed in tears, their bodies racked with sobs, they
remembered their son and brother by his affectionate nickname,
``Mikey,'' and recalled his loving attention to those around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gather today with broken hearts and angry hearts,'' said
the Rev. Bob Rost. ``...Whenever we face death or violence, we know
that God has already faced this personally and God is always with
us. ... Precious Lord, we ask you to take Mikey's hand and lead him
home. Take our hands, too. We need you to give us strength and to
heal the wounds we cannot heal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Star's Lynn Franey and Shawna Hamel contributed to this
report
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
