</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(HLW)
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans the following on the continuing crisis
in Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO on Sunday issued an aerial
photograph of what officials said could be ``possible mass graves''
of ethnic Albanian villagers killed by Serb forces in Kosovo. By
Craig R. Whitney. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Belgrade's markets were
stuffed full with meat and vegetables of all kinds for Sunday's
Orthodox Easter celebrations, with formerly scarce items, like
cooking oil and sugar, plentiful in state stores at cheap prices.
Wartime regulations, instituted a few days after NATO's bombing
campaign began 19 days ago, have kept prices down. After a few
early days of shortages, as worried residents bought up large
amounts of imperishables, the state funnelled new supplies into the
shops. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT (Brussels, Belgium) _ On her first diplomatic
foray since the NATO bombing began, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, arrived here Sunday night to show how unified the
alliance remained in pursuing the air assault against Slobodan
Milosevic. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JOURNALIST (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ A leading opposition
journalist is assassinated outside his home. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ A Russian relief convoy headed
for Yugoslavia was stopped by Hungarian authorities on Sunday after
they determined it was carrying fuel and equipment that could be
used by Belgrade's military, NATO officials said. By Michael R.
Gordon. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ More refugees cross the border
and describe the Serbian military moves near the border. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ The NATO bombing of Yugoslavia may or
may not free the Kosovars; but a thousand miles from Belgrade it
has had a profoundly liberating effect. After eight long-suffering
years, it's once again acceptable _ even de rigeur _ for Russians
to dislike Americans. Enough of them have embraced animosity, and
with such sudden fervor, that some Russian experts say it threatens
to become the guiding force in a relationship with little else
going for it. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS (New York) _ About 300 Albanians from New
York are flying to the Balkans to join the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The following two items are tentative:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIGION (Undated) _ How each religion reads its own
history into the conflict. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Dateline TK) _ A look at the refugee crisis.
</P>
