<SLUG> BC-MASS-MURDER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECONSTRUCTION OF A MASS MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL and CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ It started with two homicides on a Sunday two
weeks ago. The body count grew and eight days passed before anyone
outside the tiny corner house realized that something was terribly
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, five men were discovered dead inside Gary Beach's
rented home in the Westport area of Kansas City. Each of the
victims had been shot and left where he fell in the home. With
rooms barely 11 feet square, it became impossible for anyone inside
to move about without stepping over bodies.
</P>
<P>
   One was in the middle of the kitchen floor. One was slumped on
the couch. One blocked the doorway to the bathroom. Two lay on the
steps to the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Even with victims scattered about the house, neighbors say,
Beach came and went as he always had.
</P>
<P>
   Today he is in jail, charged in one homicide and a suspect in
the four others. He knew all of the victims: Kenneth H. Gulley Jr.,
45, stepson of Beach's brother; Michael Davis, 32, Beach's stepson,
who lived in the house; Mark Nelson, 28, who also lived at the
house; Christopher G. Conrad, 27, who knew Beach through Nelson;
and Jerry Nickerson, 56, a longtime friend of Beach's.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated requests, The Kansas City Star has been unable
to talk to Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the investigation say police think they have
pieced together a chronology of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The first two victims, Nelson and Davis, were killed March 28.
Both were shot with a .25-caliber pistol. Nelson also had been
beaten on the head with a hammer and Davis had been suffocated.
Nelson was found in the bathroom and Davis on the basement steps.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining victims were killed with a 9mm handgun. Conrad was
killed on the basement steps and Nickerson in the kitchen. Gulley
was killed April 1. He died on a couch in the front room. Neighbors
later recalled hearing gunshots that morning but had no idea what
was going on inside the house.
</P>
<P>
   They notified two Kansas City police officers who were parked
along Jefferson on an unrelated call. The officers left without
investigating. Police are trying to determine what might have
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say police think that Conrad was the principal target of
a murder plot and that the others were killed for various reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The mass murder disturbed even veteran homicide officers, who
deal with death on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most emotionally disturbing scenes I've ever
seen,'' said homicide Detective Ron Russell, a 29-year-veteran.
``It was eerie.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a typical homicide involved one body and four or five
relatives. This case involved five bodies and more than 40
relatives. Police briefed the relatives as a group Wednesday night
about the status of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You begin to feel everyone's pain,'' Russell said. ``It starts
to wear on you emotionally as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Beach became a suspect Monday after Gulley's relatives drew
attention to the Jefferson Street house. Gulley had told them he
was planning to go out with Beach after work in North Kansas City
about 12:30 a.m. April 1. When he failed to return later that day
or the next, the relatives became worried.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives followed up with North Kansas City police early
Monday and persuaded Detective Rick Landon and Detective Duane
Hostikka to check Beach's house. Gulley's brother, Dennis, and
other relatives followed the officers.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives said they had no authority to enter the house.
They radioed Kansas City police and left.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives stayed, and moments later a couple of them kicked
in the rear door. Once inside, Dennis Gulley noticed a pile of
blankets on the basement steps. Lifting them, he found one of the
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City police soon arrived and found distraught members of
the Gulley family in front of the house. Within 24 hours, police
had arrested Beach in the parking lot of a hotel near his house.
He's charged with Gulley's death and has pleaded not guilty. Police
are investigating the four other deaths. &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
