<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WITNESSES-12-C     04-11 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WITNESSES-12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    WORLD COMMUNITY BEGINS BUILDING ITS CASE TO PROSECUTE SERB
ATROCITIES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANKOVAC REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia In a quiet corner of this
sprawling tent city, a sad and exhausted man from Pristina told
international observers of the horror he witnessed the day Serbian
forces emptied the capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing to his parents' home as Serb police and masked
paramilitary gunmen began their brutal sweep of the city on April
1, the young man said he found eight lifeless bodies in one room.
Among the freshly bloodied corpses was his mother, who had been
shot twice in the back of the head. His father was missing and
dead, too, he presumed.
</P>
<P>
   The man, whose name was withheld by international authorities
here to protect his identity, wants justice.
</P>
<P>
   So does much of the world.
</P>
<P>
   With the aim of supplying a case for the international war
crimes tribunal, United Nations officials and other international
monitors at refugee camps in Macedonia and Albania are recording
eyewitness testimony from among the some 600,000 refugees forced
from Kosovo, the ethnic Albanian province in Yugoslavia besieged by
Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Observers of the 55-nation Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), who until late March sought to
monitor a cease-fire in Kosovo, have in the past week collected
testimony from hundreds of refugees in the budding effort to
prepare war crimes indictments.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any criminal case, the sooner you can get hold of the
evidence and take down those stories, the better,'' said Sandy
Blyth, spokesman for the OSCE monitors in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The detective work, slowly being organized by the United
Nations, the OSCE and non-profit agencies, will be turned over to
the war crimes tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials, seeking to bolster domestic and international
support for NATO's continuing air war against Yugoslavia, have
accused Serb authorities of mass executions, at least one mass rape
of young women at a Serb army camp near Dakovica and the pillage of
scores of cities and towns. Last week, the Pentagon announced the
names of nine Yugoslav commanders put on notice that their actions
are being closely monitored by the West.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen surmised Sunday on ABC's ``This
Week'' that ``we are going to find more and more evidence of mass
graves, mass executions, some pretty horrific stories.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no way independently to verify the accounts of killings
and other atrocities because most international aid workers and
foreign journalists have been expelled from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The task of investigators inside the refugee camps is enormous
and painstakingly slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two weeks of interviewing, I've only found a handful of
eyewitnesses to killings and from our point of view only one
witness is not good enough,'' said Ben Ward, a war crimes
researcher for Human Rights Watch, a private group that monitors
human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Ward is concentrating on reports of the methodical destruction
March 28-30 of the town of Vucitrn (CQ), north of Pristina. He
needs 10 to 12 independent eyewitness accounts to make a solid
case, and so far has only two.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the first step is simply to catalog the
testimony of refugees and then cull the most dependable stories for
further examination and verification.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence also is being collected from sophisticated U.S. spy
satellites, aerial reconnaissance and sporadic contacts via mobile
and satellite telephone connections to residents still in Kosovo.
However, those contacts are becoming rarer, officials conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best evidence is going there and seeing it with our own
eyes,'' said Sheri Fink (CQ) of Physicians for Human Rights, an
independent aid organization. ``It is frustrating that we don't
know and can't say yet what is going on in Kosovo. There may be no
one left there to tell the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   From descriptions by refugees crossing into Albania and
Macedonia, the worst atrocities appeared to have occurred in the
western areas of Kosovo near the border with Albania, where
fighting had been heaviest between Serb forces and the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium on Sunday, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea showed aerial
photographs of the village of Pusto Selo, southwest of Pristina,
that appeared to be freshly turned soil at a site that looked
``somewhat similar'' to aerial shots of mass graves seen during the
war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators in Macedonia said the prosecution of leading
Serb figures, including Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
could be hindered by the fact that the Kosovo atrocities appear to
have been random, varying from village to village or even from
block to block in the same town, and not a consistent blitz applied
to all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the villages were being cleared was systematic, but
not the atrocities,'' said an OSCE field worker at the Stankovac
refugee camp north of the Macedonian capital, Skopje. ``Those seem
to have been left to the discretion of the individual commanders
and vary from house to house and street to street.''
</P>
<P>
   Many refugees report that they could not positively identify the
police or paramilitary forces who committed killings and torched
houses because they wore masks. However, investigators are
soliciting other identifying details from eyewitnesses, such as
markings on military vehicles and troop uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Recording the eyewitness testimony _ and doing it soon _ is
crucial. Aid workers in the camps are overwhelmed trying to cope
with the basic needs of the refugees and there are too few
investigators, officials agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is wasting,'' said Fink. ``Memories fade and dead bodies
decay.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
