<HEADER>
A3931 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINT-CHIEF-KAN &LR;      04-11 1853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-CHIEF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT CHIEF IS COMPENSATION KING, BUT IS HE WORTH IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call him the $280 million man.
</P>
<P>
   That's the windfall _ so far _ that Sprint Corp. Chief Executive
Officer William T. Esrey stands to collect when he cashes in the
gargantuan stock option grants he has received in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Forget his salary and bonus. Options alone have earned him the
equivalent of $2.7 million a week, $538,000 per workday, or $67,000
an hour, as of the close of business Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it took Esrey 47 minutes to earn what an average
Kansas City, Mo., family took home during all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey didn't care to comment on his stock options, which make
him the undisputed compensation king of Kansas City and one of the
best-paid chief executives in the country, if not worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The company response, however, echoes others caught up in the
national debate about the widening wage gap between executives and
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, not every Walter Mitty out there can run a Fortune 500
company, much less generate Sprint's market-beating returns.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: In four years, Sprint has built the nation's
fastest-growing wireless phone company from scratch. Its flagship
long-distance division is beating competitors handily. And the
company is one of the most talked-about takeover targets in the
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line? Sprint shareholders have doubled their money in the
past year alone.
</P>
<P>
   So who's arguing with a few hundred million for the man in the
baronial corner office?
</P>
<P>
   Union members, for one, are wondering how one man can reap such
a bonanza when thousands who toil in the company trenches are
seeing their relatively measly base salaries frozen or increased by
3 or 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Sprint shareholders are scratching their heads,
wondering about the propriety of such eye-popping pay. The company
has even attracted its own gadfly, George Speight, who annually
proposes resolutions at the company's shareholders meeting to limit
the packages.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the issue raises the question: Is Esrey _ or any
other master of the universe _ worth that much money? Some
independent experts doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   They also wonder whether Sprint's board has simply given Esrey
an enormous golden parachute if or when he sells the company.
According to executive headhunters, the pool of managers with the
proven ability to run a Fortune 500 company is minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hot commodities that are hard to attract,'' said
Spencer Fields, a principal at William M. Mercer Inc. ``The chief
executives understand what they're worth, and the boards are forced
to acknowledge that with competitive pay packages.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock options are essentially a promise from the company to sell
a given number of shares at a fixed price for a specified period of
time. If the market price goes up after the grant, the option
holder can exercise the option, buy the shares at the old price,
then sell them at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale behind megagrants is simple: If chief executives
can jump-start a company's performance and generate high returns
for shareholders, then they deserve to share the swag.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with large salaries and bonuses, options are relatively
inexpensive for the company in terms of immediate cash outlays, and
are often rewarded in lieu of cash pay.
</P>
<P>
   Option plans also can be structured to tie the executive to the
company for the life of the option and often contain specific,
measurable performance criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, if the company underperforms, top officers feel
shareholders' pain, most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   That win-win reasoning is seen as sound corporate governance by
hundreds of companies, including the board of directors at Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company's proxy report to shareholders, the
board tries to link executive pay to the short- and long-term
performance of the company ``so as to maximize shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey can't cash in all his chips until 2002, unless someone
buys the company and accelerates the vesting schedule of his
options. Until then, he has to keep Sprint's stock levitating at
current levels or risk seeing his pot of gold shrink considerably.
</P>
<P>
   If the bull market continues, however, Esrey's financial picture
gets even rosier.
</P>
<P>
   None of the members of the board of directors' executive
compensation committee were available to comment on the specifics
of his compensation. Nor were subordinates willing to comment on
the boss's pay.
</P>
<P>
   The company did, however, release a statement saying,
``Shareholders consider his leadership critical to the steady
upward trend of the company's ... stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement also referred to the results of a recent Fortune
magazine survey that ranked Sprint as the most admired
telecommunications company _ ``results of his leadership and his
vision put into action.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's policy is to compare top officers' pay with that of
leaders at similar-size companies. The company tries to put total
compensation at the 75th percentile of those surveyed _ if
performance goals are met.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Sprint was ranked No. 88 in the Fortune 500 revenue
ranking. Esrey, however, ranked 16th in terms of the number of
options granted to Fortune 500 executives in 1997, according to
Executive Compensation Advisory Services.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by USA Today ranked Esrey's 1998 pay package _
$148.8 million, according to their calculations _ as the
10th-highest among 469 companies that had reported their executive
pay so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Esrey's compensation is definitely up there, but we see so
many of these that I can't say that it's overwhelmingly large,''
said Emily Zasada, senior project manager at Executive
Compensation, which tracks compensation at more than 1,000 public
companies. ``There's other executives who are within that
ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Disney's Michael Eisner, who exercised options valued at
more than $570 million in 1998. Or Jack Welch, the chief at General
Electric, who exercised $46 million in options and is sitting on an
additional $290 million in unexercised grants.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, consider what Sprint delivered to its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The company's regular stock, which tracks Sprint's local,
long-distance and directory publishing businesses, is up 83 percent
in the past year. The company also issued each shareholder a half
share of Sprint PCS stock for each regular share owned. Sprint PCS
stock is now worth $57 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Add in regular dividends, and Sprint is up almost 110 percent in
the past year, almost seven times the market as measured by the
surging Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   If Sprint's largest shareholders _ mostly mutual and pension
funds _ are worried about Esrey's megagrants, which are big enough
to dilute earnings slightly, they aren't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to see why. Sprint's high-octane performance has
created about $31 billion in shareholder wealth in the past year
alone, of which Esrey is on track to take home a little less than 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tony Ferrugia, a former Sprint employee who is now an
industry analyst with A.G. Edwards in St. Louis: ``If he could go
out and double my money again next year, I'd give him another 1
percent. Wouldn't you?''
According to industry studies, stock options now make up two-thirds
of a chief executive's pay. As the stock market has soared, those
executives have reaped enormous gains.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts contend that many chief executives are simply
riding the roaring bull market to mammoth paydays. With the size of
today's grants, a small uptick in stock price can produce a
windfall for the option holder.
</P>
<P>
   Many corporate chiefs also are allowed to eat their dessert
early, then go back for more. It's called a reload, or restoration
option, and allows an executive to capture any market gains in a
stock by exercising options he owns. The options are then replaced
at the new market price so any future gains also can be captured.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey exercised options on 433,580 shares of Sprint and 216,792
shares of Sprint PCS in 1998, realizing $20 million in value. In
both cases, more than half of those options were reloaded, and
Esrey has already seen an additional $17.2 million in unrealized
gains on the underlying shares.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of double-dipping rankles the rank and file, who see a
widening gap between the average worker and the occupants of the
corner offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most employees at Sprint are aware of Mr. Esrey's pay package,
and it doesn't sit well with them,'' said John Howard, an assistant
vice president at the Communications Workers of America, which
represents about 4,500 Sprint employees in 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to local union meetings, I hear about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaints have been louder this year, as Sprint is freezing
base pay for some staff and imposing an incentive compensation plan
that includes disciplinary actions _ including firing _ for those
who don't meet sales targets, union members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kingpin, the main man,'' said Jim Brimer, a spokesman
for the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which
represents 5,000 Sprint workers. ``And there's no question that
Sprint is a well-oiled machine that is churning out profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's got an entire organization behind him. Don't those
workers deserve to share in the rewards as well? This sounds like
`Sacrifice the workers, and give everything to me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Brimer is a shareholder and says he's ``tickled to death'' at
what has happened to Sprint stock. He concedes that Esrey should be
handsomely rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's reached the level of being ridiculous,'' he said.
``He's not worth that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Some compensation experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was grossly overpaid,'' said Graef Crystal, a professor at
the University of California-Berkeley and the editor of
crystalreport.com, an online newsletter on executive compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal uses a common but complicated mathematical formula known
as the Black and Scholes Model to value and compare executives'
stock options packages.
</P>
<P>
   Using that model, Crystal valued Esrey's 1997 pay package _
comprising base pay, bonus, incentive pay and options _ at $38.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   The package actually was worth far more because of Sprint's
subsequent share price appreciation. But using the more
conservative number, Crystal figured that Esrey's pay was 384
percent of the average chief executive's at a similar-size company
that generated similar performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 3 percent of chief executives among the 1,568 public
companies I surveyed were more overpaid than he was,'' Crystal
said.
</P>
<P>
   To calculate its own value of Esrey's 1997 option package, the
AFL-CIO simply picked the figures from the company's proxy report
and calculated that Esrey earned $76 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at it that way, the union figured it would take a
minimum-wage worker 7,142 years to earn the equivalent of Esrey's
1997 pay package.
</P>
<P>
   If the worker started today, he'd be finished by the year 9141.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
