<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: EGYPT IN PARIS; CHAPLIN'S `THE CIRCUS' AT HUNTER
COLLEGE; MILLENNIUM SERIES AT LINCOLN CENTER; GEORGIA O'KEEFE IN
WASHINGTON AND HARTFORD 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Conn.)   By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Out of the tombs of pharaohs and the highest
officials of ancient Egypt come more than 200 objects reunited for
the first time since they were excavated in the mid-19th century.
Dating from 3110 B.C. to 2258 B.C., these statues, bas-reliefs,
painted decors and items of jewelry have been assembled at the
Grand Palais in Paris in ``Egyptian Art at the Time of the
Pyramids.'' The exhibition closes on July 12 and will be seen from
Sept. 16 through Jan. 9 at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in
Manhattan. Information: 011-33-1-44-13-17-17.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin's `The Circus' at Hunter College
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Accompanied by a live performance of Charlie
Chaplin's original score by the New York Virtuosi Chamber Symphony
led by Gillian B. Anderson, Chaplin's 1928 comedy ``The Circus''
will be shown at 6:30 Monday night at the annual spring gala of the
Sylvia and Danny Kaye Playhouse at Hunter College. The event
introduces film to the lineup of dance, theater and music at the
Kaye Playhouse. In ``The Circus,'' Chaplin, in the guise of the
Little Tramp, samples life under the big top. Information: (212)
650-3860.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium Discussion at Lincoln Center
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What will the future be like? That subject and themes
in art, architecture, economics and fiction will be discussed from
6:30 to 8 Tuesday night at the Kaplan Penthouse at Lincoln Center
in the opening program of ``The Best of the Millennium,'' a
six-part series of lectures, commentary and discussions. The
series, a collaboration between Lincoln Center and The New York
Times Magazine's six-part Millennium series, is intended to bring
together leaders in many disciplines to explore themes prevalent
through the millennium, examine the century's issues and
achievements and identify forces likely to govern the achievements
of future centuries. Tuesday's discussion will be moderated by
Frank Rich, a columnist on the Op-Ed Page of The Times and a senior
writer for The New York Times Magazine. Information: (212)
721-6500.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia O'Keeffe and Alfred Stieglitz
</P>
<P>
   In the spring Georgia O'Keeffe seems to be flowering everywhere.
At the Phillips Collection in Washington from Saturday through July
18, she is the subject of ``Georgia O'Keeffe: The Poetry of
Things.'' An effort to illuminate the artist's esthetic, this
exhibition assembles 69 paintings and works on paper from
O'Keeffe's major series of flowers, fruit, leaves, shells, bones
and crosses. The works, from museums and private collections around
the country, are presented alongside real objects of the type she
collected. Information: (202) 387-2151. . . . At the Wadsworth
Atheneum in Hartford, five of O'Keeffe's groundbreaking paintings
will be shown with 112 photographs and photogravures in ``Alfred
Stieglitz, Georgia O'Keeffe and American Modernism.'' An
exploration of these artists' creative legacy and a chronicle of
Stieglitz's artistic evolution over 50 years, the show runs from
Friday to July 11. Information: (860) 278-2670.
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
