<HEADER>
A3933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POETRY-GATHERING-NYT &LR;      04-11 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POETRY-GATHERING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORAL TRADITIONS CONVERGE AS POETS GO OUT FOR A DRINK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont., Mass., Puerto Rico, Brazil)   By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was billed as ``a populist bacchanal'' and was
offered with a verse of advice plucked from T.S. Eliot: ``O, do not
ask what is it/Let us go and make our visit.''
</P>
<P>
   So they converged on Manhattan last weekend _ the poets, the
poetry lovers and the simply curious _ to travel in the footsteps
of Walt Whitman, Dylan Thomas, Allen Ginsberg, E.E. Cummings and
Edgar Allan Poe at the first People's Poetry Gathering. Presented
by City Lore, a New York cultural organization, and Poets House, a
literary center with a 35,000-volume poetry library, the three-day
festival took its cue from the Greek epic and explored two themes,
``Masters of Oral Tradition'' and ``Emerging Forms and Formats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The term `spoken word' is very popular right now, but we
forget that poetry began with words spoken out loud,'' said Steve
Zeitlin, the event's co-director with Lee Briccetti. ``The
gathering is the first festival that highlights the oral roots of
poetry. We're recognizing that poetry happens every day and
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   With headquarters at Cooper Union, the festival took
participants on a walking tour of some of the locations in lower
Manhattan that have nurtured the city's poetic activity for nearly
two centuries, from Washington Square Park to the White Horse
Tavern to St. Mark's Church and the American Indian Community
House.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 poets on hand guaranteed that there was someone to suit
almost every literary taste. Some wielded grand titles, like Robert
Pinsky, the U.S. Poet Laureate; others, grand traditions, like Jose
Joao dos Santos, a Brazilian who accompanied himself on a 12-string
guitar while singing of President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky and
mermaids at the bottom of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Some gleaned inspiration from their occupations, like the cowboy
poet Wallace MacRae, a rancher in Montana who wrote about saving
his land from the coal-mining industry. Still others took delight
in the unknown, like the Puerto Rican decima poets who improvised a
10-line song from a verse picked from a hat and the free-style
poets who rapped on topics sometimes unmentionable.
</P>
<P>
   True to its billing, the festival merged serious thought, joyful
abandon and a touch of debauchery. The events ranged from the staid
to the extreme, from a joint reading by Pinksy and Robert Bly, the
author of ``Iron John,'' to a midnight orgy of erotic poetry
featuring Penny Arcade, Anselm Berrigan, Max Blagg, Lee Ann Brown,
Sharon Mesmer and Edwin Torres. A ``Literary Pub Crawl'' featured
readings in some of the Greenwich Village bars that have been homes
away from home for poets.
</P>
<P>
   During the days the poets discussed topics like democracy,
education and feminism and paid homage to Pablo Neruda, Rudyard
Kipling and Federico Garcia Lorca; in the evenings they tried their
hands at performing. Don Edwards sang of rodeos and cattle drives
and riding the range; the hobo U. Utah Phillips joined the
folk-punk rocker Ani DiFranco in a sentimental ode to life on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   At a Talking Book Festival on Friday night at Irving Plaza, the
American Indian poet Sherman Alexie, the urban poet Sekou Sundiata
with his Eclectic Poetic collective, and Jerome Rothenberg, ``the
poet laureate of the underground,'' whispered, chanted and
sometimes screamed their words in time to the wail of backup bands.
Between sets the master of ceremonies, Bob Holman, shouted to the
audience, ``Go write your own poems!''
</P>
<P>
   Competition was rife. There were slams among teen-agers, slams
between the Nuyorican poets and the cowboys and hobos, slams
featuring the unlikely form of haiku. A ``New York Heavyweight
Bout'' on Saturday pitted the defending champion, Alexie, against
Patricia Smith, a former Boston Globe columnist and four-time
national poetry slam winner, in a verbal boxing match.
Neck-and-neck with Ms. Smith, Alexie produced these lines, based on
his random selection of ``the grotto'' in the final,
improvisational round to secure his title:
</P>
<P>
   Praise the soprano that gave birth to me
</P>
<P>
   Praise the vibrato of the first cry
</P>
<P>
   Praise the paper-thin lungs burned in the heat of my arrival
</P>
<P>
   Praise the vibrato of the heart-and-lung machine
</P>
<P>
   Praise my enemies lest they defeat me.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith bowed in admiration as the crowd stood and roared.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the weighty credentials and the achievement awards and
the best-seller lists and the movie deals. Maybe the cheering is
what a poet really wants after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``My deepest ambition as a poet is to become and be a people's
poet,'' said Pulitzer Prize winner Galway Kinnell, who defined his
style as academic and less often spoken aloud. ``All poetry is
one,'' he said. ``One person telling others what it is for me to be
alive, here and now. And whatever it means, good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
