<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIONS WITH RUSSIA WORSEN OVER `RELIEF' CONVOY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT,
KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-JOURNALIST) 
(jw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ A Russian relief convoy headed for Yugoslavia was
stopped by Hungarian authorities Sunday after they determined it
was carrying fuel and equipment that could be used by Belgrade's
military, NATO officials reported.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, which occurred as the convoy was trying to cross
into Hungary from Ukraine, is the latest irritant in the rapidly
deteriorating relationship between Russia and the Western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials charged the alliance was harassing its relief
efforts. NATO officials insisted, however, that the alliance was
strictly enforcing the U.N. Security Council embargo on military
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO members are not blocking humanitarian aid but trying to
filter out those elements that could have a military use,'' NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Western relations with Russia have been severely strained by the
conflict in Kosovo. While Russian officials say they have been
frustrated by President Slobodan Milosevic's refusal to work out a
peace settlement for Kosovo, Moscow staked its prestige on averting
military action.
</P>
<P>
   Now that NATO has begun bombing, Russian President Boris Yeltsin
has drawn a new line in the sand: stopping a ground invasion that
NATO says it does not now plan to launch but which has been
prepared by the Western alliance as a contingency.
</P>
<P>
   But with his political standing and physical stamina waning,
Yeltsin's comments seemed largely intended for a domestic audience.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his views remain of concern to the Western alliance,
which would like Russia to be part of an eventual autonomy
agreement for Kosovo and even contribute troops to an international
force that would police the accord. In an effort to achieve that
goal, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright plans to meet in Oslo,
Norway, on Tuesday with the Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn in Russian-NATO relations is also a concern to
Western military officials, who worry that Russia may provide
intelligence to Belgrade or dispatch military advisers or arms
there.
</P>
<P>
   One focus of concern is a Russian intelligence ship, the Liman,
which is now in the Adriatic Sea. It has positioned itself near the
U.S. aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt and appears to be trying
to count the planes taking off from the carrier, among other
things, according to a Pentagon official.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Foreign Ministry, for its part, says the information
gathered by the ship is being transmitted to Moscow. But the
Foreign Ministry has not said how the information will be used or
whether it will be shared later with other nations friendly to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, however, has not abandoned all cooperation with NATO.
More than 1,000 Russian peacekeeping troops are still deployed in
Bosnia. They are not formally under NATO command but report to Gen.
Wesley K. Clark, the supreme commander of NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sunday's confrontation over the Russian convoy epitomized
the sharp downturn in relations.
</P>
<P>
   The episode began when a convoy of 73 trucks carrying supplies
from Russia and Belarus was stopped at the border of Ukraine and
Hungary, which is one of NATO's newest members.
</P>
<P>
   The convoy carried food, medicine and toys for children. Russian
officials said they had hoped the convoy would reach Yugoslavia in
time for Orthodox Christian Easter celebrations on Sunday. The
convoy also included eight fuel tankers, which Russian officials
insisted were carrying gasoline for the relief convoy.
</P>
<P>
   Hungarian authorities, however, insisted the fuel tankers could
be used by the Yugoslav military and refused to allow them to pass.
A major aim of the allied bombing campaign has been to destroy fuel
supplies for the Serbian military.
</P>
<P>
   Hungarian authorities also refused to allow the armored vehicles
and armored Kamaz trucks to cross the border. At NATO headquarters,
Shea insisted that the Hungarians were simply trying vigorously to
enforce the U.S. arms embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday evening, Russia said it hoped to work out an arrangement
so that the supplies could proceed on civilian trucks. Money, they
said, will be sent so that fuel can be purchased in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regard any stalling of the humanitarian cargo as an attempt
to block its passage,'' the Russian Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
