<HEADER>
A3935 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-720&AMP;AD     04-11 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SHOWS PHOTO OF `POSSIBLE MASS GRAVES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT, KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS,
KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-JOURNALIST) 
(jw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO issued an aerial photograph on Sunday
of what officials said could be ``possible mass graves'' of ethnic
Albanian villagers killed by Serb forces inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph, taken on Friday over Pusto Selo, near Orahovac,
showed what appeared to be two long parallel lines of mounds in a
clearing off a road with buildings scattered nearby and tracks in
the ground that could have been left by military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freshly turned earth could indicate possible mass
graves,'' said Col. Konrad Freytag, a spokesman for the allied
military command.
</P>
<P>
   While he emphasized that the existence of a mass grave could
only be confirmed if independent observers eventually got in on the
ground, the photograph provided the first evidence other than
accounts from refugees of atrocities taking place in Kosovo since
journalists and foreign observers were expelled or evacuated from
the province last month.
</P>
<P>
   Freytag said the weather forced cancellation of some bombing
missions Saturday night and early Sunday, and the command reported
no successful attacks during that period against Serbian forces or
tanks operating in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance spokesman Jamie Shea, perhaps just putting the best
face on the situation, said: ``Last night, NATO had a night of
relative restraint, mindful of the Orthodox Easter celebration.''
Attacks, however, resumed with renewed vigor Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   In obtaining the photographs, Freytag said the allies had flown
reconnaissance missions over the area around Orahovac, halfway
between the Kosovo provincial capital of Pristina and the Albanian
border, after receiving intelligence reports that Serb military and
paramilitary police units had committed atrocities against
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The command also released aerial photographs of what it said
were displaced people near Malisevo. The reconnaissance effort
apparently came in response to complaints by some allied civilian
representatives here that the military had not been trying hard
enough to find out what had happened to tens of thousands of
fleeing ethnic Albanian civilians who vanished overnight last week
after Serb border guards turned them back at the frontier with
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are simply indicating something from the air that could be
a mass grave,'' Shea said of the first picture, ``and based on our
experience in Bosnia, of course, a number of mass graves were
identified and recovered and from the air, the form looks something
similar, and that's the reason why we've shown you these
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a mass grave, but obviously it will be up to the
international tribunal in The Hague, once it's able to go into
Kosovo, to conduct a thorough investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The photographs of what NATO officials said were displaced
Kosovo Albanians were also taken on Friday, and from high altitude.
Clouds and rain over the area since then have made it impossible to
follow up, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs appeared to show vehicles scattered along a road
and crowds of people in temporary shelters in fields or scrub land
near a destroyed village, which the command did not identify.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lack the basic elements of relief and are particularly
short of food,'' British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Sunday
in London. ``The weather currently is against them. It is snowing
today in western Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the alliance could do to help the people believed to
be hiding in the forests and mountains around the province _
400,000 of them by Cook's estimate _ Shea said Sunday, ``The best
thing NATO can do for internally displaced persons is to drive away
the Serbian forces that are attacking them.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior allied diplomat said: ``Air drops, if we could identify
where people are, could be a way of dealing with this, if we aren't
just feeding the Serbs.'' NATO planes would have to fly at high
altitude to avoid Serb anti-aircraft fire from the ground, but that
would mean an increased chance that the food and supplies they
dropped could fall into the hands of Serb forces instead of the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But the refugees are probably moving about on the ground, and
with bad weather expected to last through Wednesday, allied
intelligence is apparently finding it difficult to keep information
up to date.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Serbian Orthodox Christian calendar marked Sunday as Easter,
but allied military authorities had adamantly rejected calls from
the Vatican and from Russian Orthodox leaders in Moscow for a pause
in the bombing to cover the entire 10-day Easter holiday period
that began with Good Friday observances for most Christians on
April 2.
</P>
<P>
   Among the allies, both Greece and Italy had sought political
support for such a pause but did not press when military commanders
responded that a break in the bombing would just give Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic that much more time to push many of
Kosovo's 1.8 million ethnic Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, said in a television
interview with CNN on Sunday: ``I'm just going to be able to tell
you that we have been sensitive to this holiday, but we are going
to continue the military operation.''
</P>
<P>
   A Greek diplomat at NATO headquarters here said there had been
no political decision to show even the ``relative restraint'' Shea
spoke of.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, almost all the targets NATO planes or
unpiloted missiles hit in the 18th day of bombing, the 24 hours
ending Sunday morning, were in Kosovo and none was anywhere near
Belgrade, according to the sketchy information released Sunday by
the command.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
