<DOCNO> NYT19990411.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-MISSILE-ART-370     04-11 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-MISSILE-ART-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA TESTS NEW MISSILE, PROMPTING CONCERN ABOUT ARMS RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Eleven months after exploding a series of
nuclear bombs, India tested an intermediate-range missile Sunday
that reportedly traveled more than 1,250 miles in 11 minutes and
left no doubt about the nation's plans to develop a modern system
for delivering the megaton punch of its new weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``With today's launch we have reached a point where no one from
anywhere will dare to threaten us,'' Defense Minister George
Fernandes declared triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised address, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee,
saying that the missiles were for defensive purposes only,
concluded by quoting the 17th-century Sikh guru Gobind Singh: ``Oh
Shiva, bless me, that nothing deters me from doing good deeds, and
where I am obliged to fight, I fight for sure to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Since detonating five underground blasts in the Pokhran Desert
last May, India has spoken consistently of reaching a point of
``minimum credible deterrence.'' Though it has yet to spell out
that minimum, it has been clear that India has felt it needed the
ability to strike deep into the territory of its neighboring
nuclear powers, China and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats have been concerned that India's and
Pakistan's nuclear quests could set off a regional arms race. After
India's May nuclear tests, Pakistan quickly set off nuclear blasts
of its own _ and Pakistani officials hinted on Saturday that they
may answer again, this time with missile tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will probably have to again respond, but we will only make
a decision in a day or two,'' said Pakistan's Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, India tested an earlier, shorter-range version of the
Agni, a missile named with the Hindi word for fire. They had since
developed an Agni that could go further, but had not yet launched
it. Computer simulations, no matter how accurate, do not deter
potential adversaries like a live demonstration. Yesterday the
updated Agni II was fired off the coast of the eastern state of
Orissa, Fernandes said. It splashed into the Bay of Bengal.
</P>
<P>
   The defense minister described the weapons test with
superlatives, boasting that ``we have achieved perfection of a very
high order in missile technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioned about plans to equip the missile with nuclear
explosives, he said, ``Whatever we need to meet our security
concerns will be done.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Agni II burns solid fuel, uses state of the art navigation,
carries a payload of more than a ton and can be fired from mobile
launchers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can move the missile to rugged areas with a very compact
system,'' Fernandes said.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting a missile's location over roads lowers the odds of its
destruction in an enemy attack, though experts say it raises the
chance of accidents during the transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This test was overdue and inevitable,'' said Uday Bhaskar,
deputy director of the government supported Institute for Defense
Studies and Analysis. ``If you are going to be a nuclear state, you
have to test the weapons. And this is only the beginning. More
tests have to be done, maybe 15 to 20 tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebratory news in New Delhi about the missile test did not
travel well over the 300 miles to Islamabad. India has fought three
wars with Pakistan in the 51 years since the two nations were
created.
</P>
<P>
   Traiq Altaf, a spokesman for the foreign ministry, said in a
formal statement: ``This is a matter of serious concern to us. The
development of Agni adds to our concerns and is a threat to our
security.''
</P>
<P>
   The Agni I demonstrated two-thirds of the range of the Agni II,
already enough to hit all targets in Pakistan. The updated Agni,
however, could be deployed from Indian territory further from its
border with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan itself has an intermediate range missile, the Ghauri,
which it had tested prior to last year's tit-for-tat nuclear
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to foreign assistance, Pakistan's missile programs are
further along than India's,'' said a RAND study published late last
year, listing China and North Korea as two nations believed to have
given technological support.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, in a hopeful gesture toward peace, Vajpayee
made a bus trip to Pakistan and met with his counterpart, Nawaz
Sharif. Despite the optimism accompanying the meeting, agreements
they reached did not preclude missile tests. Rather, the two
nations simply agreed to forewarn the other before a test took
place.
</P>
<P>
   India said Pakistan received such a warning two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan is not the only nation in the region that has fought a
war with India. China defeated India in 1962, and territorial
disputes between the two remain unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Agni II, India finally has a reliable nuclear delivery
vehicle to deter China,'' said Brahma Chellaney, an Indian expert
on nuclear weapons. By his calculations, the missile could carry a
reduced nuclear payload deep into China.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could reach Beijing and Shanghai for sure,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Agni test is a setback for the United States. Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott has been attempting to dissuade
India and Pakistan from developing and deploying the missiles and
aircraft that could carry nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret very much India's decision to test,'' said Donna
Roginski, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Embassy here. ``Its leaders
had said they would take care of their military needs at a minimal
level and that does not seem to be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The Agni test was not unexpected. Vajpayee had announced the
government's intentions in a statement to Parliament in December.
</P>
<P>
   But time was running out. According to experts, the missile
needed to be tested before the start of the monsoon season in
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the timing is bound to raise some suspicions here.
The Vajpayee government finds itself embattled, facing a likely
withdrawal of support by a key ally in its coalition. A test of its
majority may come as early as this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
