<DOCNO> NYT19990411.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVENPORT-RACE-ART-2T     04-11 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVENPORT-RACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ONE MAN USED CORPORATE AFFIRMATIVE ACTION TO GET A PIECE OF A
BIG DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Md.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chester C. Davenport, the managing director of a private
investment firm in Bethesda, Md., does not deny that he got a piece
of the Ameritech &UR;  &LR; Corp.'s $3.3 billion sale of half of its wireless
telephone business, at least in part, because he is black.
</P>
<P>
   But he will also tell you that after years of struggle, he has
no problem with the concept of corporate affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   The GTE &UR;  &LR; Corp., which along with Ameritech is one of the
nation's biggest local phone companies, bought the lion's share of
the Ameritech properties _ about 93 percent. But for an investment
of about $60 million, Davenport's Georgetown Partners &UR;  &LR; agreed to
acquire 7 percent of the equity in the venture that will run the
former Ameritech operation.
</P>
<P>
   GTE did not need _ or, according to some executives close to the
deal, particularly desire _ Georgetown's help, though it made some
vague statements about Davenport's company helping develop minority
markets.
</P>
<P>
   But SBC Communications &UR;  &LR; Inc., which is trying to win approval
from the Federal Communications Commission for its pending
acquisition of Ameritech, pushed for Georgetown's participation, at
least partly to curry favor with William E. Kennard, the
commission's chairman, the executives said. Kennard, who is black,
has tried to increase minority participation in the communications
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is one of the wealthiest black entrepreneurs in the
nation with a net worth of perhaps as much as $100 million. Ask him
whether he believes that he would have been invited into the
Ameritech deal if he were white and his answer opens a revealing
window on a new sort of corporate affirmative action that people
from the Rev. Jesse Jackson to C. Michael Armstrong, chairman of
the AT&AMP;T &UR;  &LR; Corp., are seizing on to bring blacks into the
traditionally white worlds of telecommunications and finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I were white, I would own one of these damn
telephone companies, OK?'' Davenport said in an interview last
week. ``All the time I've spent here, whatever money I have now, if
I were white, doing everything I've done, I would have 100 times
more money than I have now, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's obviously shocked public-relations consultant
interjected, ``You're not joking, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not joking,'' Davenport responded. ``I would have 100
times more money than I have now, and I think that these guys know
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``these guys'' in that statement are the white businessmen
and financiers among whom Davenport seems to move easily.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment on SBC's motives in bringing him into
last week's deal. But he insisted that any benefits black people in
business may enjoy these days because of the color of their skin
are greatly outweighed by the stream of irrevocable, racially
motivated slights and pitfalls that have befallen them over the
course of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never make up that time, the opportunity,'' Davenport
said of racially motivated setbacks. ``That's what I'm saying. This
whole networking thing you're talking about, I mean just think
about it. Just think about what I had to go through. If I had that
network, the network that these guys were operating in, I'd have
100 times more money than I have now.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport has ended up with an impressive network of his own,
but he will tell you that it was forged from struggle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, just before attending his first lecture on his first
day as the first black student at the University of Georgia's law
school, he recalls looking up to find that none of his fellow
students had sat within 15 chairs of him in any direction. Before
the next class, the professor made up a mandatory seating chart.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in the top 5 percent of his class, he began his
career in the tax division of the Justice Department, followed by
stints on the Senate Banking Committee staff and with a mortgage
banking venture backed partly by Salomon Brothers. ``Back then, for
an African-American you always had to be the best,'' he said. ``It
was always, if you're not better than everybody you're not going to
get anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It was my mentality then, it is my mentality today,
that you have to be better and you have to be smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Washington around 1973 and eventually joined
Jimmy Carter's presidential campaign. After the election he became
assistant secretary of transportation and soon became friends with
two men who would become among the most influential black power
brokers in Washington, the late Ronald H. Brown and Vernon Jordan,
who later became his lawyer. Davenport stayed in the government for
about 18 months, then he made his first big business deal.
</P>
<P>
   His partner was Mortimer B. Zuckerman, who was then building his
real estate empire. Broad swaths of Washington were being
redeveloped in the late 1970s, and Davenport used his contacts in
government to help get a piece of property in southwest Washington
rezoned for commercial use.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the redevelopment authority in Washington judged
redevelopment applications based partly on their level of minority
participation. That proved lucrative for Davenport and his law
partners, James L. Hudson and Willie Leftwich, whose firm became
bond counsel for the city.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, The Washington Post reported that the three lawyers had
received 15 percent of a proposed $25 million redevelopment project
without contributing any money to the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat across the table from these guys and said, `Look, how
much are you willing to put into this?''' Nathan Landow, the
project developer, told The Post at the time. ``They looked back
and said: `This is the way it has to be. No money.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Landow added that the attitude of Washington's redevelopment
authority was `` `don't even bother to come in unless you're with
the right people.'''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport said last week that he could not recall the Landow
deal specifically, but through most of the 1980s he continued to
work mostly in the Washington real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   He founded Georgetown Capital around 1989 at least in part to
take advantage of new financing opportunities being developed by
Michael Milken at Drexel Burnham Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   Although Davenport never completed a deal through Drexel, he
studied Milken's techniques for raising high-yield debt financing.
Then in the early 1990s, Davenport and his partners acquired United
Technologies' automobile emissions testing business for about $30
million, of which about $23 million was borrowed.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was fortuitous. Georgetown Partners acquired the unit
just as Congress passed a law requiring uniform automobile testing
procedures. Georgetown sold the business last year to Stone Rivet
Inc. for $266 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Davenport has moved into the telecommunications business.
According to executives close to last week's deal, Ameritech
initially wanted to sell Georgetown all the wireless units in the
deal and had even been willing to help the firm find financing.
Such a sale would have had the benefit of keeping the wireless
units out of the hands of a big competitor, like GTE, which has
agreed to merge with the Bell Atlantic &UR;  &LR; Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But that thought died, at least partly because the Justice
Department, which was also reviewing the Ameritech-SBC merger, said
that it would not approve the deal if Ameritech helped arrange the
financing for selling its own business. (Ameritech had to sell the
wireless properties partly to avoid an antitrust conflict with
SBC's wireless business.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the facilitating roles in the deal was played by Jackson
and his Wall Street Project, the part of his Rainbow/PUSH
organization that tries to increase minority participation in big
business.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, who has known Jackson for about 10 years and who has
contributed to the Wall Street Project, told Jackson about his
interest in telecommunications. Jackson helped SBC and Ameritech
develop a list of minority entrepreneurs with whom they could do
business. Last month Rainbow/PUSH endorsed the Ameritech-SBC
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who declined to comment, has had other successes in the
communications business. At the Wall Street Project's conference in
January, Bell Atlantic, GTE, SBC and Ameritech each agreed to
direct between $50 million and $100 million of their pension funds
to minority money managers. And AT&AMP;T made good on a promise that
Armstrong made at the conference to use more minority underwriters;
it included Blaylock &AMP; Partners, a minority-owned investment bank,
among co-managers of its recent $8 billion bond offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had an ongoing dialogue with Rainbow/PUSH in sharing
their views of where we are and how we can share our wealth with
the minority universe,'' Edward M. Dwyer, AT&AMP;T's treasurer, said in
an interview. ``They helped us focus our initiatives better,'' he
said, adding that Jackson's organization had no direct role in
AT&AMP;T's selection of Blaylock.
</P>
</TEXT>
