<HEADER>
A3950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWORK-AFFILIATES-NY     04-11 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORK-AFFILIATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NETWORKS' TOUGH TALK LEAVES LOCAL STATIONS FUMING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have been partners in a highly successful marriage for most
of the century, ever since William S. Paley put the two together
for CBS radio. But for the relationship between broadcast networks
and their affiliated stations, while not permanently estranged, is
certainly on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Two networks, Fox and ABC, made decisions last week that were
directly antithetical to the interest of their affiliates. If that
message was not clear enough, executives at both networks
underscored in interviews that the moves were part of efforts to
redefine totally the network-affiliate relationship _ with the
network looking to pocket the proceeds from the redefinition.
</P>
<P>
   More pointedly, some network executives now question the
long-term value of relying on affiliated stations to deliver
network programs. The executives are confident they can force the
stations to accept tougher terms in the future because of a
fundamental shift in the way network programs are distributed, away
from traditional over-the-airwaves broadcasting and toward delivery
by cable or satellite.
</P>
<P>
   NBC President Robert Wright has said that his network might
consider the option of replacing an affiliate reluctant to renew
its network contract in ``a sensible fashion'' with a channel on a
local cable system.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior network executive, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said of the moves made by Fox and ABC last week: ``This
is only the beginning. This is what the networks should have been
doing a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason, this executive said: ``Networks aren't as important
as they used to be. And the stations are much less important than
they used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   For the affiliate side of the business, those are fighting words
that could lead to a period of open hostilities. Among the actions
one affiliate executive, Alan J. Bell, said might be possible:
significant pre-emptions of network shows and even defections by
affiliates to different networks when contractually possible.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, the president of the broadcast division of Freedom
Communications Inc., a company with three ABC affiliates, said that
ABC and Fox had ``declared civil war on their affiliates.'' He
added, ``When you make war on affiliates, you are inviting these
proud local media barons to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Barrett, the executive vice president of the Hearst
Corp.'s Hearst-Argyle Television unit and head of the ABC affiliate
board, said of the network-affiliate relationship: ``We're in a
deadly embrace here. But no one wants to have a nuclear war.''
</P>
<P>
   What Fox and ABC did last week was take steps to benefit
themselves at the expense of their affiliates, without any input
from the executives at the stations. ABC announced that it would
start a cable channel that will replay soap operas owned by ABC on
the same day that they are broadcast on ABC's affiliates. The
announcement represented the most direct challenge ever mounted to
the program exclusivity that has been a cornerstone of the
network-affiliate relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was even more aggressive. It told its affiliates it was
claiming for itself more than 20 percent of the commercial time the
stations had been selling to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Looming in the future is an almost certain drive by the networks
to end the system that has compelled them to pay affiliates a fee
for carrying network programs. That fee, known as compensation, has
come in addition to the commercial time that affiliates sell in
network shows. The networks cede the time in order to assure
themselves of access to hours on the local stations on which to
place their programming.
</P>
<P>
   Fox already does not pay affiliates compensation. The other
networks would like to stop doing so, since that would mean another
$200 million or so to their bottom lines. Those bottom lines have
been acutely depressed in recent years everywhere but at NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives, in defending their decision to redirect
affiliate revenue back toward the network, noted that Fox had
gradually improved its standing to a point where it is now a solid
No. 2 behind NBC in the most desirable audience group for
advertisers, adults between the ages of 18 and 49. Yet the Fox
network barely makes money.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many Fox affiliates have profit margins of 50 percent or
more. Moreover, the Fox executives argue that many of their
affiliates were once weak independent stations that have become
enormous assets to their companies thanks to Fox's success.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said Fox seems to have concluded that it can push its
affiliates around. ``Fox is saying to its affiliates: `I found you
in the gutter, drunk, with vomit on your clothes, and a bottle of
Thunderbird in your back pocket. Then I cleaned you up, gave you a
haircut and shave and a job in the mail room. Now you're doing
well, so you should do whatever I tell you to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling a previous showdown with a network in the late 1980s,
when CBS tried to eliminate compensation to stations, only to stir
up an insurrection and eventually back down, Bell said: ``I don't
think the Fox thing is going to stick. It's going to force them to
meet and try to do things together.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Barrett and Bell questioned the network version of
television economics, saying that the companies that own the
networks, far from being bankrupt entities, make billions in
profits from their stations and syndication divisions. ``It is
intellectually dishonest to say we're making profits and they're
not,'' Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell speculated that the networks plan to swallow the station
business whole. ``They would like to eliminate me,'' he said.
``Like radio, they want to own multiple stations in every market,
even two networks.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks have indeed pressed Congress to change rules that
limit their ownership of stations. Mel Karmazin, the chairman of
the CBS Corp., has openly said he would like to own a second
network as well, preferably NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The affiliates argue that in trying to bully them the networks
are playing a dangerous game. ``Distribution is not fungible,''
Barrett said, citing numerous examples where networks either
benefit or suffer from the strength or weakness of a local
affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   But network executives say competition from multitudes of
channels has reduced the number of local stations that have a
powerful impact on the lives of viewers, and besides, most stations
are now locked into long-term deals, which means they cannot quit
their networks for three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave pre-emptions as the affiliates' only weapon in
the near term. Bell noted that most ABC stations carry both
``Nightline'' and ``Politically Incorrect'' in their late-night
time periods, when they could make much more money by programming
repeats of a situation comedy like ``Seinfeld'' and keeping all the
advertising money to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to hurt programs as good as those,'' Bell said.
But he said revenge could become a motivation for some affiliates
who do not want to see their business relationship with their
network redefined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is not just about figures,'' he said. ``It's about
people. And that means there's a lot of emotion and drama.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
