<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, April 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Rain showers will fall in the deserts of the Southwest Monday as
a storm system associated with the southern branch of the jet
stream churns eastward. A few peals of thunder will accompany the
afternoon showers. Snow will fall in the mountains of Arizona and
southern Utah with several inches possible above 6,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   A warm front associated with the Southwest low will surge toward
the Rio Grande River, preceded by a band of rain and thunderstorms.
A few of the storms may turn severe in the afternoon across central
and western Texas as winds changing direction with height increase
the likelihood for supercells. Large hail and isolated tornadoes
are possible. Farther north, patches of rain will break out in
western Kansas and eastern Colorado as moist winds ascend the
sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, high pressure will promote tranquil conditions from
the Mississippi Valley to the Deep South, including Florida. Ample
sunshine and mild air will grace the region.
</P>
<P>
   Very cool air will enter the Northeast and Middle Atlantic
States in the wake of departing low pressure. Rain will fall in the
early morning along the coast from Cape Cod to the Delmarva
Peninsula while scattered showers of rain and snow will develop
over the Appalachians of New York and Pennsylvania as a pocket of
cold air aloft moves overhead.
</P>
<P>
   A weak storm will bring rain to coastal areas of Washington and
Oregon, with snow likely in the Cascades above 5,000 feet.
Elsewhere, high pressure will ensure a sunny and dry day for
Northern California and the northern Rockies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Late Chill and Rain
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably cold weather contributed to more than a dozen new
record minimums in southern California over the weekend. The lowest
readings occurred early Saturday in the high desert as the mercury
tumbled to 20 degrees at Idyllwild. Even the coast noted record
lows as Santa Barbara fell to 35 degrees. On Sunday, another potent
disturbance had descended on the region with a chill rain dampening
the shore and heavy wet snow, above 3,000 feet, in the mountains
around Los Angeles, perhaps tempering the effects of a serious
winter drought in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Extended Forecast Text for Monday, April 12
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Thursday: Sunshine in the Northeast will fade behind
increasing clouds as a storm approaches from the west. The
Southeast will be warmer and humid while thunderstorms rumble
through the Mississippi Valley. It will turn noticeably colder in
the Northern Plains as rain mixes with snow before ending in parts
of the area. It will be warmer in the Southwest, but still damp
along the Northwest Coast.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Saturday: A potent storm system will move into Eastern
Canada leaving behind rain or snow showers in the Great Lakes and
cooler air in the Northeast. Showers will linger in the Southeast
as a cold front stalls in northern Florida. The Middle West will be
cooler than average as sunshine makes a return. The Southwest will
be very warm with ample sunshine. While in the Northwest, a new
cold front will produce clouds and showers.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
