<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3970 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUNM-AZ     04-11 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUNM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH WAY WOULD THEIR `WIND' BLOW? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Frankly, my dear, you can find someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Conroy, author of The Prince of Tides, has walked away from
a deal to write a second sequel to Margaret Mitchell's 1936 Gone
With the Wind after getting into a dispute with the executors of
her estate.
</P>
<P>
   Previous reports said Conroy would be paid about $10 million for
the book. St. Martin's Press, the publisher, is reported to have
paid $4.5 million to Mitchell's estate for the rights to the second
sequel. ''_ The Associated Press &QL; 
_To the editors of St. Martin's Press: Pat Conroy is not only
derelict but a traitor to his country, as well. You want a big
name? You got it. I would love to take over the book. It's my duty
as a writer and a patriot.
</P>
<P>
   Any red-blooded American can tell you that this demands to be a
story about weapons. Forget Rhett and Scarlett and that mushy love
garbage. The Civil War redefined weaponry, from the Gatling gun to
the ``Monitor'' and the ``Merrimac.'' The cluster of barrels on the
early machine gun; the low, flat deck, the heavy guns, the
revolving turrets of the ``Monitor.'' I tear up just thinking about
it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, I see in Rhett Butler a Jack Ryan-type hero _ the
star of endless sequels. Rhett Butler for president! And God bless
America! Patriotically yours, Tom Clancy.
</P>
<P>
   _Dear Editors: Pat Conroy was wrong from the start. You need a
writer to explore Rhett Butler for what he really is _ a sensuous
vampire.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain his derring-do as a blockade runner for the
Confederate Army? He didn't fear death _ because he was already
dead! It's also the reason he had to leave Tara _ undead, he sadly
feels at home nowhere. This also explains his supernatural appeal
to women, including, of course Scarlett _ scarlet, the color of
blood. Coincidence? I hardly think so. Sigh. Vivian Leigh would
have looked ``so'' good in Goth. Yours without garlic, Anne Rice. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Editors: Shame on Pat Conroy. What he needs to learn is
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   And frankly, so do Rhett and Scarlett. As anyone can see, these
two need to be punished for their antics. Three marriages for
Scarlett? Rhett abandons his wife _ and curses while doing so?
Sure, ``damn'' might not seem obscene, but in the same way
marijuana leads to heroin, this leads to dirtier words, including,
yes, the Big One. These losers need to take control of their lives,
and if they can't, they need to find someone who can.
</P>
<P>
   They need to find me. You owe it to yourselves and your readers
to let me write this book! Sanctimoniously yours, a fully clothed
Dr. Laura Schlessinger.
</P>
<P>
   _Dear editors: I am willing to leap into the void and write the
second sequel to ``Gone With the Wind.'' I see it shaping up as
something you might find surprising: a bloody horror story scarier
than ``Creepshow,'' with Scarlett O'Hara as a cruel sadist and
serial killer. Impossible? Perish the thought (pun, as always,
intended).
</P>
<P>
   Here's the pitch _ Scarlett, back on her feet, takes in poor and
needy people left destitute by the Civil War. Yet, ominously, they
are never seen again. Scared yet? We learn that there is a basement
in her home, and when one spunky, sexy female unfortunate _ think
Claire Danes _ leads other wretches into it, they are shocked to
find perfectly preserved heads of victims smiling at them. Scarlett
is in a dark corner, preserving another head, blood smeared all
over her, chanting incoherently, looking like Marilyn Manson. Does
our heroine escape? Read on.
</P>
<P>
   I'm perfect for the job, and _ I don't want to brag, but it's a
fact _ a ``lot'' of my books have been made into movies. Forget
critics. Pay attention to sales. Yours in telegraphed terror,
Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Dear Editors: What we obviously have here is a Southern legal
thriller. Carpetbaggers, the financial ruin caused by the Civil
War? This was a world ripe for lawsuits. I see this as Rhett
Butler's revenge. His enemies keep showing up dead. Why? We'll find
out in court, once he's charged with murder _ murder he didn't
commit. The key to the crimes? Two words: tax laws. Throw in some
red herrings, unlikely romances and a chase scene or two and we've
get a best-seller! Litigiously yours, John Grisham. &QL; 
Contact Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
