<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MAGAZINES-NYT &LR;      04-11 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAGAZINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWCOMER CAUSES COMPETITION TO HEAT UP AMONG TRAVEL MAGAZINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nymphet in a clingy ski top gazing out from a chalet. A couple
locked in an embrace, backlit by the fingered rays of a Caribbean
sunset. A tanned woman in a white bikini walking a solitary line on
a Palau beach.
</P>
<P>
   These images _ those that grace the current covers of travel
magazines _ suggest a world of Zen serenity and connubial bliss.
</P>
<P>
   But with the economy roaring and consumers ready to spend
Dow-fattened travel dollars on summer vacations, the competition
for readers is hotter than for a round-the-world ticket on the
Concorde for New Year's Eve 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And 1998 brought a new foe. The two mainstay travel magazines _
Travel &AMP; Leisure and Conde Nast Traveler _ are dealing with a
feisty newcomer: Arthur Frommer's Budget Travel, a quarterly which
met with such newsstand success that it will be published bimonthly
starting September and, its publishers predict, monthly within the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Its newsstand sales _ twice those of its larger cousins _ made
the stalwarts take note. But it was Frommer's editor's letter in
his premiere issue last summer that really stung.
</P>
<P>
   Frommer, who publishes a series of travel guidebooks, Arthur
Frommer's Travel Guides, proclaimed that the current crop of travel
magazines are inane, irrelevant, ``elitist, haughty and
high-society.'' He argued that 90 percent of the country cannot
afford to go on the vacations ``the glossy travel magazines''
espouse. They were in fact, ``a public scandal, a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   And that hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was stupid and untrue,'' said Nancy Novogrod,
editor in chief of Travel &AMP; Leisure, which is produced by the
American Express publishing unit. ``It was graceless to attack us
in his first issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Hill, the publisher of Budget Travel, stood his magazine's
ground. ``We're not an armchair book,'' he retorted, using the term
aficionados use to refer to magazines intended for armchair
travelers and wishful thinkers. ``We're about real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they acknowledged Frommer's shots, Travel &AMP; Leisure and
Conde Nast Traveler have so far tried to ignore his magazine and
have reasons to celebrate their own successes.
</P>
<P>
   Both have been nominated for National Magazine Awards this year.
Travel &AMP; Leisure has just published its largest issue ever, at 212
pages. Thomas J. Wallace, the editor in chief of Conde Nast
Traveler _ put out by the Conde Nast unit of Advance Publications _
has won four National Magazine Awards for General Excellence in the
last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Ad pages, as estimated by the Publishers Information Bureau, are
up in both, with Travel &AMP; Leisure weighing in at 1,552 for 1998, up
36.3 percent since 1994, and Traveler with 1,428, up 32.9 percent
since 1994. Travel &AMP; Leisure, though, often features advertising by
its parent corporation; in the April issue, for example, a 40-page
advertorial about Europe is sponsored by the American Express card.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most consumer magazines, travel magazines are almost
entirely dependent on subscriptions for circulation. Travel &AMP;
Leisure's circulation is the largest, at 1,013,327, according to
the Audit Bureau of Circulations, but its subscribers _ many of
whom are drawn from American Express card data bases _ make up 97
percent of that number; only 28,418 are sold on newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast Traveler is second, with a circulation of 766,338,
only 32,535 of which are newsstand sales. National Geographic
Traveler and Hachette-Filipacchi's Travel Holiday follow with
circulations of 715,437 and 558,610, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The Frommer magazine is not yet audited by the Audit Bureau of
Circulations. According to Hill, it outsells both Traveler and
Travel &AMP; Leisure on the newsstand, selling roughly 70,000 copies an
issue that way, of a total of about 350,000. Its newsstand appeal,
he said, is its budget-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   What also rankles Frommer's magazine rivals is that he has
accused the entire category of the worst kind of collusion between
advertising and editorial: accepting free trips. Writers for the
competition, he wrote in his first editor's letter, ``get sent on
paid junkets and write rapturously of three-star restaurants and
deluxe hotels.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Travel &AMP; Leisure and Conde Nast Traveler said that
is not true. Arthur Frommer's publisher, Hill, conceded that while
expense-paid trips were out of the question at his magazine,
junkets _ organized trips for groups of journalists _ were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not take `comps,''' Hill said, meaning that a writer for
Budget Travel would not travel for free on an individual vacation
for a specific story. He did, however, concede that ``an organized
press trip is a little bit different, but there's never a quid pro
quo for advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, the magazine's executive editor, Bill
McCoy, went to Poland on a junket at the expense of the Polish
tourism office earlier this year. When he decided to stay in Warsaw
for a few extra days, the magazine covered his expenses, but the
initial costs for his trip were covered by the tourism office _ a
practice neither Traveler nor Travel &AMP; Leisure say they allow.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Bellows, the editor in chief of National Geographic
Traveler, said that no writers on assignment may accept free trips,
but that editors may occasionally travel on press trips, paying
reduced rates so that they can familiarize themselves with a
destination.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen, editor of Travel Holiday, said his magazine spends
``hundreds of thousands of dollars'' a year to send writers and
photographers on assignment. ``Do we sometimes work with people to
get press rates? Sure. But we make the itineraries. It's not driven
by public relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Other publishers consider Frommer's approach hypocritical. Lisa
Henriques Hughes, who was named publisher of Conde Nast Traveler
two weeks ago, said Frommer's magazine could not be considered
uninterested in promoting certain destinations. ``He is not an
objective reporter, because he promotes travel guides,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill dismissed the charge. ``Travel guidebooks are
nonadvertising-supported, and they are where you find the most
objective journalism,'' he said. ``The irony of her saying that is
that Arthur has made his reputation for 40 years by writing
guidebooks and being known as America's most objective critic of
travel.'' Hill added that Frommer is also not involved in the
day-to-day administration of the guidebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hughes also criticized Travel &AMP; Leisure. ``They are owned by
the largest travel-related services company in the world,'' she
said, ``so by definition they are not objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Kelly, publisher of Travel &AMP; Leisure, said the American
Express connection helps market the magazine, but has no effect on
content. For all he cared, he said, ``Lisa can go back to selling
shower curtains,'' a reference to Ms. Hughes' recent stretch as
publisher of Conde Nast's House &AMP; Garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990411.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3973 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRS-MISSING-ART-750&AMP;A     04-11 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-MISSING-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHEST WAGE EARNERS UNDER LESS SCRUTINY FROM IRS
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
 (Eds: Also moving `a' category.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tax returns from Americans earning more than $100,000 a year and
from the biggest corporations are increasingly escaping the
scrutiny of the Internal Revenue Service, new agency figures show.
</P>
<P>
   Just one of every 60 high-income tax returns was audited last
year, compared with a rate of one in nine in 1988, according to IRS
data analyzed by Syracuse University researchers. Among the 8,500
largest companies, slightly more than one in three companies were
audited last year, down from two out of three in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   While audit rates overall have fallen substantially since 1986,
some tax experts and former IRS officials are worried that the
decline in high-income and corporate audits may mean that reporting
by many of the richest taxpayers is now effectively on an honor
system, inviting abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the investments and deductions used by such taxpayers,
these critics note, are not subject to the kinds of reporting
required of employers, banks, mortgage lenders and others, which
must pass along information on income and potential deductions to
the IRS. And for the less affluent, of course, the bulk of income
taxes are withheld from paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fewer traffic policemen you have, the more chances people
are going to take,'' said Donald C. Alexander, a Washington tax
lawyer who was IRS commissioner in the Nixon administration. ``And
as people find that their neighbors are not paying their fair
share, they are encouraged to not pay their share, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRS contends that sufficient audits were conducted last
year. The assistant commissioner for audits, Tom Smith, said that
increased financial reporting requirements by employers and others,
combined with changes in tax law, had reduced the need to audit
wage earners, while other strategies, such as tip-reporting
agreements with restaurant owners, lower the need for audits, too.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in audit rates began in 1968 but accelerated in
1995, after Congress, by then controlled by Republicans, cut IRS
spending sharply and required the agency to devote more resources
to customer service. Republicans characterized the IRS as an agency
that was out of control and that was intruding far too deeply into
the lives of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, the IRS has reduced the hours it spends auditing tax
returns by 27 percent for individuals and 12 percent for
corporations, according to the new data.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, overall audit rates fell to record lows last year.
Of the 120 million individual tax returns, only one in 217 was
audited, down 36 percent from 1994. During the same period, the
number of returns reflecting incomes of $100,000 and up grew 62
percent, to six million.
</P>
<P>
   The audit data also show the reversal of a trend that emerged a
few years ago in which audits rose for the lowest-income Americans,
those making less than $25,000. Last year, one in 370 such returns
was audited, down from one in 178 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela F. Olson, a tax lawyer with the law firm of Weil, Gotshal
&AMP; Manges in Washington who is a former chairwoman of the American
Bar Association's tax section, said she was neither surprised nor
troubled by the drop in overall audit rates, given the increased
reporting required of employers, lenders and others. She said that
large, publicly traded companies also get sufficient scrutiny, not
only from the IRS but from independent auditors and the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But like a number of other tax experts, Ms. Olson said that the
IRS was paying too little attention to privately owned businesses.
``They have not gotten much in the way of audit coverage, and this
is where there is lots of room to play games,'' she said, largely
by owners charging personal expenses to the company.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS has long audited sole proprietors closely, but critics
say that small and medium-size corporations and their owners and
executives get less scrutiny. Some IRS officials have also
acknowledged privately that opportunities remain for underreporting
capital gains, which are subject to fewer formal checks than are
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Several tax experts said the new data raised troubling questions
about the equity of the tax system.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will the impact of this shift in audit policy have on
people's long-term faith in our tax system, on people feeling that
others are paying their fair share and I should pay my fair
share?'' asked Susan Long, co-director of Syracuse University's
Transactional Records Access Clearinghouse, which obtained the IRS
data.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An audit is begun for many different reasons. In many cases, an
IRS scoring system has identified deductions or other factors on a
return as being far outside statistical norms. Increasingly, the
IRS is picking specific occupations for audits to gather data about
tax-paying patterns. The agency is also selecting more returns for
auditing because of suspicions about the tax preparer whose name is
on the return or because of referrals from other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Audits about simple issues are often handled through the mail,
with taxpayers being asked to justify or explain a line on their
tax return. For more serious questions, taxpayers are asked to come
to the IRS, or an examiner visits their home or business to inspect
records and ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   The agency can refer cases for prosecution if there is evidence
of tax evasion, tax fraud or a variety of nontax crimes, including
money laundering, drug dealing and racketeering. It referred 3,990
cases to the Justice Department last year, down 21 percent from
5,078 in 1993, the clearinghouse said.
</P>
<P>
   Only 514 people were convicted of tax evasion or tax fraud in
1997, down from 594 in 1993, according to the data the
clearinghouse obtained from the Justice Department. Justice
officials cautioned that the actual number of such convictions
might be more or less than the figures in its data base, but they
did not dispute that the number of such cases was small and
decreasing.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecution of tax cheats, long a minor government activity, has
shrunk even more since 1994, other data collected by the
clearinghouse show. Last year, just 766 people were prosecuted for
federal tax crimes, according to data that the administrative
office of U.S. courts gave to the clearing house.
</P>
<P>
   Long said the data make a case for more aggressive prosecution
of scofflaws. ``If you are involved in large-scale cheating on your
taxes and all you have to do, if you are caught, is pay the money
and some penalty,'' she said, ``it is almost a reward.''
</P>
<P>
   The new IRS audit data cover the period through last Sept. 30.
In the past, publicly disclosed data on IRS enforcement efforts
were typically at least two years old. The fresh data were turned
over to the clearinghouse by Charles O. Rossotti, the computer
industry executive who became IRS commissioner last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this data, including details on incomes by state and
county, is available on the Internet at http://trac.syr.edu/
without charge. The clearinghouse also maintains a World Wide Web
site with more detailed information that it sells by subscription.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
