<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BUCS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMPA BAY EARNS TOP SLOT IN DRAFT SKILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They couldn't convince Bo Jackson to play on their team. And
they couldn't develop Vinny Testaverde into a playmaker. They
traded away the fourth overall pick in the 1979 draft for Chicago
Bears defensive end Wally Chambers, who lasted two seasons. They
traded away the first overall pick in the 1984 draft for Cincinnati
Bengals quarterback Jack Thompson, who lasted 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that the Tampa Bay Buccaneers endured 11
consecutive double digit-loss seasons. They annually made a mess of
the college draft, throwing darts and completely missing the board.
Of their 11 top-10 first-round picks from 1980 to 1993, just one _
linebacker Hugh Green _ made the Pro Bowl as a Buccaneers player.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with a change in philosophy and the promotion of Rich McKay
to general manager in 1995, the Buccaneers have become experts in
the art of the draft. Over the past five years, Tampa Bay has
drafted better than any other team in the NFL, according to a
formula, admittedly unscientific, devised by the Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, the Tampa Bay franchise focused too much on
potential and not enough on a guy's production in college, and when
you do that, you keep having busts in the draft,'' McKay said. ``We
had a small scouting department, and we weren't even computerized.
In some ways, it's like this franchise skipped the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   McKay's system has certainly proven its worth. The Bucs have
strung together back-to-back nonlosing seasons for the first time
since 1981-82.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Buccaneers have found a formula they like, there's
no consensus on how to draft. Tampa Bay, for instance, relies
heavily on its scouts. The Miami Dolphins, who finished eighth in
the Star-Telegram's study, rely much more heavily than most teams
on input from their assistant coaches. Some teams consistently
draft for need. Others target the best player/athlete available,
regardless of need.
</P>
<P>
   Yet talks with several general managers and scouting directors
revealed a few common threads among teams that draft well. Teams
that consistently hit on draft day are usually directed by a keen
talent evaluator; they hoard as many draft picks as possible,
increasing the odds of drafting a superstar, even in late rounds,
and they have luck on their side.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs have had all that.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a system that heavily awards points for drafting
All-Pros, Pro Bowlers and team leaders in major statistical
categories, the Buccaneers scored 80 points in the Star-Telegram's
study to beat second-place New England (75). The top 10 was rounded
out by Jacksonville (69), Tennessee (68), St. Louis (62), Green Bay
(62), Cincinnati (62), Miami (60), Minnesota (57) and Denver (53).
The Cowboys, whose past two drafts have helped take the sting out
of dismal 1994 and 1995 drafts, finished 15th with 48 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a whole lot of magic to drafting,'' Cowboys
scouting director Larry Lacewell said. ``People know who can play
and who can't play.'' \Nsubheds:Adopting a plan Before Malcolm
Glazier bought the Buccaneers in 1995, Tampa Bay was a team that
relied heavily on input from tenured assistant coaches to make
draft-day decisions, McKay said. With five head coaches and five
new coaching staffs in 11 years from 1984-1994, the evaluation of
talent was inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   That had all changed by the time McKay, already the club's vice
president of football administration, was put in charge of the
Bucs' personnel department. In 1992, the Bucs hired Tim Ruskell as
the director of college scouting along with two additional college
scouts and two additional pro scouts. Their directive: Concentrate
on players who had highly productive college careers, regardless of
their size or speed. The symbolic results: The Bucs took linebacker
Derrick Brooks in the first round in 1995 and running back Warrick
Dunn in the first round two years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody acknowledged that Derrick Brooks was great in
college, but half the teams were afraid of taking him because of
his size,'' said McKay of Brooks who, at 6 feet tall, is four
inches smaller than the typical pro linebacker. ``We thought that
if Derrick was that good in school, and he was a first-team All
America, then he'd be great in the NFL. Same with Warrick Dunn. A
small guy \R5-8, 178\S. But all he did was produce in college
\Rcareer rushing leader at Florida State\S. Had we been concerned
about their size, we'd have missed out on two Pro Bowlers. We're
not looking for the fastest 40 \Ryard dash\S times. We're looking
for the best football players.''
</P>
<P>
   It no doubt helped McKay take a first-round risk on Brooks when
he has two first-round picks, which the Buccaneers had in 1995,
1996, and 1997. This hoarding of draft picks through trades has
long been the way that Jimmy Johnson operates, first as Cowboys
head coach, and now as the Dolphins coach.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two years with the Dolphins, Johnson drafted a
league-high 26 players. Johnson's philosophy? The more players you
draft, the better your chances of hitting on a potential star. This
strategy brought eight starters in 1996-1997, including All-Pro
linebacker Zach Thomas in the fifth round of the 1996 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is generally regarded as one of the best evaluators of
talent in the league, having drafted two starters in seven of his
eight drafts as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Yet other personnel directors have proven to have sharp eyes for
talent.
</P>
<P>
   New England vice president of personnel Bobby Grier and
then-Patriots coach Bill Parcells drafted four Pro Bowlers and four
other starters from 1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville head coach Tom Coughlin and player personnel
director Rick Reiprish built the nucleus of their roster by finding
seven starters in the Jaguars' first two drafts.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay general manager Ron Wolf spends four days a week on
college campuses during football season watching first-hand the
players who would go in the next draft. Wolf and former Packers
coach Mike Holmgren parlayed a great working relationship to draft
12 players who started at least half the time in Green Bay from
1994-97.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time when I'm on the road it is an escape,'' said
Wolf, who has been scouting players since 1963 when he was a talent
scout with the Oakland Raiders. \Nsubheds:Blind luck Despite all of
the planning, there is still a great amount of luck involved in
drafting well.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Randy Moss was regarded as the best wide receiver
to come out of college since Jerry Rice. Yet his stock dropped in
the first round last year because he served some jail time for an
assault and was kicked out of Florida State for marijuana use.
Minnesota took Moss with the 21st pick, and he became the first
rookie first-team All Pro since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dungy was the defensive coordinator of the Vikings in 1995
when his club passed on defensive tackle Warren Sapp with the 11th
pick because Sapp had flunked a drug test at the University of
Miami. Dungy was named Buccaneers head coach two years later. No
doubt Dungy is glad his new team had drafted Sapp with the 12th
pick in the 1995 draft because he has made the past two Pro Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos were just looking for a ``camp guy,'' when
they drafted Terrell Davis with their sixth pick in the 1995 draft.
Davis had a non-descript career at Long Beach State and the
University of Georgia. He turned his chance in Denver into a
2,000-yard season, a regular-season MVP, and a Super Bowl MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey Levens transferred from Notre Dame to Georgia Tech. He
was the Packers second fifth-round pick in 1994. Given the primary
starting role with a season-ending injury to Edgar Bennett in 1996,
Levens first helped lead the Packers to a Super Bowl title, and in
1997, he became the first Packers Pro Bowl running back since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   There were 200 players drafted in 1994 before the Falcons spent
a seventh-round pick on Jamal Anderson out of Utah. Anderson slowly
worked his way into the starting lineup. Last year, he rushed for
an NFC-high 1,846 yards, and was the catalyst in the Falcons' first
Super Bowl appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, you just stumble on the right guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't call somebody smart for drafting an All-Pro in the
lower rounds,'' said Lacewell, whose club drafted All-Pro lineman
Larry Allen in the second round of the 1994 draft, and Pro Bowler
Leon Lett in the seventh round of the 1991 draft. ``If anybody knew
that somebody like Terrell Davis would be that good, they would
have drafted him in the first round. Give those teams credit for
drafting those players, though. You make the most of what you
got.''
</P>
<P>
   Some teams make more than others.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
