<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SAVING NHL FROM SEEDING FIASCO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Gary Bettman and his boys at the NHL offices have any class,
they'll send the New York Rangers a big Thank You present.
</P>
<P>
   By falling apart in the final month of the season, the Rangers
prevented what could have been one of the most heated debates in
sports this year _ the possibility of the Carolina Hurricanes
making the playoffs with the ninth-best record in the Eastern
Conference while the Rangers sat home with the eighth-best record.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost too bad the Rangers weren't left out in the cold by
way of a rules technicality _ it might have forced the NHL to
address what obviously is an unfair system.
</P>
<P>
   In splitting the league into six divisions this season to
accommodate current and future expansion, the NHL fathers believed
it best to make a divisional championship worth something. So they
declared the division winners would be the top three seeds in each
conference and the remaining five spots would go to the
non-division winning teams with the best records.
</P>
<P>
   Give them credit for trying something new and for standing
behind their decision. The problem is, it doesn't work. It's bad
enough that the Hurricanes will take the third seed in the Eastern
Conference, despite the fact they'll likely finish with the
eighth-best record. Can you imagine, though, if the Rangers had
made a late-season surge, finished three or four points better than
the Hurricanes and still not made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   There would have been outrage.
</P>
<P>
   There still should be.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the Hurricanes to the third seed changes the entire
format of the Eastern Conference playoffs. It can be argued that
the sixth seed could actually have an easier first-round opponent
(the Hurricanes) than the top-seeded Ottawa Senators, who will face
either the Philadelphia Flyers, Buffalo Sabres or Boston Bruins.
How is that in any way fair?
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference, the Phoenix Coyotes stopped battling
weeks ago because they were slotted into the fourth playoff spot no
matter what. They were too far behind the Stars to catch up for
first place in the Pacific Division and too far ahead of the fifth
seed to care about dropping. Those were the only two options for
the Coyotes _ first or fourth _ despite the fact they and the Stars
were the two best teams in the Western Conference for much of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of a great race down the stretch to establish seeding
among the Coyotes, Detroit Red Wings and Colorado Avalanche,
Coyotes fans were treated to a month of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   The league believes these inequities are flukes, chance
happenings that likely won't occur again. But in just the first
season under this system, there are already two noticeable problems
with Carolina and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock suggests having two conferences, no
divisions and then adjusting the schedule to reflect natural
rivalries. Let the Stars play Detroit and Phoenix six or seven
times each and maybe see LA and Anaheim only three or four times
apiece. And make sure that each team gets to see teams from the
other conference at least two times in a season.
</P>
<P>
   That's one answer. There could be 50 more. The league says it
has no intention of making changes, but don't be surprised if a
general manager or two raises the issue this summer.
Focus on...Al MacInnis
MACINNIS GETTING NORRIS RESPECT THAT IS OVERDUE
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the fact that everyone is so in love with his booming
slapshot. Maybe it's the fact he's played in cities (Calgary and
St. Louis) that aren't media hotbeds. Maybe Al MacInnis has just
been overshadowed in his career by Norris Trophy hogs Ray Bourque
and Chris Chelios.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, the name Al MacInnis doesn't garner the
same respect when talk turns to ``the best defensemen in the NHL.''
But the 35-year-old rearguard for the Blues should change that this
season. He's the favorite to win the Norris Trophy, going away.
Bourque, the Red Wings' Nicklas Lidstrom and the Rangers' Brian
Leetch are all fighting for second place.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame that MacInnis is getting the hype now because he's
leading NHL defensemen in scoring with 20 goals and 38 assists. The
real reason Al MacInnis should be considered the best defenseman in
the NHL is because he's just that _ the perfect mix of defensive
responsibility with offensive prowess.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, he's the closest thing to Bourque (a five-time
Norris winner) the league has seen _ and a heck of a lot more than
just a guy who can shoot the puck 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the \Rreputation of the\S shot keeps me from winning the
Norris, there's nothing I can do about it,'' MacInnis said. ``But I
think the last couple of years, people have looked at me as more
than the shot. And this year, it seems more than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Slap Shots
</P>
<P>
   MUSH MOUTH
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Marchment, Reunion Arena's favorite whipping boy, isn't
going to endear himself to fans after considering a lawsuit against
the NHL in the wake of a one-game suspension for making an
``offensive comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Give the man they call Mush some credit, though, he's not
running away and hiding. After calling Vancouver Canucks winger
Donald Brashear, who is black, a ``big monkey,'' after a fight,
Marchment owned up to the statement and said he had no racist
intentions in making it. He said he calls all ``tough guys''
monkeys and is furious with the league for implying he might be
racist.
LINDROS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Eric Lindros was moved from a hospital in Nashville, Tenn., to a
hospital in Philadelphia to continue treatment on his collapsed
lung. Lindros will miss the first round of the playoffs and could
be out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   After the lung originally collapsed and filled with blood,
Lindros had three liters of blood drained. That's one and a half of
those big soda bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Expect Lindros, whose brother, Brett, had to quit hockey because
of postconcussion syndrome, to be extremely careful in making his
decision on when to return.
SAFETY SHIELDS
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks might be the hottest team in the NHL, but they're not
without controversy.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose could move all the way up to the fifth seed in the
Western Conference playoffs, but the reason they will is because of
goalie Steve Shields, who is supposed to be the team's backup.
Shields went on an 8-0-2 run while Mike Vernon was nursing a groin
injury, and now coach Darryl Sutter will have to choose between
Vernon and Shields in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That could be particularly interesting if the Sharks play the
Red Wings, the team that traded Vernon after he won the Conn Smythe
Trophy two seasons ago.
BATTLE?
</P>
<P>
   The scribes in Alberta are having a hoot of a time making fun of
the fight between the Flames and Oilers for the final playoff spot
in the Western Conference. Once called the proud Battle of Alberta
between two teams considered the best in the league, the fight is
now labeled: ``The Crawl to the Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Larry Robinson told the Los Angeles Times that he
might quit after this season. ``It's been a tough year. Even my
wife is finding it tough.'' Robinson's Kings have missed the
playoffs three out of four seasons and were swept in the first
round last season. ... The Predators have rejected the latest
contract proposal by the agent of David Legwand, who was taken
second overall in last year's draft. The Predators have the upper
hand in negotiations as Legwand could use another year in junior
hockey. ... The Blackhawks have been spectacular under new coach
Lorne Molleken and took the interim off his title last week. The
Blackhawks are 6-2-2 in their past 10 games, despite trading Chris
Chelios and losing Doug Gilmour to back surgery. ... Blues winger
Geoff Courtnall, who has missed 55 games with postconcussion
syndrome, is practicing again with the team. He said he'd like to
be ready for the playoffs. ... Jaromir Jagr has cemented the Hart
Trophy as league MVP. In games he has not played this season, the
Penguins have been lost. ... The Ducks are 1-10-3 lifetime at Joe
Louis Arena and are scared to death of facing the Red Wings in the
first round. ... Flames defenseman Steve Smith was cut with a skate
across the neck and had to have microsurgery to close some veins.
Smith said he has lost feeling on one side of his face. ... The Red
Wings are hoping recently acquired defenseman Ulf Samuelsson
(broken foot) can play his first game today against the Penguins.
\Nsubheds:THE WEEK AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: Blues at Ducks _ Both teams fighting for right to
face Phoenix instead of Detroit. Saturday: Flames at Oilers _ This
could decide who the Stars play in the first round of the playoffs.
Sunday: Bruins at Flyers _ Flyers in jeopardy of falling all the
way to eighth place in the Eastern Conference.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
