<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN PROBABLY ON WAY OUT IN PHILLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pack your bags, Larry Brown.
</P>
<P>
   No, the ultimate coaching nomad isn't moving on again by his own
choice. This time, it will be his brittle relationship with Sixers
star Allen Iverson that forces him to leave Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how Magic Johnson forced out coach Paul Westhead in the
early '80s? How Michael Jordan longed for, and got, a coach other
than Doug Collins in Chicago? And Penny Hardaway leading a revolt
to push out Brian Hill three years ago?
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Philadelphia is headed the same direction:
</P>
<P>
   Star player and coach don't see eye-to-eye. Player gets his way.
Coach gets fired.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown doesn't already know it, Iverson is the league's
leading candidate for most valuable player and the man in Philly.
But Brown's butted heads with the lightning-quick shooting guard
all season, and even before.
</P>
<P>
   When Brown called for Iverson to re-enter last week's game
against Cleveland, Iverson responded ``About (bleeping) time.''
Brown then told Iverson, who had played all 12 minutes of the first
quarter and shot 0-for-7, to sit back down. He sat out the second
half, and was late joining the team on the bench for the third
quarter. After the game, Iverson said he would not play the next
game in Toronto and doubted that he would play at home against
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Iverson called it ``a misunderstanding, a
miscommunication. Everything is not going to be peaches and cream
all the time, but I don't have any problems with \RBrown\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Iverson scored 27 points and said, ``It's no
time to act like a baby now,'' and ``I was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates, however, say the relationship between Iverson and
Brown is headed in the wrong direction. Brown is notoriously hard
on guards, and Iverson is the poster boy for Gen-X players full of
talent and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Brown talked at length last week about players who don't put the
team first, saying `It's been a problem here the last eight, nine
years. It's been a problem in our league in a lot of cases with
losing teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson knows Brown was talking about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be; I don't put it past him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is philosophical suicide for Brown. In a league that has
already swallowed up Bernie Bickerstaff, Del Harris, John Calipari
and Dave Cowens this season, getting along with players is priority
No. 1 _ especially player No. 1. Also on the hot seat: New York's
Jeff Van Gundy, Phoenix's Danny Ainge, the Clippers' Chris Ford,
Vancouver's Brian Hill, Boston's Rick Pitino and, yes, even the
Mavericks' Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the business,'' said Orlando's Chuck Daly. ``You never
hear of anyone in the league office losing their job. You rarely
hear about a general manager getting fired. And scouts are pretty
secure, too. There's a hot seat with every franchise, and it's
usually where the coach sits.''
</P>
<P>
   Right or wrong, Brown must cool his relationship with Iverson
immediately or be the next to feel that heat.
QUICK HITS
AROUND THE EAST
</P>
<P>
   The struggling Celtics brought in Bill Russell for a formal
number retirement ceremony and a pep talk last week. ``He could
speak about anything, and I would be in awe,'' said guard Kenny
Anderson. ... The Bucks have begun to put on quite a floor show in
warm-ups, at times coming out for layups in Chris Gatling-style
headbands, putting on a dunking display or even intentionally
missing layups to get their misses out of the way. And now,
Haywoode Workman is letting out a scream on the court right before
the jump ball. ``I've never coached warm-ups,'' Bucks coach George
Karl said. ``They're free to prepare for war in any manner they
desire.'' ... Orlando's Penny Hardaway has made it clear that he no
longer wants to play point guard _ much to the frustration of coach
Chuck Daly. Things changed quickly when starting shooting guard
Nick Anderson left the lineup last week with a hamstring strain,
Hardaway moved over and Darrell Armstrong started at point guard.
The result was phenomenal. The Magic won all four games, Hardaway
scored 30, 24, 30 and 24, and now he won't go back into the box at
point guard. Anderson is healthy again, but he won't get his
starting role back.
\Nsubheds:AROUND THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   Things are rocky again in Houston for Scottie Pippen. He sat out
the final 8:02 of Thursday's loss to San Antonio, in which he was
outscored by Sean Elliott, 19-7. He's also been lit up by Utah's
Bryon Russell (25 points) and, yikes, the Clippers' Tyrone Nesby
(24 points, 10 of 14 from the field) in the past two weeks. ...
More proof that Nick Van Exel is one of the more flaky, talented
players in the league. Motivated by playing a Lakers team that
traded him last April, he went off for 41 points in LA last week.
In his previous three games, Van Exel had scored a combined 31
points. ... The Timberwolves decided last week to take the Nets'
1999 first-round draft pick unconditionally to complete the Stephon
Marbury trade.
\Nsubheds:QUOTE TO NOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep your eye and focus on God. God's going to
favor us because of our faith.'' _ Knicks guard Charlie Ward,
downplaying the team's record. Guess the Almighty favors Orlando's
faith more.
\Nsubheds:OFFBEAT BEAT
</P>
<P>
   With its plodding pace, record-low scoring and scarce
buzzer-beaters, this irregular season is nothing to jump and down
about. But don't tell that to coaches, who are quickly making
pacing the sideline a pet peeve right behind slapping hands with a
shooter after a missed free throw.
</P>
<P>
   Example: In last week's titanic Mavericks-Clippers struggle at
Reunion Arena, both veteran Chris Ford and Don Nelson were prowling
and yelling at least 10 feet from their seat on the bench. The
score was 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The king of overcoaching, however, is the Knicks' Jeff Van
Gundy. Down 12 with 19 seconds left in last week's loss at Indiana,
Van Gundy crouched near midcourt and clapped his hands to encourage
effort from players who had long _ and justifiably _ given up. In
an earlier victory against the Clippers, Van Gundy was seen pacing,
calling plays and using extensive body language in a game his team
led by 19 with 1:02 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches should take a clue from the Pacers' Larry Bird, who only
stands up to stretch his legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to stand up too much because I feel it interferes
with the play of the players, to always be looking over there for
help and guidance,'' Bird says. ``I like for our team, once the
game starts, just to play. Players can tune a coach out pretty
quickly in this league.''
Numbers Game
</P>
<P>
   ]24: Consecutive road losses by the Nuggets before last week's
victory in Vancouver. ``It was like we won the second round of the
playoffs, like we swept Utah or something,'' said guard Chauncey
Billups. Best and Worst
</P>
<P>
   Worst draft: If last week's Portsmouth Invitational predraft
camp is any indication, this year's draft could be the worst in
years. ``It's the worst group of talent I've ever seen there,''
said one Western Conference scout. ``There's not one player who
could play in the NBA next season.'' The draft's stock should
improve at this week's Desert Classic in Phoenix, where most of the
projected lottery picks show up.
</P>
<P>
   Best coaching move: LA's Kurt Rambis did the right thing by
benching free-throw clanger Shaquille O'Neal on the final
possession in Phoenix. The only thing he did wrong was apologize
for it after his designed play for Glen Rice resulted in a
game-winning jumper. ``It was probably the wrong decision,'' Rambis
said. ``Shaq's our go-to guy. He's going to make or break us in the
playoffs.'' A better move would be targeting Rice as LA's clutch
shooter.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:INSIDE THE NUMBERS
\Nsubheds:Long wait for a ring Magic Johnson and Bill Russell won
NBA championships as rookies, but the road to victory in the NBA
Finals normally takes years. Just ask Utah's Hall of Fame combo of
John Stockton and Karl Malone, who are still waiting in their 13th
and 14th seasons. A look at some of the best players in NBA history
whose patience finally paid off: Player title season Jerry West
'71-72 12th Nate Archibald '80-81 11th Oscar Robertson '70-71 11th
Elvin Hayes '77-78 10th Jerry Lucas '73-74 10th Hakeem Olajuwon
'93-94 10th Wes Unseld '77-78 10th Wilt Chamberlain '66-67 8th Dave
DeBusschere '69-70 8th Isiah Thomas '88-89 8th Bob Cousy '56-57 7th
Michael Jordan '90-91 7th Bill Walton '76-77 7th
</P>
</TEXT>
