u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-600&AMP;AD     04-11 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS BOLSTERS POSITIONS IN KOSOVO, REFUGEES SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT, KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS,
KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-JOURNALIST) 
(jw) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Serb forces are heavily fortifying their
positions in Kosovo, particularly around the Pristina Airport,
moving anti-aircraft batteries, tanks and other heavy weapons into
villages and large civilian buildings such as factories, according
to refugees arriving here.
</P>
<P>
   A second group of refugees from villages near the
civilian-military airport in Pristina _ a target of recent NATO
bombings _ was allowed through the border here overnight Saturday.
Their accounts, which correspond with the previous group's, suggest
that what is happening is not a general reopening of the border by
Serbs as a continuation of their campaign to drive out ethnic
Albanians, but a new phase, the emptying out of specific strategic
sites for military bases.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a Serb village near the airport called Skulan has been
evacuated, ethnic Albanian refugees from the neighboring area said
Sunday, so that the former Serb village can be turned into what
they describe as the major air defense point. In Skulan, they said,
surface-to-air missiles and anti-aircraft guns had been hidden in
and around a big factory that had made electrical products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night they are fighting NATO from Skulan,'' a refugee
said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been increasing Serb troop movements on the roads
over the past three days, the refugees said. They describe
concentrations of tanks and troops hiding in villages, tanks in
forested areas camouflaged with tree branches and leaves over them,
railroad tank cars full of fuel shuttled from a station during the
day and returned at night, and squads of Serb policemen rushing
about packed into civilian cars whose lack of license plates
indicate they had been taken from fleeing refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The account suggest the extensive NATO bombing has had little
effect on the Serbs' ability to move and deploy their forces, who
usually operate in small groups, in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more ominously, the accounts suggest that they are
digging in for the kind of defensive war that has always been in
the heart of Yugoslav army doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees who arrived at about 2 a.m. Sunday, roughly 5,000
of them, had traveled from two adjacent village clusters, first
Miradije-E-Ulet and Miradije-e-Larte, which they said were about
two miles from the airport. The other group had come from the
nearby village of Vragoli.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts of both groups suggested the Serb tactic was not to
terrorize them, but to move them out as expeditiously as possible.
Their treatment was marginally different from that of earlier
refugees, suggesting a new tactic. It would be absurd to call them
well treated, but by the standards of brutality that have applied
here, both groups arrived in notably better shape than the broken,
weeping, traumatized refugees who arrived in the last wave
numbering almost 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, both groups arriving here in the last
two days contained large numbers of men and there were no accounts
of slayings as the people were driven off. As has become routine,
however, they were robbed and their identifying documents destroyed
before they were sent on their way.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers said they were called together at 12:45 Saturday
afternoon and ordered to leave after an ultimatum issued the day
before, the demand reinforced by volleys of shots in the air. Like
the first group, they were directed along a lengthy circuitous
route over secondary roads left, and then back east, to join the
main highway to the border around Prizrin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like the earlier group, they traveled along roads once so
clogged with refugees it took a day to go a few dozen miles and
were now empty except for Serb military traffic. They, too, saw
burned-out farms and villages along with wandering cows and sheep,
but their descriptions of clusters of tanks and other military
activity were much more extensive, perhaps indicating the pace of
Serb military movements had stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw burned tractors, yes, but traffic, no,'' one man said.
``Only police. Private cars with no plates filled with police.''
</P>
<P>
   They said that Serb forces had moved tanks and other weapons
into Vragoli as soon as it was cleared. On the bridge over the
Sidrica River, the Serbs had placed anti-aircraft guns, a young man
said, mimicking a weapon that can be rotated and aimed by a system
of foot pedals and hand cranks, corresponding to the Soviet-style
M-75.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we left our village, I had seen with my own eyes the
tanks enter our village,'' said one man, who, like other refugees
interviewed Sunday, declined to give his name because for fear of
retribution if he returned.
</P>
<P>
   In a different different area, another villager said: ``At the
moment we left, the tanks and artillery were coming behind there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Serbs now are stuffed into the houses of the Albanians
or up on top of the hills,'' another refugee said.
</P>
<P>
   The movement of Serb troops had been so heavy, one man said,
that for three weeks his village had been isolated not by being
surrounded, but simply by the amount of military traffic.
</P>
<P>
   There was sporadic gunfire along the isolated mountainous
stretches of the Albanian-Serb border between elements of the
Kosovo Liberation Army and the Serbs. A local Albanian border
commander, Bajram Gosturani, told the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe that two people had been killed in the
village of Tropoje when a Serbian mortar shell struck the village.
</P>
</TEXT>
