<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AIRBASE-12-COX     04-11 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRBASE-12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    PRIMITIVE ALBANIAN AIRPORT BECOMES THROBBING NATO BASE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With PHOTOS 
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania In just seven days, the U.S. Air Force
has turned this primitive airport into a throbbing airbase moving
more cargo every day than the Allies flew in at the height of the
1948 Berlin Airlift.
</P>
<P>
   Against a leaden gray sky, the West's nearest airfield to Kosovo
surged with adrenaline on Sunday. Its flight line roared almost
nonstop with beating rotors from scores of humanitarian helicopters
whirling in from the refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   About every 15 minutes, the rotor noise was overwhelmed by the
whine of a giant C-17 wide-bodied Air Force transport or a smaller
C-130 screaming in from Germany. Interspersed every half hour or so
was a transport plane from one of half a dozen non-NATO aid donors.
</P>
<P>
   If the overall NATO air war against Slobodan Milosevic is bogged
down, there was no sign of it here at Rinas. In the last five days,
the Air Force has pushed more than 2,000 tons of cargo through its
single runway _ a cargo flow that the Air Force says is bigger than
the cargo tonnage handled by Chicago's O'Hare International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Berlin Airlift Two, I suppose,'' said Air Force Maj.
Brian Jurkovac, 38, of Columbus, Ohio, who flew in from a NATO base
in Germany a week ago to set up satellite communications and help
coordinate cargo unloading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's C-17 transports can carry so much more than the C-47s
and C-54s that they were using 50 years ago,'' he said. ``The flow
and amount of aircraft and the density of the aircraft is very
similar to what was used in the Berlin Airlift, except that the
tonnages and the transport planes are much bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the first day that the U.S. Air Force took over
control of all the airspace within five miles of the airport from
the Albanian air controllers.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday was the first night that the Air Force had enough
landing beacons and radars in place to extend the daylight airlift
into a round-the-clock operation. Night operations have begun, an
Air Force duty officer confirmed just before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday American airmen at this base outside the capital
Tirana expected to take over control of a wider sector _ the
so-called ``approach'' zone extending out to 60 miles from Rinas.
</P>
<P>
   The hulking U.S. transports that made up the bulk of the airlift
Sunday carried everything from aid rations to the first batch of
heavy trucks to support the U.S. Army's expected Apache helicopters
and artillery rocket launchers.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the 430 airmen and women in the Air Force's ground
party at Rinas, Sunday will be remembered more as a mudlift than an
airlift. Spring is supposed to be sunny in Tirana, but over the
last three nights it has rained buckets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water table is so high that if you dig down a foot you hit
water,'' said Staff Sgt. Jesse Parker, 32, who woke up Sunday with
eight inches of water in his tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are below ground water level, and we are living in water,''
said Staff Sgt. Neil Rothbauer, 33, of Hallettsville, Texas. ``We
are trying to build up the ground and set up our communications and
living areas, you name it.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Rinas was Albania's only functioning civilian
airport. And it wasn't functioning much.
</P>
<P>
   Without a single working radar or beacon for instrument
landings, Rinas managed to attract only about five or six flights a
day by Albania's national airline and a few intrepid foreign
carriers. The buzz among journalists covering the Balkans was that
Rinas was about the scariest airport in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In a week, almost everything at Rinas has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the ramshackle Albanian control tower, Air Force master
sergeants who are some of the top air controllers in the U.S.
military were giving crisp orders on the radio to pilots from
France, Switzerland, Germany and a half-dozen other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robot 41, re-position granted,'' intoned Air Force Tech. Sgt.
Whit Morrison, who until a week ago was on a temporary assignment
drafting radar procedures at Ramstein Air Force Base, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   There was one plane _ a slender blue and white Lear jet _ that
seemed oddly out of place as it circled the base amongst the
military hubbub. At least a dozen times, it whooshed in for
landings, only to pull up at the last second and whirl around the
airfield to make another approach.
</P>
<P>
   The Lear, based in Oklahoma City, was sent here by the U.S.
Federal Aviation Administration to test the positioning of the Air
Force radars and certify the airport for precision landings. And by
late in the day, according to Jurkovac, the FAA
</P>
<P>
   had passed the word to the military that Rinas was safe for
instrument-landing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Once officially certified by the FAA, American air controllers
here will be in direct touch with the Air Force's AWACS command
planes, said Jurkovac. The AWACS is the battle controller the Air
Force uses to run the minute-to-minute operations of the air war
over Serbia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO's urging, the Albanian parliament passed an emergency
resolution five days ago ceding to NATO the authority to take over
control of Albanian airspace.
</P>
<P>
   To bring that off in a few days, the Air Force flew in a TACAN
navigational beacon that by Sunday was already beaming out a radio
signal that was guiding planes on their final approach. Another new
olive drab radar with a rotating dish, called the Approach
Surveillance Radar (ASR), was within a few hours of becoming
operational.
</P>
<P>
   Already set in place and being tested Sunday were two more
radars that could come in handy if bad weather persists and Rinas
has to juggle humanitarian flights and attack helicopter missions
by the Army's Apache helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Precision Approach Radar and the Mobile Microwave
Landing System, they are designed to allow military airplanes to
land in soupy weather with cloud ceilings down to 200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the allies, the one runway has landing lights
and was repaved only a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   How and whether the Rinas base will fit into the overall war is
a question nobody at Rinas was ready to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea about the Apaches,'' said Capt. Mitch Maddox,
31, of Wewahitchka, Fla., whose First Combat Communications
Squadron was setting up a 20-foot-wide satellite telephone dish for
the base. ``As far as I know, we are just here to support the
humanitarian effort.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
