<HEADLINE>
FISTICUFSS AT THE BUFFET TABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A body-slam specialist is now governing the great
state of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Pro rassler Lex Luger has a headlock on Larry King, and Stone
Cold Steve Austin just tossed Clint Eastwood out of the ring in the
fight for late-night television ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Now we learn that sumo wrestlers have been proclaimed the
epicures of Japanese society.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-minute tea ceremony once represented the essence of
Japanese grace and tradition. A few sea urchin eggs embedded in a
sushi roll was the ultimate gastronomical turn-on in Kobe and
Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a pitch-till-you-win, eat-it-and-beat-it race to the
buffet table in the land of Koko, Yum Yum and Nanki-Poo.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Wall Street Journal correspondent, there are
about 180 all-you-can-eat restaurants in Tokyo alone. From the
enthusiasm of the customers, ``Load Till You Explode'' seems to be
the Japanese interpretation of Royal Fork. And the fuse is
connected to a ticking clock.
</P>
<P>
   The latest rage in Japan, we learn, are the buffet restaurants
where speed and agility are just as important as capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The diner grabs a time card from the hostess, sprints to the
buffet line, shovels the food down at the closest table, then huffs
up to the front door where he punches his card and settles the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Customers pay by the minute. In one typical restaurant _
reporter Yumiko Ono reports _ the charge is 35 yen (or 30 cents) a
minute. One typical diner reduced his average restaurant bill from
$15.95 to $5.73 when he got his competitive juices pumping.
</P>
<P>
   Yr. Obdt. Correspondent doesn't like to brag. But you had better
have your Nike's laced if you want to beat me to the buffet table.
</P>
<P>
   Usually I head first for the more expensive dishes like:
</P>
<P>
   Stop-Watch Prawns
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds large, uncooked prawns
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chili sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   One-fourth teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon liquid smoke
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   One half teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   One half teaspoon Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   Wash and shell the prawns, then distribute in a single layer
over a large oven dish.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the other ingredients in a small saucepan and simmer 10
minutes. Let cool, then pour the sauce over the shrimp and let
everything marinate for 30 minutes, mooshing everything around once
or twice.
</P>
<P>
   Shove the dish into a 300-degree oven and heat the shrimp just
until they turn pink.
</P>
<P>
   If you are serving this dish to non-paying guests in your home,
divide the prawns and sauce into four bowls and pass the French
bread.
</P>
<P>
   Or, for less money, serve the freeloaders a filling but
inexpensive meal like this one.
</P>
<P>
   Take It Easy Enchiladas
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground turkey or ground beef
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   9 flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   1 can cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons pickled jalapeno slices, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 roma tomato, chopped
</P>
<P>
   In a lightly oiled skillet, brown the ground turkey and onions.
Remove from heat and add the tablespoon of water, the cream cheese,
cumin, pepper and salt.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl combine the soup, sour cream, milk and jalapeno
peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Use one-half cup of this soup mixture to spread over the bottom
of a lightly oiled 9-by-12-inch oven dish.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon about one-quarter cup of the meat mixture over each
tortilla, roll up and place in dish seam side down.
</P>
<P>
   When all the tortillas have been filled scatter any leftover
meat mixture over the top, then pour the rest of the soup sauce
over the tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Bake, covered, in a 350-degree oven for 40 minutes. Remove
cover, sprinkle with cheese, then return to oven uncovered for 4
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and scatter the tomato bits over the top. This
should make four portions of two tortillas each with one left over
for the family's Mexican hairless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
