<SLUG> BC-FOOD-WINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OREGON WINEMAKER BREAKS ALL THE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASTORIA, Ore. _ A wine snob might shudder in alarm after
stepping into this eccentric little winery that looks out over the
Columbia River. Lining the shelves are peach wine, plum wine,
cranberry wine, spiced apple wine and _ god forbid! _ lemon
meringue wine.
</P>
<P>
   Alarm might turn to horror as the winemaker, a self-described
curmudgeon given to deadpan rants and late-night harp sessions,
introduces his crown jewel _ a small expensive bottle of wine that
he calls the ultimate creation of his older years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I create after this will be an anticlimax,'' says
Paul Van der Veldt, 74, pouring lush, syrup-thick Chocolate-Orange
wine into tasting glasses at Shallon Winery in downtown Astoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chocolate-Orange wine? A tragedy!'' the wine snob might mutter
as he backs away from the offending glass.
</P>
<P>
   But these visitors are no wine snobs. They might even be
inclined to agree with the wine judge who called van der Veldt a
genius.
</P>
<P>
   Their eyes close. A satisfied ``mmmmmm'' goes up as they sip,
then lick the wine out of their glasses. They dip the last of the
precious liquid _ as silky and satisfying as a custom-made truffle
_ from the bottom of the glass with their pinkie fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do they protest when van der Veldt tells them the
ingredients: three kinds of chocolate, orange wine and whey.
</P>
<P>
   ``No whey!'' the wine snob might scream as he backs through the
door.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, whey. The same thin liquid that is left behind when cheese
is curdled from milk. Van der Veldt buys it from the Tillamook
Creamery Association and uses it in several of his handcrafted
fruit and berry wines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whey is one of the most nutritious foods in the world. It has
all the vitamins and minerals of milk,'' says the winemaker, a
slight, bearded, dry-witted man with the intensity of a zealot.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as an aeronautical engineer, he started the winery in
1978, two blocks up from the Columbia River Maritime Museum. He
named the winery after his favorite native plant, Galtheria
shallon, the salal plant.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked inside the 1920s Mediterranean-style building is a
research laboratory, a tasting room and a manufacturing room where
barrels of wine ferment and where van der Veldt keeps his harp,
next to a chair.
</P>
<P>
   Van der Veldt, who lives downstairs, comes up late at night to
style his own free-form creations on the harp strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It relieves stress,'' says the fast-talking winemaker, who
offers _ between pours in the tasting room _ his opinions on
everything from irresponsible journalism and fine dining to local
politics.
</P>
<P>
   A third of Shallon's visitors are repeat customers. Most walk
away chuckling and toting a least one bottle of Shallon's
best-known wine, the wild evergreen blackberry. The wine,
surprisingly subtle, is redolent of berries and moss and woods,
with a character one wine critic described as ``austere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me back to my childhood near Seattle, playing around
the old cedar stumps and eating berries off the vine,'' poet Gary
Snyder wrote after tasting his first bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Van der Veldt, who proclaimed his father's blackberry wine much
too sweet, says he has a cadre of ``little old ladies'' who pick
the wild berries for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my little old ladies are dying off,'' he says, ``and kids
today won't do it _ no matter how much you pay them.''
</P>
<P>
   Van der Veldt says making wine from grapes is ridiculously
simple compared with working with the more obscure fruits. Still,
he sells a few grape varietals, including a red table wine called
``Gillnetter's Delight.'' He stomps the grapes for it himself.
</P>
<P>
   At Shallon, production is slow, quantities small, and stocks
iffy. Van der Veldt generally makes from five to 25 cases at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Prices start at $10 and top out at $25 for a half-bottle of a
heady wild black raspberry desert wine. Each bottle comes with a
story and a lecture on proper care and pouring.
</P>
<P>
   Van der Veldt calls the winery a labor of love. Satisfaction may
be abundant, but profits tend to be slim. Still, van der Veldt
remains philosophic. ``By the time I'm totally broke,'' he says,
``I'll probably be totally dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In which case, this harp-playing curmudgeon with a thing for
whey will get the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done my obituary in advance,'' he says. ``I'm not going
to have some relative write: `Oh, he was loved by all.' It's not
true.''
</P>
<P>
   The winemaker smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want it to read: `He was a cantankerous old coot.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Shallon Winery tasting room is open every afternoon from
approximately noon to 6 p.m., at 16th Avenue between Marine Drive
and Duane Street in Astoria, Ore. The phone number is 503-325-5978;
e-mail shallon &LR; aone.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
