<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. OFFICIALS SAY MILOSEVIC MUST BE REPLACED IF THERE IS TO BE
PEACE IN BALKANS
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 600.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia
again restrained by bad weather, U.S. officials escalated their
diplomatic assaults Sunday, characterizing President Slobodan
Milosevic as a war criminal and suggesting he be replaced as a
prelude to peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb leader ``is going to be held responsible'' for war
atrocities by the International War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague,
Deputy U.S. Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said on the CBS News
program ``Face The Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, and on separate news programs Sunday, White House
Chief of Staff John Podesta said Serbs need ``a new leader'' in
order to be part of a stable democratic Europe and U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen said it would be ``very difficult'' to
negotiate a peace with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, upon arriving in
Brussels late Sunday for talks to bolster NATO unity, said ``lots
of parts'' of the Kosovo peace accord negotiated last month at
Rambouillet, outside Paris, between Serbs and Kosovar Albanians
``have been overtaken by events.''
</P>
<P>
   The television appearances of Talbott, Podesta and Cohen
coincided with that of NATO Supreme Commander Gen. Wesley Clark,
who repeatedly warned that the allied bombing campaign against
Milosevic, which now involves some 600 aircraft, is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the air campaign has a long way to go,'' he said on
NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' ``I think we need to give the air
campaign a chance to do its work....''
</P>
<P>
   Clark declined to speculate in response to questions about the
use of ground troops in Kosovo even though Talbott had suggested
that contingency plans for NATO ground forces ``can be taken off
the shelf and updated at any time'' by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress returns to work from its Easter recess Monday, a
vigorous debate over Clinton's policy in Yugoslavia and the
possible use of U.S. ground troops for combat in Kosovo is expected
to dominate the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who has consistently urged Clinton to
leave open the possibility of ground troops, said Sunday that he
hoped Congress would adopt a resolution authorizing the president
to ``use all means necessary'' to win the Balkan war.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., said the president should not have
ruled out the use of ground troops when he launched ``Operation
Allied Force'' against Milosevic last month. ``I think it's
necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress returns in the wake of increasing reports of atrocities
allegedly committed by Serb soldiers, police and paramilitary units
against the hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees who
have been forced from their homes in Kosovo after the NATO bombing
began.
</P>
<P>
   NATO released aerial photos Sunday showing what allied officials
suspect are dozens of freshly dug graves in Pusto Selo, Kosovo.
NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the image, taken Friday, was not
unlike the mass graves found in Bosnia after the war there between
Serbs and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen declined to elaborate on the report of mass graves in
Kosovo. However, he did say that ``every day that goes by ... we
see more and more evidence of ... grotesque brutality'' against
Kosovar Albanians. When asked if Milosevic is a war criminal, Cohen
replied, ``What his status would be is for others to determine.''
However, under current circumstances, ``I think it would be very
difficult to deal with Mr. Milosevic,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talbott came closer than any other Clinton administration
official to calling Milosevic a war criminal. ``As for what happens
to Mr. Milosevic, he is going to be held responsible by the
international community _ and in the first instance, that means the
International War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta flatly rejected the suggestion that NATO is negotiating
at all with Milosevic. To stop the bombing, Milosevic must remove
Serb forces from Kosovo, permit the refugees to return and let them
live ``in peace and autonomy,'' he said. ``That's not
negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking beyond the current conflict, which is about to enter its
fourth week, Podesta said that for Serbia to join a peaceful
democratic Europe, it ``needs to have a measure of democracy and
the leadership that's going to respect human rights and respect the
autonomy of the people'' with the Yugoslavian republics.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he meant that Yugoslavia must have a new leader,
Podesta replied, ``I think that, ultimately, that for them to
create a stable situation, it looks to me like they're going to
need a new leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Podesta ruled out any settlement of the conflict that would
include a partitioning of Kosovo between Serbs and ethnic
Albanians. ``I don't see that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Albright, in comments to reporters accompanying her to
Brussels, declined to preclude partition _ stripping the Serbs of
all but a northern region where the Serbs have their shrines and
are more predominant in a province about 90 percent ethnic
Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that in light of Milosevic's ``scorched-earth''
campaign in Kosovo, there has to be ``some reconsideration'' of the
Rambouillet peace accords that the Serbs rejected and the ethnic
Albanians accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The Rambouillet accords call for the withdrawal of Serb troops,
paramilitary and police units. A total of 5,000 troops could remain
_ 2,500 along the border, thereby assuring Kosovo remained part of
Serbia, and 2,500 police who could remain for one year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was at the Camp David presidential retreat Sunday,
will highlight his Kosovo policy in a speech on Monday at Barksdale
Air Force Base in Louisiana. He also will meet Monday with U.S.
bomber crews at Barksdale and with congressional leaders at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
