<HEADER>
A4007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERMLIMITS-POLITICS-9     04-11 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERMLIMITS-POLITICS-910(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME POLITICIANS RECONSIDER PLEDGES TO LIMIT THEIR TIME IN OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Ariz., Fla., Idaho, S.C., Okla., Colo., Mass.)  (js) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPOKANE, Wash. _ George R. Nethercutt Jr. was the giant slayer
five years ago when, in his first race for public office, he
unseated a speaker of the House of Representatives for the first
time since the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt, pledging to serve no more than three terms in the
House, scoffed at arguments of the speaker then, Tom Foley, a
30-year House veteran, that his influence and experience were
vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is indispensable in this district,'' Nethercutt told
voters at the time. ``The state is bigger than one man.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, as Nethercutt, a Republican, travels the 5th District
in what is increasingly looking like a re-election bid, he is
telling voters that his term-limits pledge, a potent campaign tool
at the time, may have been a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I said and I wish I hadn't said it,'' he told a
town hall meeting at the Garfield County Fairgrounds earlier this
month. ``I have lived and learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Once seen as the poster child for the term-limits movement,
which seemed to be catching fire in 1994 but has quieted down after
adverse court rulings and flush economic times, Nethercutt is one
of 58 members of Congress who have set a limit on their time in
office, and one of 10 House members whose pledges come due next
fall.
</P>
<P>
   And of those 10, all but one of them Republicans, at least four
are wavering on their pledges, driven in part by the urgings of
party leaders and the high stakes involved in the 2000 races: With
the Democrats needing just six seats to retake control of Congress,
every seat is vital, and Republicans seem loath to sacrifice strong
incumbents on the altar of the term-limits cause.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews in the district here strongly suggest that, so far
anyway, few voters are waking up in the morning enraged over the
possibility that Nethercutt might run again.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, those that do break their vow to leave can
already have a taste of what may be in store for them in the form
of a television advertisement run here in Spokane recently by
United States Term Limits, an advocacy group that is threatening to
spend millions of dollars in next year's elections to express its
outrage over those who betrayed their cause.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement features footage of Richard Nixon's ``I am not
a crook'' speech, George Bush's ``Read my lips _ no new taxes''
pledge and Bill Clinton's finger-wagging declaration, ``I did not
have sexual relations with that woman.'' And then it asks: ``Will
George Nethercutt be next?''
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt has sought to turn the advertisement against its
creators, describing them as part of an ``outside group that wants
to poison the atmosphere in eastern Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   His spokesperson calls the advertisement ``off the deep end''
and says that despite the group's call for voters to flood the
congressman's office with calls demanding that he leave office,
most people are actually calling to urge him to run again.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old congressman, who now says it is not a good idea
to have a district ``perpetually served by freshmen,'' promises a
firm decision sometime this spring. Though he has toyed with the
notion of what would be an uphill race for governor against the
state's popular Democratic incumbent, Gary Locke, most indications
are that he will run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The term-limits group is based in Washington, D.C., and run by a
libertarian, Paul Jacob. So far, its rumblings have delighted the
Democrats, who feel they have an excellent chance to win in some of
the districts where Republicans are in the hot seat over
term-limits pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who scored a stunning takeover of Congress in 1994
in part over the pledge to put more ``citizen legislators'' in the
body, are openly torn on whether to stick with the theme, which
could force them to jettison incumbents and create many more ``open
races'' in coming years. Brett Bader, a Republican consultant based
in Seattle who has worked on races across the West, said in an
interview, ``We are in danger of eating our own over this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone who promised to leave in 2000 is agonizing over the
pledge. Rep. Matt Salmon of Arizona, who was elected in 1994 and
who shortly after his swearing-in theatrically handed a resignation
letter effective in 2001 to the congressional clerk, said he had no
ambivalence about honoring his promise to leave Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, it is a terrible thing to have to do,''
Salmon said, tongue very much in cheek, in a telephone interview.
``I'm going to be forced to play a lot more golf with my son. I'm
going to attend a lot more of my daughter's school plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Salmon, 41, a father of four, may stay very busy even
after he returns to Arizona full time. In a state where polls have
shown a significant degree of support for term limits, honoring his
pledge has helped vault him into the circle of candidates
prominently mentioned for the 2002 governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   The term-limits group lists 58 members of Congress as serving
under self-imposed term-limit pledges. Of the 10 who the group says
pledged to step down after next year, six say they still intend to
do so. In addition to Salmon, they are Charles T. Canady of
Florida, Helen Chenoweth of Idaho, Tom Coburn of Oklahoma, Jack
Metcalf of Washington and Mark Sanford of South Carolina. All are
Republicans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt is perhaps the most visible incumbent who is still
undecided. Others who are listed by the term-limits group as
``wafflers'' are Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat
described by an aide as leaning toward running for re-election,
Tillie Fowler, a Florida Republican who won in 1992 with the slogan
``Eight Is Enough,'' referring to the years she pledged to spend in
the House, and Scott McInnis, a Colorado Republican.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis' case may well illustrate the limited perils involved in
breaking a term-limits pledge. After saying when he first won the
seat in 1992 that he would serve just three terms, he abandoned
that commitment last year and nevertheless won re-election handily.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler, who is considering a bid for an open U.S. Senate seat,
has said she may run for re-election to the House despite the
``Eight Is Enough'' slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a big issue in the election,'' she told The Florida
Times-Union in December. ``My problem was, I was too honest with
you the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the term-limits group says the issue still resonates
powerfully with voters, others question its impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the American people were ever living and dying
term limits to begin with,'' said John David Rausch, a professor of
political science at West Texas A&AMP;M University, who has studied
term-limits initiatives. ``Now it's even less of a movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with voters here suggest that the recent television
advertisements may have backfired, with many people describing them
as too negative and others expressing such cynicism with the
political process that they said they had not taken Nethercutt's
pledge seriously to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the same old say-this, do-that,'' said Doris
Speicher, a retired homemaker in Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not to say the incumbent faces an easy ride next
year. Pressed on the issue, some people said that it might be a
factor in their vote next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like him and all,'' said Bob Sjogren, 54, a probation
officer from Colville, Wash., and a Republican. ``But maybe he
should be held accountable. The man made a pledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Sjogren's wife, Gloria, expressed surprise: ``Oh, I think I'd
vote for him again, Bob, I really do. He's right on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a district that sent a Democrat to Congress for three
decades before electing Nethercutt, and that voted for Clinton in
both 1992 and 1996, many people do not seem to think the incumbent
is right on the issues, which could pose a more ominous challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care so much on this term-limits stuff,'' said
Jim Lawrence, a computer support technician, who voted for
Nethercutt in 1994 but regrets it now. ``He let us down on schools;
he let us down on health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing down the specific issue of term limits, Nethercutt, a
lawyer and Spokane native, has sought in his visits here in recent
months to argue that he has kept a wider trust with the voters. In
response to the ``Keep your word, George'' bumper stickers handed
out by the term-limits group, Nethercutt said, ``I assume they mean
my promise to cut taxes, balance the budget and end the welfare
system as we knew it _ that's what I promised too.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has often said that though he meant it when he first said
he would step down after three terms, reconsideration is not a
terrible thing. Asked about the issue before a high-school class in
Pullman in February, he said, ``Only fools and dead people never
change their minds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
