<HEADLINE>
BAND ON THE FAST BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The best way to get noticed by sports fans at John
Elway's high school alma mater isn't so much on the playing field.
Grab a triangle and join the band.
</P>
<P>
   The Granada Hills Highlander Marching Band's next gig will be
pretending to be the pep band at Michael Jordan's
</P>
<P>
   high school in Sunday's made-for-TV flick called ``The Michael
Jordan Story: An American Hero'' with the asterisked subtitle ``An
authorized, dramatized biography of Michael Jordan.'' (Fox Family
Channel, 8 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Dena Zelig, a former GHHS drum major, works for Saban
Entertainment, which produced the movie. During scenes of Jordan
playing in high school, they needed a festive band for background.
Zelig, true to her school, suggested the Highlanders.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? They played for the Adam Sandler movie ``The
Waterboy,'' after their performance at the stadium rededication
ceremony for Elway following the Broncos' first Super Bowl win.
</P>
<P>
   Where do we sign up?
</P>
<P>
   _ Robin Givens , the former Mrs. Mike Tyson , gets to pretend
she's Mrs. MJ in this presentation. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Elway, meanwhile, came in ranked 15th on a list of the ``25
Most Powerful People in Denver'' by the city's magazine 5280 (get
it, mile high?). The mag cited Elway for his snub of President
Clinton and his TV commercials campaigning for the Broncos new
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And makes him !ital!only No. 15? In !ital!Denver ? . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Elway joined Chinese premier Zhu Rongji at a dinner Saturday
night in Denver, and Broncos owner Pat Bowlen gave the dignitary a
jersey with Elway's No. 7 and his own name _ ``ZHU'' _ on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Which should end any speculation about Elway's three-peat plans.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Elway's agent, Marvin Demoff, has said the 38-year-old has to
make his decision about coming back by about mid-May so that he can
start on his training regimen.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos aren't pushing any commitment despite the QB-rich
NFL draft this weekend because they're committed to Bubby Brister
and Brian Griese if Elway retires. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ After all the success veteran quarterbacks had last season,
especially those given up for dead, why would there be !ital!any
demand for a supply of young arms? . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Whitey Herzog has been getting far too much attention for
popping off in his new book, ``You're Missing A Great Game'' _
which is what most people told him during each trading deadline
when he came back to be the Angels' GM in the early '90s. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Why does Kareem Abdul-Jabbar's name keep coming up whenever
there's a college coaching vacancy? . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ A source at a Piggly Wigglys sezs Jim Harrick held up the
10-items-or-less line for nearly a half-hour after the bagger
stumped him with the choice ``paper or plastic?'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ There are far bigger journalistic defiance-of-ethics issues
than Sports Illustrated's Rick Reilly getting paid to share the
great taste of a true pilsner beer with self-proclaimed supermodel
Rebecca Romjin-Stamos , who still has that milk mustache going from
another advertising gimmick. Of course, SI endorsed the commercial
(and free pub). And of course we'll never be able to trust Reilly's
hypocritical stance on any major issue knowing he once was paid by
a beer company to pitch its product.
</P>
<P>
   But those are the choices you make. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.S. Olympic Committee has granted ``affiliated status''
to the U.S. Amateur Ballroom Dancers Association and full Olympic
status to the U.S. Tae kwon do Union. It apparently came up a vote
short of approving the U.S. Lawn Mower Racing Association despite
lobbying from NBC Sports chief Dick Ebersol . . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Does this mean no more shots of Brooke Shields in the crowd at
Wimbledon? . . . &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
