<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4016 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     04-11 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; LEARNING HOW TO EAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Food critic &UR; Alan Richman &LR;  writes in the latest issue of GQ
magazine that crusading vegans, easily identified by their pallor,
their grimness and what he perceives as their ``terrifying
alien-like demeanor ... are best avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Richman is not adamantly anti-vegetarian. ``Macrobiotics, who
share the vegan affinity for food that is colored brown, are kindly
souls who believe in the Zen principle of not irritating everybody
with whom they come in contact,'' he writes. ``The way I see it,
macrobiotics is the art of prolonging life, whereas veganism is the
art of making life not worth prolonging.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ovo-lacto-vegetarians we see around all the time are much
more tolerable. They are actually happier than most people, since
all they ever eat are giant chocolate chip cookies.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In response to Movieline magazine, which asked  &UR; Liam
Neeson &LR;  to describe the importance of  &UR; Helen Mirren &LR; , his former
lover, ``in your development,'' the actor seemed to call for a
platter of metaphor, consider it and pass it back without
partaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helen taught me there's more to life than meat, vegetables and
potatoes on a plate,'' said Neeson. ``Literally, I had my first
Chinese meal with her.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOO HAPPY FOR WORDS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Whitney Houston  &LR; assures Redbook magazine that she and her
husband,  &UR; Bobby Brown &LR; , are ``crazy in love _ love, love, love,
love. When we're fighting, it's like that's love for us. We're
fighting for our love.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that he has hit her are totally untrue, she says.
``Contrary to belief, I do the hitting, he doesn't. He has never
put his hands on me. He wasn't raised that way.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - News Communication, a chain of neighborhood weeklies in New
York, reported that many celebrities, including  &UR; Jesse Jackson &LR;  and
 &UR; Susan Sarandon &LR; , arrested in recent weeks at protests of police
brutality, had assistants call for convenient appointments.
According to the story, which was denied to the New York Post by
the Police Department, Sarandon's assistant called the police to
see how long the arrest would take because ``she has another social
engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   - Producer  &UR; Christopher Peditto  &LR; will release a video version of
``Jane Doe,'' a movie that starred  &UR; Calista Flockhart  &LR; before she
became famous in ``Ally McBeal,'' in June, in order to catch the
ws &LR; ave of publicity that will accompany Flockhart's appearance in
``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Flockhart plays a drug-addicted misfit. ``This was made pre-nose
job, pre-anorexia ridiculousness,'' Peditto told New York magazine.
</P>
<P>
   - Homeboys go national: San Francisco producer  &UR; Jonathan &LR; 
 &UR; Reinis &LR;  opens ``It Ain't Nothin' But the Blues'' at the Vivian
Beaumont Theater in New York on April 26, two days before the
cut- &LR; off date for Tony eligibility. Reinis' ``Dame Edna's Royal
Tour'' opens in Manhattan in October. And  &UR; Mark Bittner &LR; , the
Telegraph Hill caretaker of a flock of wild parrots, is featured in
this week's People.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a  &UR; Salman Rushdie  &LR; short story in last week's
New Yorker put the Great Quake of San Francisco in October 1984,
which leads  &UR; Judy Reimann &LR;  to debate the relative merits of
literary license and fact checkers.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Michael Robertson &LR; , reading multiple threats in the past few
weeks to bomb Serbia back to the Stone Age, recommends a kinder,
gentler bombing back to the Renaissance. It just ``sounds nicer,''
says Robertson. ``Frescoes, men in tights,'' that sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BBC DECIDES THAT `BRITISH' IS OUT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A series of seminars given for BBC staff members was apparently
infiltrated by the Sunday Times of London, which reported on
several caveats:
</P>
<P>
   - The word ``British'' is to be avoided when describing people
living in the British Isles because it might make Scots and Welsh
people feel left out.
</P>
<P>
   - The word ``nation'' is to be used rarely, for what seems to be
the same reason; it implies a unity among the Isles that is not to
be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   - Subtitles can never be used to make clear what a Scot is
saying, even if it is undecipherable.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I've never discussed it before. As a child, I used to bite &LR; 
 &UR; my toenails off, you know, instead of clipping them with &LR; 
 &UR; clippers. I was very limber.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Julia Roberts &LR;  in Cosmopolitan magazine &LR; . &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
