<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4022 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CENTURY-SPI &LR;      04-11 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CENTURY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY CHANNEL BEGINS ITS LOOK AT THE CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fact that we can look back on the past hundred years and see
it as it happened, see eyewitnesses talking about things that are
history to us and cherished memories to them, may be what we take
most for granted about this century.
</P>
<P>
   No other period in time can be seen in the oh-so-revealing light
of film and videotape.
</P>
<P>
   What a legacy! Assumptions that video will never match the
breadth and depth of the printed word are being revised as
technology combines the archival capacity of books with the
immediacy and visual impact of film. Just imagine how the next
century will be recorded and remembered.
</P>
<P>
   It's an exercise in fantasy that seems appropriate after the
first two installments of The History Channel's 15{-hour journey
through ``The Century: America's Time,'' which begins Monday night.
This is the ``other'' Peter Jennings/ABC project that takes an
approach more linear than the themed, 12-hour package that
concluded on ABC Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the rapid advances in technology that greeted the
20th century, Monday night's episodes, which start at 1900 and
conclude with World War I, are nourishing food for thought, given
how the dark side of technology is now on display in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of The History Channel's traditional, documentarian
approach will love this series, rife as it is with interviews of
those who were there, such as a passenger on the Lusitania, a
bodyguard of Lenin or the the next-door neighbors of the Wright
brothers. These people make the stories come alive, and television
makes the people come alive. No matter how familiar the footage,
it's quite a sight.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the entire schedule for ``The Century: America's Time.''
``Seeds of Change'' (1900-1914), Monday night; ``Shell Shock''
(1914-1919), Monday night; ``Boom to Bust'' (1920-1929), Tuesday;
``Stormy Weather'' (1930-1939), Wednesday; ``Over the Edge''
(1936-1941), Thursday; ``Civilians at War'' (1936-1945), Friday
(90-minute episode); ``Homefront'' (1941-1945), April 19; ``Best
Years'' (1946-1952), April 20; ``Happy Days'' (1953-1960), April
21; ``Poisoned Dreams'' (1960-1963), April 22; ``Unpinned''
(1964-1968), April 23; ``Apocalypse Now'' (1969-1975), April 26;
``Starting Over'' (1976-1981), April 27; ``A New World''
(1981-1989), April 28; ``Machine Dreams'' (the 1990s), April 29.
Repeats will begin with episodes 1-6 this Sunday, and continue with
episodes 7-11 on April 25 and episodes 12-15 on May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Media and Public Affairs reports that, of the Big
Three networks, ABC seems the most negative toward U.S./NATO
involvement in Kosovo. Based on 208 stories broadcast over the
first eight days of NATO bombing, the center said reports on ``ABC
World News Tonight'' were the most critical, with 37 percent of
statements from news sources supporting U.S. policy and 63 percent
opposed. ``NBC Nightly News'' was considered ``generally balanced''
(54 percent yea, 46 percent nay), and ``CBS Evening News'' heavily
supportive, with 67 percent of source comments in favor and 33
percent opposed. ... Imagine the pillow talk: Gerry Sheindlin will
replace Edward Koch as presiding judge on ``The People's Court''
next season. Sheindlin is the husband of Judith ``Judge Judy''
Sheindlin, currently the top-rated arbiter of right and wrong on
daytime TV. ... Helen Hunt will direct the series finale of ``Mad
About You.'' The hourlong farewell episode, scheduled May 24 at 9
p.m., will have Janeane Garofalo playing a grown-up version of Paul
and Jamie Buchman's daughter, Mabel. ... It was inevitable. After
years of gathering around the water cooler, TV characters would
eventually have to go to the bathroom. But the guys-at-the-urinal
shot has become the overused cliche of choice this season among
devotees of TV-verite. It was spoofed hilariously last week in
Comedy Central's new ``Strangers With Candy,'' when two men
introduced themselves and actually shook hands while ... well, you
get the idea. Everywhere else on TV, however, it's becoming a key
part of story exposition, as if we all need to know that Dr. Greene
on ``ER'' or Andy Sipowicz on ``NYPD Blue'' prefer the urinal on
the left. What's next? Ben Stiller's zip-up accident from ``There's
Something About Mary?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
