<DOCNO> NYT19990411.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ABRAMOWITZ-PRO     04-11 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ABRAMOWITZ-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ADVOCATE FOR REFUGEES WITH HER HAT FIRMLY IN HAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: China, Taiwan, Turkey, Vietnam, Md., Pa.)  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT,
KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-RELIGION,
KOSOVO-JOURNALIST) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sheppie Abramowitz barely had time to toss aside
her red slouch-brim hat before she was working the telephone _
cajoling and hectoring administration officials to do favors big
and small for the masses of Kosovo refugees who now wander the
earth in despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found the guy,'' she hurriedly told a fellow refugee worker
who needed her to root out a specialist in the federal maw. ``Now
we'll figure out how to do it,'' she added, ending the call with
the clipped determination of a bookmaker used to long odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shamelessly squeezing people I know in the
administration,'' Mrs. Abramowitz explained without a scrap of
apology. She is in her fourth decade of work on the harrowing
refugee problems she first encountered on the ground in the Vietnam
era, when she was a foreign-service spouse volunteering for what
has mushroomed into a passionate career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I have a sense of propriety and don't overdo it,'' Mrs.
Abramowitz added, lightening her brassy, voice with a blink of
innocence. Actually, her friends in the field say the art of
Sheppie Abramowitz is to know precisely when to overdo it, and with
whom, in working the amorphous capital underbrush where government
and humanitarian relief organizations overlap.
</P>
<P>
   Her title is vice president of the International Rescue
Committee, one of the private refugee aid organizations with years
of experience in the human disasters of the Balkans. But Mrs.
Abramowitz, a lean, scrappy figure with salt-and-pepper hair, has
the larger reputation of canny pest and benevolent fixer. She
trafficks in a deep knowledge of diplomats and administration
workers to hack away at red tape and bolster refugee services in
the field, where, she insists, the true relief workers are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a young person's game,'' said the 63-year-old relief
strategist, dropping the names not of the celebrated Washington
officials she regularly strokes and prods but of a dozen field
specialists and relief organizations she finds more deserving of
attention. It is this connection to both worlds that colleagues
rate as her singular strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something goes nuclear, as Kosovo has, and you have to
deal with a broader group of people in this town, Sheppie is so
much more an authority than the 20-somethings, bless all their
work,'' said Mark Malloch-Brown, a vice president and refugee
specialist with the World Bank. He first encountered Mrs.
Abramowitz two decades ago when she led a caravan of embassy wives
in providing first-hand help in the Cambodian refugee camps in
Thailand, where her husband, Morton I. Abramowitz, was ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``A spectacular amateur,'' said Malloch-Brown of Ms. Abramowitz,
who quickly became known as the Bangkok embassy person to see about
refugees. ``I've watched her grow and grow and grow to be one the
great champions, one of the handful who can affect policy and
really knows this issue at the field level.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyperkinetic with the Kosovo disaster, Mrs. Abramowitz seems
appalled by praise. She prefers to discuss how long-running refugee
crises in Sudan, Afghanistan and beyond must not be overlooked as
Kosovo flames up.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about herself, Mrs. Abramowitz pauses warily and then
offers the simplest summary of her life: ``I was unformed, and
refugees became a passion.''
</P>
<P>
   She met her future husband while she worked as a congressional
aide after graduating from Bryn Mawr College. Their first foreign
service posting was Taiwan in 1959, then Hong Kong where she began
dabbling in the cause, helping mainland Chinese refugees learn
``hotel English'' to get jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a passion for both of us,'' she said of herself and
her husband, who is retired from the State Department but is an
advocate on the refugee issue. It engulfed both of them in Thailand
and in Turkey, where Abramowitz was ambassador during the Kurd
refugee crisis. ``Mort offers advice, but whether we follow it
depends on how desperate we are,'' she added with equanimity.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Baltimore, where her father ran a record store, Mrs.
Abramowitz is proud that well before she faced the sufferings of
Cambodians and Kurds, her mother, Ida Glass, set the flame in her.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother worked for refugees in the Second World War,'' she
said, recalling German Jewish families living in her house. ``I
come by this very rightly.''
</P>
<P>
   She of course exploits her famous brother, Philip Glass, the
composer. ``He does great fund-raisers for our cause,'' adding that
her other brother, Marty, a businessman, ``puts up with all this.''
Her two grown children, Rachel and Michael, were raised on
volunteer refugee work.
</P>
<P>
   Her office, four blocks from the White House, is a babel of
assorted refugee causes and aid workers coming and going.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to hear me do my number right now, but remember,
I don't really like being a bully,'' she said before another phone
call in which she pressed a friend for the gist of a government
meeting on Kosovo refugees. ``I heard it from the Pentagon,'' she
persisted, flashing a trump card that produced success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me? A bully?'' she later trilled self-mockingly. To a
departing visitor Sheppie Abramowitz offered a farewell that verged
from amiable to bullying: ``Now you guys must continue to press in
on this refugee story, right?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990411.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-INDUSTRY-TESTS-45     04-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-INDUSTRY-TESTS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 INDUSTRIES PASS TESTS FOR YEAR 2000 COMPUTER GLITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.J., Pa., Md.) (See also FAA-Y2K, Y2K-LAWSUITS) 
(js) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three major industries racing to prepare their computers for the
Year 2000 _ securities, electric utilities and the airlines _ all
passed important testing milestones in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   The securities industry's test, which has been conducted on
weekends since early March, went through its single most important
phase on Saturday, when it simulated Monday, Jan. 3, 2000, the
first trading day next Year and the first day in the test to handle
both new trading and settlement of previous trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went extremely well,'' said John Panchery, the Year 2000
project manager for the Securities Industry Association. All of the
participating exchanges and the organizations that provide them
with clearing and other back-office services _ the backbone of the
$270 billion industry _ came through without any Year 2000
glitches, Panchery said. Results for individual brokers were not
available yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street tests are the most thorough performed by any
industry to deal with the inability of some computers to recognize
that ``00'' as a two-digit date means 2000. The tests involve
several hundred firms, virtually every type of equity they trade,
and, in most cases, the same equipment and software they use to do
business during the week.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Federal Aviation Agency focused on just one
airport _ Denver International _ and one flight in its test
Saturday night of air traffic control, but the test was hailed as a
reassuring success for an industry that many had seen as lagging
far behind the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
   The electric utility industry's simulation was not so much a
Year 2000 test as a drill of how it would deal with a Year 2000
disaster. More than 200 utilities in Canada and the United States
conducted exercises on Friday to see how they would respond to the
loss of voice and data communications that they normally rely on to
monitor power production and distribution. Without such
information, local utilities and then the power grids over which
electricity flows between states could become unbalanced, leading
to widespread blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   During the exercises, utilities switched to radio and satellite
communication systems and focused on making sure that the minimum
amount of information to keep electricity flowing was being passed
from substations and power plants to utility control rooms, from
the utilities to regional control centers such as the PJM
Interconnection (for Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Maryland) in
Norristown, Pa., and among the regional centers.
</P>
<P>
   It will take several weeks to gather all of the data. The drill
was described as successful, but it clearly pointed to a number of
minor problems that need further attention, according to Eugene
Gorzelnik, a spokesman for the North American Reliability Council.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among the concerns utilities reported: field staff with
out-of-date phone numbers; radio antennae in locations that provide
poor coverage, and employees unable to operate recently purchased
satellite systems.
</P>
<P>
   The drill was conducted alongside normal operations and did not
involve changes to actual generating and transmission equipment.
Many utilities have previously moved power plant computers into the
Year 2000 to make sure that they would not be tripped by the
transition and some have left them there. Some utilities, like
Public Service Electric and Gas in New Jersey, plan to move the
computers on much of their equipment forward to the Year 2000 in
stages this year so that only a small percentage will make the date
transition on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most revealing problem reported in the three
industry tests was a telephone problem affecting the securities
traders that had nothing to do with whether computers will
correctly handle Year 2000 dates. A breakdown in a device that
controls phone traffic into computers at the National Securities
Clearing Corporation on Friday was not repaired before the industry
test began on Saturday. It delayed entries of trading and
bookkeeping information for an undetermined number of firms for
several hours, according to Panchery.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of equipment problems are common, and although we
hadn't planned on it during the test, we got to work on our
contingency plans,'' said Panchery. In a sign of the times,
Clearing Corp. was unable to immediately get all of the incoming
traffic transferred to its backup phone lines because Bell Atlantic
had them tied up in some independent Year 2000 testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not much time left and everyone is rushing to get
their testing done,'' Panchery said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
