<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last is best for Braves _ again
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first week means nothing, but the first week can
suggest everything. The Atlanta Braves are off on the season's
longest road trip having learned something about their new mix over
the season's first seven days that may serve them for months.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones' two-run single off Gregg Olson with one out in the
ninth Sunday gave Atlanta its second last at-bat victory in three
days, the Braves beating the suddenly competitive Arizona
Diamondbacks 3-2 in a game they had every right to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not swinging the bats good and you win a game like
that, it's a good sign,'' first baseman Ryan Klesko said.
</P>
<P>
   The first week ends with a 4-3 record against two teams _
Philadelphia and Arizona _ coming off losing seasons. Yet the
Braves showed resourcefulness to reap what they have. After going
2-46 last season when trailing after eight innings, they already
have matched that win total in two outings against Olson, Arizona's
woeful closer who now has three blown saves in three appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not my fault,'' said Jones, who also won Friday's night
game with a 10th-inning RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel fortunate to win two out of three, to be honest with
you,'' manager Bobby Cox said, ``because they shut us down pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for smooth beginnings. The season's first homestand saw
reliever Mike Remlinger's back injury, Mark Wohlers' wreck and the
Braves come within a few precious at-bats of losing all three to
the Diamondbacks. The top three spots in the order are batting .178
and the reigning Cy Young winner is 0-2 with a 7.11 earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   Yet down 2-0 Sunday because of a domineering performance by
Arizona starter Todd Stottlemyre (eight scoreless innings, four
hits), the Braves responded.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Kevin McGlinchy pitched a scoreless eighth in relief of
Greg Maddux, who had yielded home runs to Travis Lee and Luis
Gonzalez. The Braves loaded the bases in the ninth without a hit (a
Jay Bell error and two 3-2 walks by Olson) before Jones delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how much was on the line when I got out
there,'' said McGlinchy, who wound up with his first career win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not swinging the bats real well, except a couple of
guys,'' said Ozzie Guillen, who hit the line drive that Bell
dropped to open the ninth. ``So when you're not hitting that well,
you have to be aggressive on the bases and play good defense. And
if the pitching is tough and we keep doing what we're doing right
now, we have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
