<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Club awaits word on Wohlers' choice toward the future
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The next chapter in the Mark Wohlers saga begins
today, when the reliever is scheduled to accept or decline the
Braves' designation to a minor-league assignment.
</P>
<P>
   How life unfolds after that, general manager John Schuerholz
said, ``I don't have any idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinion varies throughout the majors on Wohlers' best course
toward the future _ making a clean start somewhere else or trying
to rekindle spring's early success in the minors. But the club's
initial assurance that he was willing to remain with the Braves has
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sounds like he's giving serious thought to a very serious
matter,'' said Schuerholz, who talked with Wohlers over the
weekend. ``This is a very big decision in his life, which has a lot
of variables to it. And I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   If Wohlers declines the assignment, the Braves have 10 days to
deal with his contract. Although Arizona and Pittsburgh are
reportedly interested in Wohlers, the contract disposition becomes
a central issue. By releasing him, the Braves would become solely
responsible for the $6 million he has coming ($5.2 million in 1999
salary and another $800,000 buyout for a 2000 option year).
</P>
<P>
   The best-case scenario becomes a trade, not that far-fetched
given the current state of relief pitching in the majors. The
Braves could hope Wohlers creates a market _ 100 mph fastballs with
seven years major-league experience are a commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz rejected the idea that Wohlers has no option than to
leave the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why it would be impossible for him to stay
here,'' he said. ``Some might think it'd be more likely he'd
remain, with the support group that's in place and the
understanding everybody has of his troubles. Some other place may
be new and fresh but they may not have the understanding of his
situation that exists here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brrrrrr. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are off on a trip Federal Express wouldn't take, from
Philadelphia to Colorado to Los Angeles to Florida. Fashions run
from beachwear to apres-ski.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trip is kind of messed up,'' Andruw Jones said. ``We're
going to Philadelphia. Cold. Colorado. Cold. Florida. Maybe cold.
It's tough but that's part of baseball. Whatever schedule you have,
you have to play, but in my three years, we've never had as bad a
road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have been snowed out on the road in each of the past
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Wall ball
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan is still feeling the effects of a Friday night
collision with the right-field wall. He sat out the last two
innings of Saturday night's game to avoid aggravating his right
shoulder, which he slammed into the screen protecting the
scoreboard while trying to chase down a Tony Batista double.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
