<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kyle helps improve luck of Pettys
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bristol, Tenn. _ Only three of Richard Petty's 200 career
victories came at Bristol Motor Speedway, so the family's dislike
of the half-mile oval is understandable.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Kyle Petty said they should fill the facility
with water and use it for bass fishing tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's Food City 500, however, the first family of
stock-car racing saw its luck change. Kyle, who didn't finish
higher than 31st with two DNQs in the past five races, finished
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti, who drives the other Petty Pontiac, was fourth,
his best finish of the season and in 16 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still hate Bristol, but I love the finish,'' Andretti said.
Earnhardt moves up
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt, relegated to the back of the field to start
after wrecking his primary car Saturday, did some of his best
driving of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, using a backup car, had only 10 practice laps in the
car Saturday. He finished 10th, moving up 28 positions in the first
136 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty good for unloading off the truck and not changing
any springs,'' he said. ``We were scared to. We were scared to go
adjusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Swirvin' Irvan
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Ernie Irvan long to find a wall. Only 10 laps
into the race, Irvan hit the outside wall on the backstretch and
then caromed into the pit-road wall.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan's crew spent 187 laps repairing his No. 36 Pontiac before
he returned to the track on lap 197, without the front end of his
car. Irvan finished 43rd and fell eight spots in the point
standings to 23rd.
</P>
<P>
   Tricky Dick
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Dick Trickle had one of the busier afternoons. During
lap 107, Trickle tried to pass Ricky Rudd but smashed the
passenger-side door on Rudd's No. 10 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got caught in traffic and I guess some of the guys behind me
got a little antsy, racing like it was the last lap,'' said Rudd,
who was running seventh. Trickle later bumped Dale Jarrett's No. 88
Ford in turn 4 of lap 117. That tap caused slight damage to the
right side of Jarrett's car. Trickle then hit Jerry Nadeau's No. 9
Ford under a caution on lap 295.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
