<HEADER>
A4036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR12-COX     04-11 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace avoids Bristol wreckage
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ Rusty Wallace was about the only contender to
avoid all the debris in Sunday's Food City 500 at Bristol Motor
Speedway. Luckily, he was able to speed past his final obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   After Wallace narrowly beat Mark Martin to the finish for his
seventh victory here, he completed a ``Polish victory lap,''
driving backward on the half-mile oval to honor late NASCAR driver
Alan Kulwicki, who died in a plane crash at an airport only miles
from the speedway in April 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace won the race three days after Kulwicki's death, after
which he duplicated Kulwicki's signature celebration, which the
late driver introduced during his 1992 Winston Cup championship
season.
</P>
<P>
   But Wallace's first ride in reverse at Bristol wasn't nearly as
exciting as Sunday's.
</P>
<P>
   As Wallace left the front straightaway, track officials opened
the gates, allowing spectators to cross the track from the infield.
Fortunately, Wallace's No. 2 Ford Taurus left turn 3 into the
backstretch just as spectators started to cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kulwicki) started it and then I did it, and then everybody
did it,'' Wallace said. ``Then everybody just stopped doing it and
started doing doughnuts through the infield and stupid stuff like
that. It just irritated the hell out of me. I finally got to do it
the way I meant to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But fans on the track weren't supposed to be included.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came around three and people started running over there to
stop them,'' he said. ``That would have been a bad deal. They were
trying to beat the rush home, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The scary episode on his victory lap was nothing new for
Wallace, who barely escaped several close calls throughout the
500-lap race, the first Winston Cup event on a short track this
season.
</P>
<P>
   With only 26 laps remaining, Steve Park spun his No. 1 Chevy
into the wall in turn 2, giving the leaders a final pit stop.
Wallace, who led 425 laps, entered pit road with the lead and left
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett lost third place to Martin after his right-front
tire changer had problems during the pit stop. Jarrett was forced
to take only two tires and never threatened after the restart on
lap 482.
</P>
<P>
   That left a two-car duel. Martin attempted to pass three times
in the final 18 laps. His best opportunity came with four laps
left, when Wallace nearly rear-ended the lapped car of rookie
Buckshot Jones of Tucker, who had slowed on the backstretch. But
Wallace squeezed by Jones' No. 00 Pontiac, but not before taking a
tap in the rear from Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark was so strong at the end I didn't know if I was going to
hold him off or not,'' Wallace said. ``It was just a lapped car at
that point, and the lapped cars were racing the leaders pretty
hard. I just had to make a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to go around the top side, but (Jones) looked like
he was going to the bottom or the top. ... As I was going to the
top, Mark was going to fly underneath me. I pulled back down so
abruptly that Mark ended up tapping me in the rear a little bit. It
was a real tight deal. It was pretty hairy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hairiest scene came with 160 laps remaining. As the
leaders left turns 1 and 2, the lapped car of Jerry Nadeau spun out
and into the outside wall. Wallace exited before Nadeau's No. 9
Ford started collecting cars, but rookie Tony Stewart and Jeff
Gordon, who were running second and third at the time,
respectively, weren't as fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who had won four spring races in a row at Bristol, took
the brunt of the damage. Robert Pressley's No. 77 Ford smashed the
front of Gordon's No. 24 Chevy. Stewart spun out and nearly missed
the accident, but Ricky Craven's No. 58 Ford hit the rear of his
No. 20 Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   Both Stewart and Gordon made three pit stops during the 10-lap
caution, and they returned at 13th and 14th, respectively, at the
restart with 150 laps remaining. Stewart's problems got worse 41
laps later, however, when he bumped Mike Skinner's No. 31 Chevy,
cutting Stewart's left rear tire. Stewart had to make an
unscheduled pit stop and lost two laps.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart later regained a lap, but finished 15th. Gordon
rebounded to finish sixth, behind Martin, Jarrett, John Andretti
and Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy that caused half the yellows today finally took us
out,'' Stewart said. ``(Nadeau) was bound and determined he was
going to crash some good cars and he did. By the time I saw
everything, and it's hard when you're behind other cars, all I saw
was the No. 9 car sideways _ I think for the third time during the
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Gordon weren't the only contenders who were hurt by
lapped cars. During the 248th lap, Pressley spun out on the
backstretch and took out Bobby Labonte, who entered the race
trailing points leader Burton by only two points. Labonte's No. 18
Pontiac sustained significant damage and he finished 37th, 29 laps
behind the top 10 finishing cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just a victim of circumstance,'' Labonte said. ``It
seems like everytime we come to Bristol we have something like that
happen. We were running good. That's short-track racing and that's
Bristol for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte fell to third in points, 105 behind Burton. Jarrett took
over second, while Wallace jumped to eighth, trailing Burton by
173.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
