<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLDRAFT-KICKERS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Late rounds ideal for special teams
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the past five years, a period encompassing all the
seven-round drafts in NFL history, only five kickers and six
punters have been selected. But that doesn't mean teams aren't
taking plenty of special-teams players.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of the salary cap, every team needs some cheap
laborers, so clubs must be more selective even on their late-round
picks. Those sixth- and seventh-rounders usually make the roster
and are expected to contribute immediately by playing special
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can find in the late rounds an offensive lineman or
maybe a tight end who's able to deep-snap or a receiver with
potential as a return guy, it gives you an edge,'' New Orleans
special teams coach Bobby April said. ``If there's an exceptional
return man, you might see him go even higher.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case in '98, when the Atlanta Falcons used a
fourth-round pick to take Tim Dwight, the mighty-mite return
specialist. In retrospect, it was one of the best ``value'' choices
of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The top returners in the '99 draft _ wide receivers Torry Holt
(North Carolina State), David Boston (Ohio State) and Troy Edwards
(Louisiana Tech) and tailback Kevin Faulk (LSU) _ are standouts as
well at their primary positions and will be off the board after the
second round. But scouts also are aware of middle- and
late-rounders with special-teams prowess.
</P>
<P>
   One AFC Central team lists Florida fullback Terry Jackson among
the top all-around special teams players in this draft. Michigan
State safety Sorie Kanu lacks speed and has battled knee problems,
but is superb on kick coverage units. Texas offensive tackle Jay
Humphrey is just an average blocker but a solid deep-snapper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father has preached to me that the more you can do, the
more reason a team has to keep you around,'' said Humphrey, the son
of former Kansas City center Tom Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   That said, it's a player who does just one thing but does it
well who figures to be the first special-teams player selected.
Kansas State's Martin Gramatica may be one of the premier kicking
prospects of this decade, and could be chosen as high as the third
or fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has an extremely strong leg, and when you look at his size,
you wonder where (the power) is coming from,'' said Chiefs
personnel director Terry Bradway. ``He gives you an added weapon of
field position.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
