<HEADER>
A4038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-ROPES12-C     04-11 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-ROPES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gruesome twosome tees off first
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ On Sunday, golfers all over the country squeezed
in 18 holes and lunch before the Masters leaders teed off.
</P>
<P>
   So did Bob Tway and Trevor Immelman. Only they played Augusta
National.
</P>
<P>
   Off in the first twosome of the day, Tway, the former PGA champ
who grew up in Marietta, and Immelman, the young South African
amateur, played a relaxed, almost obligatory round. They seemed in
a different time zone than the guys 4 1/2 hours behind and 17 shots
ahead of them. As a small knot of loyal family members and friends
watched, they played past blithely curious spectators who seemed a
little surprised to see them appear out of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   A few steps behind the lawn mowers, hole cutters and leaf
blowers, Tway and Immelman teed off at 10:30 a.m., the first of 28
twosomes. There were more people in the gift shop than on the first
tee.
</P>
<P>
   The players chatted as they headed up the first fairway. As this
field's rabbits, the course stretched out before them. No waits on
any tee. No fairway divots. No spike marks.
</P>
<P>
   Both bogeyed the first hole.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of many firsts. First in the azaleas was
Immelman on No. 2, en route to the first unplayable lie of the day
and the first double bogey of the Masters final round.
</P>
<P>
   With Tway squinting like Chipper Jones and Immelman looking as
if he might cry, the two struggled. Immelman was 5-over after 4
holes, eliciting the first crowd murmur of the day when his iron
into No. 4 dropped like a dead bird, 40 yards short of the green.
</P>
<P>
   Tway, continuing his weeklong frustrating story line, couldn't
get a putt to drop. The first cheer of the day erupted behind them
when Mark Brooks birdied.
</P>
<P>
   Their supporters didn't feel too great, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are just getting through today,'' said Jim
Ferguson, a neighbor of Tway's in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not much fun to be in last place,'' added Kaye Anderson,
Tway's mother, who lives in Marietta. Only a low number today would
vault him into the top 16 and ensure an invitation back to Augusta
next year. So at this point, all he was playing for was more prize
money and, like Immelman, pride.
</P>
<P>
   But only the weather heated up, as the sun burned through and
the occasional whiff of Coppertone drifted through the crowds near
the popular observation points. Some people watched absent-mindedly
over their course maps, as they figured out what group they really
wanted to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Fans had clustered there for hours, so Tammie Tway couldn't see
all her husband's shots. But the views were still a lot better than
when he played with David Duval the first two rounds, and wide open
compared to 13 years ago, when Tway played in front of a charging
Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cheers were so loud that day,'' she recalled. ``And then
when they'd post his score, there'd be another roar.''
</P>
<P>
   A smattering of applause greeted Immelman's short birdie putt on
No. 7, the group's first red number of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Johan Immelman thought the early pairing would help his
19-year-old son. If he put up a good score, he might make up six
shots and become the low amateur. But by No. 13, Johan had recorded
26 putts by Trevor on a crumpled slip of paper, a measure of his
misery. He certainly wouldn't make the midnight Masters telecast in
Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   From watching TV, Johan Immelman knew huge crowds surrounded the
Masters leaders. He didn't expect anyone to be out this early, but
then again, he didn't expect the thousands of fans who show up for
the practice rounds. ``It's phenomenal,'' he said. ``It's really
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment wasn't returned by diehard Masters fans. Seeing
Tway and Immelman approach was a little like watching the warm-up
band at a general admission concert. Spectators had to get there
early to save a good spot, but they didn't come to see these guys
play.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the 18th green looked ghostly, with few fans dotting
the ocean of chairs. In 22 years seated pin-high, Dee Kiefer can't
remember a memorable shot by the earliest arrivals. Her record was
safe as Tway parred for a 74 and Immelman bogeyed for 79.
</P>
<P>
   To see good golf, said the bank vice president from Indiana,
``We've still got a long way to go.'' She patted a bag under her
seat. ``I just want to get all my snacks ready so I don't have to
leave after this.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
