<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4045 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI &LR;      04-11 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Monday, April
12, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   RIVER (Seattle) _ Two majestic Washington rivers engulfed in
political controversies will be named among the top ten most
endangered rivers Monday in America by a national environmental
group.
</P>
<P>
   By Heath Foser. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER (Seattle) _ Most University of Washington undergrads
toil for two nail-biting years before they can even apply for
admission to the highly competitive Computer Science and
Engineering Department. But in a bid to lure superstar high school
seniors to the UW instead of losing them such as MIT or Stanford,
the university will now let a few outstanding freshmen directly
into the major.
</P>
<P>
   By Ruth Schubert. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN (Seattle) _ The latest rage in Japan, we learn,
