<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4046 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-MOTHER-ART-     04-11 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-MOTHER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AFTERMATH OF TRAGEDY, A VICTIM'S MOTHER FINDS FINDS HERSELF ON
CENTER STAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Kadiadou Diallo is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since the Feb. 4 killing of her son Amadou in a
barrage of 41 police bullets, Kadiadou Diallo has made a journey
that has taken her further than the 4,300 miles from her home in
the West African nation of Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   A graceful and disarmingly slight woman, she has gone from
paralyzed public grief to telegenic celebrity. The bereaved mother
who collapsed not long ago on the gritty pavement at the scene of
the Bronx shooting has proved to be an engaging public presence who
blossoms in front of a microphone. A virtual stranger, she sails
serenely through New York City's choppy political waters.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo is not the first grief-stricken relative to be
propelled into the public eye _ and into the embrace of
politicians, would-be candidates and high-profile lawyers _ by the
violent death of a loved one.
</P>
<P>
   But she has proved to be the most adept in recent memory at
translating a personal loss into more universal terms, demanding
answers and accountability for the death of her son while avoiding
the pitfalls of racially divisive rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really is a star,'' said Ken Sunshine, a political
consultant working with a coalition of political, business and
labor groups that came together in the wake of the Diallo shooting
to criticize the Police Department and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knew,'' added Sunshine, ``that the mother was so
media-attractive and articulate?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo, who spent six days in the city in early February
and returned only on March 31 for a second visit, shrugs off the
notion that she is a figurehead at the prow of a nascent national
movement focusing on the mistreatment of blacks and other minority
groups by the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a symbol; Amadou is the symbol,'' the 39-year-old
businesswoman said last week, as she shuttled from one public
appearance to another in the black limousine that the Rev. Al
Sharpton and his Harlem-based National Action Network put at her
disposal.
</P>
<P>
   But her new friends in New York City would have it otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, who has acted as adviser, scheduler and companion to
the Diallo family from the start, said he planned to take Mrs.
Diallo on the road to as many as 16 cities as his rallying point
for a national protest against police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, they made their first foray outside New York City
to test Mrs. Diallo's potential as a national icon, appearing with
the Rev. Jesse Jackson at the weekly meeting of his Operation
PUSH/Rainbow Coalition in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo, who sat solemnly with other family members through
several standing ovations, was the main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Diallo case is the caboose of a long train of abuses,''
Jackson said, and Mrs. Diallo, he added, can serve ``to mobilize a
national consciousness'' about police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo responded that she was simply a mother who had lost
her son. ``I don't care if you call it politics,'' she said. ``I
have to cry out.''
</P>
<P>
   A grieving mother will no doubt evoke general sympathy around
the country, and Mrs. Diallo may even come to be a recognizable
symbol in other cities of black grievances against police officers.
But her iconic status may also prove to be a purely New York City
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Mrs. Diallo has framed her son's death, putting it
into the context of the historic struggle for justice of black
people in America, has a very deep emotional appeal in a city with
lots of African-Americans and people of African and Caribbean
descent,'' said J. Phillip Thompson, a political science professor
at Columbia University. ``Here you have a woman who symbolizes the
motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   But another large source of her appeal is entirely local. Mrs.
Diallo is admired because she is perceived to have stood up to the
mayor ``at a time when many people in the African-American
community feel like their own leaders have not stood up,'' Thompson
added.
</P>
<P>
   Others in New York have stood up to the city in the aftermath of
a personal tragedy: Iris Baez, whose son, Anthony, died in a
confrontation with the police in the Bronx in 1994, and Cedric
Sandiford, who survived a brutal racial attack in Howard Beach,
Queens, in 1986. But as prominent as they became in a brief
political season, none evoked such broad-ranged sympathy as Mrs.
Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   The intense public spotlight on Mrs. Diallo has revealed a
determined woman who can toss off a sound-bite _ ``Amadou's blood
will feed the battle for justice,'' is one she delivered recently _
and also hold her own as an inspirational speaker in front of a
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need people to come more and more, without any difference
of races and religions, because we need each other to have
strength,'' she said last week before a mostly black audience in
midtown Manhattan. ``We know what is happening is not right, but
they have the power. But God has his own power. We don't want any
violence. We need to go with dignity and pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo said she had not been coached by anyone and uttered
whatever came to her mind at the time of an interview or public
address. Sharpton, she added, simply shows her the schedule of
appearances he has arranged and tells her to ``think what you want
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said it was her decision alone, and not Sharpton's, to
refuse the city's initial offer of financial support and to refuse
to meet Giuliani, who has since complained that people around Mrs.
Diallo blocked such a meeting ``for cynical political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
