A4047 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-CONFLICTS-KA     04-11 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-CONFLICTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFLICTS NOT STRETCHING MILITARY TO BREAKING POINT _ YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this age of America as superpower without peer, the American
military insists it must possess the might to win two full-scale
wars at once.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for anything less, Defense Secretary William Cohen
stated in a 1997 report, invites ``opportunism (where) an aggressor
in one region might be tempted to take advantage when U.S. forces
are heavily committed elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   And although the attacks in Yugoslavia and Iraq do not yet meet
the Pentagon's idea of a major war, every sortie flown and each
missile launched pushes America's military closer to its limits.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, flights bringing relief supplies to Kosovar refugees
or whisking those exiles out of the region further tax American
military wherewithal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're starting to see things stretched pretty thin,'' said
Harold Rood, a professor of international strategic studies at
Claremont McKenna College near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, experts say, is not that the United States is too
weak to _ if pressed _ pummel the Yugoslav army. Serbia, after all,
is smaller in size, population and wealth than Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, analysts see a small but growing risk that U.S. forces
could find themselves shorthanded if trouble cropped up elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The American missions over the Balkans and Middle East occur
against a backdrop of significant budget cuts. Since the
dissolution of the Soviet Union, the number of fighter aircraft had
been cut by a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made ourselves vulnerable across the board,'' said
retired Army Col. Harry Summers, a fellow at the U.S. Army War
College and conservative newspaper columnist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we suddenly have a flareup in North Korea, we'll have a
hard time mustering the forces we need there.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, military leaders say they have enough firepower to
attack the armies of Slobodan Milosevic and Saddam Hussein while
guarding against even more serious challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. aircraft in theater is nothing near the total aircraft or
military capability we have today,'' said Air Force Maj. Gen.
Charles Wald. ``We still have a significant amount of forces and
reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO commanders have asked for even more than the 600 or so
aircraft now flying over Yugoslavia. The Pentagon, which has
committed about 275 Air Force planes, is dispatching 13 more
stealth fighters, five more B-1 bombers and 24 tank-killing Apache
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many billion-dollar chess pieces, aircraft carriers are
being shifted from one sea to the next so American commanders can
keep forces poised on active, and potential, battlefronts.
</P>
<P>
   The Kitty Hawk is steaming from off the coast of northeast Asia
to the Persian Gulf. The Theodore Roosevelt, in turn, has left the
gulf to lend its 75 aircraft to the Kosovo buildup.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the 48 KC-135 tanker planes from McConnell Air
Force Base near Wichita have taken part in Operation Allied Storm,
including the in-air refueling of the first combat flights of B-2
stealth bombers out of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the number of military flights ranges from two to three
times as much as in peacetime. But, said Maj. Steve Christy at
Scott Air Force Base in southern Illinois, the military is geared
for such fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the pattern that we have some times that are
busier than others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The humanitarian demands of supplying or evacuating Kosovar
refugees also have meant fewer transports available to shift the
Apache helicopters from Germany to Albania, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Air Force is fast running out of its air-launched
cruise missiles _ reserves have fallen below 100 _ and no assembly
line is in place to crank out replacements.
</P>
<P>
   After NATO joined the fight over Kosovo, American patrols
enforcing no-fly zones over Iraq dropped off. Soon F-15 and F-16
fighter jets and three electronic warfare aircraft were moved from
bases in Turkey to positions in Italy, according to The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Such shortages prompt some critics to suggest that the United
States more selectively entangle itself in military missions _ or
start asking taxpayers to pay for a larger war machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to have this standoff kind of war, you better
supply the sort of weapons needed to do it,'' said Elaine Donnelly,
president of the conservative Center for Military Readiness.
``Right now, we're not doing enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the crumbling of the Soviet Union, no military has rivaled
the United States. It boasts more than 4,000 aircraft, with more on
the drawing boards. No other country has an aircraft carrier as
large as the smallest of America's fleet of 12. The defense budget
consumes more than $260 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Even with that, military mechanics have begun to cannibalize
aging aircraft for spare parts. Because crews need time for
training and leave, the Navy can rarely count on deploying even
half its carrier force at once. And although America increasingly
patrols the world, it accounts for only about 30 percent of the
planet's military spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not hard to get overstretched when all your enemies are
on the other side of the world,'' said Loren Thompson, a defense
analyst with the Lexington Institute. ``I know that's making a vice
out of a virtue, but it's still an efficiency problem.''
</P>
<P>
   That means that instead of launching air attacks from home bases
_ the B-2 bombers that fly from Whiteman Air Force Base mark a
small and rare exception _ the United States must send aircraft
carriers to hot spots or count on allies to share their airstrips.
The latter alternative has proved more troublesome lately as Turkey
and Saudi Arabia have balked at air strikes launched from their
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said most scenarios call for some long-term presence of
American forces in Kosovo once the fighting stops, meaning fewer
military resources to patrol the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that the lingering effects of entanglements elsewhere
are responsible for shortages in the Balkans now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still bombing Iraq eight years after Desert Storm. We're
still in Korea 40 years after that war,'' Thompson said. ``The
problem is we don't get wars over quickly anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
