u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-MOTHER-ART-     04-11 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-MOTHER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: political reasons.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm a woman, a mother, and I understand who he is,'' she said.
``I saw him on TV when I got here and he said the cops were good
cops. So with or without Reverend Al, I would say to the mayor the
same thing. He could not get to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo was thrust into the public eye five days after her
son, who was unarmed, was killed in the entranceway to his Bronx
apartment building. That day, her first in the city, she traveled
in a police van to the building and, in a searing scene captured by
television cameras, she crumpled to the ground, wailing ``Amadou,
Amadou.''
</P>
<P>
   Limp and weeping, she was half-carried through the bullet-pocked
doorway and out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   When she emerged 45 minutes later, her first words established
the themes for many of her later statements. She said forcefully
that her son came from ``a good family.'' Then she added, ``Justice
must be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, more than two months after the killing, Mrs. Diallo
and other relatives stress at every opportunity that theirs is a
family of means and education that counts itself a part of the
Guinean elite. The country's foreign minister is a close friend, as
are other officials. In one of the poorest countries of the world,
they have all the modern conveniences at home: satellite
television, fax machines, e-mail and cellular telephones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the way they first talked about Amadou, like he
is from a poor background,'' Mrs. Diallo complained in a recent
conversation. ``I want to correct this idea about our family. We
are educated.''
</P>
<P>
   She is the third of nine children of a Guinean civil servant and
his wife, who wanted all their children to get a university
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up with many Western ways,'' said Bobo Diallo, the
next-youngest after Mrs. Diallo. ``But our father raised us with
the idea that money is just something you use. You don't do just
anything for money.''
</P>
<P>
   Kadiadou Diallo, however, did not finish her schooling. She
married Saikou Amad Diallo at the age of 14. She was his second
wife. Her father set one strict condition for the marriage: Her new
husband had to send her to high school. When the couple moved to
Liberia, she attended a private school for several years where she
learned English.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo had four children _ Amadou was her eldest _ and
accompanied her husband to Singapore and Bangkok, Thailand, where
they ran a business importing gemstones from Africa. When they
divorced, in 1994, she remained for a time in Thailand, so her
children could continue studying in an international school where
classes were conducted in French and English.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo returned to Guinea two years ago, remarried last
fall and now is trying to set up a joint venture with an Australian
investor in the mining sector. (Her father and both her husbands
are named Diallo, but none are closely related.)
</P>
<P>
   Her former husband, who lives in Vietnam, has also been making
speeches and giving interviews in New York City but, without his
former wife's command of English and her ease in front of a
microphone, he has not matched her star status.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the interest in the photogenic Mrs. Diallo follows
a well-worn pattern in New York City. Politicians _ both in and out
of office, for purposes of self-interest and for loftier professed
goals _ have always embraced the grieving relatives of crime
victims or victims of police violence.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   It is rare that the relatives move beyond the embrace and become
players on their own. But it has happened.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Rosenbaum, whose brother, Yankel, was killed in
disturbances in the Crown Heights section of Brooklyn in 1991,
shuttled back and forth for years between his home in Australia and
New York City for the various trials and legal proceedings related
to the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mrs. Diallo, he started as a stranger to the city's
fractious political culture, but became a celebrity of sorts,
appearing on television shows and at public meetings. But
Rosenbaum, embraced by Orthodox Jewish groups in much the same way
that Mrs. Diallo has been embraced by Sharpton's organization,
plunged into the city's political wars.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum stridently attacked the mayor at the time, David
Dinkins, campaigned for Sen. Alfonse D'Amato in his tight
re-election battle and openly endorsed Giuliani, who was Dinkins'
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Diallo said she would not allow herself to be used in local
political contests. But the fact remains that Giuliani is likely to
run for the U.S. Senate next year and his response to the Diallo
shooting will be an issue, political veterans said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not naive, so she's got to understand she's already
become a player in an as-yet undeclared Senate race,'' said a
former city official who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``I've got to believe she's accepted that role.''
</P>
</TEXT>
