<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-BILL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLS WOULD LIMIT LAWSUITS OVER Y2K BUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Customers stacked up 20 deep in 1995 on the opening day of a
gourmet grocery in Warren, Mich., before finally walking out in a
huff.
</P>
<P>
   The swipe of a single credit card with a year 2000 expiration
date had crashed the Produce Palace's computer register, which was
high-tech but not Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   That made owner Mike Yarsike an early victim of the Y2K bug. He
settled for $260,000 from the cash register company after becoming
one of the first victims to file a Y2K lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But few others will have that option if some federal and state
lawmakers have their way.
</P>
<P>
   Laws proposed in Congress and 30 states, including Missouri and
Kansas, would limit the ability of consumers to sue over Y2K
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers fear Y2K problems could trip a landslide of lawsuits
costing as much as $3 trillion. In fact, by the end of this year
and the first quarter of next year, Y2K lawyers' fees could soar
three times as high as the cost of fixing the computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, more than 80 lawsuits have been filed and almost
800 are in the prefiling stage, said Lou Marcoccio, director of
research for the GartnerGroup of Stamford, Conn. Many of those are
class-action cases aimed at high-tech companies that, plaintiffs
contend, knew about the glitch but sold faulty software anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But small businesses also have been sued for anything from a
failure to supply parts to a customer to misrepresentation of their
year 2000 readiness.
</P>
<P>
   With so much money up for grabs, business owners hope lawmakers
can give them some common-sense protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses fear they are going to do everything they can to be
Y2K-compliant and yet they are going to be sucked into a litigation
black hole,'' said Dave Clark, a Y2K lawyer with Lathrop &AMP; Gage in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses want to be able to ``concentrate their resources on
fixing the Y2K problem and not get diverted by the litigation
explosion,'' said Jim Wooten, head of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce's Institute of Legal Reform.
</P>
<P>
   But many trial lawyers and consumer groups strongly oppose legal
protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the fear of being sued that forces people to do what
needs to be done,'' said James Love, director of Ralph Nader's
Consumer Project on Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mandell, president of the Association of Trial Lawyers of
America, sees any immunity as corporate favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   Grocer Yarsike pointed out that businesses that experience Y2K
problems need some recourse. If liability laws had been in place
when he had his troubles, Yarsike said, he would be bankrupt today.
</P>
<P>
   The limited-immunity proposals in Congress are being pushed
aggressively by the Information Technology Association of America,
which represents such firms as IBM, Microsoft Corp. and AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   One bill approved by the Senate Judiciary Committee last month
would create a 90-day grace period for companies to fix computer
problems. It would encourage alternatives to lawsuits, limit
class-action cases and provide immunity to companies making
``reasonable'' efforts to solve their computer bugs.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, introduced by Sen. Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican,
and Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a California Democrat, also would cap
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is expected to reach the floor of the Senate soon,
where it may face opposition from the Clinton administration and
many Democrats who have expressed concern about curbing the right
to sue for damages.
</P>
<P>
   None of the proposed legislation would block lawsuits completely
or provide immunity in personal-injury cases.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Kansas and Missouri legislators have joined 28
other states and the District of Columbia in crafting Y2K immunity
legislation, although it is not moving as quickly as in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas House Bill 2185, introduced by Rep. Kenny Wilk, a Lansing
Republican, would allow a 60-day grace period for companies. It
also excludes class-action suits and limits Y2K awards to actual
damages.
</P>
<P>
   But that bill and House Bill 2281, introduced by Rep. Michael
O'Neal, a Hutchinson Republican, have little support so far.
O'Neal's bill helps protect the state and its employees from being
sued because of computer glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers think state law may already provide enough
protection. Dan Stanley, secretary of the Department of
Administration, isn't sure and has asked Attorney General Carla
Stovall to review the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, Senate Bill 482 protects small businesses with
fewer than 50 employees from class-action suits and provides
protections similar to those in proposed federal legislation.
Pushed by the Missouri Chamber of Commerce, the bill has received
little support, said its sponsor, Sen. Francis Flotron, a
Chesterfield Republican.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 978 protects the state from lawsuits, but Attorney
General Jay Nixon already has ruled the state is protected under
existing law. The bill is not on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas and Missouri sponsors of some of the languishing bills
aren't too concerned _ federal legislation would offer adequate
immunity, they say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
