<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech graduate plays role in Duval's slip
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jack Carswell was minding his business, reveling in
David Duval's third birdie in four holes and walking to the right
of the 11th fairway when he got up close and personal with the 63rd
Masters. Duval's errant drive flew right and bounced once into the
gallery _ and smack into Carswell's back.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Carswell, Georgia Tech class of '66, meet David Duval,
four-time Tech All-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have known what it was if everybody wasn't yelling,
`Fore!''' said Carswell, an Augustan who wore a 1990 Georgia Tech
national football championship hat. ``I'd have thought somebody
bumped me. I just covered my head and felt it hit me in the back.
No big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for Carswell, perhaps, but definitely for Duval. When
Duval's second shot was blown left by the wind, it bounced into the
water alongside the green. That led to a double-bogey 6 and
triggered Duval's erratic back nine that cost him any shot at the
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry now that I stopped it,'' Carswell said after
watching Duval go into the water. ``The ball might've rolled a
little farther. Might not be in the water.'' Get back, Jack. Not
your fault.
</P>
<P>
   Tough day for Woods
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, who opened the day in the mix at 2 under, took
himself out of contention early with a bogey on the first hole and
a double-bogey on the par-4 No. 5 en route to a front-nine score of
40. And this from the 1997 champion who spoke Saturday of shooting
in the low 30s to put pressure on the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   First Woods' putting failed him, then the rest of his game
followed. He battled to make pars. On No. 8 _ where he took an 8 in
Thursday's opening round when he hit into the bushes on the left of
the fairway _ Woods hit his tee shot into the bushes and trees on
the right. Like Thursday, his second shot hit a tree _ actually,
two trees _ and caromed about 20 feet to the right.
</P>
<P>
   He blasted out across the fairway, behind the mounds that tower
over the left of the left side of the green. He missed a par putt
and dropped to his knees. He made a bogey on the hole to drop to 1
over. Finally, he closed the front with his fourth bogey in nine
holes as his putting continued to be erratic.
</P>
<P>
   About those greens
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated with his inability to manage an under-par round for
the first time in his past 12 rounds at Augusta National, Atlanta's
Billy Andrade left the course Sunday calling several greens ``a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   While Andrade spoke after a 75 for a 7-over 295, Jeff Sluman
walked by and reaffirmed the tricked-up theme, saying, ``Anybody
seen Mickey Mouse?''
</P>
<P>
   After regrouping from a start in which he bogeyed three of his
first five holes Thursday, Andrade played solidly until bogeys at
the 17th and 18th Sunday. Combining gusting wind and rock-hard
greens, Andrade said conditions were ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrade said ``17 is a joke if you don't hit it in the left
rough off the tee. ... I don't mind greens playing tough, but when
you can't stop a 9-iron or a wedge, what's the point?''
</P>
<P>
   Among the amateurs
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kuchar's queasy Masters ended with a disappointing 78,
eliminating any chance of keeping his title of low amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar began the day one shot behind playing partner Tom
McKnight and one up on Spaniard Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who shot 73 to finish at 7-over 295, won the sterling
silver cup given to the low amateur. McKnight finished at 9-over
297, Kuchar at 11-over 299. The other amateur who made the cut,
South African Trevor Immelmman, was at 17-over 305.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough coming in here feeling so poorly. It was unlucky,
but I just tried to go on from there,'' said Kuchar, who has had
flu-like symptoms for better than a week. ``Today really showed
that I haven't been practicing. My game's not in proper
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar's undoing was a triple-bogey 8 on No. 13 (drive in the
pine straw, lay up, water, chip long, three putts).
</P>
<P>
   Next, Kuchar said, is about three weeks worth of makeup work at
Georgia Tech. Then he has to figure some way to qualify for next
year's Masters. ``Plan A is to do well in the U.S. Open (top 16
qualify for the next Masters). Plan B is to win the U.S. Amateur
(the runner-up also makes it).''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, the British amateur champion, became the first European
to gain the low-amateur honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it makes Spain proud,'' said Garcia, whose round
included four birdies. ``And I played a good round in the most
difficult of our four days here. It's exciting to know I'm the
first from Europe to win low amateur at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot in my first Masters. I learned you have to
have a lot of patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc. ...
</P>
<P>
   Having clinched the low-amateur finish, Garcia appeared on the
practice putting green to wish fellow Spaniard Jose Maria Olazabal
good luck. ... Tom Lehman closed with a 75 and called the course
``harder by far than TPC (Sawgrass). This course is a lot scarier.
We've never played Augusta before where you've had to bounce over
the ledges.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Jack Wilkinson, Steve Hummer, Glenn Sheeley,
Curtis Bunn and the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
