</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-LEDE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olazabal the new Master
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ On a wild, windy day at Augusta National Golf
Club on Sunday, as contenders regularly blew off the leaderboard
and succombed to rock-hard greens, Jose Maria Olazabal steadied
himself to recapture a dream.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Spaniard held off a charge from Greg Norman and
Davis Love III for a closing 71, a 72-hole score of 8-under-par 280
and a second green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago Olazabal couldn't walk without severe pain, let
alone play golf, because of arthritis in his feet and back
problems. Today he's again the Masters champion, and the
satisfaction is deeper than the hole his career once occupied.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at my lowest, I never thought about this happening
again,'' an emotional Olazabal said. ``I thought I would never play
golf again. To be right here standing in front of you with a green
jacket, it's an achievement that I didn't even dream about.''
</P>
<P>
   While the duel was often Olazabal and Norman, Love, with a 71,
managed to sneak in for second place at 6-under 282 by hanging in
on the back nine. Chipping in from 25 feet at the par-3 16th, Love
matched his runnerup finish to Ben Crenshaw in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   While the 44-year-old Norman, clearly the crowd favorite, again
failed to win, finishing second at the Masters for the fourth time
(5-under 283) on a closing 73, he redeemed himself from the
collapse of 1996. After eagling the 13th and briefly holding the
lead there until Olazabal knocked in a birdie on top of him, Norman
bogeyed 14 and 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a successful week and a sad week all rolled
up in one,'' said Norman, who underwent shoulder surgery last year.
``I feel I'm back in the position where I can contend again, but
obviously, there's the sadness of not winning.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point five-way tie existed for the lead. With greens
unable to hold shots and a gusting wind that made it nearly
impossible to judge ball flight and carry, Olazabal's consistency
was nothing short of masterful. If he halted Norman's momentum at
the 13th, he made his own by birdieing the 16th and then making a
fantastic par at the 17th, pushing his lead to a valuable two shots
on the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be a tough day, especially when I got
to the clubhouse and saw how hard the wind was blowing,'' Olazabal
said.
</P>
<P>
   After hooking his tee shot at the 17th, Olazabal said if he
could get a par, ``I knew the jacket should be mine.''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, seeking a 12th win in his last 35 events, was a
Sunday factor, but settled for a tie for sixth after
double-bogeying the 11th hole with a second shot to the water. His
70, one of only seven rounds under par Sunday, was the low score of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods shot a front-nine 40 and disappeared with a 75,
tying for 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Completing the huge day for Spain, 19-year-old Sergio Garcia
finished as low amateur at 7-over 295.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
