</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT_nyt </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 ALBRIGHT IN BRUSSELS TO BOLSTER UNITY IN By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ On her first visit to NATO since NATO forces
began bombing Yugoslavia on March 24, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright arrived here Sunday night for a gathering of foreign
ministers designed to show unity in the 19-member alliance as it
pursues its air campaign against Slobodan Milosevic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to belie the assertions of Yugoslav leaders that NATO
will soon weary of the air campaign over their nation, officials
said the alliance would meet Monday to reaffirm demands that
include Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, withdraw his troops from
Kosovo and allow the return of ethnic Albanian refugees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Albright insisted that, despite efforts of Milosevic to splinter
NATO, the alliance was ``wedge proof'' and had been galvanized by
his forced expulsions of hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanian
refugees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On French television Sunday, the foreign minister, Hubert
Vedrine, said the time had come to consider the shape of a
political settlement for Kosovo and that the Russians must be
involved in the outcome.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have entered a phase where there is a need for preparation,
a reflections, a consultation on what is to follow,'' Vedrine said.
In line with French policy that favors using the United Nations,
Vedrine suggested that the international security force envisioned
to bring refugees back to Kosovo should be drawn up ``within the
framework of the United Nations.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He added that it was essential to have Russia involved in a
political settlement of Kosovo and in the security force.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Previous plans spoke almost exclusively of a NATO force,'' he
said. ``The Russians could perhaps join a force that was fixed,
decided and determined within the framework of the United
Nations.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials traveling with Albright said that since Vedrine
stipulated that the political outcome in Kosovo must conform to the
demands laid out by NATO, including the withdrawal of Yugoslav
troops, they did not interpret Vedrine's comments as waywardness.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Albright is scheduled to meet with the Russian foreign minister,
Igor Ivanov, in Oslo Tuesday. The secretary said Russia could play
a ``useful role,'' but she said they still needed to get
``re-engaged.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have remained adamant in their opposition to the
NATO bombing, and under pressure from strong pro-Serbian sentiment
in the Russian parliament, Ivanov has issued almost daily
statements against the alliance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, President Boris Yeltsin of Russia said that if NATO
sent ground troops to Kosovo to ``make it their protectorate, we
cannot allow this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Clinton administration would accept a
partition of Kosovo as part of a political settlement, Albright
said it was ``premature'' to talk about such questions. But she
said that the she was not opposed to ``arrangements'' being made
for Serbs to have access to the ``holy places'' that are important
to them.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some officials have postulated that one of the aims of the
forced expulsions of ethnic Albanians was to allow Milosevic to
bargain with the West over keeping the parts of Kosovo that hold
Serbian Orthodox shrines and giving the rest to ethnic Albanians.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the public acknowledgment in the last few days that the air
campaign would continue for at least a number of weeks and perhaps
longer, NATO officials have been monitoring public opinion in
Europe very closely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of the atrocities against the ethnic Albanians by &QL; 
Milosevic, public opinion has become increasingly supportive of the
bombing raids, officials said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In France and Britain, public sentiment has surged in favor of
the NATO actions and in France more than 70 percent of the people
say they support the bombing in which their pilots and aircraft are
playing a significant role.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the public is less enthusiastic, but the German
foreign minister, Joachim Fischer, has taken the strongest stand
against Milosevic of any of the Europeans.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other alliance members were reported to be staying firm although
how long sentiment would hold in Italy and Greece was problematic,
officials said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greece, traditionally sympathetic to the Serbs, did not ask NATO
for a pause in the bombing campaign in respect of Orthodox Easter.
Albright is scheduled to meet with the Greek foreign minister,
George Papendreau, to urge him to keep with the NATO aerial
campaign.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The meeting at NATO headquarters will be the first to include
the three new members _ Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic _
who joined the alliance last month. Violent street demonstrations
against the air assaults in Prague, the capital of the Czech
Republic, added some nervousness in the Czech government toward the
bombing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
