<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARCRIMES-TRIBUNAL-55     04-11 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARCRIMES-TRIBUNAL-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIAN CROAT LEADER GOES ON TRIAL FOR WAR CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ An influential Bosnian Croat
politician, a former ally of the Croatian president, goes on trial
on Monday before the international war crimes tribunal here, a
process that is likely to throw the spotlight on Croatia's role in
the Bosnia conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The politician, Dario Kordic, is accused of a series of war
crimes against Muslims in Bosnia. He was the leader of the Bosnian
wing of the political party of Croatia's president, Franjo Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was a key political figure when not only Serbia but
also Croatia instigated violence in Bosnia, prosecutors in The
Hague considered Kordic one of the most wanted war crimes suspects
on the Croatian side of the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Kordic was charged in 1995 with ordering the expulsion and
killing of scores of Muslim families living in the Lasva Valley of
central Bosnia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have argued that the expulsions were part of a
strategy to empty the valley of its Muslim inhabitants and give the
party affiliated with Tudjman control over a central part of
Bosnia. They say the ultimate political and military goal was to
annex part of Bosnia to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   The Kordic trial begins as the trial of another senior Bosnian
Croat, Gen. Tihomir Blaskic, is going on at the tribunal. Blaskic,
who was charged in some of the same incidents as Kordic, gave
himself up to the tribunal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Kordic surrendered to the tribunal in October 1997 after intense
pressure from American and European governments on Tudjman.
Washington went as far as blocking loans to Croatia from the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   For months after his indictment and until his surrender, Kordic
enjoyed high-level protection and lived in an apartment in Zagreb,
the Croatian capital, which was reportedly owned by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with trial here see it as significant that even
now Kordic's defense lawyers are being paid for by the Croatian
government. In most cases so far, the tribunal itself pays for
defense counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators and diplomats say Kordic knew a great deal about
the inner workings of the Zagreb government during the Bosnia war.
As part of the inner political inner circle, he could offer
important evidence about the Croatian leaders who were behind
Zagreb's version of ``ethnic cleansing'' in Bosnia, the strategy of
getting rid of Muslim, Serbian and other non-Croatian civilians by
terrorizing them.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say Tudjman himself is under investigation for his
role in a range of ethnic cleansing incidents during the war that
followed the breakup of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kordic may also have information about secret meetings that
Tudjman is said to have had with Slobodan Milosevic, at the time
the president of Serbia and now the president of Yugoslavia. At
those meetings, during the Bosnian war, the two leaders are alleged
to have discussed the carving up of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   A military commander, Mario Cerkez, will be tried with Kordic.
Cerkez, 40, a Bosnian Croat, was the local military commander of
the so-called Croatian Defense Council in the town of Vitez and one
of Blaskic's subordinates. He surrendered to the tribunal at the
same time as Kordic.
</P>
<P>
   Cerkez, too, has been charged with war crimes. Both men have
pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The indictment charges that Kordic bears leadership
responsibility for planning and overseeing attacks on Bosnian
Muslims from 1991 to 1994. It says that Cerkez, as commander of the
Vitez brigade, ``was directly and actively involved in the
wide-scale persecution of Bosnian Muslim civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment places Kordic at the forefront of the strategy to
drive out non-Croats and join part of Bosnia to Croatia. It says he
signed orders and documents and ``exercised power, command and
authority in, over and through the Croatian Defense Council.''
</P>
<P>
   After the defense council was set up in 1992, Kordic became its
vice president, acting as the chief executive and defense authority
in an area that called itself the Croatian Republic of
Herceg-Bosna, though it was never recognized by the international
community.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says that as ``part of the highest circle of
political and military leaders,'' Kordic made policy and strategic
decisions, negotiated or countermanded cease-fire agreements,
issued military orders, dressed in military attire and decided if
relief convoys or U.N. vehicles could pass through checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Cerkez, a former car mechanic and factory worker, became
commander of the Bosnian Croat brigade of Vitez in 1992. He is held
responsible for a series of crimes carried out by his subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, both men hold direct responsibility
in the terror campaign in which Muslim civilians in towns or
neighborhoods ``with no military significance'' were driven from
their homes, often at night, and their houses and mosques were
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Many were imprisoned in squalid detention camps where they were
beaten, sexually assaulted and wounded. A former prison commander,
Zlatko Aleksovski, is standing trial separately at the tribunal in
connection with Lasva Valley crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment of Kordic and Cerkez cites more than a dozen
towns and villages of the Lasva Valley where Muslim neighborhoods
were terrorized.
</P>
<P>
   But the most notorious assault happened in Ahmici in 1993.
Members of a British contingent of U.N. peacekeepers have told the
tribunal that more than 100 Muslims, including women, children and
old people were killed in Ahmici, some burned in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the Croatian campaign against the
Muslim population of central Bosnia took place on such a large
scale that by 1994 the Bosnian Muslim population ''was
substantially reduced and relocated.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial opening Monday will be the eighth trial going on at
the U.N. criminal tribunal for the former Yugoslavia. It has 26
people in detention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
