<HEADER>
A4078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-NYT &LR;      04-11 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-RELIGION,
KOSOVO-JOURNALIST)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Del.)  
 U.S. STRATEGISTS OPENLY DISCUSS ISSUE OF G.I.s ON YUGOSLAV SOIL  
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT,(js) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and
senior administration officials talked more openly Sunday about the
possibility that U.S. ground troops would be sent into Kosovo, but
insisted again that President Clinton had no intention for now of
sending soldiers to do battle there.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials also strongly suggested that Yugoslavia
would have to oust President Slobodan Milosevic for the nation to
have any hope of restoring normal relations with its European
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, Gen. Henry H. Shelton, said that NATO planners
estimated last year that as many as 200,000 soldiers from the
United States and other NATO members would be needed for a ground
war, and that they might have to invade Serb-dominated areas of
Yugoslavia north of Kosovo, the southern province in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't excluded using more than one point of entry or
numerous points of entry,'' he said on the ABC News program ``This
Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton nodded his head when asked if NATO would consider
entering Kosovo from the north _ after a NATO invasion of other,
more northern regions of Serbia, the major entity in Yugoslavia.
``If in fact that was required,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton and the senior administration officials making the
rounds of the Sunday television talk shows appeared eager to do
what they have not done in the past _ leave open the possibility
that ground troops would be needed to finish a war that has so far
proved unwinnable from the air.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the NBC News program ``Meet the Press,'' John
Podesta, Clinton's chief of staff, said that ``the president does
not have the intention to use ground troops'' but that ``those
plans and assessments could be updated quickly if we decide to do
that _ need to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The new willingness to discuss the possibility of using ground
troops was in part a response to criticism from Congress, where
prominent lawmakers from both parties have called on the
administration to prepare detailed plans for use of a ground force
in Kosovo. Clinton is scheduled to meet with congressional leaders
on Monday to discuss the U.S.-led military campaign against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on ``Meet the Press,'' Sen. Joseph R. Biden of
Delaware, the ranking Democrat on the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, said, ``I don't think we should have ever taken ground
troops off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, Republican of Arizona and member of the Armed
Services Committee, said on ``Fox News Sunday'' that he was urging
Senate leaders to prepare a resolution that ``authorizes the
president to use all means necessary in order to achieve the stated
goals,'' including ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. George A. Joulwan, who retired in 1997 as NATO's military
commander, suggested on the same program that NATO ground troops
might even be needed to march on Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, in
order ``to stop this terrible unacceptable behavior by Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Clinton administration officials questioned whether the
United States could ever again negotiate with Milosevic after the
reports of mass killings, rapes and other atrocities by Serbian
forces in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
