<SLUG> BC-FAA-Y2K-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA TO FLIERS: LET THE MILLENNIUM BEGIN! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo.)  (jw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A large portion of the air traffic control system
appeared to function smoothly early Sunday as the clocks in radar
centers around Colorado rolled over from Dec. 31, 1999, to Jan. 1,
2000, in a dress rehearsal for New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy New Year! It worked!'' proclaimed Jane Garvey, the
administrator of the Federal Aviation Administration, at a news
conference at the Denver Terminal Radar Approach Control, just
outside Denver International Airport, at 1:30 a.m. Sunday. The
conference followed the three-hour drill observed by aviation
executives and two hours of briefings for them.
</P>
<P>
   The test was designed to ensure that the system's computers
could handle the so-called Year 2000 problem, the breakdowns that
could arise because some computers cannot recognize that the
two-digit date ``00'' means 2000. Some computer experts and
aviation officials have warned against flying on Jan. 1, out of
concern that air traffic systems around the world would be
unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garvey said the test showed that the system ``worked as it
should, smoothly, efficiently and safely.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rollover was blissfully boring. While all airline
flights in the region were handled by the usual computer system
running the real date, a backup system, advanced to New Year's Eve,
shadowed each move to assure that it could track everything in
flight and perform all other critical functions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, an FAA plane was under the guidance of an air
traffic controller whose radios and radar screens were controlled
by the system that rolled over to 2000. It took a determined effort
by that pilot and controller to wring any measure of drama from
their exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Convair three-niner,'' called the air traffic controller to
the pilot, who was heading for the Denver airport. ``Denver
Approach,'' she identified herself. ``Time is one minute prior to
entering the new millennium in our test system. How do you read
this transmission?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Loud and clear,'' said the pilot, ``and if we disappear off
the screen, it means we went into the next millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger, three-niner,'' replied the controller, a laugh in her
voice, but, as she and the pilot suspected, the plane did not
disappear from the controller's radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, a twin-engine propeller model, proceeded uneventfully
toward Runway 16, just as the blip proceeded uneventfully across
the controller's radar screen. Seconds later, after the rollover of
dozens of clocks, including one in the computer that controls the
radio frequencies, the controller asked the pilot again if he had
heard her transmission. ``It went right through the sound barrier
very nicely,'' he assured her.
</P>
<P>
   The agency will take several days to study the data, but on
first blush, the test seemed to meet the goal set by Ray Long, who
directs the agency's Year 2000 preparedness program.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were fairly confident, having run most of the major
elements of the test on four occasions in the last few months.
These tests followed what they described as an exhaustive
examination of their computer systems, which include software
written by generations of programmers long gone, some of it in
computer languages now mostly forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   On the real New Year's Eve, Ms. Garvey and Long plan to leave a
Washington airport in the afternoon, on a westbound commercial
flight, and to be aloft at midnight Greenwich Mean Time, the
standard that air traffic control computers use around the United
States. They plan to choose a flight that will land at a major
airport somewhere in mid-continent, and have a news conference,
late in the evening of Dec. 31, local time, and then to board
another flight for California, which will have them aloft at
midnight local time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It truly happens at midnight Universal Coordinated Time,''
Long said, using an aviation term for Greenwich Mean Time, which
comes at 7 P.M. Eastern time. ``There's still a regular midnight,''
he said, referring to local time. And among the public, he said,
``There's still some anxiety over that. But we'll know at 7
o'clock.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to Long, of 423 systems that are considered ``mission
critical,'' or required for safe functioning of the system, 151
required modification.
</P>
<P>
   Officials discovered that many of the agency's systems were
``date dumb.'' For example, they found that among their 627
computer systems, there were 11,027 ``interfaces,'' or places where
the systems passed information among them. But only 485 of the
interfaces handle date-related information, and of those, only 119,
or about 1 percent, had a date problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through a great deal of testing, a great deal of
analysis, a lot of work, a lot of manpower, to pretty much prove to
the world what we knew all along, that there's not a lot of risk in
our system,'' said Jim May, the test manager.
</P>
<P>
   Officials picked Denver for the test because its backup
computers could be isolated from computers handling ``live''
traffic, and have their clocks advanced to New Year's Eve. A second
set of controllers sat at the second set of screens, monitored all
``live'' conversations, and made corresponding entries on their
isolated system, as if they had been controlling the planes.
</P>
<P>
   A second FAA aircraft, a Lear Jet, flew a circuitous route to
test equipment in several places. And United Airlines filed flight
plans for 14 flights, leaving shortly before midnight or shortly
after, to see if the FAA computers advanced to New Year's Eve could
accept the requests and issue clearances smoothly by the standard
electronic route to United's main computer in Chicago and then to
computer printers at boarding gates, where pilots pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate test a month ago, the agency successfully issued
such a clearance directly into the on-board computer of one of
United's most advanced planes, a Boeing 747-400, with that plane's
on-board clock advanced to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That plane was on the ground, and in the test here, with the
exception of the conversations with the Convair, handling of
aircraft in flight was not affected, officials stressed.
</P>
<P>
   By last month, the FAA had finished devising a Y2K fix _ or
determined that none was necessary _ for every critical system, and
for 218 noncritical ones, and had tested all the fixes. Sunday's
test was of many of those computer systems linked together in their
normal working environment. The last step, about 88 percent
complete and expected to continue until June, Mr. Long said, is to
install all the fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Renovations on critical systems are running slightly behind
renovations on noncritical ones, however.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
