<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA PLACED ON DISABLED LIST UNTIL APRIL 25  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The New York Mets announced on Sunday, as expected,
that the All-Star catcher Mike Piazza would be placed on the 15-day
disabled list with a sprained right knee. The move will be
retroactive to Saturday, and Piazza will be eligible to come off
the disabled list April 25.
</P>
<P>
   The team received good news Sunday about the condition of
Piazza's knee, which he injured running the bases here Friday
night. Dr. David Altchek, a team physician, examined Piazza and
said the sprain involved just the medial collateral ligament, and
not the posterior cruciate ligament as well.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Piazza said he was ``really, really frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not want to go on the disabled list,'' Piazza said by
telephone from Manhattan, where he underwent a magnetic resonance
imaging test on Saturday. ``I felt like I could play in a week. But
the doctor made it clear that if I do play and run the bases and
have to suddenly change direction, it could be a full tear. And
that would mean surgery. Considering that possibility, I figure
this is for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Piazza, who signed a seven-year contract worth
$91 million in the off season, had been on the disabled list just
once in his six-plus seasons in the major leagues, when he tore a
thumb ligament in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with the decision in a way,'' Piazza said. ``I
hyperflexed my same knee on a slide in 1996 and kept playing on it
and it kind of hung around for a month. This way, hopefully it will
be 100 percent when I come back. But I'm not happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who said he would be at Shea Stadium for the Mets' home
opener on Monday, was batting .429 in five games with a pair of
home runs and eight runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was swinging the bat well when it happened, so
it's very frustrating,'' he said. ``But when I'm eligible to come
off the disabled list, I'll be ready to play. I'll be able to jump
right back in without missing a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who also face the loss of the starter Rick Reed to a
strained Achilles' tendon, are expected to make one or more
personnel moves before Monday's game. The utility players Melvin
Mora, Craig Paquette and Shane Halter and the minor league catchers
Pedro Grifol and Jerry Brooks are among those who could be called
up. The team's best catching prospect, Vance Wilson, took a ball
off his left arm last week and will not be able to play for several
more days.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets may also decide they want to recall a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever moves the Mets make, Manager Bobby Valentine said he
could see Piazza putting in time at first base when he returns, to
lessen the strain on his knee.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza did not sound very comfortable with the idea of playing
anywhere but behind the plate. But he said he would do whatever the
team wanted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
