<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRS Doing Fewer Audits On High-Income Returns
</P>
<P>
   Tax returns from Americans earning more than $100,000 a year and
from the biggest corporations are increasingly escaping the
scrutiny of the Internal Revenue Service, new agency figures show.
</P>
<P>
   While audit rates over all have fallen substantially since 1986,
some tax experts and former IRS officials are worried that the
steepening decline in high-income and corporate audits may mean
that reporting by many of the richest taxpayers is now effectively
on an honor system, inviting abuses.
</P>
<P>
   3 Industries Pass Year 2000 Tests
</P>
<P>
   Three major industries racing to prepare their computers for the
Year 2000 _ securities, the electric utilities and the airlines _
all passed important testing milestones recently.
</P>
<P>
   A trickle of new lawsuits in recent months is expanding the
legal landscape of the Year 2000 problem. But so far, the cases
offer little support for the dire predictions that courts will be
choked by litigation over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   A Magazine for the Tourist Class
</P>
<P>
   The two mainstay travel magazines _ Travel &AMP; Leisure and Conde
Nast Traveler _ are dealing with a feisty newcomer: Arthur
Frommer's Budget Travel, a quarterly that has met with such
newsstand success that it will be published bimonthly starting in
September. Its newsstand sales _ twice those of its larger cousins
_ made the stalwarts take note. But it was Frommer's editor's
letter in his premiere issue last summer that really stung. Frommer
proclaimed that current travel magazines are ``elitist, haughty and
high-society.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft to Offer Audio Alternative
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is expected on Tuesday to enter the battle to deliver
music to consumers who download files through the Internet,
according to people close to the company. The software giant's MS
Audio 4.0 will be an alternative to the popular MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia Defense Is Rejected
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia, Italy's No. 1 phone company, has failed to win
shareholder support for fending off Olivetti's $65 billion
unsolicited offer. The rejection opens the way for foreign rivals
to join the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   China Sets Up Commerce Web Site
</P>
<P>
   In the first official foray into electronic commerce for the
world's fastest-growing economy, the government of China has set up
an Internet site intended to help its companies market goods to
American corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Fan Material Finds Niche Online
</P>
<P>
   Although online entertainment programming initially turned out
to be a disappointment for many companies, there is a resurgence of
entertainment-based material on the Internet. Rather than original
programming, though, the biggest successes are the most derivative:
online extensions of music, TV shows and movies that fans already
know.
</P>
<P>
   A Century of Advertising
</P>
<P>
   In an exercise likely to cause lively debate, the trade
publication Advertising Age is offering a special retrospective
issue devoted to what the editors label ``the advertising
century,'' listing the top icons, campaigns and people. First among
the issue's most contentious designations would undoubtedly be the
declaration of the Marlboro Man as first on a list of the top 10
icons, followed by figures like Ronald McDonald, the Jolly Green
Giant, Betty Crocker and the Energizer bunny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
