<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-BOS &LR;      04-11 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEEING KOSOVARS ARE FORCED TO HIDE IN HILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHARR MOUNTAINS, Macedonia-Yugoslavia Border _ With official
border crossings closed, thousands of refugees took to these
snow-capped mountains on foot Sunday in a desperate and dangerous
attempt to flee Serbian terror within Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers feared as many as 200,000 refugees could be hiding
in the forests and mountains of Kosovo along the Macedonian and
Albanian borders, as Serbs continue to prevent them from leaving
and have even laid land mines to ensure they do not.
</P>
<P>
   At least 500 refugees were seized here in the last two days by
Macedonian police patrolling the mountain passes. Police officials
said they then bused the hungry and cold families to refugee camps
ringed with barbed wire inside Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Shivering, distraught, and with two broken ankles, Urmije
Selmani, 30, survived a three-day ordeal escaping through the
mountains. She told of her ordeal from a stretcher in an emergency
medical tent at the border Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no other way. I was dead if I stayed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers estimate thousands have have sneaked through the
steep inclines and snowdrifts of the mountain range, and are hiding
in the homes of ethnic Albanian families in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   But the ethnic Albanians who manage to escape to Macedonia have
walked into a country that is growing increasingly resentful of the
wave of refugees and fearful that the new arrivals will upset the
delicate ethnic equation here.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians represent about 25 percent of Macedonia's
population of 2 million people. Many Macedonians, whose numbers are
about 65 percent Slavic and 5 percent Serbian, fear that the
Albanian government has designs to use the refugee crisis to carve
out a ``greater Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   That specter threatens to ignite even more tensions in the
already blazing Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Angira Shuku, 28, was waiting on the road just over the mountain
pass to see if her father and mother, who she last heard from a
week ago inside the Kosovo capital of Pristina, might have tried to
flee through the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray they make it through,'' she said, casting her gaze
toward the distant mountains. ``But the truth is they will face the
same hatred here in Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Macedonian government, which is eager to join the European
Union, has been careful not to go too far in mistreating the
fleeing Albanians, but observers have described it as brutal. There
have been steady reports of Macedonian police and army troops
beating ethnic Albanians and, on some occasions, turning them back
at the border. The Macedonian government outraged humanitarian aid
workers when they rounded up tens of thousands of refugees in the
middle of the night last week and, without telling them where they
were being taken, began busing them to neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces built a string of refugee camps in Macedonia and
have had a heavy presence protecting the Albanians. But Sunday,
NATO announced it would begin a gradual withdrawal, touching off
panic among the refugees that they would be left at the hands of
the Macedonian police.
</P>
<P>
   The resentment among the Macedonians ripples beyond the camps
and into the community.
</P>
<P>
   There is anti-Albanian graffiti throughout the Slavic and
Serbian neighborhoods of the capital, Skopje, and plenty of hateful
insults are muttered on the street.
</P>
<P>
   In the stone churches that dot the remote villages in the
foothills here, Serbian and Macedonian Christians attended
candlelight Easter services Sunday. They seemed indifferent to the
fact that, less than a mile into the mountains, Albanians were
running for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Athanasius's Eastern Orthodox Church in the village of
Leshok, Bishop Kiril said, ``The Albanians cannot stay here. They
talk openly of a greater Albania and this is what they want to
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about how he balanced the Christian belief in helping
those in need with his views on the refugees, Bishop Kiril said,
``My message Monday is to help those who may be fleeing. Accept
them, clothe them, feed them for three days. After that, ask them
where they want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   During a party held by the bishop for the wealthy Christians who
own vacation homes in the mountains, families sat at a large picnic
table covered with a linen tablecloth and discussed the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Dragalubia Lazov, general manager of the Macedonian lottery,
said, ``This is like the US getting 25 million refugees dropped on
its doorstep in one week. What do you think the reaction would
be?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are coming. You see it on the street and in our towns. We
feel surrounded,'' he added. ``I am very afraid of this. If they
try for a greater Albania, there will be a war. That is a
certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   The small Slavic village is indeed surrounded by three towns
overwhelmingly populated by ethnic Albanians. Minarets of mosques
tower over a sprawling community in Leshok that is now expanding
even further as thousands of refugees from Kosovo are packing into
the homes of extended family members. Some houses have as many as
50 people living in three bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Macedonians argue that the arrival of 130,000 refugees into
their struggling country, which broke off from Yugoslavia in 1992,
will not only put strain on the economy but has already increased
the Albanian proportion here by almost 7 percent overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian demographic specialists said that if the refugees
stay, their percentage of the population would surge to a majority
in less than a generation because of the high Albanian birth rate.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hill from the church and the bishop's party, a group of
village men were drinking beer and pulling hard on cigarettes in
the town common.
</P>
<P>
   Yastre Popouski, 44, a foreman at a textile factory and a father
of two teenagers, said, ``The refugees have to go back to Kosovo.
Why should we let them come in here and take the jobs from our
kids?''
</P>
<P>
   On the same hillside between the church and the town common, an
Albanian refugee from Kosovo was hiding in the office of a friend
who is a physician. The refugee, a 52-year-old professor of
economics, said he was frightened that he may be discovered by the
Macedonians and asked that his identity not be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   He said ethnic Albanians in Macedonia, where members of his
extended family live, face institutionalized racism, economic
inequality, and pure hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were given the same rights, there would be no need for a
greater Albania,'' he said. ``But we cannot live like that. We will
not live like that. And that is why we will see more violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
