<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAP-OPERA-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      04-11 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAP-OPERA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL HUSTON GUIDES HIP-HOP TOWARD OPERATIC LEAPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hip-hop magazines like Blaze are hailing Prince Paul as a
genius, an Einstein. Another magazine, Request, says his new CD,
``Prince Among Thieves,'' is ``a social and musical masterwork.''
Vibe calls ``Prince Among Thieves'' ``the world's first
hip-hopera.''
</P>
<P>
   A rap opera? Well, that may be hyperbole. ``Prince Among
Thieves'' is an album, and it has never been performed live.
``Anything I do, they give it a name,'' said the artist, Paul
Huston, a shy, visionary 31-year-old from Long Island. ``I call it
a movie on wax.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was writing a real cool movie'' or ``an
adult-kiddie record,'' he said. ``You listen to the story, and it
goes into song.''
</P>
<P>
   As a producer he has helped transform rap from a relatively
simple form, with a steady beat and bragging lyrics about ghetto
life and female treachery, into something more complex. In rap the
producer is the one who creates the soundtrack, as opposed to the
M.C. or the rapper who composes the rhymes.
</P>
<P>
   Huston's albums, particularly those he produced for the
groundbreaking group De La Soul, are zany collages of skits,
parodies, music from the television show ``Spiderman'' and samples
of anything from classical music to language-instruction records.
Now he is advancing the form further.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``Prince Among Thieves'' different from most rap CDs
is that it has a story line running all the way through it. Like
the librettos of many great operas, this one seems stark in
synopsis.
</P>
<P>
   The CD begins with sirens and a minor-key melody. Tariq, a
would-be rapper played by Breeze, and his best friend, True, played
by Sha, both relative unknowns, have shot each other after an
argument, and as Tariq lies wounded, his life flashes before him.
</P>
<P>
   His problems began when he needed $1,000 to finish a rap demo to
show to RZA of Wu-Tang Clan, and True enticed him into selling
drugs for Large (played by the rapper Chubb Rock), a billionaire
crime boss who also deals in ``loan sharking, gambling, nuclear
weapons,'' says Tariq. As Tariq earns money selling crack, his
customers are played by the comedian Chris Rock and members of De
La Soul. Tariq buys a gun from Crazy Lou (played by Kool Keith, or
Dr. Octagon). Crazy Lou ``was an ex-Marine captain who got
discharged for sexual misconduct with a deadly weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Count Mackula, ``a pimp supreme,'' (played by the sex
symbol rapper, Big Daddy Kane) lures Tariq to an assignation with a
prostitute: ``Hoes come a dime a dozen, baby.'' While Tariq is in
flagrante delicto, the police storm in. ``Anything you say can be
twisted around and used against you,'' says a cop, played by
Everlast from the Irish rap group House of Pain.
</P>
<P>
   Tariq's mother sends a minister to bail him out. After his
release, he overhears True rapping to his music; he has hijacked
the record contract that Tariq was working toward. Like many
operas, ``Prince Among Thieves'' ends in tragedy. Tariq dies, but
True survives because he had on a bullet-proof vest.
</P>
<P>
   And like much gangsta rap, it is a cautionary tale but also a
satire of hip-hop machismo and a sly comment on how art and life
intersect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prince Among Thieves'' is filled with Huston's distinctive
touches, samples from Beethoven's Fifth Symphony, ``Popeye the
Sailor Man'' and voices pushed through distorting filters. It
sounds, Blaze magazine said, like ``Jonathan Swift smoked a blunt
with Rodgers and Hammerstein, then invited the Juice Crew over.''
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop magazines often show Prince Paul dressed in a typical
rapper's tough-guy garb, leather jacket, wool cap or baseball cap
on backward and dark glasses. But he usually wears jeans and a
button-down-collar shirt. Despite the lyrics on his albums, Huston
says his mother, Peggy, does not drink, smoke or swear. She likes
her son's music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you want to move,'' she said. But the lyrics? ``If I
hear a bad word, I just blank it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Huston is temporarily at home with his mother and his son, Paul
Jr., 7, in a pleasant house in Massapequa until he buys a place by
himself. He went to court to gain custody of Paul from the boy's
mother, his former girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge looked at me, a young, black, male rapper,'' Huston
said, and awarded custody of the boy to his mother. Huston
appealed. Paul Jr. now spends the school year with his father and
summers with his mother in the South. Huston has a steady
girlfriend, Atiya Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   He composes tracks in the basement. ``He's like some kid who
must have spent some time in his bedroom at home coming up with
really strange fantasies,'' said Monica Lynch, president of Tommy
Boy Music, which released ``Prince Among Thieves.'' His love of
music came from his father, Thomas, now dead, who was a truck
driver and jazz enthusiast, Huston said. His mother was a home
health aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father would take him to the park and put the radio in the
carriage,'' Mrs. Huston said. ``He used to play him `Moody's Mood
for Love.''' Huston has woven that jazz favorite into ``Prince
Among Thieves'' ``as a dedication,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Huston had little music training. ``I took clarinet in the
second grade for one month,'' he said. But ``I had a mean
teacher,'' and he quit. Today he mostly plays the synthesizer.
</P>
<P>
   Young Paul's idol was George Clinton, leader of the
unpredictable Parliament-Funkadelic. He watched the D.J.'s in the
park on Great Neck Road. He saw Biz Markie, sometimes called ``the
human beat box'' for his vocal imitations of percussion sounds, and
Rakim, known for his complex, metaphoric rhymes. In junior high
Paul became a D.J. at parties. He used samples from old records,
``Batman'' and ``The Dating Game'' theme and played records
backward and with the turntable upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The three members of De La Soul graduated from Amityville High
School, though Huston didn't know them there. ``You'd think, `Yeah,
this is one of Amityville's best,''' said Kelvin Mercer, who is
Posdnous (that's ``soundsop'' backward) of De La Soul.
</P>
<P>
   At a housing project party in Brooklyn at which Huston was the
D.J., Daddy-O and Delite of of the hip-hop group Stetsasonic saw
him and were impressed enough to seek his services. They were
wearing spikes and leather, and he thought they intended to beat
him up. But eventually he produced the title track for their 1988
CD ``In Full Gear.'' When the members of Stetsasonic visited his
house, they told his mother he was a genius.
</P>
<P>
   Huston went to Five Towns College, a music school. ``A waste of
time,'' he said. Through his high school music teacher, who had
been a drummer with the Isley Brothers, he met Maseo, the D.J. for
De La Soul. Maseo introduced him to Posdnous and Trugoy,
(``yogurt'' backward) the Dove. They had the same visionary and
irreverent attitude toward rap as Huston did and were eager to
carry rap from the ghetto to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respected all those rappers,'' Posdnous said. ``But
obviously we were not seeing that every day growing up in Long
Island. There was so much to talk about instead of just drugging.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   De La Soul's first album, ``Three Feet High and Rising,''
produced by Huston in 1989, revolutionized rap. It had words from a
French language instruction record, along with a game show parody
with questions like, How many fibers in a shredded wheat biscuit?
and How many feathers on a Perdue chicken? It was probably the
first rap album to intersperse songs with skits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it would bug people out,'' Huston said. The album went
platinum.
</P>
<P>
   Huston worked on ``De La Soul Is Dead,'' released in 1991, which
went gold. De La Soul's ``Buhloone Mind State'' in 1993, which
Huston produced, won over critics but not the public. ``We were
beginning to take on more serious stakes,'' said Mercer. ``A lot of
rhymes were very complicated,'' he said, ``not tangible for the
average person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get our message to certain youth who needed to
hear it,'' he said. Huston bowed out of the group's next album,
``Stakes Is High.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My style has been quirky, they're maturing,'' Huston said.
``I'm still like the high school guy that puts something on the
door that will fall on your head. I had to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Wu-Tang Clan's producer, RZA, and the rappers Too
Poetic and Fruitkwan he formed the Gravediggaz, which released a
camp-horror album, ``Six Feet Deep,'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving De La Soul, ``I had this music nobody ever
liked,'' Huston said. He found a psychoanalysis self-help record
and made a CD, ``Psychoanalysis (What Is It?),'' in 1996. It
consists of rappers' raunchy dreams and fantasies with comments
from a psychoanalyst with a Viennese accent. ``It's a beautiful
night for a date rape,'' one line goes, ``a beautiful night for a
homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   The album is a macho fantasy. ``A lot of my friends I hang out
with, we're really nice guys,'' he said. ``We just took the
craziest people we knew, and we were going to make it 10 times
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a joke that went too far,'' Huston said. ``The next
thing, I'm getting write-ups about people getting shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that record was the end of my career,'' he added.
``Next thing, all the work comes in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Library of Congress asked to use the CD cover in its touring
exhibit ``Sigmund Freud: Conflict and Culture,'' which opens Sunday
at the Jewish Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychoanalysis'' also attracted Chris Rock's attention. ``He
really approaches it like a comedian,'' Rock said of Huston's work.
His recordings ``aren't just good rap albums, they're really
funny,'' Rock said.
</P>
<P>
   He asked Huston to produce his comedy album ``Roll With the
New,'' which won a Grammy in 1997. He is negotiating with Huston to
make a movie of ``Prince Among Thieves.''
</P>
<P>
   Huston's work is ``smart without being preachy,'' Rock said.
``He makes fun of that stuff all the time. It just seemed right up
my alley.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be a bond between the two men. ``One reason Chris
and I are friends is that we're both nerds,'' Huston said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
