<HEADER>
A4087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-ART-520&AMP;ADD     04-11 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WONDERTROSS PROBABLY OUT OF DERBY, BUT MANY OTHERS LOOKING TO GET
IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky._ Wondertross, the favorite who ran sixth in the
Blue Grass Stakes on Saturday, went to the hospital Sunday with a
case of colic that probably added him to the list of casualties for
the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But an even longer list of candidates for Louisville is growing,
because no dominant horse has emerged from this year's trials and
prep races. From California, from Arkansas, even from Dubai ,
3-year-old contenders are being primed for the trip of their lives,
suggesting a wide-open field that would have to be reduced to the
maximum number of 20 starters by Derby officials at Churchill
Downs.
</P>
<P>
   The newest star to rise toward the top of the list is Menifee,
who won the Blue Grass in the final strides over Cat Thief and
Vicar. He seems certain to head for the Kentucky Derby as one of
the favorites along with Prime Timber and General Challenge, the
stars of Bob Baffert's richly stocked West Coast barn.
</P>
<P>
   So another shootout appears likely between Baffert, who won the
last two runnings of the Kentucky Derby with Silver Charm and Real
Quiet, and Elliott Walden, whose Victory Gallop ran second in the
Derby and Preakness last year before snatching the Triple Crown
sweep away from Real Quiet in the Belmont Stakes. It is Walden who
stands in Baffert's path again this year as the trainer of Menifee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he came out of it in good shape,'' a beaming
Walden said Sunday morning outside Barn 36 at Keeneland. ``Now,
it's time to get ready for the Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee won the Blue Grass as the fourth choice in a strong
field of eight colts. It was his fourth victory in five starts, his
first around two turns, his first in a stakes race and his first in
a Grade I stakes.
</P>
<P>
   He is a sleek bay son of Harlan and the mare Anne Campbell, and
he is owned by his breeder, Arthur Hancock 3rd _ the elder son of
the legendary Bull Hancock of Claiborne Farm _ and Arthur Hancock's
longtime friend, Jimmy Stone, an oil and gas executive from New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no joy at Nick Zito's barn, where Wondertross was
moved from his stall at 8 a.m. to an equine clinic for treatment
for an intestinal inflammation. The colt lost the Florida Derby
last month by a nose to Vicar after a rousing rush to the wire, and
became an instant contender for the Kentucky Derby. But he never
got going in the Blue Grass and finished a badly beaten sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no excuse,'' said Jerry Bailey, his jockey. ``From
the gate to the wire, he was never in the race. It's the worst race
he's ever run.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito, in a more temperate mood, said after the race: ``I'm
confused. I don't know what happened. I'm totally mystified.''
</P>
<P>
   But this morning, Zito was guardedly optimistic about getting
his horse back on the Derby trail, saying: ``We left the barn last
night about 8 o'clock. He was kicking and bucking. I thought
everything was fine. This morning, we had to get him over to the
clinic. We hope to get him back quickly. If we can get him back on
the track and back to where he was, we'll see. But we have to take
one step at a time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zito was left with at least two potential starters for the
Derby: Adonis, who won the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct Saturday while
Wondertross was striking out at Keeneland, and Stephen Got Even,
who won the Turfway Stakes a week ago. The trainer also announced
that Jorge Chavez would continue to ride Adonis, and that Chris
McCarron would ride Stephen Got Even in the Triple Crown series.
</P>
<P>
   The list of horses trying to qualify for the Derby grew over the
weekend to somewhere between 20 and 30, meaning that prize money
already won would be invoked to determine who makes the cut.
</P>
<P>
   From the Blue Grass alone, the top five finishers were booked
for May 1 in Churchill Downs: Menifee, Cat Thief, Vicar, Kimberlite
Pipe and Lemon Drop Kid. From the West Coast, there were Baffert's
two stars plus a pair of fine fillies, Silverbulletday and
Excellent Meeting.
</P>
<P>
   From the Arkansas Derby there was the 30-1 winner, Valhol, who
somehow raced into prominence in his third start, and from Dubai
the highly regarded Worldly Manner, who hasn't raced since he won
the Del Mar Futurity last September.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas, the trainer of Cat Thief, put the Derby into
perspective: ``We don't have a great horse; just a good, solid
horse like so many other guys this year. We're not overpowering,
but neither is anybody else. There are no Spectacular Bids or
Seattle Slews out there this year.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
