<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4092 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS12-SIDE-CO     04-11 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS12-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once again, The Shark sinks to second
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ The moment was fleeting. Greg Norman led the
Masters by himself at Sunday's final round at Augusta National, an
eagle on No. 13 sending him to the top of the leaderboard and the
massive gallery into a frenzy. The view from there must have been
majestic. This lasted all of two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   His playing partner at the Masters was friend Jose Maria
Olazabal, who had led by a shot but then trailed by one when
Norman's 25-foot, right-to-left putt dropped. It was Olazabal's
turn, from 21 feet for a birdie and share of the lead, and he
nailed it. The Great White Shark's moment was over.
</P>
<P>
   And, essentially, so was his quest to earn the elusive green
jacket. Norman bogeyed the next hole and was unable to make a
birdie in the remaining four, dropping to third behind Davis Love
III and champion Olazabal, who finished at 8-under for the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It was a piercing defeat for Norman, who had a four-day total of
283, including Sunday's 73. But it was also rewarding. He had a
legitimate shot with five holes to play on the same course that
made him an international sympathetic figure. The 1996 meltdown was
that bad, one of the worst in majors history: squandering a
six-shot lead on the last day to Nick Faldo. But Sunday he did not
collapse. He was valiant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a successful week and a sad week all rolled up into
one,'' he said. ``I feel good I'm back where I know I can contend
again. This is not a heartbreak. I'd like to say I could've won. I
had my chances. I got my nose to the front, but not all the way
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``(So) this is easier to take,'' he added. ``Ninety-six was a
totally different animal - the tournament, the emotions, the way I
lost. I climbed a pretty good mountain today.''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking the confirmation of his physical recovery from
shoulder surgery and, most importantly, his mental strength. When
he finished Saturday one shot off the lead, the questions persisted
everywhere about his ability to hold up after having imploded on
the '96 Sunday. Norman answered them in impressive, if not
victorious, fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good with myself and what I did,'' he said.
``Don't take that the wrong way. I'm sad I lost. . . But don't make
a mountain out of a molehill on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: He lost, but it was more the course and Olazabal
beating him than himself.
</P>
<P>
   Norman did contribute, however. His tee shot on No. 14 hit a fan
and landed in the rough. His 7-iron second shot from 138 yards
carried to the back fringe of the green and he 3-putted for bogey -
his taste of first gone.
</P>
<P>
   Then Norman dropped to third when he made a six on the par-5 15.
Still, he held on to hope until the end, even after Olazabal
matched his par on a tough putt on 17, a green so slick Love called
it ``unplayable.'' Down two shots going to 18, Norman mused to
himself: ``If I make a 2 (on 18) like somebody else did to me, I
might still have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. Olazabal was unshakable. Norman embraced him when it
was over, a very different embrace from the one Faldo gave Norman
in '96. This time, the Shark, 44, had enough reason to talk of
playing into his 50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a warrior in that arena is what it's all about,'' he
said. ``It was an enormous emotional experience. . . I put
everything into perspective. The reality is that I came out, played
hard, but not well enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he enjoy golf more now that before the Masters, Norman,
victor in defeat, answered: ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
