<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4095 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS-     04-11 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS-ART-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN-AMERICANS PLAN TO JOIN THE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photos of Albanian-Americans who are volunteering for the
KLA are being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Majria Shala's favorite cousin drove her to
Kennedy International Airport for an Easter visit to Detroit, she
remembers him making a little joke: ``Maybe when you get back, I
will be gone to liberate Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shala was still in Michigan last Friday when her cousin,
Victor Ljekocag, called her on the phone. ``He said, `I'm going to
be a soldier,' '' Ms. Shala recalled Sunday. `` `I love my country.
If you want to see me, come Sunday at 1.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Ljekocag and about 300 other Albanian-Americans _ mostly
young men, and a handful of women _ formed ranks on a parking lot
in Yonkers, N.Y., dressed in newly bought camouflage fatigues
bearing the red-and-gold insignia of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteer soldiers _ who included a 17-year-old female high
school student from the Bronx and a 60-year-old man _ were to fly
from Kennedy International Airport this week to an undisclosed city
in Europe, and from there to training grounds in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian emigres say it is a story repeated in Albanian
communities in Europe since NATO started bombing Yugoslavia and the
Serbs drove hundreds of thousands of the ethnic Albanian majority
in Kosovo from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   While all the recruits in Yonkers say they have relatives in
Kosovo, many were born in the United States, and some have never
set foot in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shala and 15 or 16 relatives flew in early Sunday to see
Ljekocag off. `` We all tried to stop him,'' she said. `` But he's
doing it from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   As patriotic exhortations of Albanian-American leaders boomed
from loudspeakers, the recruits and the crush of their relatives
shivered in the raw chilly wind _ weather that seemed to match both
the fervor and sorrow in the air. One woman, her faced spotted with
rain and tears, spoke of her relatives on the way to the Balkans to
fight in the ranks of a rebel army that is heavily outgunned by the
Yugoslavs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One brother-in-law, three sons, my favorite uncle,'' she said.
``I don't know if they are coming back, but Milosevic is a Hitler,
this is another Holocaust. But it's happening now, in real life,
not on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   People around the country have felt revulsion at the
developments in Kosovo, but for Albanian-Americans _ many of whom
have family members in Kosovo _ these weeks have been the most
agonizing in a year of grief, since the undeclared war between
Serbian security forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army erupted in
March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The calls for volunteers to stave off the destruction of the
homeland began showing up in Albanian-language newspapers and radio
programs after the first NATO bombings three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to that time, the KLA wanted our money more,'' said Shaban
Brahimaj, a computer programmer who lives in the Bronx and is an
American citizen. ``However, now they are saying `Help our country
now or it will be never.' ''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is no way to tell whether these new recruits will ever
make it into Kosovo, or fight battles there. But the deep
attachment of Albanian-Americans to Albania itself, and by
extension to Kosovo, is evident.
</P>
<P>
   They say they had long sent money to the underground Albanian
government of the Serbian province, founded after Slobodan
Milosevic, now the Yugoslav president, stripped Kosovo of autonomy
in 1989 and ethnic Albanians were either fired from or quit their
state jobs. A parallel society emerged, in which Albanians ran
their own schools, hospitals and media, and a government-in-exile
ran the distribution of funds gathered abroad to fund Albanian
institutions in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Since the massacre of KLA fighters and their families in Kosovo
in March last year, which galvanized support for the previously
ragtag rebel army within Kosovo, the vast majority of expatriate
Albanians began supporting the guerrillas, too. The money enabled
the rebels to buy guns, and helped its ranks swell.
Albanian-American community leaders say there are about 500,000
people of Albanian descent in the United States, half in New York,
New Jersey and Connecticut. They are now donating tens of thousands
of dollars to the rebels, according to Hysni Syla, a KLA
representative for the United States and Canada. Those figures
could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, about 300 would-be soldiers gathered at a
catering hall in North Bergen, N.J., for the first meeting _ a kind
of strategy session and pep rally _ of the rebels' newest American
recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must fight the big beast!'' cried a man who said he
represented the guerrillas. ``We must liberate the motherland!
Today we are all Albanians in Kosovo!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We may die,'' shouted one man. ``But not Kosovo!''
</P>
<P>
   Many feel torn between their country overseas and their lives
and family here. Shaban Brahimaj, for one, has to support his
parents, wife, 5-year-old daughter and 7-year-old son, and a niece,
13, who is orphaned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't go there I would feel like a very bad person.''
</P>
<P>
   Brahimaj had volunteered for the KLA and the U.S. Army, planning
to choose the one that took him first. But last week, he received
calls from both. And Friday _ he said, with regret in his voice _
he had accepted the U.S. Army's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had doubts,'' he said of the KLA. ``Where are they going to
get guns? And believe me you need a little training.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we are not going to a wedding,'' said Agin Gjevukaj,
26, who is joining the KLA. His family left Kosovo when he was 16
and settled in the Bronx, where he found work making pizzas. Last
week, after 10 years as a pizza-maker, he baked his last pie, quit
his job and signed up to return to Kosovo as a guerrilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to war _ we'll be killed, some of us. I love my
country, and my people are very strong. I am very happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
