u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT &LR;      04-11 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ FLIRTS WITH PERFECTION AS YANKEES ROUT TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez blew hot air into his right hand
before every pitch on this chilly and nearly memorable day, staring
at catcher Jorge Posada with his serious brown eyes and focusing on
his next task.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez wanted everything to be perfect, from the warmth of
his hand to the kick of his leg to the delivery of his pitch.
Everything almost was.
</P>
<P>
   In weather better suited for football, Hernandez brought extra
drama to Yankee Stadium Sunday by retiring the first 19 Detroit
Tigers he faced. A walk to Gregg Jefferies stained the masterpiece
in the seventh inning, but Hernandez kept his no-hitter alive for
one more out. Then Tony Clark reached out and pulled an 0-2
fastball into shallow right field for Detroit's first hit.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez nodded as 32,398 fans cheered him, then blew on his
hand and went back to work. He lost the shutout, too, but the New
York Yankees' 11-2 victory was still something special.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was dominant, maybe as dominant as he was all last
year, and the Yankees, who received their 1998 World Series rings
before the rout, performed like a machine.
</P>
<P>
   Save those ring sizes, especially Hernandez'.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy can pitch,'' said Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim
manager. ``It ain't by mistake. The guy knows how to pitch. When
they're looking for the fastball, they get the breaking ball and
vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez proved Sunday that he might be even more confusing to
hitters now that he throws more changeups from different arm angles
to complement the fastballs and sinkers he uncorks from so many
angles. The Yankees proved that they were serious about defending
their title. Real serious. Sunday's emphatic victory was their
fifth in a row after a loss in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' determination showed in the way that Hernandez, who
prefers the tropical climate of his native Cuba, toyed with the
Tigers in 44-degree weather, striking out nine, walking just one
and giving up only two hits in his seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The determination also showed in the way the Yankees used their
patience and a sprinkling of well-timed hits _ they finished with
nine walks and nine hits _ to torch the Tigers' starter, Justin
Thompson. Derek Jeter homered, drove in three runs and scored three
runs, and Paul O'Neill also knocked in three.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Yankees took a 9-0 lead behind seven hits and six walks
after three innings, the attention shifted to the pitcher known as
El Duque _ and he put on a stylish show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about what was going on until later in the
game,'' said Hernandez, with Posada as his translator. ``I was
trying to get people out. I saw the crowd getting up and I was
getting pumped up. I wanted to do it, but it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a wild afternoon, reminiscent of another Sunday at
the Stadium: May 17, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of David Wells' perfect game last year in that
he was that sharp,'' David Cone said. ``I thought he was that good.
It was a classic try for a perfect game or a no-hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada, who caught Wells' perfect game, started thinking about
duplicating that perfection. When Hernandez was not in the
clubhouse keeping warm, Posada abandoned the superstitious ritual
of not speaking to the still-perfect pitcher and lectured him about
the hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted it,'' Posada said. ``It was amazing that I was
catching another one. I couldn't believe it. I was trying to call
the right pitches so he could get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez retired four of the first nine batters on strikeouts,
twice going to a 3-2 count before whiffing Damion Easley and Brian
Hunter. Scott Brosius glided to his left to snare Juan
Encarnacion's grounder to start the fourth and, after Hernandez
caught Easley gazing at another 3-2 pitch, the rumbling started in
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   When Hernandez climaxed the fifth by getting Bobby Higginson on
a gorgeous 3-2 changeup, the fans' excitement grew.
</P>
<P>
   After Chuck Knoblauch snared Deivi Cruz's liner on one hop and
Tino Martinez made a neat scoop on Knoblauch's one-bounce throw to
begin the sixth, the tension was palpable. Fans who had cellular
telephones started calling their friends. El Duque was cruising.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a pitching staff like ours, anything can happen,'' Jeter
said. ``He had it today. He could have pitched a no-hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hernandez struck out Encarnacion on an 0-2 changeup to
start the seventh, he fell behind, 2-0, to Jefferies. Hernandez
rebounded with a strike, but missed with a 3-1 pitch to end his
pursuit of perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The fans chanted ``Du-que, Du-que,'' trying to keep the faith
for a no-hitter. Although Hernandez went ahead of Clark, 0-2, his
fastball caught enough of the plate and Clark flicked it for a
clean single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to give the team a chance and me a chance to win,''
Hernandez said. ``I want to throw a no-hitter, but that's not the
main priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hernandez was casual during a news conference about
losing the no-hitter, he was more animated as he returned to the
clubhouse afterward. Hernandez said Clark hit a ``good fastball,''
then he stopped walking and mimicked Clark's swing, showing how the
first baseman had reached across the plate to pull the pitch.
Hernandez shook his head and shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see me clapping for myself just because I got a
hit,'' said Clark, who then saw Higginson follow with a run-scoring
double.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Tigers were too thrilled about their weekend trip to
New York. On Friday, Cone held them to one hit and one run in five
and one-third innings as the Yankees sailed, 12-3. On Saturday,
Roger Clemens held them to three hits over seven and two-thirds
innings in a 5-0 victory. But Sunday Hernandez might have been the
best of the imposing threesome.
</P>
<P>
   From Cone to Clemens to Hernandez. It made Detroit manager Larry
Parrish, whose team has lost five consecutive games, want to drive
the bus to the airport himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see somebody else play them right now,'' Parrish
said. ``I'm ready to get out of town.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
