</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS SHELL ALBANIAN VILLAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a government cease-fire called for the
Orthodox Easter weekend, Serbian forces shelled three villages in
northern Albania on Sunday. US officials in Washington, meanwhile,
gave their first hints that planning is under way for deployment of
allied ground troops into the region.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb artillery reportedly killed two civilians in Tropoje,
on the third day of fighting between Kosovar rebels and Serb forces
along the border with Albania. Yugoslav authorities accused Albania
of aiding the rebels, while Albanian leaders called on NATO to bomb
Serb positions on the border.
</P>
<P>
   In Yugoslavia, officials said a NATO missile fell on a densely
populated neighborhood in Novi Sad, the country's second-largest
city. No deaths or injuries were reported. In observance of the
religious holiday, NATO said it showed ``relative'' restraint in
the skies over Belgrade Sunday, while carrying out extensive
bombing in Kosovo. Kosovo is a province in Serbia, the dominant
republic in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William S. Cohen joined other Clinton
administration officials Sunday saying that, while he still
believes the war against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic can
be won from the air, a 1998 plan for a troop deployment exists and
could be activated ``fairly quickly'' if NATO generals request it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have an assessment that was done last fall, as far as what
it would take in a nonpermissive, or hostile environment, down to a
detailed plan . . . allowing the troops to go in,'' Cohen said on
ABC's ``This Week.'' ``So those plans could be updated fairly
quickly if such a request were ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with opinion polls that show growing public support for
ground troops, and facing the likelihood of an emotional debate in
Congress this week, the White House appeared to be laying the
groundwork Sunday for what could be a sustained, escalating, and
expensive involvement in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Other developments in the region Sunday included:
</P>
<P>
   -- &UR;  &LR; NATO officials in Brussels showed an aerial photograph of
what they said appeared to be freshly turned earth near Orahovac,
Kosovo. Colonel Konrad Fretag, a NATO spokesman, said it ``could
indicate the possibility of a mass grave site.''
</P>
<P>
   -- &UR;  &LR; International monitors likened a refugee camp, where Kosovo
Albanians live on a muddy field surrounded by armed guards, to a
``concentration camp.'' Macedonia's defense minister denied
allegations of abuse by guards and said his government was doing
the best it could with the flood of 130,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   -- &UR;  &LR; Yugoslavia's official news agency, Tanjug, said Serb forces
fought off a ``terrorist'' incursion into Kosovo on Saturday,
killing and wounding several rebels. The Kosovo Liberation Army
operates out of mountain camps across the border in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   -- &UR;  &LR; NATO's supreme commander, General Wesley Clark said the
alliance ``was sensitive'' to the observance of Orthodox Easter by
limiting bombing over Belgrade. Despite bad weather that forced
NATO to cancel 30 percent of its missions, spokesmen said bombs
struck a munitions dump, bridges, petroleum facilities, and Serb
forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   -- &UR;  &LR; Yugoslavia's ambasssador to the United Nations said it was
``out of the question'' that his government would permit
international peacekeepers into Kosovo as an occupation force.
Vladislav Jovanovic also denied US reports of rape camps in Kosovo
as ``an entirely outrageous accusation.''
</P>
<P>
   -- &UR;  &LR; A prominent opposition Serb journalist, Slavko Curuvija,
owner of the daily Dnevni Telegraf, was shot dead outside his home
in central Belgrade. Serbian police said Curuvija had been killed
``by unknown perpetrators.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright arrived Sunday night in
Brussels, where NATO's foreign ministers prepared to meet Monday.
They were expected to reaffirm the alliance's commitment to
continued airstrikes and to holding Milosevic accountable for the
plight of the ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the Serbian attack on Albanians in Kosovo means
fewer Serb troops will permitted to remain in the province than has
been previously discussed. In another signal that US policy could
shift, she also did not not rule out partitioning Kosovo as part of
a settlement _ as long as there were guarantees to protect Orthodox
holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, White House Chief of Staff John Podesta suggested
that Yugoslavia would have to replace Milosevic if it ever were to
become a member of the European community.
</P>
<P>
   ``To create a stable situation, it looks to me like they are
going to need a new leader,'' he said on ``Meet the Press.''
Podesta added, however, that NATO airstrikes were not intended to
oust Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Other administration officials also toured the Sunday talk shows
and insisted that the NATO air campaign, now in its third week and
about to be beefed up with an additional 82 US warplanes, was going
well and would succeed on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air campaign . . . is taking an ever-mounting toll on''
Milosevic's ``military machine,'' Clark, the NATO supreme
commander, said on ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming increasingly effective and more intense,'' he
said. ``I think we need to give the air campaign a chance to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   But several senators said US policymakers and generals are
making a serious strategic mistake if they reject the option of
using allied ground troops and have no contigency plans for a
deployment that logistically and politically could take months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's foolhardy to take the option off the table at the
outset,'' Senator John Kerry, a Massachusetts Democrat, said on
``Fox News Sunday.'' ``Now that doesn't mean that we will get to
the point that you have to use them. It may well be that if we're
preparing more visibly to use them, that we will come quicker to
some resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, a decorated Vietnam War veteran and a member of the
Foreign Relations Committee, said he spoke to national security
adviser Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger Saturday and urged the
administration to view the ground troops option as ``a realistic
possibility to achieve our objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain of Arizona, a Republican presidential
hopeful and former prisoner of war in Vietnam, called on
congressional leaders to put forward a resolution this week that
would authorize the president to use whatever means necessary,
including ground troops, to achieve victory in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that having such support from Congress would be
``very important,'' and that he expected Clinton to lobby lawmakers
for such a resolution in meetings over the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also said on ABC that he suspects ``we are going to find
more and more evidence of mass graves, mass executions, some pretty
horrific stories.''
</P>
<P>
   While Cohen said it remained up to NATO to make the ground
troops request, he and other administration officials indicated
such a deployment secretly has been part of the military equation
for months.
</P>
<P>
   General Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
said that based on an assessment made last year, a NATO ground
force could vary in size from 20,000 to ``a couple of hundred
thousand,'' depending on ``various conditions it would take to do
the job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The build-up of a force this size would depend on how many
entry points you used coming in'' to Kosovo, Shelton said on ``This
Week.'' ``And we haven't excluded using more than one point of
entry or numerous points of entry.''
</P>
<P>
   Podesta repeated the conditions for an end to NATO airstrikes:
Milosevic must remove his forces from Kosovo, allow refugees to
return, provide a degree of autonomy, and permit installation of an
international peacekeeping force. A partition of Kosovo ``is not on
the table,'' Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta also disclosed that the administration soon would seek
more money for the Defense Department through a supplemental budget
appropriation, but did not state a figure.
</P>
<P>
   Former vice president Dan Quayle, a Republican presidential
candidate, said Sunday the Clinton administration should pursue a
peaceful settlement in Kosovo as quickly as possible in order to
avoid more foreign-policy blunders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been thought out in the wrong way, we are a long way
down the wrong road, and there are no good options right now,''
Quayle said on ``Meet the Press.'' ``Hopefully we can get a
political settlement, we can get peace, so the Albanian Kosovars
can return to Kosovo. It has to be that way. The sooner, the
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
