</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REFORM TEST IN THE HOUSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, April 12:
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Washington Monday after two weeks off, Congress
faces debates over taxes, budgets, the minimum wage and Kosovo. But
the first priority for House members, beginning Wednesday, should
be to sign a petition demanding that Speaker Dennis Hastert
schedule a prompt vote on campaign finance reform. The petition
route has been forced by Hastert's repeated rejection of requests,
even from fellow Republicans, to schedule consideration of such
legislation rapidly enough for it to pass before the next election.
Many Republicans supporting reform are loath to join with Democrats
to challenge the speaker. But if they do not, its chances could
slip away.
</P>
<P>
   In his first months as speaker, Hastert has offered bland
promises of openness and cooperation with Democrats on the
legislative process. But whenever anyone asks him about campaign
finance reform, which commands overwhelming support in the House,
he shrugs and talks about the crowded Congressional calendar. In
fact, Congress has not done much this year and probably will not do
much until the summer, when it wrestles with appropriations bills.
The one area in which the speaker has set a frenetic pace is
fund-raising itself. He has harvested huge sums, and the money is
coming from lobbyists and special interests eager to influence
financial deregulation, health care and other items on the
Republican agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are raising money, too. A six-figure donation
earns an invitation to a ``retreat'' with the party's Congressional
leadership at the Kennedy compound in Hyannisport, Mass.
Fund-raising by presidential candidates from both parties is
already reaching into the tens of millions of dollars. By itself,
fund-raising is not going to be outlawed any time soon. But
Congress can pass the reform bill long advocated here, and
sponsored again by Reps. Christopher Shays, Republican of
Connecticut, and Martin Meehan, Democrat of Massachusetts. It would
ban open-ended party donations by corporations, unions and rich
individuals and the use of such money for partisan campaign ads at
election time by supposedly independent groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill passed the House last year, 252 to 179. It
commands even more support this year. But if it is not taken up in
the House before the Memorial Day recess, six weeks from now, it
could easily get pushed aside by budget and tax issues in the
summer. Hastert knows that to delay the bill is to deny its
chances. Wednesday marks the first day that lawmakers can sign the
petition to force the bill to the floor. Almost all  &QC; the House's
211 Democrats are said to be on board. If only some of the 54
Republicans on record as favoring the bill sign up, Hastert will
have to yield, as Newt Gingrich was forced to do last year.
</P>
<P>
   Shays, for party unity reasons, does not want to sign the
petition right now and confront the speaker. He thinks it would be
better to wait to see if Hastert brings the bill to the floor in
the next few weeks. But if Shays and other Republicans wait more
than a few days, they will be dooming the chances of the bill they
say they support.
</P>
<P>
   To walk away from this opportunity will consign voters to
another cycle of party fund-raising, corruption revelations and
voter cynicism. The House can do better, and it must. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
