<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS LOSE ANOTHER PLAYER, WIN ANOTHER GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Last season, the Montreal Expos were particularly
hard on the New York Mets. So far this year, the Mets again have
experienced tough going against Montreal, though not on the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   One week into the new season and it seems as if magnetic
resonance imaging tests have become a part of the Mets' daily
routine.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed, a 16-game winner last season, strained his left
Achilles' tendon here Sunday afternoon running out what should have
been a double in the Mets' 6-3 victory over the Expos. The
right-hander will undergo an MRI in Manhattan on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza underwent his own MRI in Manhattan on Saturday after
having sprained a knee ligament in a rundown here on Friday night.
The All-Star catcher will be out for at least two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And still the Mets headed home for the first time this season
firm in their belief that they had a good week. Taking five of
seven games on the road from the two low-budget teams that had
perplexed them last season _ the Florida Marlins and the Expos _
was enough to temper the disappointment of two potentially serious
injuries to Piazza and Reed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't lose them,'' manager Bobby Valentine said before
the Mets boarded their charter plane back to New York for Monday's
Shea Stadium season opener against the Marlins. ``And if we in fact
can play as well as we're capable of playing, when Mike comes back,
it will be like a shot in the arm for us. And Rick is just
temporarily sidelined. He's not lost either.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed has been bothered by his Achilles' tendon since March 26,
when he tweaked it in spring training. With the Mets trailing, 2-1,
in the top of the fourth Sunday _ and Reed only beginning to settle
down on the mound _ he tied the game with a run-scoring hit down
the left-field line. And then something happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It popped,'' Reed said of his tendon injury, which occurred as
he was halfway between first and second base. Reed struggled to
reach second and flopped headfirst toward the bag, only to be
beaten by the throw and tag. But, after writhing in pain on the
ground for several minutes, Reed was able walk off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it feels pretty good,'' Reed said after the game.
``I'm not saying I could go out and run a marathon. But I don't
think it's anything serious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he looked like he got shot was a sign that it snapped
or that there was a real bad pull,'' Valentine said. ``But now
we're very confident it wasn't torn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have a day off Tuesday and another one a week from
Monday. So Valentine may be able to juggle his staff to let Reed
miss a turn without him going on the disabled list. But when Reed _
who led the Mets with 31 starts last season _ was asked if he felt
his Achilles' tendon injury would cause him to miss a turn, he
said: ``I don't think I will. I think I'll be OK''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Watson did not think he would be pitching when Reed got
hurt because Josias Manzanillo was warming up. But Manzanillo
experienced stiffness in his forearm, so Watson was put in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Watson failed to cover first in time on Montreal pitcher Carl
Pavano's hard grounder in the fourth, and the Expos went on to
score the go-ahead run. ``That was stupid,'' Watson said. ``I had a
brain cramp. I caught myself watching the play. I probably thought
I was still in the dugout watching the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets retook the lead, for good, in the fifth on Luis
Lopez's two-run single with the bases loaded. And Watson (1-0),
Turk Wendell, Dennis Cook, Armando Benitez and John Franco held the
Expos scoreless the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We threw the old righty, lefty, righty, lefty, righty, lefty
at them,'' the quirky Wendell said after Franco picked up the 399th
save of his career. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
