<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S PRIME MINISTER SEES U.S., PLUS BRONCOS AND A BULL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Colo., Calif.)   (jw) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Prime Minister Zhu Rongji of China took his tour of
America to the heartland Sunday, tossing footballs with Denver
Broncos, inspecting a Black Angus bull and listening to a Tibetan
sing Chinese nationalist songs.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Denver and Chicago after sharp exchanges in Washington
over trade and human rights, Zhu tried to show an interest in
everyday Americans and their culture. But he refused to relax the
grueling pace he has set since he began an American tour in Los
Angeles a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   He zipped around the two cities in his 40-car motorcade for most
of the weekend, slackening the pace slightly Sunday evening for
private meetings with Chinese-Americans in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters calling for independence for Tibet made scattered
appearances in both cities, usually in groups of two to three
dozen, sometimes stationed on highway overpasses along the
motorcade route. One group of 30 protesters outside the Hilton
Chicago &AMP; Towers in downtown Chicago chanted, ``Red China, shame on
you'' loud enough to be heard on the upper floors of the hotel
where Zhu was staying.
</P>
<P>
   Some wariness toward China followed him from Washington. Over a
dinner of fillet of beef and Colorado spring greens, Gov. Bill
Owens of Colorado instructed Zhu, who stands third in China's
political hierarchy, on liberty and the ``American way of life.''
But the comments elicited only smiles from the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   In the tradition of senior Chinese leaders who visit America,
Zhu, well-known for his economic focus, sought to show that his
interest in America went beyond trade and technology. In late 1997,
President Jiang Zemin visited the United States and explored
Revolutionary War sites. Zhu had a more modern passion: football.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials said that although he was told that spring was
not football season, Zhu insisted on visiting the Denver Broncos
and expressed a particular interest in meeting John Elway, the
quarterback who led the Broncos to back-to-back Super Bowl
victories in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The visit was a fumble of sorts. Zhu's interest in football
exceeded his knowledge of the game. When he visited the Broncos'
elaborate training facility outside Denver, he joked that the
uniforms and shoulder pads ``look like the garb on ancient
warriors.'' He said he did not dare wear the equipment. ``I am
afraid my legs would buckle and I would fall down if I tried,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu experimented with throwing a football on the Broncos' heated
practice turf. He first tried shoving it away from his chest, like
a medicine ball. Given a second chance, he side-armed a blistering
pass into a group of television cameras, hitting a reporter in the
face.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister seemed slightly upset when none of the
champion Broncos' big stars showed up for the event, including
Elway. There had been rumors that Elway, whom some local
politicians are hoping to recruit to run on a Republican ticket,
did not want to have his picture taken with a Chinese Communist.
But Elway put those to rest when he appeared at a dinner for Zhu on
Saturday night. Zhu also accepted a gift of a blue and orange
Broncos shirt, with ``Zhu'' and No. 7, Elway's number, on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu also made a quick stop at the Denver open-air Red Rock
amphitheater. The program featured some local music. But in what
seemed like a deliberate effort to counter the ubiquitous protests
against Chinese rule of Tibet, the organizers included a
performance by a Tibetan opera singer, Dorji Ciren. He belted out a
robust version of ``My Homeland, Kind as a Mother,'' a song of
homage to mainland China akin to ``My Country Tis of Thee.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was presented with gifts at every stop, none compared
to the 1,500-pound black Angus bull, genetically engineered by
scientists at the University of Illinois to produce calves that
make the highest grade of beef. The bull was a gift from Thomas
Pritzker, president of Hyatt Corp., who also owns an 865-acre farm
40 miles northwest of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu briefly inspected the young bull. But he seemed more
intrigued by a 10-ton Caterpillar combine parked nearby. To the
consternation of the Secret Service officers surrounding him, he
climbed the steep stairs to enter its cab and peppered the operator
with questions about details _ like the capacity of its hopper, its
horsepower and its cost ($250,000).
</P>
<P>
   He also continued his energetic politicking for China to be
accepted by the World Trade Organization. China failed, at least
temporarily, to win entry, when talks on admission fell through
last week.
</P>
<P>
   While most of his delegation remained inside their buses and
limousines to escape bitter winds, Zhu courted local farmers
gathered on the farm. He urged them to call President Clinton
personally and relate how much they want China to join the world
trade body.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us to call the president directly and tell him how
much we want this WTO thing,'' said Pete Tekampe, 57, who grows
corn and beans on a 1,000-acres nearby. ``I don't know if I can do
that for him, but maybe I'll call my local representative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
