<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' DRY REIGN ALL WASHED UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When he was traded from the New York Mets to the
Dodgers last December, Todd Hundley figured his days of seeing
games rained out at home were over.
</P>
<P>
   Think again, Todd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible,'' Hundley said after the Dodgers-Rockies game
was rained out Sunday. ``I've never seen it rain in L.A. until
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has seen a Dodgers home game postponed because of rain
since April 1988, when three consecutive games against the Padres
were washed out. Their streak of 856 home games without a rainout _
the longest in the majors _ ended at 2:45 p.m., when the official
word came down.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's game, which started about an hour late because
of rain, turned out to be an omen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to playing today,'' Hundley said.
``There's good things and bad things. Some guys get the days off
and get to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers left for Phoenix on Sunday night to start a
three-game series tonight against the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are 5-1 and in second place in the NL West. As a
team, they are hitting almost 100 points (.297 to .202) above their
opponents, and the staff ERA is 3.32.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers already have 10 homers and 10 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of good things happened this homestand,'' said Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson. ``We continued our good play (from spring
training). We didn't need (a rainout), but we'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Non-issue: Johnson discounted any possibility of bad blood from
the Dodgers' last series against the Diamondbacks carrying over to
these games.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Dodgers starter Chan Ho Park, who is starting
tonight, threw a pitch that went behind Arizona's Matt Williams.
Williams, who once publicly declared his distaste for the Dodgers
and then-L.A. pitcher Orel Hershiser, yelled at Park and both
benches cleared. There was some shoving between a few players but
no punching.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks starter Todd Stottlemyre expressed regret the next
day for not retaliating. Stottlemyre threw Sunday against the
Braves and won't pitch in this series.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Devon White, who played for the Diamondbacks last
year, said he's not sure what to expect from the Arizona pitchers,
and he doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let something like that interfere,'' White said. ``We
can't worry about what (manager) Buck (Showalter) and his crew are
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumped: Johnson said the rest of the starters will be bumped
back a day, meaning a rematch between Kevin Brown and Randy Johnson
from opening day won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (1-0) was scheduled to pitch Thursday in the series
finale. Instead, he will pitch the opener at San Diego on Friday.
Ismael Valdes, who was supposed to start tonight, moves to Tuesday.
Carlos Perez will start Wednesday and Darren Dreifort will face
Johnson on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   History repeating?: The Dodgers' hot start, coupled with their
21 victories in spring training, has followers of the team drawing
parallels to 1988, the year the Dodgers won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's rainout, the first since that season, drew another
comparison. White said Dodgers coach John Shelby, a member of that
world-champion team, mentioned the coincidence in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's (begin ital)deja vu(end ital) territory,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   There's also one element that seemed to propel the '88 team that
also is catching on as a buzzword on this club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chemistry,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Closing in: Johnson, who has the highest winning percentage of
all active managers, is 10 wins away from 1,000 in his career. He's
also nine behind Colorado's Jim Leyland and is 46th on the all-time
managerial list for wins.
</P>
<P>
   Patience means success: Raul Mondesi, who has four homers, 10
RBI and a .381 average, has been more selective at the plate and it
is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, who is batting fourth, walked twice Saturday, giving
him at least one walk in four consecutive games for only the second
time in his six-year career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
