<HEADER>
A4110 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT &LR;      04-11 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL COMPLETES COMEBACK FROM INJURY TO WIN MASTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Three years ago, Jose Maria Olazabal suffered
through days when he couldn't walk, crippled by intense pain in his
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Olazabal walked away with the sweetest victory of his
career, his second triumph at the Masters to go with the one in
1994 and a victory that amplified his talent and courage.
</P>
<P>
   He was not the sentimental favorite _ Greg Norman was. Olazabal
started shakily, making three consecutive bogeys on the front nine,
and losing the one-stroke lead he held when the day started.
</P>
<P>
   But on the back nine at Augusta National Golf Club, where so
many golfers have created memorable moments, Olazabal was truly
masterful. He made a terrific 10-foot putt for birdie at No. 10 to
tie Norman for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Norman made a sensational 25-foot eagle putt at No. 13,
sending a roar through the gallery that shook the azaleas, Olazabal
answered his playing partner boldly, making a 22-foot putt for
birdie that kept Norman and Olazabal tied.
</P>
<P>
   After Norman bogeyed No. 15 to give Olazabal the lead for good,
Olazabal made another spectacular birdie at the 170-yard, par-3
16th, hitting a 6-iron tee shot that landed three feet from the
cup, followed by the putt for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after reaching the 17th green with a two-stroke lead,
Olazabal put the exclamation point on his victory with a crucial
par save at No. 17, hitting a gorgeous 5-iron from the rough that
rolled through the fairway and reached the green. Minutes later,
Olazabal made a nerve-testing seven-foot putt for par, which doomed
both Norman and Davis Love 3rd, and a putt that let everyone know
that this 33-year-old Spaniard had come too far to squander
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a final-round 71, Olazabal finished at 8-under for the
tournament (280). He won by two strokes over Love ( 6-under par,
282) and by three strokes over Norman, who played well but was
denied at the Masters once again.
</P>
<P>
   Many started the day pulling for Norman, the two-time British
Open champion who has finished second three times at Augusta, most
recently in 1996 when he lost a six-stroke lead to Nick Faldo on
the final day. But at the end of the day, there was true joy for
Olazabal, who has recovered from the health problems that
threatened his career to return to the top his profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very satisfying, and it's very difficult to express how I
feel,'' said Olazabal, who cried tears of joy at one point during
his post-tournament press conference. ``I'm very proud of myself,
not just for myself, but for all the other people who supported me
through bad times, my family, my friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at my lowest, I never thought about this happening
again. I thought I would never play golf again. To me to be right
here, with another green jacket, is an achievement that I didn't
even dream about.''
</P>
<P>
   What Olazabal did Sunday was no dream, and though he lost at the
Masters again, Norman insisted that this was not another nightmare.
There could be only one winner, and while Norman wanted that winner
to be him, he also felt joy for Olazabal, who became a close friend
years ago when they played together in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a heartbreak,'' said Norman, who also shot 71, and
who held the lead ever so briefly before Olazabal answered Norman's
eagle at No. 13 with a birdie. ``It's a successful event, and
sadness involved too. But look at that leader board. There's a lot
of other guys who can sit here and say they're heartbroken too.''
</P>
<P>
   Count Love among them, who has finished in the top seven four
times in the last five Masters, including two second-place
finishes. Love made the most spectacular shot of the tournament, a
chip shot for birdie at No. 16 that floated softly onto the
severely sloping green, then took a 180-degree turn and rolled
slowly down the hill about 25 feet until it settled into the cup.
The gallery exploded as the ball disappeared, and Love raised his
arms in triumph, knowing it was the kind of miracle shot that can
make champions.
</P>
<P>
   But Love was still one stroke behind Olazabal, and after
Olazabal's birdie at No. 16, Love could only make par at both No.
17 and No. 18, and he knew another chance at Augusta had been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said Love. ``I left a lot of shots out
there, but I'm pleased that I had a chance to get nervous on the
weekend. But I'm happy for Jose. A few years back, we had heard
that might not play anymore. To come back from something like to
win the Masters again is really something, and I know how much he
loves this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal's health problems began in 1995, when he began to
experience pain in his feet, caused by a nerve problem in his back
that was not detected for more than a year. Until the cause of
Olazabal's pain was discovered, he suffered, missing the 1996
Masters because he was in no condition to play.
</P>
<P>
   Watching that tournament at home, and watching Norman's
tribulations that year was a doubly painful experience for
Olazabal, but Sunday, he was back where he belonged, making great
shots on a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   So many people started the day with a chance to win, like Bob
Estes and Steve Pate, who finished tied for fourth place at 4-under
par, as well as David Duval (3-under) and Lee Westwood (3-under),
both of whom made final-day charges and reached five under par at
one point.
</P>
<P>
   But it finally came down to a three-player race, and Olazabal
proved his worth, and his class. After the 13th hole, Norman and
Olazabal pointed at each other, a sign of respect after great
putts.
</P>
<P>
   Then as Olazabal prepared to walk up the 18th fairway, he waited
for Norman, and the too walked up the together as the gallery
cheered. Finally Olazabal, made the final putt to win, and his long
journey back to the top at Augusta was over.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a long, painful road back. But the end was sweet.
``The first time I won here, I didn't have the knowledge or the
time to really enjoy,'' said Olazabal. ``This one, I'm really going
to enjoy much more.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
