<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN SHOWS UP AND PLAYS WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ In the unpredictable tug-of-war between the yin and
yang of Dennis Rodman's world, sometimes it takes a couple of days
for the good and the bad to achieve a happy balance. But the scales
evened again Sunday, as they usually, eventually do.
</P>
<P>
   First, he showed up. Then he resumed his role as a starter, as
if the ill behavior of the previous two days was wholly irrelevant.
And then Rodman played as if it indeed had been.
</P>
<P>
   Playing 40 minutes against the Sonics, Rodman grabbed 13
rebounds and added six points, two steals, an assist and a blocked
shot. Other than a technical foul, hardly a surprise, Rodman's
behavior was impeccable.
</P>
<P>
   So who cares if he refused to re-enter the fourth quarter Friday
or come to practice Saturday? Not his Laker teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of just went like this, right over the top of our
heads,'' Kobe Bryant said, passing his hand over his Afro. ``We had
a game to get ready for.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no airing out of issues between Rodman and teammates
or Rodman and coach Kurt Rambis, and when the coach was asked what
Lakers management's response was to recent events, the answer, he
said, was a nonplussed, ``Oh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis comes to play every night,'' Shaquille O'Neal said.
``We think you guys (reporters) make more of a big deal of it than
we do. . . . We don't let it bother us. . . . It's really not
(Rodman) that needs practice time. There's a lot of other guys on
this team that need practice time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman did not address reporters, but in comments provided by
the Lakers, he said: ``I am taking most of the heat right now (for
the team's struggles), just because. . . . But I am used to it, so
it really does not bother me. Probably most of the blame will fall
on me no matter what I do, so I do not care if they blame me or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie maneuvers: Glen Rice was home with a sore throat and a
fever, and Rambis decided not to mess with his bench rotation, so
rookie Ruben Patterson got his first career start Sunday, and the
challenge of a lifetime _ guarding Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson played 11 minutes and survived the attack, using three
fouls and all the defense he had to limit Payton to a layup and two
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did a good job against him today. He didn't do
nothing to me,'' Patterson said. ``He's a good player, he talks a
lot of trash, but I wasn't listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan favorite Tyronn Lue played 15 minutes at point guard and the
rookie again impressed, scoring 10 points on 4-of-5 shooting,
including a pair of 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   The last word: Olden Polynice was a minor factor in the Sonics'
victory (four points, eight rebounds), but that didn't stop him
from providing the best smack talk of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Last time these teams met, O'Neal derided Polynice, saying,
``I'm the bridge, Olden is water. . . . He'll always be under me.''
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Polynice responded: ``You can tell Shaq I might
still be water and he's the bridge, but guess what, the bridge was
man-made and the water is made by God. I will always survive. And
he better watch out before I rise over him. I don't care what he
says, he's still going to be Shaquille and I'll still be The Man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
