<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Eds.: New lead and top paragraphs to emphasize bombing activity) 
FEWER BOMBS FALL, AS NEW ATROCITIES ARE ALLEGED  (jw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO held back from intensive bombing on a
day of cloudy weather over Kosovo Sunday, hampering its attacks
even as alliance officials accused the Serbs of carrying out new
atrocities against ethnic Albanians in their southern province.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the alliance had ordered a
``night of relative restraint'' for the Orthodox Easter
celebration, but military commanders referred only to the weather
as the reason.
</P>
<P>
   No successful attacks were reported between Saturday night and
Sunday morning against Serbian forces or tanks operating in Kosovo.
Attacks resumed with renewed vigor on Sunday night, however.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown in the NATO campaign came as alliance officials
Sunday released aerial photographs, including one of freshly turned
earth, that they said could be mass graves, and another of clusters
of people described as ethnic Albanians driven from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Officials stressed that the photographs, taken on Friday, could
not be confirmed as graves until they could be examined on the
ground, but they said the first image resembled aerial photographs
of graves taken in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   One aerial photograph, which officials said was taken over Pusto
Selo, near Orahovac, showed what appeared to be two long parallel
lines of mounds in a clearing off a road with buildings scattered
nearby and tracks in the ground that could have been left by
military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freshly turned earth could indicate possible mass
graves,'' a spokesman for the allied military command, Col. Konrad
Freytag, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph, if what it appears to show can be verified,
would buttress refugees' accounts of atrocities, which have been
impossible to verify since the journalists and foreign observers
were expelled or evacuated from Kosovo last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are simply indicating something from the air that could be
a mass grave,'' Shea said, ``and based on our experience in Bosnia,
of course, a number of mass graves were identified and recovered
and from the air, the form looks something similar, and that's the
reason why we've shown you these photographs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a mass grave, but obviously it will be up to the
international tribunal in The Hague, once it's able to go into
Kosovo, to conduct a thorough investigation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Freytag said the allies had flown reconnaissance missions over
the area around Orahovac, halfway between the Kosovo provincial
capital of Pristina and the Albanian border, after receiving
intelligence reports that Serb military and paramilitary police
units had committed atrocities against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Other aerial photographs released by the command, also taken on
Friday, showed what officials said were internally displaced
persons near Malisevo.
</P>
<P>
   The reconnaissance effort apparently came in response to
complaints by some allied civilian representatives here that the
military had not tried hard enough to learn what had happened to
tens of thousands of fleeing ethnic Albanian civilians who vanished
overnight last week after Serbian border guards turned them back at
the frontier with Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs were all made from a high altitude. Clouds and
rain over the area since then had made it impossible to follow up
since, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The weather also hampered alliance attacks. Clouds ranging in
altitude from 2,000 to 8,000 feet shrouded most of Serbia over the
weekend. The F-117 stealth fighter typically flies missions between
15,000 and 25,000 feet, out of range of anti-aircraft fire.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs showed what appeared to be vehicles scattered
along a road and crowds of people in temporary shelters in fields
or scrub land near a destroyed village, which the command did not
identify.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lack the basic elements of relief and are particularly
short of food,'' British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Sunday
in London, referring to the internal refugees. ``The weather
currently is against them. It is snowing Sunday in western
Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the alliance could do to help the people believed to
be hiding in the forests and mountains around the province _
400,000 of them by Cook's estimate _ Shea said Sunday, ``The best
thing NATO can do for internally displaced persons is to drive away
the Serbian forces that are attacking them.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior allied diplomat said, ``Air drops, if we could identify
where people are, could be a way of dealing with this, if we aren't
just feeding the Serbs.'' NATO planes would have to fly at high
altitude to avoid Serb anti-aircraft fire from the ground, but that
would mean an increased chance that the food and supplies they
dropped could fall into the hands of Serbian forces instead of the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But the refugees are probably moving about on the ground, and
with unfavorable weather conditions expected to last through
Wednesday, allied intelligence is apparently finding it difficult
to keep information up to date.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian Orthodox Christian calendar marked Sunday as Easter,
but allied military authorities had adamantly rejected calls from
the Vatican and from Russian Orthodox leaders in Moscow for a pause
in the bombing to cover the entire 10-day Easter holiday period
that began with Good Friday observances for Western Christians on
April 2.
</P>
<P>
   Among the allies, both Greece and Italy had sought political
support for such a pause but did not press when military commanders
responded that a break in the bombing would just give Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic that much more time to push many of
Kosovo's 1.8 million ethnic Albanians from their homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
