<DOCNO> NYT19990411.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-PAPERS-ART-68     04-11 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-PAPERS-ART-680(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDSHIP AND TRUST AT HEART OF CASE CHALLENGING VALIDITY OF
KENNEDY PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John M. Reznikoff remembers an August day two years ago, when he
sat with his family on a beach on Cape Cod and felt on top of the
world. He had established himself as a respected dealer in stamps,
coins and other collectibles, even locks of hair from famous
people. But he was best known for his vast collection of autographs
of noted figures, tens of thousands of them, including every
president, from Washington to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It was no easy feat, especially in a business so quirky and
insular, where a person's word and trust mean everything. But just
a week later, Reznikoff's world came apart, undone by allegations
of fraud, betrayal and a shattered friendship. His reputation was
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   It all turned on hundreds of documents, supposedly handwritten
by John F. Kennedy, that he was helping a close friend sell.
Reznikoff recalls that the friend, who had already sold 200 of the
documents to more than 100 investors for several million dollars,
tearfully confessed to him that all the papers were fakes, forged
by him. Reznikoff said he soon came to see that his friend's life
had been full of deceit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe the feeling,'' Reznikoff said. ``You
work on something, and everything's rosy for four or five years,
and then it's like somebody punches you in the stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   The friend, Lawrence X. Cusack II, recanted his story the next
day, Reznikoff said, but the seed of doubt had been planted. On his
lawyer's advice, Reznikoff secretly taped a conversation with
Cusack. He gave the tape to the U.S. attorney's office in
Manhattan, hoping to clear his own name and helping to bolster the
criminal case against Cusack, whose trial on fraud charges begins
Monday in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, government prosecutors say ``the evidence is
overwhelming'' that the documents are forgeries and that Cusack
``is the person responsible.'' The most explosive of the papers
purports to detail an affair between Kennedy and Marilyn Monroe,
and Kennedy's agreement to pay hush money to the actress to remain
silent about their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack has pleaded not guilty to the charges, and has maintained
in numerous interviews that the papers are genuine.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing on Friday, Judge Denise L. Cote signaled that she
expected that Cusack would try ``to rebut any implication that he
forged or even knew of any forgeries.'' Neither Cusack's lawyer,
Robert F. Katzberg, nor officials with the the U.S. attorney's
office would comment about the impending trial.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the jury weighs Cusack's guilt or innocence, the
central drama of the trial may be Cusack's relationship with
Reznikoff, who is expected to be the government's chief witness and
whose tape will offer some of the government's most crucial
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The tape transcript, a draft of which has been filed in public
court records, shows Cusack as a conflicted and distraught man,
admitting that he had misled friends, associates _ even his wife _
and had given people the false impression that he had served in the
Navy in Vietnam and had graduated from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   He seems unable to extract himself from the web of lies. ``It's
sort of like, how and when do you 'fess up?'' Cusack says at one
point, adding, ``How am I going to explain that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You start covering for yourself,'' he explains later, adding,
``It's like a self-perpetuating lie that you can't get away from.''
He ultimately decided, he said, to let the lies be his ``cover
story'' and ``let it sit.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he concedes, ``It just got out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Cote has allowed most of the tape to be admitted into the trial,
over the objections of Cusack's lawyer, Katzberg, who contends that
some aspects could prejudice the jury. It is also not clear from
court records how Cusack views the taped conversation, or how
Katzberg will portray it to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff's lawyer, Russell M. Gioiella, said he advised his
client to make the tape because he saw no other way for Reznikoff
to prove his own innocence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a recent interview at Gioiella's office in lower Manhattan,
Reznikoff discussed his relationship with Cusack, although he
avoided talking about some aspects of his conversations with Cusack
because they might be used at trial.
</P>
<P>
   He said he first met Cusack in 1992, when he bought some stamps
from him, and grew to like him. ``I was impressed with how he
carried himself, the way he talked,'' he recalled. They socialized
together; their wives became friends. Reznikoff called him ``a very
close friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in 1993, Cusack first showed Reznikoff copies of the
Kennedy papers, the government has said in court papers. Cusack had
said that he had found them in the office of his late father,
Lawrence X. Cusack Jr., a prominent lawyer who had represented the
Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff said he saw no reason to disbelieve Cusack or to
suspect any bad faith on his part, and he helped him obtain letters
of authentication from handwriting experts for every document that
was eventually sold.
</P>
<P>
   At some point in 1994 or 1995, the government says in court
papers, Cusack invited Reznikoff to attend a ceremony at the U.S.
Naval Academy at Annapolis, Md., where one of Cusack's relatives
was a plebe.
</P>
<P>
   As a federal prosecutor, Paul A. Engelmayer, described the event
in court papers: ``To buttress his false claim of Navy service,
Cusack on that occasion wore the full dress-white uniform of a
lieutenant commander, with a chest full of medals, including the
Naval Cross, and as a result, received salutes from thousands of
midshipmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff says he was impressed by his friend. ``One of the
things that was most endearing about him,'' he said in the
interview, ``was his military background. I'm a patriot. I have an
intense appreciation of patriotism.''
</P>
<P>
   After questions were raised in August 1997 about the papers'
authenticity, Reznikoff returned from a vacation in Truro, Mass.,
to his office in Stamford, Conn., and met with Cusack on Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   `` Cusack broke down, cried and stated that he had been
praying,'' the government said in a federal complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff asked Cusack whether the documents were forged.
``Cusack responded by asking whether they could just give the
purchasers their money back,'' the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, ``Reznikoff asked Cusack if he had forged all of the
documents, and Cusack said yes,'' the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, Cusack called Reznikoff and took it all back,
the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff said that for weeks he was utterly confused about
where the truth lay, and in October consulted with a lawyer,
Gioiella.
</P>
<P>
   Gioiella advised him to protect himself, and to meet again with
Cusack, with a tape recorder running.
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff said he resisted this plan, hesitant to betray a
friend. He said he finally agreed for his family's sake, fearing
that he would be dragged into the government's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the secretly taped session on Oct. 18, Reznikoff recounted
for Cusack their earlier conversation, and he recalled how Cusack
had sat there holding his head, crying and admitting that he had
forged the papers, the transcript shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're sitting there and you're telling me that you're guilty,
that you did everything, that everything's fake,'' Reznikoff says,
according to the transcript.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm listening to you,'' Cusack replies.
</P>
<P>
   In the transcript, which runs 30 pages, Cusack is shown
equivocating and shifting ground, while still maintaining that the
papers are genuine. But he does not deny Reznikoff's version of his
earlier confession. Nor does he suggest that Reznikoff had a role
in any forgery scheme. The government has said in legal papers that
the tape shows that Reznikoff ``had not been aware of the
forgery.''
</P>
<P>
   The transcript also shows Cusack admitting that he did not serve
in the Navy. Reznikoff asks why Cusack misled him, reminding him of
their trip to Annapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw you wearing that uniform and I saw 3,000 people saluting
you,'' Reznikoff says, adding: ``I believed all along from Day One
that you had this unbelievable military career. And I loved that
about you.''
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff adds, ``I need an explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack says it began as a joke among friends years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``But why would you let your friend, supposed friend, believe
that?'' Reznikoff asks. ``Why would you let me believe? Why would
you let me have that faith in your military career?''
</P>
<P>
   That was when Cusack said he did not know how to `` 'fess up,''
that it had all got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff said he now wonders how much of their friendship
itself was genuine. If the government's allegations are borne out
at trial, he said, then Cusack was involved in the forgery scheme
as early as 1993 _ shortly after the two men met.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very generous to me throughout those years and to my
family,'' Reznikoff said. ``If everything that's alleged is true, I
almost feel more sorry for him than I feel angry.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he hopes he was not manipulated. ``I like to think that
some of the friendship was real,'' he said, ``and I think I am a
good friend, someone who's fun to be with, and that I do add to a
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``But who knows? I don't know what the ultimate answer
to that question is. A lot will be revealed in the weeks to come.''
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
