<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBY COMES ON STRONG AS KNICKS TOP NETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J., _ Marcus Camby has had to build a trust
with New York Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy layer by layer.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't come easy. But each time he performs with an edge,
each time he refuses to back down, Camby inches a little closer to
Van Gundy's inner circle of players he can count on.
</P>
<P>
   Camby made a huge gain on that realm Sunday by putting a hand up
in the face of the New Jersey Nets' momentum during the second
quarter when he scored 13 of his 19 points to help the Knicks win
their second game in a row, 93-78, at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Camby finish his shots on the fast break and use a
fancy drop-step for a layup, he flustered the Nets' star threat,
Keith Van Horn, and held him to 3-of-14 shooting by using his
windmill-like arms to alter Van Horn's jumpers, runners and layups.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is still a debate as to whether Camby is physical
enough to withstand the likes of Orlando, Miami and Indiana, this
was the kind of game that goes a long way with Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to go out and hope that Jeff has enough
confidence in me to play me against Miami and Indiana,'' said
Camby, who also had eight rebounds and one blocked shot against the
Nets. ``I've been doing everything he has asked of me. I've just
been waiting for my turn to get minutes. I wasn't discouraged about
the lack of playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby has been used selectively this year. He has put up
impressive numbers against teams like Boston (15 rebounds) and
Chicago (eight blocks), but when faced with Orlando, Miami and
Indiana, he has averaged 7.8 minutes and 1.8 rebounds a game and is
2 of 8 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Often labeled as too frail and weak, Camby made strides in
changing that image last week. After missing three games with a
strained groin, Camby played with pain against Atlanta on Friday
and shot 4 for 6 and had five rebounds in 19 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he punched another hole in his soft image. Irritated by
a foul, Camby slipped the notice of the officials as he sent a
forearm into the shoulder of Jamie Feick. Although Feick barely
felt the blow from the slender Camby, it was a snapshot of
aggression rarely associated with Camby.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, Camby is linked with his failure to be like
the rugged Charles Oakley. Camby is usually stuck being compared
with the folk hero he replaced, even though he is more of a finesse
player and Oakley is more of a bully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough at the beginning, because of all the talk about
me and Oak,'' Camby said. ``But I just want to go out and be
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby's game hasn't always fit Van Gundy's plans. That did not
always sit well with the team president, Ernie Grunfeld, who signed
Camby to a six-year, $48 million contract extension despite his
limited playing time. There has been tension caused by how big a
role Camby should play. For his part, Camby has stayed out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, coming in, Marcus had some big shoes to fill,''
Larry Johnson said. ``But he's doing an excellent job. He's been
the difference in our last two games. He's done a good job handling
the minutes he is getting and the ones he's not. He's waiting for
his turn and not pouting in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby did the job in his matchup with Van Horn. During the Nets'
surge of having won five of six games entering Sunday, Van Horn had
averaged 27 points a game. Along with Kurt Thomas, Camby held Van
Horn to 10 points. Adding a little offensive flair, Camby played a
large part in dampening the Nets' recent good mood.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson helped as well. He scored a game-high 22 points by
barging his way around the Nets' soft interior defense, and helped
give the Knicks a 44-16 edge on points in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the pressure off Patrick Ewing, who was 6 of 17 for 15
points, the Knicks worked the ball around and played with the
unselfish style that has been lacking at times during a year of ups
and downs. Chris Childs delivered six assists as a part of a sleek
second unit that featured Camby flashing his potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Marcus has made improvements because of
confidence, feeling more comfortable or just getting an opportunity
to play, but he's playing well,'' Van Gundy said. ``I thought the
matchup with Van Horn was perfect for him. He's continuing to make
the most of his opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby would like a chance to prove himself. But at no time has
he thought the limit on his playing time had anything to do with
Van Gundy's displeasure with the trade of Oakley for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about that twice,'' Camby said. ``He told me he
wasn't against the trade. All I can do is go by the man's word.''
</P>
<P>
   All Camby can do is continue to build that trust.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
