<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SUCCESS AND SADNESS, AND THREE BAD SHOTS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also GLF-MASTERS) 
(rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ When Greg Norman curled in a 25-foot eagle putt
on the 13th green, he was suddenly 7- under par and leading the
Masters. The roar of all those people down in that corner of
Augusta National almost blew the blossoms off the azalea bushes. He
nodded and tipped his cap.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Jose Maria Olazabal holed a 20-foot birdie putt
to share the lead. Another roar. Norman waved to the Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the game was on,'' the 44-year-old Australian was
saying now. ``When I made my putt, I never doubted that he'd make
his. But I was trying not to draw off the emotion of the gallery
because it can work against you. I had to walk away so it wouldn't
be too much. And after Ollie made his putt, you just want to go to
the next tee and put it in the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   But off that next tee, Norman's drive soared to the right,
bounced off a spectator and stopped in ``the second cut,'' alias
the short rough grown at the Masters for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to shoot for the flagstick, Norman skidded a 7-iron over
the green. He chipped short, then two-putted from 15 feet. Bogey.
And when Olazabal made par, he was leading by one.
</P>
<P>
   Off the 15th tee, Norman's drive sailed to the right, stopping
behind the new transplanted pine trees. Unable to go for the green,
he laid up in front of the pond, then squirted a wedge into the
right bunker and blasted out long. When his par-saving putt lipped
out, he had another bogey. And when Olazabal got his par, Norman
had dropped two behind.
</P>
<P>
   With a 71 for 280, Olazabal would win his second Masters, two
strokes ahead of Davis Love 3rd and three ahead of Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a successful week and a sad week all rolled up in
one,'' Norman would say later. ``Success from the pure fact of all
my hard work and dedication to get back from shoulder surgery. I
feel like I'm back in the position where I can contend again. And
obviously the sadness of not winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Norman considered it anywhere near as ``heartbreaking''
as his 1996 Masters loss when, with a six-stroke lead after three
rounds, he soared to a 78 as Nick Faldo shot 67 to win by five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heartbreaking? Not at all,'' he said. ``Some people might
interpret it that way, but like I said, it's a successful event
with sadness involved too. It's not a heartbreak. There's probably
a lot of other guys here who can say they're heartbroken too. Don't
make a mountain out of a molehill. I was more disappointed in '96,
and '96 was totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   In that mano-a-mano with Faldo in the final pairing, Norman just
collapsed, early and often. In Sunday's duel with Olazabal in the
final pairing, he snatched the lead momentarily with that eagle
putt on the 13th green before reverting to the Norman who has often
pushed his shots to the right in the crucible of the finishing
holes in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   On the 72nd hole of the 1984 U.S. Open Championships at Winged
Foot, he pushed a 4-iron toward the grandstand near the green. Only
a 50-foot par putt put him in a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, on the second hole of the 18-hole playoff with
Fuzzy Zoeller, Norman pushed his tee shot into the trees. He had a
double-bogey six there as Zoeller, who holed a 60-foot putt, took a
quick three-stroke lead. The playoff was virtually over.
</P>
<P>
   On the 72nd hole of the 1986 Masters, Norman, needing a par to
force a playoff with Jack Nicklaus, pushed a 4-iron to the right of
the green. Bogey. At age 46, Nicklaus won.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday, Norman pushed three crucial shots _ his drive at the
14th that led to a bogey, his drive at the 15th and the wedge into
the bunker that led to another bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the tee shot at the 14th, I hit it just dead straight,'' he
said. ``On the tee shot at the 15th, I tried to hit a hard smoker,
turn it off the trees, but I caught it a little high on the driver
face and that's why it didn't turn over.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, those two tee shots and the wedge from
only 94 yards that squirted into the bunker cost Norman whatever
chance he had to finally put on a green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say that I wasn't tournament tough in rounds one and
two,'' he said, ``but in three and four when you've got yourself
into contention, you'd be surprised how quickly you can get back
into it. That's what you really miss. Even though I've said I
didn't miss the game, you don't miss the game, but you miss these
moments and that's why you play.''
</P>
<P>
   But in those moments, Greg Norman has often pushed his golf ball
at the worst possible time. As he did again Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And when he was asked if he had been beaten by Jose Maria
Olazabal, by Augusta National and its wind gusts, or by himself, he
said, ``I think it's probably a combination of all three.''
</P>
<P>
   As well as those three bad shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
