<HEADLINE>
PATE HATES 17TH HOLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Steve Pate figures the staid Masters, with its
wide fairways and slick, undulating greens, was a perfect fit for
his game if not his fun-loving personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought this was by far my best chance to ever win
a major because of the way I putt,'' Pate said before Sunday's
final round. ``I don't three-putt very often, which is a good
attribute on this course. You have to drive it well but not
perfectly, which is good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, it was tempting to size the Agoura Hills resident
mentally for a green jacket Sunday afternoon when he came out of
the gate and coaxed 10 straight pars out of Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   Would the first of golf's four majors go to a Southern
California Junior Golf alumnus for the third year in a row? Pate
was nicely positioned to match the success here of Tiger Woods in
1997 and Mark O'Meara in 1998 when he made the turn tied for the
lead at 5 under par.
</P>
<P>
   The former UCLA golfer was one of six players who owned or
shared the final-round lead. His afternoon took a turn for the
worse at the 11th hole when he hit an errant second shot and
settled for a bogey 5.
</P>
<P>
   Birdies at 13 and 15 elevated Pate to within one of the leader,
Jose Maria Olazabal. He fell back with consecutive bogeys at 16 and
17, the latter of which was Pate's Waterloo. He bogeyed it all four
days, those four excess strokes effectively separating him from the
winner, Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   Pate didn't want to comment on the hole _ which turned out to be
the third- most-difficult for the week _ after carding his
1-over-par 73. ``No good can come of me talking about it,'' he said
with a shrug. His playing partner, Davis Love III, wasn't so
circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it, but that 17th green is unplayable,'' said
Love, who carded a 71 to finish second. ``It's like putting on
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate, 37, finished in a tie for fourth with Bob Estes at 4-under
284, his finest finish here since his tie for third in 1991. He has
three top-six finishes in six appearances here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had told me at the beginning of the week that I'd be
tied for fourth, I'd have thought it was great,'' Pate said. ``But
the way it turned out, I'm not feeling too good right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
