<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS NEED A-ROD BACK FAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sitting in the Mariner clubhouse, Alex Rodriguez
looked like an accident in a Crayola crayon box.
</P>
<P>
   His golf shirt was lime green. His corduroy pants were kelly
green. The eye-offending combo would have made Martha Stewart
blanch.
</P>
<P>
   That Rodriguez had the nerve to wear this clashing get-up to the
Kingdome Sunday was a dead give-away of the shortstop's current
state of disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be the drugs,'' first baseman David Segui said,
rolling his eyes at the major league sartorial faux pas committed
by the usually super-slick, Armani-clad Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Rodriguez said, attempting to defend himself. ``It's
green for the Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's post-operative knee might have meant a few
doctor-ordered painkillers were on his training table. Three days
after arthroscopic surgery, he had the right to act and feel a
little woozy.
</P>
<P>
   And Rodriguez's teammates and friends could afford to tease the
young man. He will be back in action soon. The four to six weeks
Rodriguez is expected to miss with torn cartilege in his left knee
is probably an outside forecast, if you consider all the advice he
is getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there are a lot of doctors around here. Dr. Segui. Dr.
Martinez. Dr. Griffey,'' Rodriguez said, as if his older, wiser
teammates were all but telling him this knee surgery is a rite of
baseball passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out two weeks when I had it done,'' Segui said,
remembering his 1997 knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long did it take you?'' Rodriguez asked Dave Henderson,
the former Mariner who made a point to stop by the Kingdome
clubhouse Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a different situation than you do. I had to get ready
for the playoffs. I was back in two weeks,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Rodriguez got up out of his chair and applied the
first bit of pressure on his tender leg by walking down the length
of the Mariner clubhouse _ without his crutches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch how fast I bounce back,'' Rodriguez said, hobbling off
to rehab.
</P>
<P>
   After an opening week like this past one, with Rodriguez
diagnosed with torn cartilege and then his impressive replacement
Carlos Guillen tearing an anterior cruciate ligament in a freaky
rundown play Saturday, the Mariners had to wonder. Is their middle
infield more of a jinxed minefield?
</P>
<P>
   Guillen, mind you, led the M's in spring, setting a club record
with 35 hits. He was ready to claim his place in the big leagues,
until Tony Phillips took him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it. Ever,'' said Jamie Moyer,
the winning pitcher in the Mariners' 11-8 win over Oakland Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really an unfortunate thing, although Alex seems like
he's on his way back. I don't care what club you're talking about,
though. That's the key part of any club. Any team in baseball, top
to bottom, that's where your team is the strongest. Pitcher.
Catcher. Second base. Shortstop. Centerfield. That's where a lot of
the game is played, so when you're missing those two guys up the
middle, you're really hurting,'' Moyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, all those infield errors and not enough back-up led
to near disaster, especially at second and third base as Joey Cora
and Russ Davis struggled, each leading both leagues in errors by
position.
</P>
<P>
   We can only imagine what would have happened if Segui had not
vacuumed up so many errant throws and cherry-picked so many wicked
hops.
</P>
<P>
   But this season ... goodness gracious.
</P>
<P>
   The infield, and particularly the middle infield, was a bright
spot. It was supposed to be shored up stronger than the Ballard
locks, in large part because Guillen was turning out to be much
better than the no-name minor leaguer most locals assumed he was
when the M's got him from Houston in the Randy Johnson deal.
</P>
<P>
   But now, five games into the season, the entire middle infield
has been forced to take a knee.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Guillen hobbled into the clubhouse to join Rodriguez in
what Ken Griffey is calling the Kingdome MASH unit. Guillen, who
will have surgery in 10 days and faces up to nine months of rehab,
said he did not speak with Oakland leadoff hitter Tony Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was booed at every at-bat but none of the Mariner
pitchers took a turn at returning the painful favor to him. To most
of the players, what Phillips did was within the realm of
reasonable force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony plays hard but he doesn't play dirty,'' Griffey said as
he helped detail how Guillen's knee was blown out not by Phillips'
collision but right before it, when Guillen planted his leg to try
to check the runner.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Mariners, they got lucky last season when
Cleveland's John Hart agreed to send David Bell to Seattle in
exchange for Cora. Now Cora is back home in Puerto Rico, managing
his local baseball team and the M's, thankfully, have Bell to eat
up the remaining 156 games in the season at second base.
</P>
<P>
   As for shortstop, the M's have brought up Giomar Guevara, who
started off the game by overthrowing Segui not once but twice for
two errors before settling down. They also have 31-year-old Domingo
Cedeno to share duties until Rodriguez comes back.
</P>
<P>
   As of now, with a ton of advice from his meddling but
well-meaning teammates and with Guillen out for the season,
Rodriguez seems willing to take the accelerated road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-11-99 2300EDT &QL; 
