<SLUG> BC-BBN-WOHLERS-BRAVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers changes mind, refuses reassignment with Braves
 &HT;    (EDS: Must credit Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Wohlers had a change of heart since talking with
manager Bobby Cox and general manager John Schuerholz on Friday
when they informed him he was designated for assignment in AAA
Richmond in hopes that he would regain the form who made him one of
the premier closers in baseball from 1995-97.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers, who suffered a relapse in his comeback attempt in his
first two outings this spring (six walks in two-thirds of an
inning), seemed eager to accept the assignment to Cox and
Schuerholz on Friday. But on Sunday Wohlers notified Schuerholz he
was refusing it.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz said the decision didn't completely surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   ``While he first indicated he was very optimistic and interested
in accepting the assignment, he obviously decided, either on his
own or after talking to someone, that he was not going to accept
the assignment,'' Schuerholz said. ``That's his right under the
Basic Agreement. I'm disappointed that the whole process didn't
work, for Mark's sake and the team's sake. It would have been the
perfect ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers could have accepted the assignment, refused it, or
declared for free agency. By refusing it, the Braves are still
responsible for his $5.2 million salary unless they trade him
within 10 days. They will release him if they can't work out a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Among teams believed to be interested in Wohlers are the
Pittsburgh Pirates and the Arizona Diamondbacks, both of whom would
pay a portion of Wohlers' salary. Schuerholz said some clubs had
expressed interest in Wohlers over the winter and early spring but
he would not divulge which ones.
</P>
<P>
   While Schuerholz expressed regret that Wohlers refused the
assignment, he stood by the decision he made on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Mark was a big part of our success,'' Schuerholz
said. ``He showed in spring training he has a chance to recapture
some of his outstanding major league capabilities. We were hopeful
he'd do it with us. As everybody who watched our team the other
night realized, we had no choice but to make a move. Our bullpen
was not going to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
