<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHECKETTS STAYS AFLOAT OVER MESS HE CREATED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ On days like Sunday when everything
seemed so right, so wonderful, you looked at the New York Knicks
and wondered, ``So what's the problem?'' They stormed the New
Jersey Nets' home court and flattened a team that is supposedly on
the rise.
</P>
<P>
   After the Knicks beat the Nets Sunday, 93-78, the Nets' interim
coach, Don Casey, said, ``There's nothing wrong with New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Knicks appeared to be teetering: they had lost
three consecutive games, five of six, and if you believe what you
read, the entire front office was headed for the guillotine. There
was a spate of good old-fashioned speculation over who would be
fired first.
</P>
<P>
   Initially it was Jeff Van Gundy, the Knicks' beleaguered head
coach, whose players supposedly had quit on him. The scrutiny
became so ferocious that Ernie Grunfeld, the Knicks' president, who
has miraculously escaped scrutiny for the last decade, found
himself smoked out, accused of squandering $68 million on a
haphazard collage of players with incompatible skills.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Knicks won a game in Atlanta on Friday and turned in a
gem Sunday against the Jayson Williams-less Nets. Every penny
seemed well spent: Marcus Camby, whose arrival had sent the beloved
Charles Oakley to Toronto, scored 15 points off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Fire the coach? Fire the president? Why?
</P>
<P>
   So Sunday was another one of those moments when victory becomes
a metaphor for a grand turnabout. Van Gundy tossed a double-edged
bouquet to Marcus Camby: ``He played hard and continued to work
hard,'' Van Gundy said, ``and when you do that, you become
coach-able.''
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell said: ``I am glad we are able to put two wins
together. We are feeling a lot better. Confidence is a lot greater
now. This is something the team can build on.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing said, ``The last two games, we were playing the
way we should have been playing all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the Nets were blowing kisses. Kendall Gill said:
``The Knicks have one of the best teams in the East. They have the
players, but they need to believe in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury was not so charitable. ``They still need a point
guard,'' Marbury said. ``They'll never win no championship with
them two guys, ever. Never. They will never, ever win.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll take that concept a step further: The Knicks may not win
with the current backcourt, but they won't win championships with
the current front office, either.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Mayfield, in another era, sang, ``If there's a hell
below, we're all going to go.'' That applies to the Knicks, whose
age-induced slide over the last five seasons led to this season's
maelstrom over who might be fired: Van Gundy or Grunfeld?
</P>
<P>
   But the executive who has floated like a feather in and out of
the storm is Dave Checketts, the Madison Square Garden president.
He has ridden in a sleek luxury car and made it through all the
egg-throwing without being touched.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the cavalcade of bizarre maneuvers has had his blessing, has
been his design. Grunfeld is the facilitator. Now Checketts is
gently nudging his pal down the plank.
</P>
<P>
   If Van Gundy walks the plank, Grunfeld should follow. If
Grunfeld walks, Checketts, the architect of this puzzle without a
plan, should jump, too. Checketts is no idle spectator; he is a
master of being in it but not of it.
</P>
<P>
   When the Knicks traded for Latrell Sprewell, Checketts said the
Knicks had made the move because they wanted to get past the second
round of the playoffs. Checketts even traveled to Milwaukee to meet
with Sprewell and sat with him for two hours asking tough
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, when Checketts was asked about the ugliness
surrounding the Oakley trade, he said, ``I wish we had done that
differently.'' Then he shifted the burden to Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try to put yourself in the place of a general manager,''
Checketts said, ``who, on the one hand, would like to acknowledge
the contributions of a player, and on the other hand, does not want
to spend so much time that it detracts from the job at hand, and
that's to go out and win a game. It's not an easy situation.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's going on here? ``I think you're seeing a bad situation
that has been created by losing,'' Checketts said. ``I see a team
that is losing more than they should. People say, Well, why is
this? Where does it come from? Is it the mix of talent? Are they
too small to compete in the half-court East without Charles
Oakley?''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' front office has effectively fooled season
ticket-holders into believing they are riding a winning horse when
what they are riding is the same old merry-go-round. They get off
after an exhilarating ride without having gone anywhere. At a more
cynical level, the Knicks are simply background music for corporate
schmoozing; one more amusement park ride.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are all sorts of intrigues. Patrick Ewing recently
went over Grunfeld's head to make an appeal for Van Gundy;
Checketts promised him that Van Gundy would remain the coach
through this season and next. Sunday, Van Gundy referred
cryptically to outside forces attempting to drive a wedge between
coach and players. Checketts escapes and floats above the chaos he
helped manufacture.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, Sprewell, Camby _ even Ward and Childs _ may yet bail out
the whole lot of them. Or they could hit another slick spot and
slide. Just remember: If there's a hell below. ... &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
