<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-AD-COLUMN-NYT     04-11 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: RETROSPECTIVE ISSUE OF ADVERTISING AGE SURE TO FIRE UP
CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is there anything that the folks who work in
advertising enjoy more than gossiping about their competitors?
Perhaps it is strolling down that side street off Madison Avenue
named Memory Lane to judge the merits and demerits of campaigns,
slogans, jingles and characters, not to mention the executives who
have led the major agency, marketing and media companies.
</P>
<P>
   The trade publication Advertising Age is offering 134 pages of
grist for the mill with a special retrospective issue devoted to
what the editors label ``the advertising century.'' The term is a
play on the phrase ``the American century,'' coined by Henry Luce,
the founder of Time Inc., who is No. 17 on a list of the ``top 100
advertising people.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen? What do you mean? How can Henry Luce be ranked only
17th on any list? What the ...
</P>
<P>
   Aha! Now you see one reason why Advertising Age published the
issue. In an industry so filled with opinionated participants, the
discussions generated by such lists are, to quote the old slogan of
the Cunard Line, half the fun _ which by the way did not make the
Advertising Age list of the 10 top slogans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of why you do it is to stir up debate,'' said Scott
Donaton, the New York-based editor of Advertising Age, published by
Crain Communications Inc. ``We knew and expected that.''
</P>
<P>
   First on a list of the issue's most contentious designations
would undoubtedly be the declaration of the Marlboro Man, created
by the Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago for what is now the Philip Morris
Cos., as first on a list of the ``top 10 advertising icons,''
followed by familiar figures like Ronald McDonald, the Jolly Green
Giant, Betty Crocker and the Energizer bunny.
</P>
<P>
   It has been apparent since last year that a decision to select a
cigarette smoker as the premier advertising icon _ however great
his prowess as a salesman _ would be playing with, well, fire.
That's because of a backlash to advertisements that Crain had run
to promote the issue, which speculated that the Marlboro cowboy
character could win that honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can dispute that the Marlboro Man is a brilliant
creation and a powerful icon,'' said William D. Novelli, president
of the National Center for Tobacco-Free Kids in Washington, an
advocacy organization. ``The question is, what harm has it done?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd urged folks in the public health community to tell
Advertising Age that the Marlboro Man is not a fitting icon for the
advertising industry,'' he added. ``And we intend to step up the
pace, mailing reprints of the icon article to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Novelli's organization bought ads in Advertising Age to counter
the Crain ads. That continues with a full-page ad in the special
issue carrying a headline based on data showing that nearly 60
percent of underage smokers smoke Marlboros: ``Six in 10 kid
smokers agree. The Marlboro Man is a marketing icon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than 40 years,'' the text reads, the character ``has
led kids down the road to addiction and disease. It's time to send
him out to pasture _ for good.''
</P>
<P>
   The article acknowledges the charged nature of the designation,
describing the puffing cowpoke, who is home on the conceptual range
known as Marlboro country, as ``the most powerful _ and in some
quarters, most hated _ brand image of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But even those ad professionals who abhor the tobacco
industry,'' the article asserts, ``will, when pressed, agree that
the Marlboro Man has had unprecedented success as a global
marketing tool.'' Indeed, Marlboro has grown to become the world's
best-selling cigarette brand.
</P>
<P>
   The character ``was born at a time when cigarette smoking was
widely accepted,'' said David S. Klein, the Chicago-based associate
publisher and group editor at Advertising Age, before ``the tobacco
issue divided the advertising industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlboro threads its way through the issue, much like the smoke
that once wafted from the cigarettes puffed by the singer Julie
London, who warbled the brand's pitches in television commercials _
missing, alas, from the list of top jingles starting with ``You
deserve a break today'' for McDonald's at No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlboro campaign by Burnett was ranked third on the list of
the ``top 100 advertising campaigns,'' behind only ``Think small''
for Volkswagen by Doyle Dane Bernbach, now part of the DDB Needham
Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group, and ``The pause that refreshes''
for Coca-Cola, by the D'Arcy Co., now part of the D'Arcy Masius
Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications unit of MacManus Group.
</P>
<P>
   And the Marlboro campaign is described as ``a legendary example
of advertising's power to build a global business'' that
``ultimately became a magnet for legislative crackdowns on tobacco
marketing'' in a profile of Leo Burnett, the agency's founder, who
is No. 3 on the list of 100 advertising people.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising Age's ranking of Burnett contrasts with an issue of
Time magazine published in November that named him the only
advertising executive on a list of the 20 most influential business
leaders of the century. An executive who was a runner-up to him in
Time's estimation is ``the hands-down winner'' of Advertising Age's
honor as the most important advertising person: William Bernbach, a
co-founder of Doyle Dane.
</P>
<P>
   Bernbach was ``the single most influential creative force in
advertising's history,'' Advertising Age declares, for low-key
campaigns that sold with a smile for products like the VW Beetle,
Levy's rye bread, Life cereal, Alka-Seltzer, Polaroid cameras and
Cracker Jack.
</P>
<P>
   The special issue was distributed with subscription copies of
the March 29 issue of Advertising Age. Additional copies are being
sold on newsstands at $9.95 each. Plans call for a special report
on ``the next century'' in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be ranking the greatest commercials of the 21st
century,'' Klein said, smiling. Donaton predicted that they would
be ``affixed to our eyelids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
