<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- April 11, 1999 -- KENNEDY-PAPERS, 4-11 --
John M. Reznikoff, a collector of autographs of noted figures,
including every U.S. president, says he had no reason to disbelieve
claims by his close friend Lawrence X. Cusack III that Cusack had
papers written by John F. Kennedy. Reznikoff says he soon came to
see that his friend's life had been full of deceit. ``It's hard to
describe the feeling,'' he says. In court papers, government
prosecutors say ``the evidence is overwhelming'' that the documents
are forgeries. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LAS VEGAS -- April 11, 1999 -- LASVEGAS-WYNN, 4-11 --
Steven Wynn, in his Mirage Hotel office with ``Frieze'' by Jackson
Pollock. Wynn's gallery, the Bellagio Gallery of Fine Art, is the
latest attraction in this vast casino and has drawn crowds despite
a $12 admission fee. It seems that the gamble by Wynn is paying off
in spades: the same crowd that clamors for Siegfried and Roy is
also attracted to a $300 million collection of Van Goghs, Picassos
and Monets. (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- April 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS-3,
4-11 -- Some of the 300 Albanian-Americans volunteers for the
Kosovo Liberation Army comfort friends and relatives who came to
bid them farewell on Sunday before the volunteers leave for
training grounds in Albania. While all the recruits in Yonkers say
they have relatives in Kosovo, many were born in the United States,
and some have never set foot in the Balkans. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- April 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS-2,
4-11 -- A young Albanian-American woman standing amongst some 300
Albanian-American volunteers for the Kosovo Liberation Army on
Sunday in Yonkers, N.Y. The volunteer soldiers are to fly from New
York this week to an undisclosed city in Europe, and from there to
training grounds in Albania, to help fight in a rebel army that is
heavily outgunned by the Yugoslavs. (James Estrin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NY-VOLUNTEERS-1,
4-11 -- Some 300 Albanian-Americans -- mostly young men, and a
handful of women -- form ranks in a parking lot in Yonkers, N.Y.,
on Sunday, dressed in newly bought camouflage fatigues bearing the
red-and-gold insignia of the Kosovo Liberation Army. The volunteer
soldiers are to fly from New York this week to an undisclosed city
in Europe, and from there to training grounds in Albania, to help
fight in a rebel army that is heavily outgunned by the Yugoslavs.
(James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NY-MOOD-FLOATER,
4-11 -- With bombs falling on Belgrade, the mood was somber Sunday
as Easter was celebrated at the Serbian Orthodox Cathedral of St.
Sava in New York. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PUSTO SELO, Kosovo -- April 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NATO, 4-11
-- Aerial photographs released by NATO Sunday show what it said may
be evidence of new graves in Pusto Selo, Kosovo. At top, no graves
are seen; an image taken Friday, bottom, shows newly turned earth,
NATO says. (New York Times Photo via NATO)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CONAKRY, Guinea -- April 11, 1999 -- NY-DIALLO-MOTHER-2,
4-11 -- Kadiadou Diallo, center, being greeted by well-wishers at a
memorial service for her son Amadou in her native Guinea. Since the
Feb. 4 killing of her son in a barrage of 41 police bullets, Mrs.
Diallo has made a journey that has taken her further than the 4,300
miles from her home in the West African nation of Guinea. She has
gone from paralyzed public grief to telegenic celebrity, demanding
answers and accountability for the death of her son. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 11, 1999 -- NY-DIALLO-MOTHER-1, 4-11 --
Kadiadou Diallo, flanked by the Rev. Al Sharpton, speaking to a
crowd of supporters about the death of her son Amadou, who was
killed in a barrage of 41 police bullets on Feb. 4. Mrs. Diallo
shrugs off the notion that she is a figurehead at the prow of a
nascent national movement focusing on the mistreatment of blacks
and other minority groups by the police. ``I am not a symbol;
Amadou is the symbol,'' says Mrs. Diallo. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ANAHEIM, Calif. -- April 11, 1999 -- MURDOCH-TV-SPORTS,
4-11 -- A Fox Enterntainment cameraman working a recent Anaheim
Angels-Cleveland Indians game. In intricate deals worth billions of
dollars, Rupert Murdoch's Fox Entertainment unit has moved to take
outright control of two of the nation's top five regional sports
networks, as measured by number of cable subscribers. (Kim
Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- April 11, 1999 --
KOSOVO-ABRAMOWITZ-PROFILE, 4-11 -- Sheppie Abramowitz, 63, vice
president of the International Rescue Committee, one of the private
refugee aid organizations with years of experience in the human
disasters of the Balkans. Ms. Abramowitz is in her fourth decade of
work on the harrowing refugee problems around the world. ``My
mother worked for refugees in the Second World War,'' she says,
recalling German Jewish families living in her house. ``I come by
this very rightly.'' (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WARREN, Mich. -- April 11, 1999 -- Y2K-LAWSUITS, 4-11 --
Produce Palace International, a Warren, Mich., grocery store chain
which was recently awarded a $250,000 court settlement based on a
jury's finding that the business had been repeatedly interrupted by
the failure of a computerized checkout scanning system to read
credit cards expiring in the Year 2000. The case is the the first
to result in a settlement paying damages to a plaintiff involving
Y2K problems. (Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- April 11, 1999 -- RAP-OPERA, 4-11 -- Rap
producer Prince Paul, a k a Paul Huston, a shy, visionary
31-year-old, in his studio in the Long Island house he and his
mother share. As a producer for such groundbreaking groups as De La
Soul, Huston has helped transform rap from a relatively simple
form, with a steady beat and bragging lyrics about ghetto life and
female treachery, into something more complex with skits and
parodies. (Richard Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- April 11, 1999 -- MARLENE-THEATER-REVIEW,
4-11 -- Sian Phillips as Marlene Dietrich in ``Marlene'' at the
Cort Theater. The self-described ``musical play'' by Pam Gems,
which stars the commanding Welsh actress Phillips looking like a
cryonic version of the title character, portrays a woman who
definitely didn't stint on sentimentality. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- April 11, 1999 -- GIULIO-OPERA-REVIEW, 4-11
-- Sylvia McNair as Cleopatra and Brian Asawa as Tolomeo in
``Giulio Cesare'' at the the Metropolitan Opera. The look of this
production is distracting but not fatally so. The Met's ``Giulio
Cesare'' also survives sets reminiscent of a Las Vegas hotel lobby.
Gilt and marble are the materials of choice, obelisks and throw
pillows the recurring accents. Female supernumeraries balance big
headdresses while posing like showgirls. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
