A4168 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN     04-11 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL TINKERING WITH MECHANICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Angels went into this season hoping that
pitcher Ken Hill's surgically repaired right elbow would be
healthy. Hill's health, manager Terry Collins has said, is the key
to the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Hill's elbow is not only feeling good and strong,
but it might be feeling a little too good and strong.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Hill had adjusted his mechanics last season to
help take the strain off his painful elbow before the surgery. But
now that his elbow is fine, he's had trouble adjusting back.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the problem has to do with his leg kick during his
delivery motion.
</P>
<P>
   Hill struggled in his first start, giving up four runs and six
hits in 41/3 innings against the Indians. He walked four, but
Collins said Hill was barely missing with his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ball has so much movement, it's a matter of getting a feel
for what he's got to do with it,'' Collins said. ``I think he's
very close to having it figured out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who will start today against the Rangers, says he has
figured it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on some things, and I watched some video
tape of last year,'' Hill said. ``I'm doing some things different.
I just recognized it yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Praise for Velarde: The Angels looked into getting a second
baseman during the offseason, one that was young and could run
well. When their efforts failed, they ``settled'' on Randy Velarde.
</P>
<P>
   But Velarde, even at 36, is probably in better shape than anyone
on the club. Although he missed a year and a half after
reconstructive elbow surgery, Velarde is as strong as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's a baseball player,'' Collins said. ``He doesn't
quit, he never slacks off. You know what kind of workaholic he is.
In batting practice, every swing has a purpose. I knew when he came
into camp he was ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde had four hits in Saturday's game and took a .429 (9 for
21) batting average into Sunday's game, best on the club.
</P>
<P>
   Break for Greene: Todd Greene was not in the lineup Sunday so
that he could be as rested as possible for today's game. It will be
Greene's first start at catcher in a major-league game since Aug.
20, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who has been hampered by shoulder problems the past year
and a half, caught in only four spring-training games and never
more than six innings. But Collins said there's a chance Greene
will go all nine today.
</P>
<P>
   Change of plans: Center fielder Jim Edmonds did not arrive in
Texas on Sunday, which was surprising news to Collins. Collins
thought Edmonds, who is on the disabled list, would be in town so
that he could take batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels won't take BP today because it's a day game, so
Edmonds is now expected to join the team Tuesday in Oakland. He's
eligible to come off the DL Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Series finale: The Angels and Rangers finish their series today
(11:35 a.m.) at The Ballpark in Arlington. Hill (0-1, 4.15 ERA)
will start for Anaheim against Texas' Mark Clark (0-0, 8.31).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
