<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT &LR;      04-11 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ENDURING THE UNENDURABLE IN POSTWAR JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States occupied and ruled Japan with an iron grip for
six years and eight months after World War II, a period nearly
twice as long as American involvement in the war itself. Yet
because of lingering sensitivity over that anomalous moment in
history, little discussion or reflection has occurred in either
country about what happened and how people felt during the
occupation, at least compared with commentary about the war and
Japan's economic rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   With America increasingly frustrated over bending others to its
designs around the world, it is startling to remember that only 50
years ago the United States actually tried and largely succeeded in
remaking a hated enemy in its own image. A powerful new book,
``Embracing Defeat'' by John Dower, draws on archives, diaries and
recollections to recount the events after 1945 in great detail,
shattering one myth after another about the occupation era.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, the occupation was a success. For all its
current economic problems today, Japan is an egalitarian and
democratic state that continues to embrace an American-imposed
Constitution renouncing war. But from Emperor Hirohito on down to
the lowliest peasant, Japanese behavior in the immediate postwar
years comes across in Dower's book as far more clever and complex
than is suggested by the cliches of a happily liberated people
embracing democracy and pacifism from on high. Resentment and fear
of the occupiers were never far below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, on the other hand, emerge in this account as
basically humane rulers whose behavior was often appallingly
hypocritical. The Japanese effectively encouraged prostitution to
protect the rest of their womanhood from defilement. Hundreds of
thousands of American G.I.'s exploited this arrangement, treating
the country as a giant brothel at a time when the occupation
enforced equal rights for women.
</P>
<P>
   Dower, a professor of Japanese history at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, has written a sobering monument to the law
of unintended consequences. He shows how much of the mysteriously
hierarchical conduct that frustrates Japan's trading partners today
is rooted in crucial decisions imposed by the occupation forces
under Gen. Douglas MacArthur. The so-called ``Asian model'' of
state capitalism, in which government bureaucrats provided
``administrative guidance'' to business and industry, is often
discussed by experts ``in a vapor of rhetoric about Confucian
values,'' he notes. In fact, it arose in large part from a
conscious decision by the occupying forces to preserve Japan's
wartime economic structure, and to use Japan's elite bureaucrats to
carry out their policies.
</P>
<P>
   The occupation's initial goal was to instill ``democratization
and demilitarization,'' but American authorities also did not
hesitate to suppress left-wing disruption and criticism. ``This was
not a screen for weeding out threats to democracy (as official
justifications claimed),'' Dower writes, ``but rather a new chapter
in an old book of lessons about acquiescing to overweening power
and conforming to a dictated consensus concerning permissible
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Dower's prize-winning ``War Without Mercy,'' published in 1986,
opened many people's eyes by documenting the racial hatred and
cruelty on both sides. The most explosive chapters in this book
will surely be Dower's unflinching study of Hirohito, much of it
based on material only recently available. Dower shows that
MacArthur insisted on keeping the emperor in office to guard
against chaos and Communism in Japanese society, but that he
secretly used the threat of Hirohito's removal to get the Japanese
parliament to accept the Constitution. Dower theorizes, however,
that not holding Hirohito accountable for his wartime conduct
effectively transformed him into a false symbol of innocence. That
step, along with the arbitrariness of the war-crimes trials,
allowed the Japanese people to think that they, like the emperor,
had been hijacked by militarists and bore no responsibility for the
war themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the aloof, dithering image cherished by many Japanese,
Hirohito is seen here as a wily survivor who managed to convince
Americans that he did not know about Pearl Harbor in advance, when
the evidence shows that he did, and that he had unequivocally
renounced his divine status in a speech, even though Japanese
listeners understood him to be doing no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   Only 50 years later it is possible to see that the destitution
and destruction of Japan could lead one day to reconciliation and
prosperity. In defeat, Hirohito called on the Japanese to ``endure
the unendurable.'' Dower has provided the most human and moving
account yet of how that struggle led to a triumph over fear, hatred
and humiliation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
