<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN MAY MEET HER REMATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman begins her run for the
U.S. Senate with so many political advantages that it would be easy
to mistake her for a prohibitive favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who announced last week that she would seek the
seat being vacated next year by Sen. Frank Lautenberg, a Democrat,
has been blessed with a robust economy and low unemployment rate.
She faces no major primary challenge and can trumpet her own record
of enacting 17 separate tax cuts. It is also clear that Whitman
relishes the possibility that her Democratic opponent may be former
Gov. Jim Florio, the man she unseated in 1993 after his $2.8
billion tax increase enraged many New Jersey residents.
</P>
<P>
   But political experts in both parties warn that the volatility
of the New Jersey electorate, together with the fact that Whitman
has never managed to win more than 50 percent of the vote, will
make the 19 months leading up to the general election tumultuous
and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Registered Democrats outnumber registered Republicans in New
Jersey by 25 percent to 19 percent _ nearly 300,000 voters _ and
that gap has widened in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Whitman has nationwide stature as a tax-cutting
Republican with moderate views on social issues, she has never won
the overwhelming support of New Jersey voters.
</P>
<P>
   There are two predominant theories for Whitman's lackluster
performance at the polls. Her supporters tend to blame her
political opponents' negative advertising, which often portrays her
as a patrician out of touch with the everyday concerns of the poor
and middle class. Others say that her cool management style
projects an image of competence _ the governor as CEO _ but does
little to forge an emotional bond with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Her 1997 re-election bid, which many New Jerseyans expected her
to win handily, nearly ended in disaster. James McGreevey, the
little-known mayor of Woodbridge, lambasted Whitman for New
Jersey's high property taxes and auto insurance rates and came
within 1 percentage point of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   If Florio does run against Whitman _ which is not a sure thing,
given many Democrats' reservations about the former governor _
their rematch is likely to be fierce.
</P>
<P>
   In their last contest, the Whitman campaign was so rocked by
Florio's relentless criticism that Republicans ran a television
commercial that featured Whitman's 16-year-old daughter, Kate,
defending her mother's honor. Florio, whose tax increase had
incited a recall effort early in his term, pulled ahead in the
polls within six weeks of Election Day. Whitman then unleashed her
most potent weapon, a proposal to cut income tax rates by 30
percent. Although voters were initially skeptical of the promise,
it helped her eke out a narrow victory.
</P>
<P>
   Florio appears eager for a rematch. He maintains that the tax
increase was the only responsible way to pay for a court-ordered
increase in school aid, but concedes that he did not explain it
well enough to voters. Florio also contends that Whitman's vaunted
tax cuts have forced the state to increase its debt and have
brought higher local property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But Florio still faces a difficult battle to win the Democratic
nomination. Many party leaders outside his political base in South
Jersey are openly courting other potential candidates, like Rep.
Frank J. Pallone Jr., a congressman from Long Branch; Susan Bass
Levin, the mayor of Cherry Hill; Michael Murphy, the Morris County
prosecutor; B. Thomas Byrne Jr., the former chairman of the state
party, or Jon S. Corzine, co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever ends up opposing Whitman, even some Republicans say she
will also face the personal challenge of focusing her message so
she connects with voters. Carl Golden, press manager for her 1993
campaign, said the criticism he heard most often was that Whitman
gave intellectual answers to emotional questions.
</P>
<P>
   When Whitman was asked Thursday why her approval rating among
voters was not as high as previous second-term governors, she said
she hadn't a clue. She also showed little interest in a drastic
make-over of her campaign style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, I don't rely on polls for anything I do, and just
as fortunately, I've managed to win my last two elections,'' she
said. ``Would I have wished to have rode in on the people's
shoulders with a huge plurality? Of course. Everybody does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
