<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-11 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIULIO-OPERA-REVIEW-A     04-11 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIO-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIULIO CESARE': FLORID, YES, BUT MODERN ALL THE SAME
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a strong cast, good musicians and deft
direction, Handel in the modern opera house confounds its critics.
Prior speculation on the Metropolitan Opera's new ``Giulio Cesare''
has been justifiably dim: the wrong space, the wrong instruments,
the wrong style. Yet the Met's new production captivated its
audience on Saturday night and with reason.
</P>
<P>
   The singers are uniformly splendid. Jennifer Larmore (Caesar),
David Daniels (Sesto), Sylvia McNair (Cleopatra) and Brian Asawa
(Tolomeo) attack Handel's florid figuration with confidence and
sing simply when he requires it. As Cornelia, Stephanie Blythe's
big, dark sound meets the Baroque on common ground. She does not
shrink her dimensions; Handel does not raise his voice. Rather a
place is found where both parties remain themselves.
</P>
<P>
   John Nelson conducted a similar set of negotiations. Nelson's
musical direction had the full attention of stage and pit. Ensemble
was precise, and spirits were buoyant. The Met's string sections
sang out but largely without vibrato, in the 18th-century manner.
``Giulio Cesare'' is a nightmare for horn players (it was probably
even more so in Handel's pre-valve era), and there were teetering
moments on Saturday. Important, however, was the correctness of
scale: the resonance that was needed to fill a big hall and yet the
exactitude befitting a smaller one.
</P>
<P>
   The success of this all-American cast is less surprising when we
remember that it was singing an Italian opera written by a German
for British audiences. The problems of ``Giulio Cesare,'' however,
go beyond singing. For here is opera as bloodthirsty seriousness
with a coy streak of humor running through its middle.
</P>
<P>
   John Copley's restraint is admirable. Ms. McNair's Cleopatra is
a subtle exercise in ditsiness. Dignity is everywhere. Ms. Larmore,
singing with great command, projects a powerful presence. Ms.
McNair is a charmer. Daniels, urged on by an audience full of
supporters, sang with beautiful tone and urgency. If there is a
musical memory I shall take away from this season, it will be he
and Ms. Blythe in their duet of leave-taking at the end of Act I.
</P>
<P>
   During the set pieces, stage tableaux do not give off the usual
Handelian impression of people standing around and waiting. Deeper
into the more serious arias, Copley walls off the singers from the
set behind them, pushes them toward the front of the stage,
creating a sense of closeness between character and listener.
</P>
<P>
   Opera seria, with its strings of circular arias, comes with
difficulty to audiences bent on action. This production does very
well convincing us that it is not what these characters do that is
paramount but what they are thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The Met's ``Giulio Cesare'' also survives sets reminiscent of a
Las Vegas hotel lobby. Gilt and marble are the materials of choice,
obelisks and throw pillows the recurring accents. Female
supernumeraries balance big headdresses while posing like
showgirls. Tolomeo is dressed up as Ming the Merciless; Cornelia
might be Elizabeth I.
</P>
<P>
   The look of this production is distracting but not fatally so.
The supporting singers _ Julien Robbins, Mariusz Kwiecien and
Daniel Taylor _ are excellent. The sets were by John Pascoe and the
costumes by Michael Stennett. This is Handel that meets the modern
world with intelligence, talent and style. Given the built-in
disadvantages, you will be surprised just how good it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
